<SLUG> BC-HEATING-BILLS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TASK FORCE TO PREPARE CONSUMERS FOR HIGH WINTER HEATING BILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE EVERLY  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Kansas regulators on Friday brought together a task
force of state agencies, gas utilities and community groups to
begin preparing consumers for higher heating bills expected this
coming winter.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas Corporation Commission hatched the idea for a task
force within the last month as natural gas prices reached levels
nearly double those from a year ago. At current prices, consumers
can expect to pay an additional $200 to $300 to heat their homes
this winter.
</P>
<P>
   John Wine, the commission's chairman, said there are increasing
concerns about the potential effect of rising natural gas prices on
consumers. He said thousands of Kansas families could be
economically devastated by their heating bills this winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt it's going to be a problem this winter,''
Wine said.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas task force plans to meet a half-dozen times. While it
is still formulating plans, the emphasis will be on education.
Caulking, weatherstripping and other conservation techniques will
be stressed. Consumers also will be asked to consider the
level-payment plans offered by utilities that spread out the amount
owed.
</P>
<P>
   Wine said higher natural gas prices will affect most gas
customers, but poor residents will be particularly hard hit. Some
federal assistance is available to help pay utility bills, but the
task force is exploring other sources of revenue that could be used
to supplement those funds.
</P>
<P>
   Wholesale gas prices on Friday were about $4 per 1,000 cubic
feet, down 10 percent from last week's prices. But that price is
still nearly double a year ago and earlier this year. Higher gas
prices are passed directly to a gas utility's customers.
</P>
<P>
   The average household uses 120,000 cubic feet per year and most
of that in the winter.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is caused by tight supplies. Electric
utilities are using more gas to generate power at the same time gas
utilities are buying fuel to put in storage to meet winter demand.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the expected $200-to-$300 rise in heating bills
for an average household this winter, expenses could go higher if
there are additional price spikes or a colder-than-normal winter.
The last two winters have been warmer than normal.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Johnson, a spokesman for Kansas Gas Service who also is on
the task force, said the utility will put inserts in its bills this
fall advising consumers of gas prices and their effect on heating
bills.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas Gas Service recently got approval to spend up to $6
million on its hedging program, which provides some protection from
price spikes in the winter. A hedge works by purchasing financial
options that put a cap on how much a utility pays for the natural
gas.
</P>
<P>
   The cap, under current market conditions, would be above $5 per
1,000 cubic feet of gas. Johnson said Kansas Gas Service has
decided the hedge is still worthwhile because the volatile market
for natural gas could cause prices to climb above those levels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
