 PM-BUDGET-NYT 
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For SATURDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Saturday, July 8.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND-ASYLUM (Birr, Ireland) _ For the last decade, membership
in the European Union has helped fuel a tremendous economic boom in
Ireland, transforming an isolated, desperately poor economy into
the proud success that calls itself the Celtic Tiger. But the boom
has brought another European dividend: waves of unwanted newcomers
seeking refuge from politically unstable, war-ravaged areas of
Africa and Eastern Europe. By Sarah Lyall. 1,600 words.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients)
</P>
<P>
   WAR-CRIMES-DEFINED (Undated) _ From the grisly amputations of
the hands of innocents in Sierra Leone to the systematic sexual
abuse of women in Bosnia and Rwanda _ or, some would say, to the
bombing of Kosovo refugees by NATO war planes _ modern conflicts
raise new and complex issues. There still is not total agreement on
universally accepted moral codes. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NEV-DRUGS-ELDERLY (Carson City, Nev.) _ Nevada has adopted a
prescription drug program for the elderly very similar to one
approved last month by the U.S. House, but it is off to a rocky
start. Insurance companies have spurned Nevada's invitation to
provide coverage. The risks and the costs are too high, they say,
and the subsidies offered by the state are too low. By Robert Pear.
1,600 words.
</P>
<P>
   NY-COURTS-ABUSE (New York) _ As the supervising judge in Bronx
Family Court, Judge Clark Richardson handles all of the cases when
the city's child welfare agency has removed children from their
homes because one of their parents has been the victim of domestic
abuse. The city can take children into foster care if a parent is
believed to ``engage in acts of domestic violence.'' In practice
that usually means that a mother who is a victim of abuse can be
charged with a failure to protect her children from danger. Often,
she may have done nothing wrong or negligent, but simply lacked the
financial or emotional resources to leave an abusive partner. In
such cases, it falls to Richardson and other Family Court judges
across the state to decide whether those mothers get their children
back, and under what terms. By Somini Sengupta.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: NYT15 is being sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   EPISCOPALS-LUTHERANS (Denver) _ The General Conference of the
Episcopal Church, meeting here, is to take up a proposal that would
unite the 2.4 million members of the Episcopal church and with the
5.2 million members of the Evangelical Lutheran churches. Church
leaders see the proposal for ``full communion,'' which the
Lutherans have already approved, as a landmark step for the two
denominations. It would be more a pact than a merger, but would
allow the churches to recognize each other's sacraments, share
clergy and pool resources, particularly in inner city and rural
areas where congregations are often small and financially
hard-pressed. Although the two churches are close in matters of
theology and liturgy, and both ordain women, they have had
significant differences over the role and authority of bishops,
which has been a sticking point. By Michael Janofsky and Laurie
Goodstein.
</P>
<P>
   TEACHERS-FELDMAN (Undated) _ Public lives on Sandra Feldman,
president of the American Federation of Teachers. By Jodi Wilgoren.
</P>
<P>
   JAMAICA-MISSING-EDITOR (Negril, Jamaica) _ Frederick and Mary
Ann Kirschhoch have made two trips to Jamaica, where their
daughter, a travel editor, vanished around May 27. They came
because they believed they could describe their daughter to
Jamaicans in a way that only parents could. By Edward Wong.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-PARENTS (Kennebunkport, Maine) _ Former President George
Bush and his wife, Barbara, talk about their son's candidacy for
president and his chances of winning. By Frank Bruni. 1,600 words.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos NYT6 and NYT12 and graphic are being sent to
NYT photo and grphic clients)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DULUTH-SISTERCITY (Duluth, Minn.) _ On the street here these
days you hear French, Swedish, Russian, Japanese and at least half
a dozen other foreign tongues. It's not tourists who give the city
this cosmopolitan air, but business executives. Not too bad for a
city that 80 years ago, under the alias Zenith, was branded as
hopelessly small-minded and provincial by Sinclair Lewis in his
novel ``Babbitt.'' Duluth is still no New York or Los Angeles, of
course. Or even a place like Rochester, home of the Mayo Clinic.
But it has focused more on the wider world not just because of its
shipping trade through the Great Lakes but also because of its
sister-city program _ the nonprofit city-to-city network inspired
by President Dwight Eisenhower's suggestion in 1956 that citizen
diplomacy might lessen the chance of future world conflict. By
William H. Honan.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SEASIA-ECON (Singapore) _ Despite Southeast Asia's economic
recovery from the crisis that began three years ago this month,
foreign investors have been dumping stocks and currencies from the
region. Its markets this year are the worst-performing in the
world, having dropped more than 22 percent on average. By Wayne
Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-SOFTWARE (Shanghai, China) _ Janet Reno isn't the only one
worried about Bill Gates' software monopoly. China's leaders are,
too. They are concerned that the country is growing overly
dependent on the Windows operating system, which controls computers
running everything from China's banks to President Jiang Zemin's
e-mail box. But the Chinese government, itself a master at
monopoly, is taking its case against Microsoft not to the courtroom
but to the marketplace, albeit with a bit of administrative fiat.
It is backing the Linux operating system, created by a Finnish
university student in 1991 and distributed free to anyone who wants
it. By Craig S. Smith.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LEWIS-COLUMN _ Anthony Lewis writes about Ralph Nader.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BBO-ANDERSON-COLUMN (New York) _ Sports of The Times column on
the Yankees-Mets series and a look back to a 1903 two-ballpark
doubleheader in the city. By Dave Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT (Moved ``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WRITING-FOR-KIDS (Undated) _ As those who do it best have
testified, writing well for children is, first and last, very
difficult. And as memoirs and biographies have shown, the great
children's works have often been the products of personal
difficulty and stress, a distillation in narrative form of
anguished experience. By Eden Ross Lipson.
</P>
<P>
   MARX-BOOKS (Undated) _ Two recent books about Groucho and his
brothers. By Edward Rothstein.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-VIOLENCE (Undated) _ Critic's Notebook: Does popular music
incite violence? By Ann Powers.
</P>
<P>
   GUERNICA-DOCUMENTARY (Guernica, Spain) _ It's hard to imagine
the scene as it was here some 60 years ago, when one of the first
major atrocities of World War II took place. A new documentary
film, ``The Bombing of Guernica: The Mark of Men,'' produced by a
peace research center here, includes the voices of the people who
survived the Luftwaffe attack. By Herbert Mitgang.
</P>
