<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-FRAUD-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER CARONDELET HEALTH EXECUTIVE SENTENCED FOR DEFRAUDING
MEDICARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GLENN E. RICE  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Richard Michael Abell, former president and
chief executive officer of Carondelet Health, was sentenced Friday
to five months in a halfway house and five months home detention
for defrauding Medicare of more than $91,000.
</P>
<P>
   Abell, 61, of Overland Park, Kan., also must spend three years
under supervised release and must pay a $15,700 fine. U.S. District
Judge Ortie D. Smith imposed the sentence.
</P>
<P>
   The case is part of a government crackdown on health-care fraud,
said Chris Whitley, a spokesman for the U.S. attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Abell waived indictment and pleaded guilty to one
count of felony health-care fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Abell falsely claimed more than $361,000 in personal expenses as
business expenses, and the hospital reimbursed him for those
expenses, according to federal authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Abell's fraudulent business expenses, in turn, had been
submitted over several years to Medicare, the government health
program for the elderly. Medicare reimbursed St. Joseph Health
Center in Kansas City for a portion of that amount, more than
$91,000.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors said Abell had committed fraud from about
Jan. 1, 1993, to Oct. 5, 1998. He spent the money on a variety of
items including travel, meals, entertainment and gifts, Whitley
said.
</P>
<P>
   Abell was fired by Carondelet, which includes St. Joseph Health
Center and St. Mary's Hospital of Blue Springs, Mo., in October
1998 after an internal audit.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Abell was the recipient of the Missouri Hospital
Association's Distinguished Service Award. Abell had been a
hospital administrator for nearly 30 years and had held executive
positions at hospitals in Tennessee and Kentucky before moving to
Kansas City in 1986 to join St. Joseph Health Center as its
president.
</P>
<P>
   George A. Zara, who replaced Abell as Carondelet's president and
chief executive officer in 1999, issued a statement Friday, saying
it was time the hospital put the matter behind and moved forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our hope is that this sentence will serve as the beginning to
the end of a 20-month process and healing can take place for all
parties involved,'' Zara said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
