<HEADER>
A6410 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-STATES-KILLINGS-KAN &LR;      07-08 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-KILLINGS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPLIT BY STATE LINE, PROSECUTORS DISAGREE ON MURDER CASES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD ESPINOZA and ERICA WOOD  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Chris Koster, the prosecutor of Cass County,
Mo., and Paul Morrison, the district attorney of Johnson County,
Kan., want the same thing: to try John E. Robinson Sr. for murder.
</P>
<P>
   But they aren't in total agreement on how to go about it.
</P>
<P>
   Koster said Thursday that he wants to bring the serial murder
suspect across the state line from Kansas soon to begin Missouri's
case against him.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, when Morrison heard about the plan to arraign
Robinson in Missouri and then return him to Kansas, he said it
probably wouldn't work and might jeopardize the cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``My understanding is there are serious legal problems with
bringing a prisoner back and forth over state lines while there's a
charge against him,'' Morrison said. ``We're not going to inject
any legal difficulties into this case.''
</P>
<P>
   After five women's bodies were found in barrels in Linn County,
Kan., and Cass County, Mo., early last month, Robinson was charged
in Kansas with two counts of capital murder and in Missouri with
three. Authorities also have connected him to three women and a
baby missing since the 1980s. Robinson remains held in the Johnson
County Jail on $5 million bond.
</P>
<P>
   When the charges were filed, Koster indicated that he would wait
for Kansas to finish its case.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he said, he's working with the Missouri attorney general on
a plan that would allow Robinson to be transported between Missouri
and Kansas, so that Missouri can begin its pretrial discovery
process, which includes collecting statements from witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Koster stressed that he's not trying to keep Robinson in
Missouri but just wants to arraign him and then send him back to
Johnson County.
</P>
<P>
   But under the federal Interstate Agreement on Detainers Act, if
a trial is not held on an indictment, information or complaint
before a prisoner is sent back to his original place of
imprisonment, the case will be dismissed and cannot be refiled.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Kansas and Missouri agreed to move Robinson across the
state line, another problem would remain. Either Robinson would
have to agree to the plan, or each move would trigger an
extradition hearing that could take months, Morrison said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just can't control all the variables, and it would be an
understatement to say we would be playing with fire if we attempted
any of that,'' Morrison said.
</P>
<P>
   Koster said he's not trying to be antagonistic. But if Missouri
has to wait until Kansas completes its case, it could be four years
before both cases are finished, he said.
</P>
<P>
   If Missouri's case is put on hold, Koster said, he would have to
deal with witnesses' fading memories and old evidence. He wants
access to witness statements in the Kansas cases so the witnesses
will not have to give the same information several years later.
</P>
<P>
   Morrison said Kansas investigators would continue to share
information with Missouri, as they have since June, when the case
led from bodies on Robinson's Linn County farm to a storage locker
he rented in Raymore in Cass County.
</P>
<P>
   Morrison said supporting a case with old memories and evidence
is a common problem that prosecutors must deal with regularly.
</P>
<P>
   Koster said he expected Missouri to indict Robinson sometime
this month, while Robinson's preliminary hearing in Kansas is not
scheduled until October.
</P>
<P>
   ``Missouri's ready to go,'' Koster said. ``I believe we have
everything needed to try this case.''
</P>
<P>
   Before he spoke to Morrison on Friday about stepping up
Missouri's part of the case, he had said he thought authorities in
Kansas would go along with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``A spirit of cooperation has permeated the entire case, and I
have every expectation it will continue,'' Koster said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he thought the technical issues involved, such as the
legality of transporting Robinson back and forth, could be worked
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``His crimes did not pay any heed to the border that runs down
state line,'' Koster said. ``Neither should prosecutors benefit
John Robinson with such technicalities.''
</P>
<P>
   Plus, Koster said, Missouri's case has an added sense of urgency
because the law is harsher on murderers of police officers and
corrections workers. Beverly J. Bonner, one of the women whose
bodies were found in Raymore, once was a corrections worker at a
Missouri prison where Robinson served time.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's that added sense of seriousness,'' Koster said. ``I
don't believe it needs to wait to have justice done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
