<HEADLINE>
HARRY POTTER'S SPELL WORKS ITS MAGIC ON READERS AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN MARK EBERHART  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ After months of anticipation that seemed more
like years to children, bookstores began selling Harry Potter and
the Goblet of Fire at 12:01 a.m. today.
</P>
<P>
   Booksellers across the area, nation and world opened late Friday
night for Harry Potter pajama parties to welcome the fourth book in
J.K. Rowling's series; sales started ringing up just after the
stroke of midnight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been waiting January, February, March, April, May,
June and finally JULY!'' said 8-year-old Chase Hodge of Fairway.
</P>
<P>
   Chase and his mother, Mary, and sisters Caroline, 10, and Lissy,
5, made arrangements to get up late Friday night and troop off to
Rainy Day Books in Fairway, Kan., where their reserved copy awaited
them. The family reads the books aloud together, but it has been a
long drought since last year's Harry Potter and the Prisoner of
Azkaban.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're this excited, I can certainly get up and get the
book in the middle of the night,'' Mary Hodge said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad it's finally here,'' said Jan Snyder, manager of The
Last Chapter Bookshops in Overland Park and Shawnee, both in
Kansas. ``Everything in my life the last couple of days has been
oriented around Harry Potter.''
</P>
<P>
   Scottish writer Rowling's previous three novels about the young
