<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-SHOOTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFF-DUTY OFFICERS KILL MAN WHO ATTACKED THEM ON PARKWAY, POLICE
SAY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga.)  By EDWARD WONG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two off-duty police officers Friday fatally shot a
man who began punching them after a bizarre traffic altercation on
the Grand Central Parkway in Queens, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Although police officials did not explicitly defend the shooting
at a news conference Friday night, they suggested that it was
justified, saying that the shooting victim relentlessly punched the
officers and grabbed at one of their handguns. The officers had
apparently stopped on the parkway during what seemed like a traffic
accident, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   The incident began around 6:20 p.m., when the shooting victim,
Darnell Cisco, a chef in his early 20s from Rome, Ga., leaped out
the passenger side of a moving green Kia Sephia four-door sedan
being driven by his friend, the police said. The car was traveling
in the far left lane of the parkway near Francis Lewis Boulevard
and going up to 45 mph, the police said. Police officials said they
did not know why Cisco jumped, but that the impact peeled skin off
the right side of his body. Cisco was wearing a T-shirt, baggy
shorts and work boots, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   An airport cab run by All Seasons was coming up behind the
Sephia and swerved to the left shoulder to avoid hitting Cisco, the
police said.
</P>
<P>
   The two off-duty Queens officers _ a male sergeant and a female
detective _ were traveling in a black Dodge Dakota pickup truck
behind the cab. The sergeant, who was driving, stopped on the
roadway at a 45-degree angle to avoid hitting Cisco, a senior
police official said.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco then got up and ran around to the driver's window and
began punching the sergeant, the police said. The sergeant stepped
on the gas to get away, but slammed into the rear of the cab,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco ran around to the passenger side and tried to drag the
detective out the open window, the police said. She resisted, and
both officers pulled out their badges and identified themselves,
the police said. But Cisco punched the detective and tried to wrest
a handgun away from her when she drew it, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Then the officers began shooting, the police said. The sergeant
fired one shot, and the detective fired three, but it was unclear
how many shots hit the assailant, officials said. He died at the
scene.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear whether the victim was armed, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   ```We have no idea why he did it,'' said William Allee, chief of
detectives. ``We don't want to speculate.''
</P>
<P>
   Cisco's body was found slumped over the seat in the pickup truck
the officers were in, and later covered with a white plastic bag.
</P>
<P>
   Mattie Real, the victim's grandmother, said in a telephone
interview that he had never been involved in any kind of trouble.
He had been staying with her and his mother, Regina Real, in their
apartment in Glen Cove because Cisco's aunt was sick, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very sweet person,'' Real said between tears. ``He
doesn't get involved with anybody. That's what I don't
understand.''
</P>
<P>
   She said that Cisco liked music and often went to a studio
somewhere in the city to cut tapes with his friend.
</P>
<P>
   Real said she saw Cisco earlier that morning before she went to
work at a day care center in Glen Cove. He was going to take a nap,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities did not release the names of the officers
involved in the incident.
</P>
<P>
   The two officers suffered bruises to their faces and were taken
to North Shore University Hospital in Manhasset.
</P>
<P>
   The incident comes at a time when the New York Police Department
is under scrutiny after a series of high-profile shootings of
unarmed men. Those victims included Amadou Diallo, who was killed
last year in the Bronx, and Patrick Dorismond, who was shot earlier
this year.
</P>
<P>
   The police were questioning the driver of the Sephia FRiday
night. He was not injured. No arrests had been made.
</P>
<P>
   The cabdriver and his passenger were not injured.
</P>
<P>
   Three hours after the incident, traffic was still slowed to a
crawl in the eastbound lanes of the parkway. The police had shut
down two of the three major lanes, leaving only the far right lane
and an exit lane open. About 15 marked and unmarked police cars,
two tow trucks and an Emergency Service Unit vehicle were parked at
the scene. The three cars involved in the incident were still on
the shoulder, with the front of the pickup truck smashed into the
rear of the airport cab.
</P>
</TEXT>
