 JOB OF FIRE TOWER LOOKOUT A REMINDER OF EARLIER TIMES  &HT;     By JANET WELLS 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOUNT ELIZABETH, Calif. _ Fire lookout Herb Self is sure that
his office _ a 65-foot-tall, glass-walled aerie overlooking the
Stanislaus National Forest _ is the ideal place to be during a
Sierra lightning storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fireworks. Beautiful,'' said Self, a grizzled, bearded
man who favors short sentences and the long silences of the forest.
``Thunder here sounds like you got your head stuck in a cannon.''
</P>
<P>
   Just a few days shy of his 70th birthday, Self is one of the old
guard of the forest, a vanishing breed of folks who spend hour upon
hour peering at a bird's eye view, waiting to spot a telltale wisp
of smoke before it can turn into a raging blaze ravaging mountain
towns and thousands of acres of timber.
</P>
<P>
   California once boasted more than 700 lookout towers staffed by
the National Forest Service and the California Department of
Forestry, forming the backbone of a vigorous program to protect
more than 20 million acres of public and private lands.
</P>
<P>
   Now, because technology and poor air quality are making human
eyes obsolete, only 55 federal and 30 state lookouts are staffed
during fire season.
</P>
<P>
   While California's dwindling use of the towers mirrors a
decades-long trend across the country, there is a growing movement
of fire look o)YyJWKw &UR; buffs. The Forest Fire Lookout Association
formed in 1990, and now has chapters in 25 states.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fire lookouts are probably one of the most romantic reminders
of the post-cowboy United States, the idea of the lone foO
</P>
</TEXT>
