<SLUG> BC-ECONOMY-SLOWS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 STOCKS LIKE SLOWER U.S. JOB GROWTH  &HT;     By DAVID LAZARUS 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The rocket-powered U.S. economy appeared to be headed for a soft
landing Friday as the latest employment numbers suggested that a
year of steady interest-rate increases are finally starting to pay
off.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street, for its part, responded in high style, with the
tech-heavy Nasdaq composite index erasing most of its losses for
the year.
</P>
<P>
   So just how cool  &UR; is  &LR; Alan Greenspan?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's pretty amazing,'' said Jeff Lancaster, a portfolio
manager at San Francisco investment firm Bingham, Osborn &AMP;
Scarborough. ``It's as if he foamed the runway with just the right
touch.''
</P>
<P>
   It looks like the Federal Reserve chief has pulled off the neat
trick of slowing U.S. economic growth _ thus keeping inflation at
bay _ while at the same time maintaining a high level of confidence
among Wall Street investors.
</P>
<P>
   The latest evidence that Greenspan's tactics appear to be
working came as the Labor Department reported that U.S. companies
hired fewer workers than expected last month and that wages rose
only modestly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The data would support the conclusion that Alan Greenspan is
doing a darn good job,'' said James Meyer, research director at
Janney Montgomery Scott in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses added a mere 11,000 jobs in June, the Labor
Department said. Economists had been expecting payrolls to expand
by about 250,000 positions.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, average hourly wages gained 0.4 percent, or 5 cents,
to $13.71, in line with expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Investors liked the sound of that. The Nasdaq climbed 62.63
points to finish the week at 4,023.20 _ its first close above 4,000
in more than two weeks and just 46 points below its level at the
start of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones Industrial Average jumped 154.51 points to
10,635.98, and the broader Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index rose 22.23
points to 1,478.90.
</P>
<P>
   While a slowing economy and potentially tighter labor market may
not be the best of news to Main Street _ employers will have to pay
more to retain workers _ for Wall Street it's an enormous relief.
</P>
<P>
   If subsequent data bear out the trend, the Fed is unlikely to
raise interest rates at the next meeting of its policy-making
committee on August 22. The Fed left rates unchanged when Greenspan
&AMP; Co. convened last month.
</P>
<P>
   Janney's Meyer said the latest jobs data indicate that while the
economy is slowing, it is by no means screeching to a halt. Growth
will continue, he said, albeit at a more moderate clip.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is taking this to mean that we will not have a
recession and that we will have a soft landing,'' Meyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Meehan, chief market analyst at Cantor Fitzgerald in New
York, said investors were looking for any sign that the economy is
throttling back to a pace more to the Fed's liking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything that came in reasonably close to expectations, or
better, was going to be met with pretty aggressive buying,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Investors favored a number of old standbys. Hewlett-Packard
jumped $6.38 to $124.75, while Sun Microsystems advanced $2.56 to
$90.06.
</P>
<P>
   Among the handful of losers Friday, Yahoo dropped $5.88 to
$116.50 after an analyst downgraded the stock to ``buy'' from
``strong buy,'' while Qualcomm tumbled more than 8 percent to
$56.63 after South Korean wireless operators opted to go with a
rival's technology.
</P>
<P>
   Meehan said that while he is encouraged by the latest jobs
numbers, he isn't yet ready to say that Greenspan is done raising
rates for the year. Another quarter-point increase next month is
not out of the question, he said.
</P>
<P>
   After that it gets a little tricky. This is an election year,
and the Fed historically has refrained from fiddling with interest
rates ahead of a presidential vote.
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts believe Greenspan would be risking considerable
political fallout were he to raise rates at the Fed's fall
get-together in October.
</P>
<P>
   Al Kugel, senior investment strategist at Stein Roe &AMP; Farnham in
Chicago, said investors hope that past increases will continue
putting the brakes on economic growth and that the Fed will be
content for the remainder of the year to reap the fruit of past
labors.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's managed to make things work out exactly the way he wanted
it,'' Kugel said.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of ECONOMY0 (64111 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Looking ahead, he expects to see solid earnings for leading
companies and for the market to remain robust through the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't have 5-percent economic growth, but instead growth in
the 3 percent or 4 percent range,'' Kugel said. ``And 3 percent
growth is still good enough.''
</P>
</TEXT>
