<SLUG> BC-MISSILE-TEST-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-590(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEST OF PROPOSED U.S. ANTI-MISSILE SYSTEM IS BEING WATCHED AROUND
THE WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (UPDATES with test beginning)  
 By ELAINE SCIOLINO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A gleaming 63-foot Minuteman II rocket carrying a
mock warhead thundered into the sky from a Cali- fornia air base
early Saturday, in what is expected to be the decisive test to
determine whether President Clin- ton proceeds with a plan to begin
development of a $60 billion national missile defense.
</P>
<P>
   The rocket lifted off from Vanden-H burg Air Force Base, 125
miles north of Los Angeles, at 12:19 a.m., and headed toward the
Marshall Islands 4,300 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-one minutes later, a 54-inch, 130-pound ``exoatmospheric
kill vehicle'' was launched from Kwajalein Atoll in an attempt to
find, intercept and smash into the approaching warhead in space
above the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   The test was awaited anxiously by protesters, who took to the
seas, skeptical scientists and Pentagon planners.
</P>
<P>
   The test lasted only 30 min- utes; it cost $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   The test was being watched around the world. Not since 1983,
when President Reagan envisioned a defense based in space that
would render nuclear weapons obsolete, has an issue of military
technology seized the imagination of U.S. policy-makers and
politicians and alarmed America's friends and foes.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has also entered the presidential campaign, with Vice
President Al Gore endorsing a limited version of the plan and Gov.
George W. Bush backing a more ambitious system.
</P>
<P>
   And it has raised a chorus of criticism from a sizable swath of
scientists in the United States, some of whom argue that the
proposed $60 billion system is not feasible and that the tests are
rigged.
</P>
<P>
   The test involved sending the 37-year-old remodeled Minuteman
missile with a mock warhead and a decoy balloon thundering aloft
over the Pacific from the tightly-guarded launch pad at Vandenberg.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty minutes later, a 54-inch, 130-pound ``exoatmospheric kill
vehicle'' was launched from Kwajalein Atoll about 4,300 miles away
in the Pacific and to guide itself to a collision with the incoming
mock warhead in midflight. If the kill vehicle destroys the mock
warhead, the sky will be filled with a blinding flash.
</P>
<P>
   The test had been scheduled to take place during a four-hour
win- dow that began late Friday night. But a last-minute technical
problem set back the launching by about two hours. The problem was
related to electronic signals that keep the ground control informed
about the missile's flight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hitting a bullet with a bullet,'' is the way one Pentagon
official described the hoped-for collision. ``Steel on target,''
said another.
</P>
<P>
   The test follows two previous tests attempts to intercept a
target, part of a series of nineteen planned tests.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, the Pentagon hailed its first intercept test as a
complete success, but later acknowledged that the kill vehicle
initially had drifted off course and picked out the large bright
decoy balloon instead of the mock warhead.
</P>
<P>
   In the next and more complicated test in January, the kill
vehicle missed the mock warhead by between 300 to 400 feet after a
cooling line clogged and shut its heat-seeking sensors. ``There was
an ice cube in one of the lines,'' a Pentagon official explained.
``We fixed that problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the last test, this time a communications system was
added that transmits information directly to the kill vehicle about
the location of the target after it has lifted off. Called a
global-positioning-system transmitter, it used the same technology
that helps motorists from getting lost.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say that the new test is a misleading guide because it
is taking place under conditions that do not reflect a real attack.
They say that the decoy is not a true decoy, but is more like a
lure that attracts the kill vehicle to the real target, and that an
adversary would use many decoys, not one. About three to four weeks
after the test, Secretary of Defense William Cohen is to give
Clinton a formal recommendation of whether it is feasible to build
the system. Even if the test is a failure, he may recommend that
the plan proceed.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is expected to decide this fall whether to push the
United States down the road to a national missile defense system by
starting construction of a radar in the Aleutian Islands.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Administration lawyers have advised Clinton that, in their view,
he could begin building this first phase of the missile defense
without violating the 1972 AntiBallistic Missile Treaty with
Russia, one of the cornerstones of arms control agreements between
Washington and Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   But the administration has been hit by a storm of criticism from
prominent scientists, arms control experts, former officials and
the General Accounting Office over the cost, technology and effect
on relations with other countries.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Korb of the Council on Foreign Relations called the
entire system a ``shield of dreams'' whose supporters believe that
``if you build it, it will work.''
</P>
<P>
   Even within the administration, a debate is raging among
intelligence and Pentagon officials and policy analysts over the
nature and extent of the potential threat from countries like North
Korea, Iran and Iraq that is the official justification for
building a missile shield. Some senior Pentagon officials have
warned that the administration's schedule is much too accelerated
and therefore risky, because testing would continue even as
construction has begun.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to stop the test, Greenpeace, the anti-nuclear
organization, said that a small team of missile defense opponents
entered the grounds of Vandenberg Air Force Base on foot. Equipped
with survival gear and supplies for several days, they intended to
stay inside the area as long as they could, according to a
Greenpeace statement.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Dutch vessel Arctic Sunrise threatened to enter
one of the hazard zones designated by the Pentagon in the shores
off Vandenberg.
</P>
<P>
   An unidentified man was caught entering the base, but base
spokesman John Cherry said that there was no evidence of intruders
in the heavily-guarded area around the launch pad.
</P>
<P>
   At a news briefing in Washington, a group of business leaders
and scientists weighed in with eleventh-hour criticism of both the
test and the entire plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stop this insensate and tortuously rationalized arms race that
drains money away from our vital civilian programs,'' said Alan
Kligerman, the chief executive officer of Akpharma Inc., and a
board member of Business Leaders for Sensible Priorities, which
seeks to cut military spending. He added, ``If I would represent my
products and sell them with the same shortcomings in the products
as regard to what they are supposed to do, I would be indicted. My
products would be seized'' by the Food and Drug Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Blair, president of the Center for Defense Information,
argued at the same briefing that the development of a national
missile defense is justifiably seen by Russia as a threat to its
nuclear deterrent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia today can barely cope with U.S. offensive power, let
alone a combination of offense and defense, a one-two punch that
could deliver the knockout blow to their strategic forces,'' Blair
said.
</P>
<P>
   Russia and China are adamantly opposed to aU.S. missile defense
because they consider it a threat to their ability to defend
themselves. European countries are also distressed that the United
States would take such a position without regard to Europe's
security.
</P>
</TEXT>
