<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 01:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6428 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r n BC-QUACKENBUSH-AIDE-SFCH     07-08 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUACKENBUSH-AIDE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 EX-AIDE SAYS QUACKENBUSH OK'd MOVES  &HT;     By LYNDA GLEDHILL 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ A former top aide to Chuck Quackenbush says the
insurance commissioner was fully involved in the decision to use
settlement funds for political advertising, his lawyer said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   George Grays, who resigned from the department earlier this
year, is prepared to tell investigators that such deals were
routinely discussed in executive staff meetings, said William
Portanova, one of Grays' criminal defense attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   Grays' testimony could be crucial to investigators in
determining what role, if any, Quackenbush played in coercing
insurance companies to pay money into foundations in lieu of paying
fines, and then funneling the money to political events for the
commissioner. So far, investigators have not named Quackenbush as
the focus of a criminal probe.
</P>
<P>
   But Grays, who invoked his Fifth Amendment privilege before the
investigating legislative committee and has been named by the
attorney general's office as the person who directed the
foundation's operations, has some serious credibility problems.
Among other things, he has been accused of forging foundation
checks and taking $90,000 in kickbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's done something criminal it makes him useless as a
witness,'' said one attorney familiar with the case. ``He doesn't
get any more valuable, he gets less valuable.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Grays' account Friday, a spokesman for Attorney
General Bill Lockyer said a criminal investigation is continuing
and there has been no deal with the former Quackenbush aide.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; `Mistakes' Acknowledged
</P>
<P>
   Without discussing specifics, Portanova acknowledged Friday that
Grays' ``mistakes'' make skepticism justifiable, but said others
have said similar things.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who is more credible, the person who made the mistake and
denied it or the person who made a mistake and is trying to tell
the truth?'' he said. ``What he is saying is consistent with
others.''
</P>
<P>
   Quackenbush resigned last week to avoid almost certain
impeachment by the Legislature. Lawmakers were investigating
Quackenbush's creation and use of a nonprofit foundation financed
by his department's settlements with insurance companies after the
deadly Northridge earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   His resignation came after he learned that two of his top
deputies were prepared to confirm that they heard Quackenbush say
he ``needed $4 million for a media buy.''
</P>
<P>
   Portanova said there were similar exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Grays is prepared to testify that the linking of the
insurance settlement contributions to the insurance commissioner's
foundations with the purchasing of media buys was well-known and
openly discussed at executive staff meetings at which the
commissioner was present,'' said Portanova.
</P>
<P>
   Quackenbush has denied any wrongdoing, and his lawyer said
Friday that Grays is not telling the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's gotten caught with his hand in the cookie jar, and now
he's trying to extricate himself by putting the spin of criminal
behavior on what has happened,'' said Donald Heller, Quackenbush's
attorney. ``He's trying to say things to extricate himself that are
false.''
</P>
<P>
   Heller said that the foundations were established but that the
goal was outreach.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were never designed for purpose of benefiting Chuck
Quackenbush politically,'' he said, adding that Portanova's
decision to describe Grays' story to the media without first
reaching a deal with prosecutors is ``reprehensible.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockyer's probe has focused on what the foundations did with the
money. One legal issue still unresolved is whether the department
had the authority to create the foundations in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   An opinion by the legislative counsel has said no, but lawyers
for the department have insisted that they do. An opinion on that
matter by Lockyer's office is still pending.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general has gone to court and has effectively shut
down the foundation. The remaining $6 million has been frozen by a
judge, pending the outcome of a lawsuit filed by two taxpayers who
want the money returned to the state's general fund.
</P>
<P>
   If Quackenbush is found to have been part of a conspiracy to
divert money from the foundation's stated purpose, there is
potential criminal activity, said Joe Remsho, a San Francisco
attorney who is not involved in the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a crime if a group of people conspire to divert funds,''
he said. ``It is not just the person who signs the check _ it can
be the criminal intent,'' he said. ``The problem always is in
proving that.''
</P>
<P>
   Also Friday, Acting Deputy Insurance Commissioner Clark Kelso
accepted the resignation of Deputy Commissioner Dan Edwards. The
move came a day after six other top staff members in the department
resigned.
</P>
<P>
   Kelso is a law professor who has been tapped to run the
department until Gov. Gray Davis can name Quackenbush's successor.
Kelso also appointed Elaine Bush, the former director of the
Department of Alcohol and Drug Programs, as his chief deputy.
</P>
</TEXT>
