<HEADER>
A6429 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-BORDERAIR-AZR &LR;      07-08 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERAIR-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-BORDERAIR-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    MERCY FLIGHTS ALONG BORDER(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By PAT FLANNERY(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) - The U.S. Border Patrol is borrowing airplanes to fly
extra missions of mercy along Arizona's remote frontier as the
death toll rises among illegal border crossers.
</P>
<P>
   The Tucson sector, which includes most of Arizona's border with
Mexico, has been this year's hot spot for immigrants in distress,
the Border Patrol said. The numbers tell the story: 844 people
rescued and 52 dead since October.
</P>
<P>
   Three out of five rescues on the nation's Southwestern border
have taken place in the region. The number of deaths so far this
fiscal year is nearly twice that of last year's.
</P>
<P>
   The Border Patrol announced Friday that seven planes from Texas,
California and Washington are reassigned to Arizona's southern
deserts for 90 days, nearly doubling the number of aircraft
available to patrol during the hottest months.
</P>
<P>
   Putting more eyes in the sky improves the agency's chances of
finding and helping immigrants flogged by the desert elements,
Border Patrol spokesman Rob Daniels said. They may also discourage
some crossers from even attempting the trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it's an enforcement tool as well,'' Daniels said.
</P>
<P>
   Stepped-up enforcement is partly to blame for the rising death
toll. More agents are patrolling populated border communities,
pushing undocumented immigrants into rugged, isolated corridors
where they are easier to spot and catch {ndash} and where they also
are more vulnerable to the elements.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights activists say pressure is building to abandon the
tactic because of the human toll.
</P>
<P>
   Mountain cold has claimed lives along California's border, while
heat and cold both have been deadly in Arizona's deserts this year.
</P>
<P>
   In one particularly gripping case in May, a 19-year-old Mexican
mother died under a paloverde on the Tohono O'odham Reservation
west of Tucson after giving her 18-month-old infant her last sip of
water. The child survived.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that any effort by an organization to prevent people
from dying in the desert is a good thing,'' Guadalupe Castillo of
Derechos Humanos, a Tucson immigrant rights group, said after
hearing of the new air patrols.
</P>
<P>
   But Castillo added, ``Until their (immigration) strategy is
terminated, we will continue to see deaths in the deserts of
Arizona, the mountains of California and the rivers of Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona rescues are most common in the arid plains and mountains
from the Tohono O'odham Reservation to the mountains east of Yuma,
and in a narrow desert corridor stretching from the mountains east
of Nogales nearly to Douglas.
</P>
<P>
   Immigrants often cross with little or no water or food, and
without proper clothing for the elements.
(beginitalic)Coyotes(enditalic), the smugglers they pay to lead
them across the border, sometimes abandon their charges in the
middle of nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   Two airplanes and seven helicopters already patrol the Tucson
sector using special technology to scour the desert for people- and
drug-smuggling activities day and night. In the first half of the
fiscal year, the Tucson air wing helped stop more than 23,000
border crossers and $11.1million in narcotics.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the undocumented immigrants who are rescued are detained
for processing and immediate return to Mexico or deportation to
their country of origin. Those who need it are given food and
water.
</P>
<P>
   Although more people are likely to be stopped with the new air
support, Daniels hopes to disarm critics by focusing on the
agency's humanitarian concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Could you imagine if we ignored this?'' Daniels said. ``We are
being compassionate. These guys are putting themselves at risk to
help these folks.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach the reporter at Pat.Flannery(a)ArizonaRepublic.com or
(602) 444-8629
</P>
