<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUALYE-OBIT-AZR </SLUG>
  
James Quayle, father of former Vice President Dan Quayle and
one-time owner of the weekly (beginitalic)Wickenburg
Sun(enditalic), died Friday in a Sun City West nursing center. He
was 79.QUAYLENewsman dies at 79
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUAYLENewsman
</P>
<P>
   James
</P>
<P>
   Quayle
</P>
<P>
   dies at 79
</P>
<P>
   James Quayle, father of former Vice President Dan Quayle and
one-time owner of the weekly (beginitalic)Wickenburg
Sun(enditalic), died Friday in a Sun City West nursing center. He
was 79.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of death was not known, but he had been in ill health
for some time.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle, a big, bluff ex-Marine whose conservative beliefs
influenced those of his politician son, had lived in Wickenburg
with his wife, Corinne, at least part of the year since the late
1970s, when he bought the (beginitalic)Wickenburg Sun.
(enditalic)In recent years, they were full-time residents. In 1987,
he sold the newspaper to his son, Michael, who sold it again three
years later.
</P>
<P>
   Among other community activities in Arizona, James Quayle was a
member of the Thunderbirds public-service organization.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle, who belonged to the ultraconservative John Birch Society
in the 1960s, spent most of his adult life as a small-town
newspaper publisher.
</P>
<P>
   He was not shy about expressing his politics. At his death, he
was chairman of the board of Huntington Newspapers Inc., owner of
the (beginitalic)Huntington (Ind.) Herald-Press(enditalic), which,
in the days when he actively ran the paper, was known in some
Democratic circles as the ``Herald-Suppress'' because of his
disinclination to publish stories favorable to his political
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Though some people were put off by his views, they found him
charming personally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim was a very gregarious, very likable individual, as
conservative as the day was long,'' said Mike Dooley, a columnist
for the (beginitalic)Fort Wayne (Ind.) News-Sentinel (enditalic)who
at one time worked as a reporter for one of Quayle's newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Shover, former public affairs director for (beginitalic)The
Arizona Republic(enditalic), seconded that view.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim was a very affable, fun-loving man who enjoyed life to the
fullest,'' Shover said.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle's irrepressible personality got the best of him during
his son Dan's 1988 campaign for the vice presidency. The elder
Quayle was quoted by the (beginitalic)New York Daily News
(enditalic)as saying Dan's main interests in school had been
``broads and booze.'' Later, James said he had been misquoted. ``I
said, `If he's anything like his old man, it was probably broads
and booze,''' the father said. ``He (Dan) isn't that kind of guy.''
</P>
<P>
   James Cline Quayle was born May 25, 1921, in Joliet, Ill. As a
youth, he worked for his family's business, the Chicago Dowel Co.,
making the famous Lincoln Log toys.
</P>
<P>
   He attended DePauw University in Indiana, where he met and
married Corinne Pulliam, the daughter of newspaper magnate Eugene
C. Pulliam, who founded Central Newspapers Inc., which recently
sold (beginitalic)The Arizona Republic(enditalic) to Gannett Co.
Inc.
</P>
<P>
   From 1943 to 1945, Quayle served in the Marine Corps, seeing
combat in the Pacific Theater of World WarII as an air transport
crewman. He later named his politician son James Danforth Quayle
after a serviceman and friend, James Danforth, who was killed in
the war.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, Quayle began a long career in the newspaper
business. He worked in advertising sales for the
(beginitalic)Lebanon (Ind.) Reporter (enditalic)and the
(beginitalic)Portsmouth (Ohio) Times(enditalic), then was
advertising manager from 1948 to 1955 at the
(beginitalic)Huntington Herald-Press (enditalic)in Huntington, Ind.
He then moved his family to Arizona and worked from 1955 to 1963 as
public relations and personnel director for (beginitalic)The
Arizona Republic (enditalic)and (beginitalic)The Phoenix
Gazette(enditalic).
</P>
<P>
   In 1963, he returned to the Huntington paper as publisher, and
he and his wife bought it the following year. In addition to his
role at the (beginitalic)Huntington Herald-Press(enditalic), he
also was publisher of the (beginitalic)Muncie (Ind.) Star and
Evening Press (enditalic)from 1972 to 1979.
</P>
<P>
   At one time, he served on the board of Central Newspapers Inc.,
stepping down in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle is survived by his wife; sons James Danforth of Paradise
Valley, Michael of Vincennes, Ind., and Christopher of Phoenix;
daughter Martha and several grandchildren.James Quayle was the
father of former Vice President Dan Quayle and one-time owner of
the  &UR; (beginitalic)Wickenburg Sun(enditalic)(beginitalic).
</P>
<P>
   (enditalic)
</P>
</TEXT>
