<HEADLINE>
ORTIZ GETS PLENTY OF SUPPORT AS ANGELS WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- Ramon Ortiz returned to a big league mound Friday
night for the first time in nearly two months, and his Angels
teammates welcomed him back in a way only a pitcher can appreciate.
</P>
<P>
   With home run, after home run, after home run in a 12-4 victory
over the Colorado Rockies before 29,826 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   The three home runs were not the most the Angels have hit in a
game this season, but these were bombs. Bengie Molina hit a grand
slam, and Troy Glaus hit two home runs, including a three-run homer
that was estimated at 465 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Glaus now has 25 home runs this season, matching the most ever
by an Angel before the All-Star break (Leon Wagner had 25 at the
break in 1962). He also seemed to bang his way out of a slump that
had him 1 for 29 going into the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels had 13 hits in all, including three by Mo Vaughn and
two each by Darin Erstad, Kevin Stocker and Glaus.
</P>
<P>
   While all the offense certainly was pleasing to the Angels,
offense has not been a problem. The problem has been keeping five
starters healthy and productive. Ortiz got his opportunity Friday
because Tim Belcher returned to the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz was sent to Triple-A Edmonton on May 10 after struggling
in six starts with the Angels (2-2, 6.90 ERA). He was told to work
on his command and let his pitches work for him by not
overthrowing.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, it was time well-spent.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz pitched hit best game of the season, going eight innings
and giving up three runs and five hits. He hit 96 mph on the radar
gun while striking out Mike Lansing in the first inning, and 93 mph
as late as the eighth inning. But it was more than velocity that
made Ortiz better.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz (3-2) seemed to have more confidence in himself,
challenging hitters and letting the defense make plays behind him.
He walked only two and hit a batter.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies took a 1-0 lead in the first after Tom Goodwin
tripled and scored on a groundout by Todd Helton. But they trailed,
4-1, by the time they scored again. In the fifth a double by Brent
Mayne and a triple by Neifi Perez led to two runs to cut their
deficit to 4-3, but that was as close as the Rockies would get.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels pecked and nibbled in the early innings, scoring once
in the first and second innings and twice in the third. Stocker was
thrown out at home in the fourth, trying to score from first on a
double by Erstad.
</P>
<P>
   But the Angels broke the game open in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   It started with a walk by Scott Spiezio, followed by a single by
Vaughn. After Tim Salmon lined out, the key play of the inning came
with Garret Anderson at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson hit a grounder up the middle that barely scooted under
the glove of pitcher Kevin Jarvis (2-4). Had Jarvis fielded the
ball, it probably would have been an inning-ending double play.
Instead, the ball rolled into center field, scoring Spiezio and
sending Vaughn to second.
</P>
<P>
   Glaus followed with a walk to load the bases, and that was it
for Jarvis. Lefty Scott Karl entered the game, but Molina slugged
his first pitch over the fence in left field for his first career
grand slam.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels added three more runs in the sixth on Glaus'
three-run homer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
