<HEADLINE>
L.A. BUSINESSES FEAR RUIN FROM DEMOCRATIC CONVENTION PROTESTERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 &HT;    By ERIK NELSON  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Despite assurances Friday from police and city
officials, downtown Los Angeles business owners said they cannot
rely on police to protect them from protesters who threaten to
target the area during the Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Still reeling from the riotous Lakers' championship riot that
caused as much as $750,000 in damage, business owners said they are
planning to work together and may hire private security.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we feel safer now? No. Not at all,'' said an irate Jason
Kim, sales manager of Pico Store Equipment and one of 50 business
owners, residents and officials who attended the closed-door
meeting at Patriotic Hall downtown.
</P>
<P>
   During the meeting, police, convention planners and city
officials mapped out a strategy to protect lives and property, but
business owners said they were not impressed _ and were frustrated
by a lack of detail.
</P>
<P>
   A k1%ce Cmdr. David Kalish said police have tried to provide as
much information as possible about their plans, but ``obviously the
department must be sensitive to what type of information can be
released so that confidential information is not provided.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly understand their apprehension,'' Kalish said.
``However, the Police Department is absolutely committed to
protecting the people and property of this city.''
</P>
<P>
   Protest organizers have threatened to flood downtown streets
with as many as 50,000 demonstrators who will target banks and
corporate offices, including the World Trade Center at Figueroa and
Third streets.
</P>
<P>
   The department plans to deploy about 2,000 officers on the
street each day of the convention, which runs Aug. 14-17. Other law
enforcement agencies, including the Los Angeles County Sheriff's
Department and the California Highway Patrol, also will be on alert
to send more officers if needed, Kalish said.
</P>
<P>
   During the Lakers riot, Kim's store sustained $30,000 in damage
after looters smashed windows, stole cash and made off with
mannequins. Now, store managers are contemplating equipping their
store windows with a transparent covering that renders glass
unbreakable.
</P>
<P>
   His mood was reflected by other business owners who attended the
meeting, which was organized by the Figueroa Corridor Partnership,
a coalition of businesses along Figueroa and Flower streets. The
area was hardest hit by Lakers riot looters and vandals.
</P>
<P>
   Ishai Jesse Hizami, who owns the Kentucky Fried Chicken
restaurant at 3850 S. Figueroa, harkened back to the 1965 Watts
riot and the 1992 riot after the acquittal of four Los Angeles
Police officers accused of beating African-American motorist Rodney
King. Hizami, too, said he was unimpressed with the official
response to damage caused by mobs after last month's championship
game and parade.
</P>
<P>
   ``They take the broom, they lift the carpet, tho weepj$(R9I1::B
</P>
