<HEADLINE>
WNBA ROOKIE ADJUSTS TO PRO LIFE, BUT MISSES MOM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DARRIN SCHEID 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Lynn Pride said the toughest part of professional
basketball is not trying to guard players such as Sheryl Swoopes.
</P>
<P>
   Or get playing time.
</P>
<P>
   It's not even that Portland, an expansion franchise, is stuck in
seventh place. All those things have to do with basketball, Pride's
comfort zone during her playing career at Sam Houston High School
in Arlington, Texas, and the University of Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   The hard part is that Pride and her mom, Charla Pride-Lofton,
haven't seen each other since Senior Night at Kansas in March. The
normal two or three phone calls per day have often been replaced by
a quick ``hello,'' from a hotel room in various cities. For Pride,
21, adjusting to the real world _ getting a first job, moving into
an apartment, the constant travel and missing her mom _ is proving
the toughest adjustment of all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still wish I could see my mom every day, but I guess it's
all part of growing up,'' Lynn Pride said during a road trip
through Houston. ``I think we've both been doing a pretty good job
of handling it. This is the hardest part, all the travel.''
</P>
<P>
   Back home in Garland, Pride-Lofton keeps up with her daughter's
progress by watching television and checking the WNBA box scores
after each game. Before the season started, Pride-Lofton ordered
the special WNBA television package. So far, she's not happy with
what she receives.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems the Portland games are never on,'' she said. ``Every
day, it's Houston or Los Angeles or somebody else.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what happens when your daughter's team is 4-13.
</P>
<P>
   Pride, a 6-foot-2 forward and three-time All-Big 12 pick at
Kansas, was the seventh overall pick by the Fire in this year's
draft. After getting selected, she didn't even have enough time to
clean out her dorm room before heading to Portland. Pride-Lofton
and Lynn's stepfather, Lonnie Lofton, drove to Kansas and hauled
her stuff back to Garland.
</P>
<P>
   Portland coach Linda Hargrove said the team chose Pride on
potential, hoping her resume in the WNBA will someday resemble what
it did at Kansas. Pride improved each season for the Jayhawks,
finishing her career with a 17.4 scoring and 7.9 rebounding
average.
</P>
<P>
   For the Fire, Pride is averaging 3.8 points per game and 14.9
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Although the results confirm that Pride has a long way to go to
reach stardom, Kansas coach Marian Washington said it might by only
a season or two away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she's learning and she's toughening it out,''
Washington said. ``Lynn is the type of person who responds to a lot
of encouragement, and I think she needs a confidence boost. That
will come as she learns more and gets more used to the league. She
has the type of personality that will make her successful because
she's able to see the whole picture.''
</P>
<P>
   Pride's playing time is less than second-round pick and former
Michigan forward Stacey Thomas. That's hard for a parent to
understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time she messes up, they take her right back out of the
game,'' Pride-Lofton said. ``How can she perform if she's scared? I
just tell her, `Get on out there!qnd work hard bEcY].Y
Qt'.HV+Kk$oR,59:JE
</P>
