<SLUG> BC-BBO-RANGERS-PADRES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEGUI'S BASES-LOADED SINGLE IN 10TH LIFTS RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ David Segui's bases-loaded single in the
bottom of the 10th inning off reliever Matt Whiteside scored Luis
Alicea with the winning run and gave the Texas Rangers a 5-4
victory over the San Diego Padres at The Ballpark in Arlington on
Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Catalanotto, pinch hitting for shortstop Kelly Dransfeldt,
started the game-winning rally with a double to deep center, and
Luis Alicea drew a walk. Rusty Greer followed with a grounder up
the middle, and Padres second baseman Bret Boone made a terrific
diving stop. But shortstop Kevin Nicholson dropped the flip as he
tried to turn the double play, and Alicea slid in safely, loading
the bases.
</P>
<P>
   Scarborough Green, who entered the game as a pinch runner for
Rafael Palmeiro in the eighth inning, then tried to surprise the
Padres with a bunt. But third baseman Phil Nevin jumped on it and
forced Catalanotto at home.
</P>
<P>
   Whiteside then got Ivan Rodriguez to pop out, but Segui grounded
a single through the right side to win it. The victory gives the
Rangers a four-game winning streak, and it was their first victory
in five extra-inning games this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like this win,'' Alicea said. ``This was a good win. We've
won four in a row now. Hopefully, we'll win two more before the
All-Star break and be flying into the second half.''
</P>
<P>
   Doug Davis, on an exhausting night for the Rangers bullpen, got
the victory with a 1-2-3 inning in the top of the 10th.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of guys out there who came through with one
or two big plays that kept us in the ballgame,'' manager Johnny
Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Ivan Rodriguez provided the Rangers with their first four runs
with a first-inning grand slam, the second of his career and the
second this season by a Ranger. Alicea started the inning with a
single off Padres starter Woody Williams, who then walked Greer and
gave up another single to Rafael Palmeiro.
</P>
<P>
   All of that, plus a double by Segui, came with nobody out, and
it appeared Williams would be finished early. But suddenly he found
himself and found a way to get the Rangers out, holding them
scoreless on two hits over 7 1/3 innings. It was only Williams'
second start after missing two months because of surgery needed to
remove an aneurysm in his right armpit.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers starter Matt Perisho lasted 5 1/3 innings, allowing two
runs on three hits, including a two-run homer to Boone in the
fourth. He also walked four and threw 111 pitches, which forced
Oates to go to the bullpen quicker than he had hoped.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers were ahead 4-2 when Perisho left, but the Padres
tied it with a run off Jeff Zimmerman in the seventh and one off
Tim Crabtree in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman, who found out earlier in the day his father had died,
struck out four in his 1 2/3 innings of work, which suggested he
brought his best stuff to the mound. But he walked Eric Owens with
one out in the seventh and that cost him. Zimmerman struck out
Ruben Rivera, but Owens stole second on the third strike, then
scored on Ryan Klesko's bloop single into center field.
</P>
<P>
   Crabtree got himself into trouble with one out in the eighth
when he hit Wiki Gonzalez with a 1-0 pitch and then walked Dave
Magadan, who was in a 2-for-33 slump. Crabtree got Damien Jackson
on a liner to left, but Nicholson grounded a single through the
middle to score Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland's ninth inning was just as adventurous, beginning with
a leadoff walk to Rivera. Ryan Klesko forced Rivera with a grounder
to shortstop before Nevin singled to left, putting runners at first
and second.
</P>
<P>
   Boone followed with a sharp grounder up the middle. Wetteland
knocked it down with his barehand, scrambled quickly to recover,
then threw high to third base. But Mike Lamb reached high to grab
the throw, then reached back and got the tag on Klesko for the out.
Wetteland then got out of the inning when shortstop Dransfeldt made
a nice play on Gonzalez's high chopper.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
