<SLUG> BC-CAR-IRWIN-CRASH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENNY IRWIN JR. DIES IN CRASH AT NEW HAMPSHIRE TRACK
</HEADLINE>
nt06 NU5 &AMP;Xz3 
rsbx (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kenny Irwin Jr., who credited his NASCAR Craftsman Truck victory
at Texas Motor Speedway in June 1997 with helping him land a
Winston Cup ride, was killed Friday in a crash while practicing at
New Hampshire International Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin, 30, died of ``multiple injuries'' after his car slammed
into a wall at 150 mph while entering Turn 3 of the 1.058-mile oval
in Loudon, N.H. Irwin crashed at almost the same spot where
19-year-old Adam Petty was killed while practicing for a NASCAR
Busch Grand National race on May 12.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin, the 1998 Winston Cup Rookie of the Year, was entering the
third turn when his car struck the wall and flipped onto its roof
during practice for Sunday's New England 300, a Winston Cup race.
The upper part of his body was covered with blood, and he appeared
lifeless when removed from the car.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Dearborn, Concord Hospital spokeswoman, reported that
Irwin died of multiple injuries but offered no other details.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation centered on a stuck accelerator that would have
prohibited Irwin from slowing enough to complete the turn. That
also was believed to have been the reason for Petty's crash,
although NASCAR has been unable to verify the cause.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin was three races into his rookie Craftsman Truck Series
career when he won at the Homestead-Miami Speedway in Florida in
March 1997. Three months later, Irwin won the inaugural Pronto Auto
Parts 400K under the lights at TMS. That victory marked Irwin as a
bona fide Craftsman Truck Rookie of the Year candidate, and boosted
his stock in the Winston Cup garage.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1997, team owner Robert Yates introduced Irwin, a
native of Indianapolis, as driver of the No. 28 Texaco Havoline
Ford during a news conference at the Indianapolis Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``That win (at TMS) helped a tremendous amount,'' Irwin said at
TMS in April 1998. ``To the Winston Cup car owners, this (TMS) was
probably the most controversial track on the circuit (in 1997). So
when we were able to come in here and run good and win the race, it
showed that I had what it took to run Winston Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still had to do the calling to Robert Yates. This just
helped to get him on the phone.''
</P>
<P>
   Irwin recorded the second of his three career Winston Cup poles
at TMS in Fort Worth on March 26, 1999, when he toured the 1.5-mile
quadoval at 190.154 mph. It was the track Cup record until broken
by Texan Terry Labonte in March.
</P>
<P>
   Despite early comparisons to three-time Cup champion Jeff
Gordon, Irwin's Cup career never took off with Yates, who fired him
after the 1999 season. Irwin signed with flamboyant team owner
Felix Sabates and Sabco Racing. He stood 28th in the standings
after 17 races with only one top-five and one top-10 finish. Irwin
was winless in 87 career Cup starts.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Petty, Adam's grandfather, said it was a coincidence
that two drivers were kil,jb$zpvwBo\59q at 15 &QC; M!Bn! 2HHspot at the
New Hampshire track.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those things are circumstances beyond human control,'' said
Petty, the king of stock car racing with a record 200 victories and
seven championships. ``There ain't nothing the matter with the
racetrack.''
</P>
<P>
   But other drivers were quick to criticize the track, which
features corners banked at a relatively flat 12 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Pole-sitter Rusty Wallace said there is a bump at the end of the
long backstretch, where cars reach about 150 mph, and that most
drivers are prepared for it. Wallace also said dirt and rubber
buildup on the asphalt surface make the oval among the slickest on
the circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Martin said the track's design left little margin for
error.
</P>
<P>
   ``This racetrack and Martinsville are a particular danger to
stuck throttles because the corners are so sharp,'' Martin said.
``At a lot of the bigger racetracks with sweeping corners, you have
a chance to do something about stuck throttles.''
</P>
<P>
   Ward Burton, visibly upset after visiting Irwin in the infield
care center before his friend was taken to the hospital, said he
would like to see the almost-flat turns banked higher in view of
the deaths.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two's a problem,'' Burton said. ``I think it needs to be
addressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Geof.~hO2ine, who survived a parts-spewing crash during a
Craftsman Truck race at the Daytona International Speedway in
February, said the deaths of Petty and Irwin had left him feeling
numb.
</P>
<P>
   ``My body is shaking it's so numb, knowing what happened here,''
Bodine said. ``We have to cope with it. Everyone has to. When we
climb in these windows,  &LR; XICknow &QC; 5Q!%9
</P>
