<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVERICKS PROMISE NO REPEAT OF SMITH FIASCO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ARTHUR GARCIA 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ To the outsider, Mark Cuban's spending habits may seem
a bit wacky.
</P>
<P>
   He bought the Dallas Mavericks for an NBA-record $280 million in
April. He bought a $42 million executive jet _ on the Internet.
Friday, he basically bought a person, paying $125,000 to have a
local sports radio personality _ KTCK//1310 AM's Gordon Keith _
change his name to Dallasmaverick (one word) for one year.
</P>
<P>
   But even if Cuban's habits seem unorthodox, he finds value in
each buy.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, the investment Cuban made in the players selected
in last week's NBA Draft isn't taken lightly. Cuban and the
Mavericks coaching staff did their homework on Etan Thomas,
Courtney Alexander, Donnell Harvey and Eduardo Najera. But the
risk, for Cuban, doesn't end with pre-draft background checks. The
Mavs suffered from the Leon Smith fiasco last summer _ before Cuban
arrived _ and the rookie owner has set up a system to hopefully
avoid similar scenarios.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plan is to put together very specific programs for the
players and (assistant coach) Kiki (Vandeweghe) is going to
coordinate and develop all of that,'' Cuban said. ``Everything from
media training, to nutrition, to eating, to strength and
conditioning. Things that they may not pay as close attention to as
you or I.''
</P>
<P>
   Out of the current rookie class, Harvey has been slated to do
individual work with Vandeweghe. Harvey, 19, played only[ just] a
season at Florida and though he remembers the Smith situation,
Harvey said his circumstance is different.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read what happened but this isn't the same,'' said Harvey,
drafted 22nd in the first round by New York before being traded.
``I feel like I an ready to play in the NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, drafted at the end of the first round by San Antonio and
traded to the Mavs, had a much-publicized falling out with
assistant coach Donnie Nelson at minicamp last summer. Smith's
emotional problems, which included a suicide attempt, led to his
eventual negotiated release from the Mavericks, who were criticized
for their handling of the rookie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than having him learn on the job, like we've all had to
do in various jobs, it sort of gets him in a corporate-training
introduction program,'' Cuban said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Nelson: ``The NBA is such a mental game. These young kids
just don't know those elements that go into our sport and are
really taken aback when they're first exposed to them. With Harvey,
it's no different. He seemed to pick things up pretty quickly out
there, but he's a young man. Guys like him, it generally takes a
little bit longer.''
</P>
<P>
   While Harvey's off-the-court skills are polished, it's his play
on the hardwood that has the Mavs optimistic about his future.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be quite honest, Donnell plays like a man,'' Alexander
said. ``I think Donnell, in that respect, will be fine. Obviously
he has a lot of growing to do, he has a lot of learning to do, but
he doesn't fear too much. I'm just hoping he can carry over what he
did in college to help our team.'' BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ The NBA fined the Mavericks and Milwaukee Bucks $50,000 each
Friday for violating league rules that prohibit teams from having
more than four draft-eligible players competing on the court at the
same time during workouts and from having those players compete
against veteran NBA players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought the fine was a bit heavy,'' Cuban said. ``If we did
something, we'll go ahead and pay it. I just want to make sure they
weren't picking on us.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuban said the team had some five-on-five scrimmages when draft
eligible players were in town and suspects that was what the
violation was, although he hadn't received details from the league.
</P>
<P>
   _ Draft picks Etan Thomas and Eduardo Najera signed contracts
Friday, leaving Donnell Harvey as the only unsigned rookie.
Courtney Alexander signed on Thursday. Thomas' deal, the maximum
for the 12th pick of the draft, is for three years at $4,479,128,
with club options for a fourth and fifth season. Najera, who
arrived from Mexico for minicamp Friday on a tourist visa, signed a
two-year deal starting at just over $300,000 for next season.
</P>
<P>
   _ Summer-camp signee Gheorghe Muresan arrived Friday and he's
expected at Saturday's afternoon practice.
</P>
<P>
   _ Free-agent center Bruno Sundov said his sprained left ankle
will probably keep him off the court two more weeks. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
