<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS LEARNED LOYALTY AT CAROLINA, APPLIED IT AT KANSAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Roy Williams has made the toughest decision that a college coach
ever faced. Williams stayed at Kansas on Thursday, choosing loyalty
to his players over the lure of what everyone thought was his dream
job.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely has a coach had to choose between two high profile jobs
such as North Carolina and Kansas. The Tar Heels are second on the
NCAA's victory list; the Jayhawks are third. Only at Kentucky is
the basketball blood as blue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision that I've made came after the toughest seven days
of my life,'' Williams said Thursday night. ``That's quite a
statement because that also means that I'm the luckiest basketball
coach to ever live. I had the options that I had from two
universities and basketball programs that I love.''
</P>
<P>
   Coaches rarely make lateral moves. The goal is to move up the
ladder. Gene Bartow went from Illinois to UCLA, Jim Harrick from
Pepperdine to UCLA. Tubby Smith went from Tulsa to Georgia to
Kentucky. Rick Pitino went from Kentucky to the Boston Celtics.
Mike Krzyzewski went from Army to Duke. Bob Knight went from Army
to Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   When North Carolina coach Bill Guthridge made his surprise
resignation announcement last week, it all seemed so simple. Media
speculators figured that Guthridge had gone to Dean Smith, the
North Carolina Godfather, and told him the news. Smith then called
the Chosen One, Williams, to make sure the Tar Heels had a
successor in place.
</P>
<P>
   But done deals become done deals only when they're done. There
was intense pressure to get the story _ two North Carolina papers
reported that Williams had agreed to change jobs _ but this was a
one-man decision. Only Roy Williams knew what Roy Williams was
going to do.
</P>
<P>
   For Williams, choosing between Kansas and North Carolina was a
gut-wrenching decision. By remaining at Kansas, he will continue to
coach a program that he has lifted to its greatest heights and
consistency. By moving home to North Carolina, he would have been
working in the shadow of Smith's legacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now he's the Dean Smith of Kansas,'' former Kansas guard Ryan
Robertson said. ``You can't predict what he can accomplish over the
next 10, 15 years with the recruits he's going to get now.''
</P>
<P>
   There is an ironic symmetry between Kansas and North Carolina.
Dean Smith was a reserve on Kansas' first national champion in
1952. North Carolina's first national championship was a
triple-overtime defeat of Kansas in 1957. Williams is a North
Carolina native and a Tar Heel alum. The Tar Heels' last two
coaches _ Smith and Guthridge _ are Kansas natives.
</P>
<P>
   And in this Kansas vs. North Carolina battle, the Jayhawks came
out the winner. Williams was the Tar Heels' first choice. Whoever
they hire to replace Guthridge comes from the ``B'' list. The next
time North Carolina loses to Duke, Tar Heels fans will wonder
``Could Williams have done better?'' The next North Carolina coach
will be fighting a legend and a ghost.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' decision goes against the grain. Coaches leave their
teams at the drop of a richer contract. Williams is such a do-good,
dad-gum straight shooter that many people roll their eyes at his
``aw shucks'' attitude. But Williams chose to stay at Kansas using
his gut and his heart. Emotion ruled over logic, devotion won out
over ambition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made the decision based on the most important thing _ my
players,'' Williams said. ``My mentors taught me that loyalty is
the most important thing. And, that was the decision _ I couldn't
leave my players. That became more important than my dream of being
at North Carolina.''
</P>
<P>
   Dean Smith's coaching ability is validated by his Division
I-record 879 victories. His ability as a teacher is demonstrated by
Williams' decision to stay at Kansas. That Williams learned the
lesson so well is unfortunate for North Carolina.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
