<HEADLINE>
GLAVINE MAKES HIMSELF AT HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Braves5Red Sox3
</P>
<P>
   As homecomings go, it was a much better night for Billerica's
Tom Glavine than it was for the Sons of Jimy Williams.
</P>
<P>
   A double rainbow penetrated the dark skies that draped the Fens
Friday night but the thunder generated by Sox bats during a
four-game sweep in Minnesota was muzzled by lefthander Glavine in a
5-3 Atlanta win that quieted a sellout crowd of 33,686 until Braves
reliever John Rocker was summoned for his obligatory razzing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being from here, I expected it to be much like it was in New
York for John,'' said Glavine, who was spotted a 5-0 lead by Sox
lefthander Pete Schourek after two innings, then shut out the Sox
on four singles through seven innings until turning a 5-1 lead over
to Rocker with the bases loaded and one out in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker, who dashed from the bullpen through a gantlet of boos
that was Cordero-esque in its intensity, required no additional
security like that deployed last week upon his return to New York,
according to Sox spokesman Kevin Shea.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crowd wasn't that bad at all,'' said Sox closer Derek
Lowe, who observed the interaction between Rocker and the
right-field bleacherites from the neighboring bullpen. ``I saw him
giving autographs out there. Everything was fine. The loudest the
crowd got was when he was pitching. There wasn't any extra security
or anything.''
</P>
<P>
   What Rocker needed more than another bodyguard was someone to
give him directions to home plate. The lefthanded reliever threw
two quick balls to Ed Sprague, then wound up walking him on a full
count, forcing in the run that made it 5-2.
</P>
<P>
   When he threw ball one to pinch hitter Brian Daubach, Rocker's
night was cut short by manager Bobby Cox, whose intent in bringing
in Kerry Ligtenberg was as obvious as his answer afterward when
asked why he elected to tarry no longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to win the (expletive) game,'' Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   Cox's desired outcome was still in doubt when Daubach, after
fouling off a couple of two-strike pitches, worked Ligtenberg for
another full-count walk to force home a third run. But Jason
Varitek, who had entered the game an inning before as a pinch
hitter for Scott Hatteberg, flied out to end the threat, and after
a two-out single by Jeff Frye in the ninth, Ligtenberg left Nomar
Garciaparra punching the air in frustration after flying out to end
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a chance,'' manager Jimy Williams said after the Sox'
record in interleague play fell to 3-7, 1-3 against the Braves.
``We couldn't get that one more hit to get us back even. (Glavine)
was tough on us all night.''
</P>
<P>
   While Glavine was styling, Schourek was staggered yet again,
disappearing almost as quickly as the rainbows. Schourek lasted
just five outs, ushered out of the game and perhaps the Sox'
starting rotation by a five-run Atlanta rally triggered by Andres
Galarraga's rain-maker of a home run, a high fly ball that just
cleared the left-field screen.
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga's 20th home run of the season came in his first-ever
at-bat in Fenway Park, and should have portended a long night for
the Sox. The Braves are now 17-2 in games in which the
inspirational Galarraga, the 39-year-old first baseman making a
remarkable comeback from cancer, has homered. It was his third home
run in four games against the Sox this season, and fifth in 18
at-bats against the Red Sox in his career.
</P>
<P>
   Schourek, who now has not won in 10 starts dating back nearly
two months (May 15), was soon issuing line drives like tickets to
double-parkers on Boylston Street. Javy Lopez laced a single to
left. Bobby Bonilla, the disgraced ex-Met who has proven to the
Braves he still has a few cards left in his deck, followed with a
double to center, sending Lopez to third, and Reggie Sanders's
ground ball brought home Lopez to make it 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   Schourek was on the verge of escaping trouble when he whiffed
Walt Weiss, but he hit Quilvio Veras in the forearm with a pitch,
then uncorked a wild pitch that allowed both runners to advance
just ahead of Andruw Jones's two-run single through the left side.
When Chipper Jones's liner over the head of Carl Everett ticked off
the center fielder's glove and went for a run-scoring double,
Schourek was done.
</P>
<P>
   The loss dropped his record to 2-8, while his ERA shot to 4.67.
That left Williams fielding as many questions about Schourek's
status as he did two years ago in the playoffs, when he chose the
lefthander to pitch rather than Pedro Martinez on short rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, he's in that spot, yep,'' said Williams, who issued
a similar response when asked if Brian Rose's spot was secure, then
yanked him a day later.
</P>
<P>
   Hatteberg insisted that Schourek's record was not an accurate
barometer of his season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's had some great games where we didn't score any runs for
him at all,'' Hatteberg said. ``But after a game like tonight, I'm
sure people will look at his record and use it against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't have his fastball tonight. He doesn't just baby the
ball in there. He throws 90, 91 (miles per hour) and when he didn't
have that tonight, it makes it a tough game to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Schourek hoped that his wasn't an easy job to lose, even though
the reemergence of Tim Wakefield, the arrival of rookie Paxton
Crawford, and the pending return of Pedro Martinez gives Williams
some options.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't speak for them,'' Schourek said, ``but I would hope
I've thrown well enough and shown enough good games to be able to
contribute in the second half.''
</P>
<P>
   Glavine, meanwhile, has no such worries after shutting down a
team that had cranked out 44 runs on 53 hits and 13 home runs while
sweeping Minnesota. He is now 9-5, and his next scheduled
appearance is in Tuesday's All-Star Game in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd much rather win this game than the All-Star Game,'' said
Glavine, an All-Star seven times, now a winner in Fenway twice
over.
</P>
<P>
   His larger point was that this one counted in the standings,
unlike Tuesday's exhibition. But yes, he acknowledged, ``It's extra
special to win here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-00 0224EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
