<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUMMER-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MADSEN TO MAKE DEBUT AS LAKER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SEAN KEARNS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ The head of new Laker power forward Mark
Madsen is spinning with options.
</P>
<P>
   Read the defense here, the offense there, make a cut. Such are
the intricacies of the triangle offense and Madsen is a new
student, completing his second day of school in the highly complex
offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``The triangle offense has so many different options,'' Madsen
said Friday. ``If I get the ball on the wing there are four or five
different options. What you have to do is read what the defense is
doing and you read your teammates as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Madsen will make his debut as a Laker as well as his debut
running the triangle offense tonight at 7:30 p.m. at the Pyramid as
the Lakers summer league team faces the Portland Trailblazers. The
Summer Pro League begins play today and will run through July 30.
</P>
<P>
   The summer pro league is routinely a place where many current
top NBA players have made their profession debuts - Kobe Bryant
comes to mind.
</P>
<P>
   This year is no different. While the Clippers won't have their
top picks playing in the SPL, other teams do. The highest pick on a
roster is swingman Mike Miller, taken fifth overall by the Orlando
Magic.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas has its three first round picks on its roster - power
forward Etan Thomas (12th overall), shooting guard Courtney
Alexander (13th) and power forward Donnell Harvey (22nd). The
Trailblazers have point guard Erick Barkley (28th) on their roster.
The Seattle Supersonics have swingman Desmond Mason (17th) and
power forward Olumide Oyedeji (42nd) on their.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers have swingman Corey Hightower (54th) and Madsen
(29th) making their debuts today.
</P>
<P>
   Madsen, from Danville, Calif, is no stranger to Long Beach. His
mother Erlyn, went to Millikan High School. Madsen come to Long
Beach to visit his grandfather, Bill Gould, the former president
and CEO of Southern California Edison who resides near Long Beach
State.
</P>
<P>
   The top priority for Madsen during this visit to Long Beach is
to learn the offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my big goals coming out of here is an understanding of
the triangle offense and being more equipped to handle the rules
like illegal defense,'' Madsen said.
</P>
<P>
   Not only has Madsen had his first exposure to the triangle
offense but he's also had his first contact with the Zenmaster
himself, Phil Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about coach Jackson is he really wants to make sure
the team is working together as a team,'' Madsen said. ``He really
wants to blend all the individuals on the floor together.'' So far
Jackson, who has been known to assign books for his players on the
road, hasn't assigned any reading for Madsen. But he has given
Madsen solid NBA advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things he told he is the NBA is a physical league
and for rookies there is going to be an adjustment period because
you have to be physically and mentally ready,'' Madsen said.
</P>
<P>
   Madsen could need that advice sooner rather than later. He has
entered a unique situation for the draftee of an NBA Champion. It
just so happens that the Lakers have a hole in the starting line-up
at Madsen's position.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first exercises for Laker fans at the Pyramid
watching Madsen will be to imagine him next to Shaquille O'Neal.
It's not an exercise Madsen is participating in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an area where they can use some help,'' Madsen said. ``I
feel I can offer rebounding and defense and energy and hustle. I'm
not too worried about my role on the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Madsen, nicknamed the ``Mad Dog,'' has been well known for his
energy and hustle in four years at Stanford. Remember him dunking
on Rhode Island as a sophomore, leading the Cardinal to the final
four?
</P>
<P>
   But the aggressive Madsen is happy not to be on the opposite
side as Shaq during games, even though the two might face each
other in practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure I'll feel a couple elbows in practice sometimes,''
Madsen said.
</P>
<P>
   ROSTER NAMES
</P>
<P>
   The SPL is always a sort of lottery for what stars will show and
what stars won't. A player might be on a roster but that doesn't
mean he'll actually play. But just for fun, here's a list of what
might happen.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix Sun guard Penny Hardaway is on the roster for the NBA
Pros.
</P>
<P>
   The SLAM roster features a number of star quality NBA players
including Pacer forward Austin Croshere, Pacer power forward Dale
Davis and Rocket swingman Shandon Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   The Hornet Anthony Mason, who most recently was charge with
trying to start a riot in New Orleans, is on the Primetime roster.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Mason on the Primetime roster is Clipper Lamar Odom, who
has been on summer vacation on the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Former UCLA guard and current Charlotte Hornet Baron Davis is on
the SMC stars roster.
</P>
<P>
   FIRST DAY
</P>
<P>
   So who might you see on the first day? Chances are you'll see
the Trailblazers Jermaine O'Neal, the topic of numerous offseason
trade rumors (Bulls GM Jerry Krause, who is interested in O'Neal
might not be very far behind). Also playing should be Seattle
Supersonics forward Rashard Lewis, who will be a highly sought
after second tier free agent.
</P>
<P>
   For local fans, former UCLA guard Toby Bailey is on the Nutriolo
roster.
</P>
<P>
   You could see some high powered coaches: Paul Westphal of the
Sonics, Mike Dunleavy of the Blazers and Jackson of the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   TICKETS
</P>
<P>
   Tickets for the Summer Pro League are $8 for general admission
and $10 for reserved seats. Tickets are good for all five games at
the Pyramid each day. Tickets can be purchased at the Pyramid, by
calling the Pyramid Box Office at (562) 985-4949 or by calling
Ticketmaster at (213) 480-3232.
</P>
<P>
   Games start at 10:30 every day, with the last game starting at
7:30 p.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
