<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-IRWINKILLED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNEASY ACCEPTANCE OF HAZARDS OF JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ As ironic as it was for them to do it, several
NASCAR drivers stood here Friday and essentially eulogized one of
their own. Their elegies were for Kenny Irwin, who was fatally
injured when he lost control of his Chevy on Turn 3 at New
Hampshire International Speedway. He was 30.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the men spoke of Irwin's smile and his ability to play
golf. Some of them said they were humbled and sick to their
stomachs. One of them, noting that Irwin's trailer was quickly
closed, said he wouldn't mind if everyone shut down their trailers
and went home for the day.
</P>
<P>
   No one, though, could answer a question that mystifies many of
us: Why do these men do this?
</P>
<P>
   Why do they speed in circles _ seemingly ad infinitum _ knowing
that a single slip of the hand or malfunction of the throttle could
turn an on-site eulogizer into the eulogized? Their fans form an
elaborate necklace from California to Nevada to Texas to Tennessee
to Alabama to the Carolinas to New Hampshire. Why is there such
devotion to a sport that has its participants flirt with death with
each practice and each race?
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Wallace is 43 years old. He has been a pro since 1980. He
said he was saddened by Irwin's death and acknowledged the
unusually high dangers of his sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the days that make you really sit back and look at
yourself in the mirror and go, `Why do I do this?' '' Wallace said.
</P>
<P>
   He recently vacationed with his wife, Patti. He was away from
the grease, away from the mechanics, away from the culture where
symbols of capitalism (constant advertising slogans) and racism
(Confederate flags) are often juxtaposed.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace enjoyed his time away and wondered why he should go
back. But he did. Most drivers do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thinking, `What the hell am I doing at some greasy
racetrack banging fenders with these guys?' he said. ``Here I am
clearing tire rubber out of my eyeballs, and grease out of my
fingernails, and friends getting killed, and these are days that
make you not want to do it, I'll tell you that. It'll really make
you question why you're doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was eight weeks ago when we were asking the same vexing
question: Why? It was also a Friday, just before noon, when
19-year-old Adam Petty also lost control of his car on Turn 3. He
suffered fatal injuries. His grandfather, Richard, was here Friday.
At five minutes before 11, Richard Petty began to give interviews
in the Media Center. Five minutes after he left the infield
facility, there was the crash on Turn 3.
</P>
<P>
   Petty was asked if the track is flawed. The incidents have
happened in the same area, a turn that is believed to be the
fastest point of the 1.058-mile oval. Petty, the man known as The
King of racing, said the layout is fine. No driver here submitted a
rant against the track and its owner, but Wallace did suggest that
a barrier be placed on Turn 3's walls. There would be something to
absorb the car in the event of a crash.
</P>
<P>
   In the event of a crash. That is, these drivers expect that
crashes will happen. They accept this hazard. They accept it the
same way boxers accept that if they are knocked unconscious enough
times, their motor skills may never be the same. They accept it the
way football players accept the hits, knowing that men such as
Darryl Stingley have been paralyzed playing the sport. Drivers
accept the quirks of their job, just as you accept yours and I
accept mine. It is what we all do, even if people outside of our
circles don't completely understand our love of our (often
eccentric) jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing prepares you for this,'' Ricky Craven said Friday.
``It's easy to take for granted. You have a passion for what you
do. You beat yourself up because you didn't qualify by a few
seconds, and the reality is this . . . qualifying is quite
insignificant right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Craven, a 34-year-old driver, tried to explain why he does what
he does.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in intensive care twice (because of racing injuries)
and said to myself, `I don't care if I ever race again,' '' he
said. ``And within two or three days, both times, when the pain
started to go away and you begin the recovery process, you have
this form of amnesia. You forget how bad it was and you just get
hungry again. You get competitive. You get real eager.''
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even understand it,'' he said. ``I can't explain
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Irwin was a spokesperson for BellSouth. He spoke on
disaster prevention. ``Prevention is the key to surviving any
disaster,'' he said May 18. He was talking about the dangers of
hurricanes, not the dangers of his job.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Holley is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by e-mail
at holley(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-00 0226EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
