<SLUG> BC-OLY-WATERPOLO-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S., CANADA MOVE TOWARD SHOWDOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE IRVINE  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ALAMITOS, Calif. _ The sport happens to be water polo, but
when the United States and Canada get together it isn't the sport
that matters most, it's the rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it's Canada and the U.S. it always a big competition,''
said Johanne Begin, the Canadian's leading scorer during the first
four days of the Holiday Cup at the U.S. Aquatics Center in Los
Alamitos. ``Whether it's basketball, water polo or any other
sport.''
</P>
<P>
   If that is indeed true, then Sunday's championship game of the
Holiday Cup will be a big competition as it appears the two nations
could be playing each other for the title.
</P>
<P>
   Canada edged closer to the championship game by holding off
Australia, 6-5, in the first game on Friday. The Canadians (3-1-0)
will advance to the final with at least a tie against Russia in
today's final session of round-robin play at 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. assured its spot in the title contest on Sunday at 7
p.m. by whipping winless Kazakhstan, 13-2, before 1,000 in the
nightcap on Friday behind five goals by Ellen Estes, three from
Rachel Scott and another steady game in goal by Gahr High product
Nicolle Payne. The Americans, who are the tournament's lone
unbeaten team after four games, close round-robin play at 5:30 p.m.
today against defending world champion Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   It will be the second time in the tournament that the Canada and
the U.S. have renewed a rivalry that began long before any of these
players jumped into the pool. The U.S. trailed for much of the
first meeting but stormed back for a 12-9 victory over the
Canadians on the opening day of the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``On that given day, they were a better team than us,'' Canadian
coach Daniel Berthelette said. ``But, in this tournament, it's one
game at a time. It's not do or die (during round robin play). It
will be a new day.''
</P>
<P>
   A Canadian loss on Friday would have pretty much secured a spot
in the final for the Australians. And, according to Begin, beating
the Australians hasn't always been easy for Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was mainly mental,'' said Begin, who added that a
victory over the Australians earlier this year got Canada past the
mental block. ``We always had a problem with them for some
reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Begin, who has eight goals in the tournament and six in the past
two games, scored both Canadian goals in the fourth period,
including the winner with 55 seconds left, of the tense game that
never featured a lead bigger than a goal. Australia nearly tied the
score with 28 seconds left but Naomi Castle's crisp shot bounced
off the bar.
</P>
<P>
   There was no drama in the U.S. win as Estes scored three times
in the first period to help the Americans built a 4-1 lead that
grew to 7-2 at halftime. Estes, who only had one goal in the first
three games, added goals in the second and fourth periods to give
her five from the game.
</P>
<P>
   The American offense, which scored 46 times in four games, was
its usual spectacular self as six players scored goals, including
Coralie Simmons, whose two goals gave her tournament best 11 after
four games. Also scoring were Catherine Von Schwarz, Julie Swail
and Courtney Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the game, the U.S. was sharp on the 6-on-5 situation,
converting on 4 of 7 in the first half. In the second half,
however, they converted only 2 of 7 attempts.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. also has shown strength in goal with the combination of
Payne and Bernice Orwig. Payne, who was in goal during an earlier
victory over Australia, had six saves in the win over Kazakhstan
and helped hold Kazakhstan to 2 of 9 on the player-advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Netherlands 11, Russia 9: Netherlands (2-2-0) led for most of
the way but it took a tally by Gillian van der Berg with 29 seconds
left to ice the win over Russia (1-3-0).
</P>
</TEXT>
