<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RODRIGUEZ KNOCKED OUT IN LOSS TO DODGERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ For five minutes Friday night, the citizens of Seattle
got a taste of life without Alex Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   They stood there, 45,206 strong at Safeco Field, silent,
unnerved by the scene before them _ the last of the Mariners'
superstars prone on his back in the infield, motionless.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez eventually got up, first to a seated position, then to
his feet and the waiting arms of two trainers. He was knocked
unconscious while attempting to break up a fifth-inning double
play. Taken to a nearby hospital as a precaution, the All-Star
shortstop and free-agent prize apparently suffered a concussion
from a knee to the head.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yeah, the Mariners lost to the Los Angeles Dodgers 3-2 in 11
innings in a game that was as compelling as Rodriguez's injury was
frightening. Eric Karros settled it with a one-out homer, his 25th,
over the fence in right-center.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody be sure and tell Rodriguez who won.
</P>
<P>
   With runs scarce in the interleague matchup, the golden one
tried to keep a rally going. Rodriguez slid in hard and was hurt in
a collision _ ironically, with Alex Cora, the younger brother of
his former Seattle infield mate, Joey Cora.
</P>
<P>
   While the Dodgers infielder writhed on the ground, Rodriguez lay
still. Trainer Rick Griffin moved Rodriguez's gold necklace off the
player's face. Another trainer ran off the field and returned with
two ominous-looking medical bags, one black, the other orange.
</P>
<P>
   Designated hitter Edgar Martinez, whose bases-loaded grounder
started the sequence of events, squatted behind his fallen
teammate. Mariners manager Lou Piniella stood behind Martinez, arms
crossed.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd applauded as Cora climbed to his feet, but there was
nothing from Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Rodriguez stirred, almost automatically snapping into a
seated position. He was out five minutes, out before he hit the
ground. He looked around groggily, answered a few questions, then
was escorted from the field, fists clenched. He rubbed an eye
before disappearing into the clubhouse. Forty-five thousand sighs
of relief could be heard in unison.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez might have regained his feet, but his team never did
against the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   In Freddy Garcia's long-awaited return, the Mariners spotted Los
Angeles two runs in the first, got one back in the fifth and
squandered late opportunity after late opportunity. Seattle left
the bases loaded in the eighth, two runners on in the ninth and a
runner on third in the 10th.
</P>
<P>
   History also was made. In the fifth Ricky Henderson walked. It
was the 2,020th free pass of his career, breaking a tie with Ted
Williams for second all-time. Henderson needs 42 more to catch the
leader, Babe Ruth.
</P>
<P>
   Back from a broken leg and a two-month absence, Garcia looked
strong but not sharp. He lasted six innings, walking five and
striking out six. He allowed two runs, on a two-out, bases-loaded
double by Dodgers catcher Todd Hundley. He gave up just four hits.
</P>
<P>
   Against junk-throwing lefty Carlos Perez, the Mariners had
runners on base in every inning. However, they didn't score until
the fifth, when Rodriguez walked with the bases full and one out.
He only had four pitches to savor the at-bat before Martinez
started the fateful play.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners tied the game 2-2 in the eighth, when Carlos
Guillen drew a two-out, bases-loaded walk. The inning was extended
when Los Angeles third baseman Adrian Beltre booted a grounder by
the previous batter, pinch-hitter Raul Ibanez.
</P>
<P>
   Karros' game-winning homer broke up up a Seattle no-hitter _ at
least from the third inning on. He made reliever Arthur Rhodes pay
for a grooved 3-2 pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Adding further irony to the evening, Rodriguez's agent, Scott
Boras, was in attendance. Hours before game time, he entertained
reporters asking for updates on Rodriguez, who might become the
most sought-after free agent in baseball history.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, whose availability for Tuesday's All-Star Game is
unknown, has maintained he won't consider his future until the
season is concluded, but has said a winning team is paramount to
his decision.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, to maintain that bargaining power, he needs
to stay healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Boras talked about his player's value on the market, breaking it
down four ways: 1) his premium position (shortstop, center fielder,
catcher or pitcher); 2) his slugging talent (40 homers or more); 3)
his leadership traits; and 4) his icon status (ability to draw fans
and attract other players to a market).
</P>
<P>
   ``Most players can never offer that to a franchise,'' Boras
said.
</P>
<P>
   It all flashed before his eyes Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Dan Raley can be reached at 206-448-8008
</P>
<P>
   or danraley &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-00 0246EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
