r s BC-BBO-DODGERS-WRITETHRU     07-08 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-DODGERS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KARROS' HOMER IN 11TH BEATS MARINERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE - One hit after the third inning, and just five in the
game. Eleven batters strike out. A solid effort by the starting
pitcher wasted.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, a victory for the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Karros' home run to center in the 11th inning gave Los
Angeles a 3-2 victory Friday night in its first game at Safeco
Field in front of a sellout crowd of 45,206.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers (44-40), who won their third in a row and National
League-leading 25th road game, managed just four hits through 10
innings before Karros sent Arthur Rhodes' 3-2 offering deep to
center.
</P>
<P>
   The shot made a winner out of Matt Herges (6-0), who pitched two
shutout innings of no-hit, three-walk, four-strikeout ball.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Fetters pitched the 11th for his third save, but it wasn't
easy. He gave up a single to Mark McLemore and walked John Mabry
before inducing John Olerud to ground to first which sent the tying
and winning runs in scoring position. Fetters ended it by striking
out Jay Buhner.
</P>
<P>
   The victory took 4 hours, 27 minutes, eight minutes short of the
team's longest game of the season, May 22 against Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Rhodes (2-3) struck out three in two innings and gave up just
the one hit.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Dodgers' offense was mostly invisible Friday, the
pressure fell to the pitching, and starter Carlos Perez again threw
well.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Dodgers left-hander hasn't won since May 20, he
gave up one run in 6 innings, but the Mariners scored two runs on
bases-loaded walks to keep him out of the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Perez had about the worst season possible last year, going 2-10
with a 7.43 ERA and making everyone wonder why he was earning
$5,333,333 this season.
</P>
<P>
   But then came this year. He started 3-1 and led 7-3 in his May 9
start against Arizona but earned no decision when the Diamondbacks
rallied and won in 12 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, he's 1-3 with seven no-decisions, but look at some
of those outings: two runs in 6 innings against Philadelphia, one
earned run in seven innings against Oakland and Friday's effort. A
lack of run support hasn't helped.
</P>
<P>
   He also had a couple of five-run outings, too, but then came his
two relief stints, in which he gave up one earned run in 8 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers got just five hits, but that was enough.
</P>
<P>
   Leading 2-0 into the fifth inning and never retiring the side in
order, Perez ran into trouble when he loaded the bases (that
included issuing Rickey Henderson's 2,020th career walk, moving him
into second place all-time). Then he walked Alex Rodriguez to force
in a run.
</P>
<P>
   Edgar Martinez grounded to short, and Alex Cora turned a 6-3
double play to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   However, when Cora forced Rodriguez at second, he tried to leap
over the Mariners star. Instead, Rodriguez's head hit Cora's knee
and upper thigh. Rodriguez's neck snapped back and both players
fell to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Cora got up after a few minutes and remained in the game.
Rodriguez wasn't so lucky, however. It took several minutes for him
to get up, and he appeared disoriented. He was preliminarily
diagnosed with a concussion and went to a local hospital as a
precaution. Rodriguez's status for Tuesday's All-Star Game could be
up in the air.
</P>
<P>
   Perez, meanwhile, went about his business and stopped another
Seattmoqally with Todd Hollandsworth's help.
</P>
<P>
   Olerud led off the sixth with a double. One out later, David
Bell singled to center, and Hollandsworth threw out Olerud at the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   When Perez gave up a single to Carlos Guillen to lead off the
seventh and then got Henderson to fly to right, he was gone in
favor of Terry Adams, who retired the side.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle tied it in the eighth, starting with two singles off
Adams. Adams struck out Bell for the second out, but Adrian Beltre
bobbled pinch-hitter Raul Ibanez's grounder to load the bases.
Adams then walked Guillen to force in the tying run.
</P>
<P>
   Adams retired the side by getting Henderson to ground to short.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers took a 2-0 lead in the first inning on Hundley's
two-run double off Freddy Garcia, who came off the disabled list
before the game, having recovered from a fractured tibia. It was
his first start since April 22.
</P>
<P>
   Hollandsworth had walked with one out and Sheffield had singled.
One out later, Hundley pulled a Garcia pitch down the right-field
line.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers wasted a scoring chance in the third inning.
Hollandsworth and Sheffield opened with singles, Hollandsworth
taking third. Shawn Green struck out and Karros grounded before
Beltre was intentionally walked. But Garcia got Dave Hansen to
ground to third.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia gave up four hits, none after the third inning, and the
two runs were earned in six innings with five walks and six
strikeouts.
</P>
</TEXT>
