<SLUG> BC-BEIRUT-RETURN-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BEIRUT I KNEW WASN'T SO DIFFERENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
John Kifner was the Beirut bureau chief for The New York Times from
1979 to 1982 and from 1984 to 1985.  
 By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon _ The last time I had set foot in the Beirut
airport, exactly 15 years before, a hijacked Trans World Airlines
jet sat on the runway. A U.S. Navy diver had been murdered and
thrown from the plane, and 39 Americans would be held hostage for
17 days before being freed in Damascus, Syria.
</P>
<P>
   In the filthy shambles of the terminal, pistol-waving hijackers
wearing hoods made from airline pillowcases held a news conference
that turned into a near riot when television cameramen climbed on
the table that the hijackers had carefully laid out with Lebanese
dishes. The windows in the control tower were still shattered from
the time a few years earlier when they were shot out by the man
known as ``Hamzi the Hijacker,'' who was working on his ninth
plane.
</P>
<P>
   The airport was convenient for hijackers in those days. When
they were done, all they had to do was to cross the tarmac to go
home, melting into into the surrounding Shiite Muslim shantytowns.
</P>
<P>
   Now, when I returned in the early summer of 2000, the terminal
was new and clean, partly lined with gleaming tile. An efficient
line processed visas, where once a grimy customs inspector
whispered to me, ``Be careful, my friend, you are in the Orient
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside, instead of the chaos I used to know, was an orderly
taxi line with a no-haggling fixed price. A smooth new highway,
swooping through tunnels and overpasses, had replaced the old
rutted road studded with militia checkpoints.
</P>
<P>
   We drove past gleaming new high-rises and glittery restaurants
to the Phoenecia, a huge and gaudy palace right on the Green Line,
the no-man's land that once divided the city. The hotel district
was one of the first and fiercest battlegrounds of the civil war
that made a Lebanon a synonym for brutal anarchy in the 1970s and
'80s, and next door the battered, shell-holed hulk of the Holiday
Inn still loomed.
</P>
<P>
   Just to travel across the city back then was to risk your life.
Snipers were dug into the broken buildings on each side: as the war
wound on they became skilled, hitting people in the head more
often.
</P>
<P>
   Christian right and Muslim left were the working cliches for the
journalists, but the reality was much more complex. Christians
killed each other to eliminate rivals, and alliances shifted
bloodily on the Muslim side. Even a traffic accident could set off
a gun battle that quickly spread through a wide area and lasted for
hours. All the militias had their own jails. Piles of rotting
garbage, occasionally set afire, lined the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinary Lebanese hunkered down through artillery barrages,
power outages and water shortages, siege and invasion, somehow
maintaining the extravagant style that is their endearing hallmark.
There are no real statistics here, but it is generally estimated
that 150,000 people died and 17,000 are still missing.
</P>
<P>
   The morning after I arrived I walked around the streets I used
to know. There were no gunmen and no garbage. A McDonald's stood at
the corner where the Associated Press correspondent Terry Anderson
was kidnapped in 1985; it had valet parking for the Range Rovers.
It was eerie at first to walk on the streets where 15 years before
you could not go, in the city center that had been the heart of the
Green Line, where I once met a gunmen who been in position so long
he had planted a garden.
</P>
<P>
   The old buildings, Ottoman and French Colonial, have now been
meticulously restored into one of the most gorgeous downtowns
anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   What happened, I wondered. Could these people have all suddenly
come to their senses?
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately not.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you see, it's all a facade, a fake veneer,'' grumbled a
veteran Lebanese journalist, launching into an hourlong tirade
against government corruption and inefficiency, an economic crisis
spinning out of control and Syrian domination _ after, of course,
making sure that his name would not be used.
</P>
<P>
   The new highway and the luxury hotels skirt and conceal the
slums and squatters in much of the city. Even in the flashy stores
on Rue Verdon _ Gucci, Versace, Valentino _ business is down. The
rebuilding was almost entirely the single-minded effort of Rafik
Hariri, prime minister from 1992 to 1998; his enemies are now in
power and cutting off his permits.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
