<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 11:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6478 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v AM-NYT-BUDGET &LR;      07-08 1572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(lh) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, July 9:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MISSILE-FAILURE (Washington) _ A crucial test in the Pentagon's
program to defend the United States from missile attacks collapsed
in failure because the high-speed interceptor that was supposed to
destroy a dummy warhead in space never separated from its booster
rocket, the Pentagon said. By Elaine Sciolino.
</P>
<P>
   MISSILE-ASSESS (Moscow) _ With the failure of the Pentagon's
anti-missile test, the Clinton administration has reaped all of the
diplomatic disadvantages of its program to build a national missile
defense and none of the potential rewards. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-VOICES (Tel Aviv, Israel) _ Everyone in Israel, the West
Bank and Gaza is a prisoner of what President Clinton labeled the
``abject dreariness of the pursuit.'' Everyone cares and almost
everyone is afraid to care too much, fearful of having their hopes
dashed or their fears realized. In a day of interviews throughout
Israel and the West Bank, it was only the Jewish settlers, and even
those in settlements unlikely to be uprooted, who were treating the
coming summit as a potentially pivotal event. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   DRUG-PRICES (Langata Rongai, Kenya) _ Two competing forces have
intensified the international battle over prescription drugs: the
1994 world treaty on intellectual property that underpins free
trade and the AIDS epidemic, which is devastating whole continents
too poor to pay the going rate for patented drugs. The public
health advocates and an increasing number of Third World countries
say the 1994 treaty allows them to manufacture or import much
cheaper generic drugs to avert national disaster; the drug
companies argue that the costs of developing drugs are so high that
they cannot afford to lower the prices of the few that become
wildly successful. A special report. By Donald G. McNeil Jr.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-ADMIN-SCHOOL (Strasbourg, France) _ For more than four
decades, France's National School of Administration, dedicated to
shaping top students for a life in government, has done just that.
It has not been easy to get into this state-subsidized finishing
school for the elite, known here as ENA. The exams are legendary in
their difficulty. The odds of success have sometimes been as high
as 200 to 1. But not today. In an undeniable sign of all that is
changing in France, the number of applicants to the school has
dropped 30 percent in the last four years alone. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-PUTIN (Moscow) _ President Vladimir Putin assembled both
houses of parliament and a national television audience Saturday to
present his assessment of the state of the nation. In a word, it
was forbidding. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S. (Beijing) _ A visiting U.S. official praised China
for becoming ``a major participant'' in nonproliferation efforts in
Asia and around the world but said two days of talks did not allay
concerns about Chinese help for Pakistan's anti-ballistic missile
program. Allegations of such aid to Pakistan have complicated
passage by the Senate of normal trade status for China. By Erik
Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-AIDS-EDUC (Durban, South Africa) ``My boyfriend just
wants sex,'' ``The Naked Truth,'' and ``Oral sex.'' ``Talk about
it.'' These and similar messages have sprung up in recent months on
billboards in South Africa as part of a campaign to encourage young
people to talk freely about sex and the risks of teen-age
pregnancy, AIDS and other sexually transmitted diseases. The erotic
and hard-hitting phrases are part of a funky campaign aimed at
reducing by one-half the rate of infection from HIV, the AIDS
virus, in South Africa in five years. The 4.2 million HIV-infected
people in South Africa is the largest in the world. By Lawrence K.
Altman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   RACE-COPS-DRUGS (New York) _ For Harlem narcotics detectives,
race colors everything. It lies just beneath the surface in an
argument over tactics between a white sergeant and a black
undercover detective. Race is out there in the neighborhood where
African-American informers are pitted against Dominican drug
dealers. Race is in the police radio descriptions (``suspect is a
dark-skinned Dominican, mid-20s ...''), and race amplifies the
anger on the street when the police drive up and arrest yet another
dark-skinned man. In 1998, the killing of a black man, Amadou
Diallo, by four panicky white policemen touched every Harlem
narcotics officer to the core. And yet they do not discuss it. Cops
do not discuss race. It's too risky. They need to get along. By
Michael Winerip.
</P>
<P>
   (Eds: An abridged version of this story,
RACE-COPS-DRUGS-ABRIDGED, is also being filed.)
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   GENETICALLY-ALTERED-GRASS (Marysville, Ohio) _ Standing in long
rows in Greenhouse No. 3, part of the Scotts Co.'s research
laboratory here, are pots of grass that could be a suburbanite's
dream come true. The grass, which Scotts hopes will eventually
carpet every lawn and golf course around the world, is genetically
altered to withstand applications of the most potent weed killers
and remain shiny, green and healthy, creating fields of unblemished
green. The company is also working on genetically modified roses
and other flowers that will bloom longer than the ones found in
nature. Critics are horrified. By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-BOLINAS (Bolinas, Calif.) _ Long known for its
live-and-let-live attitude, this spirited community of surfers,
poets, artists, writers and aging mavericks about 30 miles up the
coast from San Francisco has reached a tipping point of sorts.
Perhaps nowhere is the Bay Area's relentless collision between
hippie-van and BMW culture becoming more pronounced than in this
preternaturally beautiful place, where earthy hand-built houses
topped with lurching towers commune with shingled New England-style
cottages with achingly sweet gardens. But two recent developments
typify the threat that many see to the town's personality. By
Patricia Leigh Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ALCOHOLICS-MODERATION (Seattle) _ After she founded a self-help
program called Moderation Management seven years ago, Audrey
Kishline became a national spokeswoman for the notion that problem
drinkers could be taught to cut back without abstaining altogether.
Having recently pleaded guilty to two counts of vehicular homicide
after a binge drinking episode last March, Kishline said through
her lawyer that she has a new message: Moderation Management ``is
nothing but alcoholics covering up their problem.'' By Sam Howe
Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   POTTER-FRENZY (New York) _ Very early Saturday morning,
8-year-old Gabriel Back-Gael was standing guard over the door of
the Community Bookstore in Park Slope, Brooklyn. Behind him
stretched a line of hundreds of children and parents, all awaiting
their first chance to buy ``Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire,''
the fourth book in the wildly popular series about the exploits of
Harry Potter, the boy wizard. To many it was a historic occasion _
some even brought cameras to record the purchase. By David D.
Kirkpatrick.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (Moving in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-JUSTICES (Austin, Texas) _ In recent weeks, particularly
after the U.S. Supreme Court's 5-4 ruling that the government may
not prohibit doctors from performing a procedure that opponents
call partial-birth abortion, the issue of judicial appointments has
percolated into the presidential race. Vice President Al Gore has
warned that George W. Bush, if elected, would appoint conservative
Supreme Court justices hostile to abortion rights. But a look at
Bush's record in Texas shows that he has appointed justices who
have been a moderating influence on the Texas Supreme Court, often
regarded as among the most conservative and pro-business in the
country. By Jim Yardley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Washington) _ Spitballs? Or no spitballs? By
Maureen Dowd.
</P>
<P>
   KRUGMAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Stocks: the bad, the good, and the
silly. By Paul Krugman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVING LATER:  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS-BUDGET _ A rundown of sports stories will move by 1 p.m.
ET.
</P>
<P>
   AM-FRONTPAGE-NYT _ A description of the front page layout of the
first edition of The New York Times will move at 12 noon.
</P>
