<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 11:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6483 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKE     07-08 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE WEEK IN REVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   One Thing Made Him Sweat
</P>
<P>
   When Queen Elizabeth II knighted Sean Connery in his hometown,
Edinburgh, Scotland, the actor called the occasion ``one of the
proudest days of my life.'' Shame on him. Didn't Connery know that
for James Bond, the legendary superspy he portrayed in seven
movies, the prospect of a knighthood was as horrifying as that of a
vodka martini stirred, not shaken?
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Man With the Golden Gun'' (1965), the last James Bond
novel written by the character's creator, Ian Fleming, Bond is
recommended for a knighthood _ specifically, the Knight Commander
of St. Michael and St. George (KCMG) _ but declines the honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had never been a public figure,'' Fleming wrote, ``and he
did not wish to become one. He had no prejudice against letters
after one's name, or before it. But there was one thing above all
he treasured. His privacy. His anonymity. To become a public
person, a person, in the snobbish world of England, of any country,
who would be called upon to open things, lay foundation stones,
make after-dinner speeches, brought the sweat to his armpits.''
</P>
<P>
   So in a telegram to M., the head of the British Secret Service,
Bond writes, ``EYE AM A SCOTTISH PEASANT AND EYE WILL ALWAYS FEEL
AT HOME BEING A SCOTTISH PEASANT AND EYE KNOW COMMA SIR COMMA THAT
YOU WILL UNDERSTAND MY PREFERENCE AND THAT EYE CAN COUNT ON YOUR
INDULGENCE.''
</P>
<P>
   007, being a Scottish spy, also had a Scottish reason for
spurning a knighthood. In a sentence that he ultimately strikes
from his telegram, Bond says: ``MY PRINCIPAL REASON IS THAT EYE
DONT WANT TO PAY MORE AT HOTELS AND RESTAURANTS.''
</P>
<P>
   Bond, presumably, has helped make Connery so wealthy that he no
longer has to worry about such things.
</P>
<P>
   _ By THOMAS VINCIGUERRA
</P>
<P>
   Quidditch, Anyone?
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, J.K. Rowling, a struggling single mother in
Edinburgh, completed a children's novel, written mostly in coffee
shops. Today ``Harry Potter'' is the biggest publishing phenomenon
in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone'' and two sequels, all
about an orphaned boy with wizard powers, have sold nearly 21
million copies. The fourth book _ ``Harry Potter and the Goblet of
Fire'' _ is being published with the kind of hoopla reserved for
the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The book was published Saturday, when a record first printing of
3.8 million copies went on sale in the United States. Scholastic
Inc., released the book at 12:01 a.m., and bookstores around the
nation gave midnight ``Harry Potter'' parties, with clerks dressed
as wizards and witches.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have been excited about this for months,'' said Barbara
Theroux, owner of the Fact and Fiction Bookstore in Missoula, Mont.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the extraordinary secrecy with which the book was
published, newspapers report that several lucky children in
Virginia received early copies. An 8-year-old girl in Fairfax got
one from a clerk who apparently didn't realize the book was
embargoed, and a Richmond Wal-Mart store mistakenly sold 20 copies
before the book was pulled from the shelves.
</P>
<P>
   To the delight of Scholastic and Warner Brothers, which owns the
movie rights, Rowling has promised three more ``Harry Potter''
books before the series concludes.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BERNARD WEINRAUB
</P>
<P>
   Camp Clinton Opens For the Summer
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has invited Israel's prime minister, Ehud
Barak, and the Palestinian leader, Yasser Arafat, to Camp David
this week to try to end a half-century of conflict. Administration
officials cautioned that success was not guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   News of the summit was greeted with skepticism among Palestinian
leaders, while two political parties announced they would pull out
of Barak's coalition government, leaving him with just 59 of the
120 seats in parliament.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JANE PERLEZ
</P>
<P>
   Cartel Comedy
</P>
<P>
   In a week marked by missteps and contradictory messages, the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries seemed more like the
Gang That Couldn't Shoot Straight than an immensely powerful global
cartel.
</P>
<P>
   First Saudi Arabia, the world's largest petroleum producer,
announced it would increase output by 500,000 barrels a day to
drive down high oil prices, and crude futures fell sharply.
</P>
<P>
   Then, other OPEC members said the Saudis had been misunderstood,
and a production increase was not imminent. Crude prices rose
again. The Saudis have since stayed quiet, and gas prices, not
surprisingly, continued to climb in most of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   _ By NEELA BANNERJEE
</P>
<P>
   Chechnya, Again
</P>
<P>
   Just one week after a Russian general proclaimed the war in
Chechnya all but won, a series of bombings killed at least 33
Russian troops in the breakaway republic.
</P>
<P>
   The truck bomb attacks, which occurred on Sunday night, took
place in towns and cities supposedly under Russian control.
President Vladimir Putin promised to curtail the role in Chechnya
of Russian police _ whose troops were killed in the bombings. The
police came from throughout Russia and their deaths have sent shock
waves through the nation.
</P>
<P>
   _ By MICHAEL R. GORDON
</P>
<P>
   Two Apples for Gore
</P>
<P>
   As expected, Vice President Al Gore received overwhelming
endorsements from the two national teachers unions and enormous
ovations when he visited their conventions. Gore spoke first to the
American Federation of Teachers in Philadelphia, then flew to
Chicago to address the National Education Association.
</P>
<P>
   The teachers are part of a large labor coalition backing Gore
candidacy, and have been energized by his staunch opposition to
vouchers, which would allow public money to be used for
private-school tuition. His opponent, Gov. George W. Bush, supports
them.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JODI WILGOREN
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-00 1141EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000708.0050 </DOCNO>
