drive down high oil prices, and crude futures fell sharply.
</P>
<P>
   Then, other OPEC members said the Saudis had been misunderstood,
and a production increase was not imminent. Crude prices rose
again. The Saudis have since stayed quiet, and gas prices, not
surprisingly, continued to climb in most of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   _ By NEELA BANNERJEE
</P>
<P>
   Chechnya, Again
</P>
<P>
   Just one week after a Russian general proclaimed the war in
Chechnya all but won, a series of bombings killed at least 33
Russian troops in the breakaway republic.
</P>
<P>
   The truck bomb attacks, which occurred on Sunday night, took
place in towns and cities supposedly under Russian control.
President Vladimir Putin promised to curtail the role in Chechnya
of Russian police _ whose troops were killed in the bombings. The
police came from throughout Russia and their deaths have sent shock
waves through the nation.
</P>
<P>
   _ By MICHAEL R. GORDON
</P>
<P>
   Two Apples for Gore
</P>
<P>
   As expected, Vice President Al Gore received overwhelming
endorsements from the two national teachers unions and enormous
ovations when he visited their conventions. Gore spoke first to the
American Federation of Teachers in Philadelphia, then flew to
Chicago to address the National Education Association.
</P>
<P>
   The teachers are part of a large labor coalition backing Gore
candidacy, and have been energized by his staunch opposition to
vouchers, which would allow public money to be used for
private-school tuition. His opponent, Gov. George W. Bush, supports
them.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JODI WILGOREN
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   America Needs Lawyers
</P>
<P>
   Law school is hot, and business school is not. In a turnaround
that surprised educators, the number of people applying to the
nation's law schools has increased in each of the last two years,
after a decade of steep declines. Meanwhile, almost every top
business school received fewer applications this year. Some
experienced declines of up to 20 pecent.
</P>
<P>
   In a tight labor market, some deans said, companies may be
discouraging workers from returning to school.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID LEONHARDT
</P>
<P>
   Criminal or Kangaroo Court?
</P>
<P>
   A revolutionary court in the southern city of Shiraz convicted
10 of 13 Iranian Jews of spying for Israel. They received sentences
ranging from four to 13 years in prison. The other three were
acquitted.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict and the closed trial were greeted with protests by
Jewish and human rights groups, who saw the proceedings as possibly
more political than criminal in nature.
</P>
<P>
   Ismail Nasseri Mojarrad, part of the defense team, expressed
hope that the sentences would be reduced by the appeals court.
``The court lacks evidence except confessions by some of the Jews
which we insist are not valid according to the law,'' Mojarrad
said.
</P>
<P>
   _ By NAZILA FATHI
</P>
<P>
   A World of Misery
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations' annual Human Development Report ranks
nations according to the availability of schools, clean water,
medical care, life expectancy and political rights.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the report found that Sierra Leone was the worst
place in the world to be born, and that 30 of the 35 countries at
the bottom of the index were in sub-Saharan Africa. In that region,
the survey showed, life expectancy is down to the 40s and 50s, and,
largely because of AIDS, is falling for the first time in decades.
Less than half the regional population goes to school and most
people lack clean water.
</P>
<P>
   The next lowest-ranked nations, from the bottom up, are Niger,
Burkina Faso, Ethiopia, Burundi, Guinea-Bissau, Mozambique, Chad,
the Central African Republic and Mali.
</P>
<P>
   Haiti was the sole representative from the Western Hemisphere
among the bottom 35 countries in the survey.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BARBARA CROSSETTE
</P>
<P>
   Closing the Books
</P>
<P>
   The German Parliament approved a bill, on a vote of 556-42, that
set the stage for compensation to Nazi slave laborers and other
Holocaust victims. German industry and the government will each pay
$2.5 billion to the fund.
</P>
<P>
   The vote ends a half-century of denial of responsibility by
German manufacturers, including the German subsidiaries of Ford and
General Motors.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, German manufacturers argued that the Nazis had
simply required them to use the forced workers.
</P>
<P>
   Other People's Mail
</P>
<P>
   Is America using a vast surveillance network, known as Echelon,
which receives and analyzes satellite communications, to give its
corporations a leg up in their business dealings? Washington says
no, but a lot of Europeans aren't buying it.
</P>
<P>
   The European Parliament has voted to form a committee to
investigate the matter and a French prosecutor has begun a
preliminary inquiry. What might become of either inquiry is
unclear, but together they testify to Europe's growing wariness of
U.S. global power.
</P>
<P>
   ``Echelon is used by the National Security Agency for strategic
and economic gains,'' Prosecutor Jean-Pierre Dintilhac said. ''You
cannot make me believe that the information is not passed on to
American companies.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By SUZANNE DALEY
</P>
<P>
   A Brief Reprieve
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration will postpone the first federal
execution since 1963. A convicted murderer, Juan Raul Garza, is
scheduled to be executed on Aug. 5, but the White House, citing
concerns about the fairness of the death penalty and the absence of
clemency procedures, is awaiting Justice Department regulations on
how inmates on death row should seek clemency.
</P>
<P>
   The regulations should be completed within a couple of weeks,
said a Justice Department spokesman. They will provide for the
lawyers of those sentenced to death to make oral presentations
before a clemency panel.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-one other prisoners are currently on death row in federal
prisons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
