<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 11:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6489 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-MEXICO-DEMOCRACY-REVI     07-08 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-DEMOCRACY-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO'S VOTERS SPOKE. NOW THE VICTOR MUST ACT. 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By GINGER THOMPSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ On the night that Vicente Fox wrested control of
the Mexican presidency from the ruling Institutional Revolutionary
Party, the jubilant victor rushed out to celebrate with throngs of
supporters who had gathered at the monument of the Angel of
Independence in the capital.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of miles away in a rural village in the eastern state
of Veracruz, a small group of potato farmers gathered around a
black-and-white television set to watch grainy images of the
celebration. Sometimes it was hard for them to hear Fox above the
chants from the crowd around him. But what the crowd had to say
came through loud and clear. ``Vicente no nos falles,'' the
televised crowd blared.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vicente, don't fail us.''
</P>
<P>
   The words stirred the farmers in Veracruz, and they picked up
the chant. That simple plea, said one farmer, summed up the deep
sense of betrayal people have long felt toward their government and
their desperation for change. But there was also an edgy challenge
in the plea.
</P>
<P>
   Mexicans will no longer hand over their votes and expect little
in return, the farmers said. And what they most expect from Fox are
programs and reforms that will help the nation's new democracy
expand beyond elections.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment of their greatest expectation, however, some
voters do not quite realize that the new president's powers have
also been radically reshaped _ in some ways weakened _ by some of
the same currents that carried him to victory. He is not part of
the one-party apparatus that for 71 years monopolized power in
Mexico but so often failed its people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Fox has made a lot of promises to the people, that he
would move the country forward,'' said Alvaro Gonzalez Arenas, 24.
``We have put our faith in him; faith that we are finally going to
be free of corruption and that we will be able to live with
dignity.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the first step in the development of a democracy _ free
and fair elections _ was accomplished here last Sunday in contests
that displayed an extraordinary level of civility and respect.
</P>
<P>
   But democracy, as shown from Central America to the former
Soviet Union, requires more than fair elections. Those in power
must prove able to work in cooperation with their opponents. In
Fox's case, only then can he take on Mexico's urgent tasks:
creating a credible justice system that protects civilians from
crime and corruption, and anti-poverty programs to lift the poor;
and opening education and employment opportunities to the best and
the brightest, rather than the best and most well-connected. Such
goals are extraordinarily complex, of course, and have been set
before.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have felt so betrayed by promises from candidates that
were never intended to be fulfilled and they not only stopped
believing in the government, but they stopped believing in
themselves,'' said Julio Faesler, a congressman and member of Fox's
National Action Party. ``It took a great leap of faith, and a lot
of internal courage for people to trust in something other than the
PRI. And living up to that confidence will not be easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Showing that he plans to work hard to fulfill his campaign
promises, Fox has barely taken a moment to rest since his victory.
But when he assumes power on Dec. 1, some analysts say he will be
in a weaker position than his PRI predecessors. He will not have
the support of the vast PRI machinery _ its political bosses, its
labor union and farmers' cooperative leaders and the directors of
the wealthiest social welfare programs. These were an important
part of the muscle that could support, and often impose, the will
of a PRI president.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-00 1154EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000708.0055 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 11:54 </DATE_TIME>
