<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 12:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6502 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-THEATER-SUPERSTITION-     07-08 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-SUPERSTITION-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUT SPOTS, CATS AND BAD LINES 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Short of dinner theater or being cast in a musical about tooth
decay, there are few terrors that hold more sway over theater folk
than the curse of ``Macbeth.'' Legend has it that the hex dates
from the first production in 1606, when the actor playing Lady
Macbeth died backstage, cursing the play.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, various productions of ``Macbeth'' have been waylaid
by death and disaster. Over the years, the myth has gained such
authority that many actors are loath to utter even the name of the
play, preferring instead to call it ``the Scottish play,'' or
occasionally ``the Scottish play about the guy who wants to be king
so bad he knocks off some other dudes and then watches his wife go
totally bonkers.'' Others refer to it merely as ``the Scottish play
I've never read.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the hex claimed yet another victim when the Broadway
production of ``Macbeth'' starring Kelsey Grammer of the hit
television series ``Frasier'' folded after only 13 performances.
That gave it the shortest run since the 1998 comedy ``More to
Love,'' a four-performance wonder that featured an actress in the
role of an electrical fuse. Just a day after Grammer's reviews came
out, the jinx struck the British actor Antony Sher, who was
starring in a production of the play in New Haven, Conn. He walked
offstage at the end of Act I but did not return. A throat infection
kept him out for several days.
</P>
<P>
   Of course the ``Macbeth'' curse is hardly the only superstition
hanging over the black-magic-laden world of the theater, a
profession in which open incantations of blood lust (``Break a
leg!'') are routine.
</P>
<P>
   The list of taboos is long: never whistle in the dressing room,
never open an umbrella onstage and never, never be cast as an
electrical fuse. So treacherous are these potential psychic land
mines that, in the name of public service, the following is a brief
rundown of some current and ancient omens plaguing the stage:
</P>
<P>
   Cats: According to ``A Brief Dictionary of American
Superstitions,'' by Vergilius Ferm (Philosophical Library, 1959),
it bodes ill if a cat walks across a stage during rehearsal. The
exception, of course, is if you invested in the musical ``Cats,''
Broadway's longest-running musical. In which case, bring on the
kitties.
</P>
<P>
   Chorus girls: If a chorus girl dances on spilled powder before a
performance, it can inspire good fortune. Or a bout of wheezing.
</P>
<P>
   Costumes: It is considered very bad luck to change costumes if
your first performance was a success. It is considered very bad
taste to never change it.
</P>
<P>
   Curtains: According to Ferm, yellow curtains are said to bring
bad luck to a new play. No reason is given, except for the obvious
garishness, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Death: A death in the audience is considered bad luck for the
production. It's particularly unfortunate for the poor theatergoer.
</P>
<P>
   Disney: Considered very good luck for investors; produced ``The
Lion King,'' a sellout for nearly three years; ``Aida,'' Broadway's
second-highest-grossing musical; and ``Beauty and the Beast,''
which is in its seventh year on Broadway. You do the math.
</P>
<P>
   Flowers: Artificial flowers are preferred over the real thing in
the theater, except by actresses, who have divorced men for less.
</P>
<P>
   The Gypsy Robe: One of Broadway's oldest traditions: a chorus
member from the last musical to open passes along a robe to the
most recently opened musical. Each cast embroiders a memento on it
before the robe goes to the next production. When all the space is
used up, a new one is begun and the old robe is retired to the
Museum of the City of New York; the chorus members, meanwhile,
retire to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Horror Movies: ``Carrie: The Musical'' (1988) is widely
considered one of the greatest flops in Broadway history. The play
was a stunning display of both bad taste _ a big dance number
centered around a pig slaughter _ and money ($7 million, all lost).
Its director was Terry Hands, whose most recent credit was
``Macbeth,'' with Grammer.
</P>
<P>
   Knitting: Engaging in this handicraft onstage is taboo,
especially during any big dance scene.
</P>
<P>
   Peepholes: Once considered acceptable on Broadway, where actors
could sneak peeks at the audience. Accidentally banned in 1998 as
part of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's anti-sex campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Sales: According to the superstitions of theater managers, if
the first purchaser of tickets is young, the run will be short. If
the buyer is elderly, it means a long run. By this logic, and the
demographics of Broadway today, every show on Broadway would be a
hit.
</P>
<P>
   Talent Agents Having an agent is considered good luck. Not
having one is considered bad luck. Lately, being Grammer's agent is
considered particularly bad luck.
</P>
<P>
   Television Stars: See above.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-00 1208EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
