<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, July 9, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A surge of warmer and more humid air toward the Northeast on
Sunday will produce clusters of showers and thunderstorms from the
Great Lakes to the northern Appalachians. Clouds will thicken
across much of New England as patches of showers arrive later in
the day. The Middle Atlantic region will notice dim sunshine and
higher humidity, but only isolated storms.
</P>
<P>
   The heat wave in the Southeast will lessen as less humid air
allows for a small drop in temperatures. A few thunderstorms will
erupt over the central Gulf region along an air mass boundary
Sultry conditions will persist in the Plains, but thunderstorms
will form from the southern Rockies to the northeast Plains along
the perimeter of very humid air. The Northwest will become a bit
cooler with more clouds.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: EUROPEAN EXTREMES
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, temperatures rose above 100 degrees across much of
the central Mediterranean as a blistering heat wave entered its
fifth day. Athens, Greece, hit 104 degrees on Wednesday, and Tunis,
Tunisia, rose to 111 on Saturday. Oddly, the surface winds across
most of this region were from the northeast, or the interior of
Europe. As is true in the winter, temperature extremes on this
continent originate from its eastern section, far away from the
moderating influences of the Atlantic Ocean. The heat wave should
lessen slightly early this week as maritime air returns to sections
of southern Europe  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
