</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: MUTANT MASTER HITS L.A. 
</HEADLINE>
   By MAUREEN DOWD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Democrats yearn to be manly.
</P>
<P>
   First Al Gore had his alpha coaching. Then Dick Gephardt gave
lawmakers warrior lessons, screening clips from the movie
``Gladiator'' at the Capitol before the recent Medicare clash with
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The House leader might want to show his gang the ``X-Men''
movie, about superhero mutants who cleverly change color and
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats' very own Mutant Master is getting ready to show
off his latest metamorphosis at the Los Angeles convention. Gore
must reintroduce himself to an electorate already suspicious of his
serial reintroductions. It's tricky, because the question is the
answer. Who is Al Gore? Al Gore is the man who keeps remaking Al
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The reinventor of government can't stop reinventing. But the
national stage is not the place to figure out who you are. Consider
Hillary with her 83 hairdos.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president's story arc doesn't exactly track. First, he
goes on a monthlong ``We're Fat And Happy and Let's Keep the
Prosperity Going Tour,'' trying to get credit for something he
actually deserves some credit for. Then, on Friday, at the very
end, he retools himself as champion of the little guy, bashing big
business _ drug companies.
</P>
<P>
   The Fiery Populist went after the pharmaceutical front group,
Citizens for Better Medicare. Oops. Turns out Gore's message guru,
Carter Eskew (who made a fortune on ads for Big Tobacco), pitched
the group to handle its TV advertising before he joined the Gore
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats watch Gore flopping and yearn for consistency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care if he says he's an Italian Communist,'' says one.
``I just want him to get something he's comfortable with and
believes in, that doesn't come from focus groups, and stop
hand-wringing.''
</P>
<P>
   The truth about political commitment is that people only get
excited about a cause or candidate that stays the same today and
tomorrow and the day after.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore struggles to get into the place he wants to be,'' says
the California Democratic strategist Bill Carrick, ``while Bush is
this 
Southern-fried-Tom-Dewey-stay-out-of-traffic-don't-say-anything-cont
roversial-run-for-an-hour-in-the-middle-of-the-day-and-I-have-to-get
-to-the-ranch-by-the-weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats find themselves in a topsy-turvy world where their
issues and their candidates at the congressional level are stronger
than their presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The governor and the vice president seem frozen in a high school
tableau of the guy in the back of the room throwing spitballs (as
W. used to do at baseball owners' meetings) and the guy up in front
turning in the guy in back for throwing spitballs.
</P>
<P>
   Given the choice between the pious smarty-pants and the amiable
idler, Americans may prefer the latter _ unless the debates show
that his idling has left him grossly unprepared.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's biggest problem is that people don't like to like him,
even when they like him. He comes across as a man who calculates
every gesture. He even checked with Eskew to see if it would look
bad if he baby-sat for his grandson instead of joining his wife and
daughter at the Million Mom March.
</P>
<P>
   People do like to like W., even when they don't like him. This
allows the Texan to behave opportunistically, without seeming as
smarmy as his rival. W. gets to toady to the right wing while
proclaiming his moderation.
</P>
<P>
   How amazing that Gore can't simply body surf the rising economic
tide. Writing about the demand for luxury goods, The Washington
Post reports that orders for yacht charters are up 400 percent.
There's a huge back order on Patek Philippe women's bracelet
watches, selling for $6,250, and men's gold calendar watches,
selling for $26,500.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even Bill Clinton can only muster this about his beloved
protege: ``It's still more likely than not that he will win.''
</P>
<P>
   Former President George Bush told The New York Times' Frank
Bruni on Friday that he thinks his son will prevail, not
necessarily because of his charms, but for the same reason the
father lost to Clinton. ``I think people kind of like change, like
the idea of change from time to time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The clenched vice president should heed the classy ex-president:
Americans enjoy change from time to time. Not moment to moment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-00 1310EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
