<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6538 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-VOICES-ART-90     07-08 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-VOICES-ART-905(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON BOTH SIDES, VIEWS OF SUMMIT ARE SUBDUED 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT1 and 2 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can
purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEL AVIV, Israel _ Last Friday, as they do every week, a group
of Israeli men who were classmates at Balfour Elementary School in
the early days of the state gathered at Cafe Lenzner on bustling
Sheinkin Street for an informal salon.
</P>
<P>
   They drank iced tea, smoked cigarettes, watched girls and
engaged in their familiar routine of banter and political debate.
</P>
<P>
   These men and the friends who joined them have lived Israel's
history and prehistory, fought its various wars, established its
businesses, served in its government, emigrated and reimmigrated.
There is a lawyer, an architect, an economist, and a factory owner
who survived the Holocaust on Schindler's list.
</P>
<P>
   Outsiders might assume that the debate last Friday would be
particularly intense, that these men would be obsessed by the Camp
David summit meeting that begins on Tuesday with the momentous aim
of resolving the bitter Israeli-Palestinian conflict that has
overshadowed their country's existence. But outsiders would be
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had so many moments of truth,'' said Danny Simon, 54,
a businessman who considers himself a leftist. ``We are not naive.
We would never attach too much importance in advance to any one
event. Do we feel on the edge of something historic? We are not
holding our breath. We can only hope that the process keeps inching
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli-Palestinian conflict is the backdrop to life here,
even on Sheinkin Street, the epicenter of Israeli secularism. Young
adults with spiked hair, nose rings and bare midriffs affect a
willful distance from the battles and animosities that defined
their parents' lives, and they do not live elbow-to-elbow with the
conflict like Jerusalemites or settlers.
</P>
<P>
   But everyone in Israel, the West Bank and Gaza is a prisoner of
what President Clinton, announcing the summit meeting, labeled the
``abject dreariness of the pursuit.'' Everyone knows that immutable
deadlines are always broken and that two steps forward are always
followed by one step back. Everyone cares and almost everyone is
afraid to care too much, fearful of having their hopes dashed or
their fears realized.
</P>
<P>
   In a day of interviews throughout Israel and the West Bank, only
the Jewish settlers were treating the summit as a potentially
pivotal event. Only in the settlements _ where children stopped
cars to plaster them with stickers that said, ``Peace, yes!
Suckers, no!'' _ has daily life been altered to plan for what many
see as the most significant political battle of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should we give the Arabs anything?'' said one of the young
settlers, Yishai Cacotai, 14. ``We give them land, they give us
buses that go boom-boom.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, people refused to be distracted by what they saw as
the latest stop on the local train to a lessened conflict, if not
peace. In Ramallah on the West Bank, for instance, behind the
opaque glass of a rare women-only cafe called Privacy, two modern
young Palestinian sisters sat smoking a fruit-flavored water pipe _
an unusual activity for women here. They waved away talk of Camp
David.
</P>
<P>
   ``I follow it closely,'' said Samar Alkour, the cafe owner, who
is 35. ``But I don't go into discussions. Let me tell you about
this peace process: The big men are cooking, and the little people
are eating. We will take what we are served, because we will have
no other choice.''
</P>
<P>
   At the nearby Cafe Brazil, a men-only cafe with thick sawdust on
the floor, one group of men playing cards seemed like the
Palestinian equivalent of the Israeli salon in Tel Aviv, a circle
of longtime companions who finished one another's sentences.
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad Faidi, a hotel owner, laid down an ace of spades,
snorted and said, ``Arafat will go and return without
achievements.'' He was referring to Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian
leader. ``It's all nonsense,'' he muttered, and no one disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   Down the street, at the Sanabel Bakery, Khaled Rabieh, 27,
stacked sugary elephant-ear pastries. He said that he considered
the peace effort to be ``a show'' and that Camp David would be one
of the ``last scenes before the curtain comes down.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabieh's family originally came from a town next to Jaffa,
where, as far as they are concerned, they still own 250 acres of
agricultural land, which he said he routinely visits, parks beside
and stares at with frustrated longing.
</P>
<P>
   Rabieh, like most refugees, believes that if a peace agreement
is achieved, it will be at the refugees' expense. He said that if
the Israelis obtain what they want _ separation from the
Palestinians _ he will not even be able to visit his land. He said
that he looked ahead to Sept. 13, the deadline by which Arafat has
pledged to declare a Palestinian state, as a day more bitter than
sweet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a day when we laugh at ourselves,'' he said. ``It
will be a day when we get a state without power, without
sovereignty. ''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking with profound distrust of the Israelis, Rabieh said he
saw the peace effort as their attempt to eliminate the barriers to
their economic domination of the region.
</P>
<P>
   A world away, in the nearby settlement of Bet Horon, Avi
Weissman, who immigrated 30 years ago from New York, spoke with
equally deep-seated suspicion of the Palestinians' ultimate
intentions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole process of what's called peace,'' he said, ``it
amounts to giving the Arabs a part of our homeland that they can
use as a military base for taking the rest.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Weissman wearily unloaded groceries from his car and trudged up
the terraced slope to his hilltop home of 23 years. Inside the
white-walled, red-roofed house that is typical in the more
suburban-style settlements, he gazed from a window at the seemingly
peaceful landscape of undulating hills, a view of the disputed
territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very, very worried and very, very upset,'' Weissman said.
``With the mood of this government, and the mood of the Israeli
people, you can't feel safe. In my wildest dreams, I can't think
that the Arabs will ever be willing to live in peace with us. And
yet we go to Camp David? Why? Because we have lost our motivation,
we have gotten soft. They are willing to spill their blood, to be
martyrs, but we don't want to lose a single soldier.''
</P>
<P>
   At Cafe Lenzner on Sheinkin Street, it was hard to separate the
strands of serious conversation from the fast-flying repartee.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to know the history of this country?'' said Lutek
Harel, the Holocaust survivor, who owns an airplane-parts
manufacturing business. ``We had nothing. What we have now, we took
it all. If we want to talk about peace, we have to talk about the
people who were here when we arrived. We have no choice but to live
as two people on one land.''
</P>
<P>
   Moti Lenzner, the resident right-winger who is also Harel's
lawyer, hooted. ``I will give back your factory in Jaffa, then! It
belongs to these Arabs you so love.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Give it back!'' Harel said. ``I could use a rest. Maybe I'll
go to Camp David. That sounds like a nice break.''
</P>
<P>
   Simon, the businessman, said the left was afraid that the
situation would disintegrate before it improved. ``Even if
something comes out of Camp David,'' he said, ``things will slip
backward. They always do. It will take a lot of aggravation, a lot
of deaths, a lot of riots, a lot of smoke to get to the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Working hard to get a word in, Yoram Fogel, an architect, was
interrupted by the table's running commentary on the girls walking
by. ``People forget how much progress we have made,'' he said.
``Slowly, slowly, we accept peace. It's a revolution in the life of
Israel. It doesn't matter if Camp David succeeds or fails. It's a
process.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Shilo, 55, an economist, suggested that a partial agreement
could be reached, one that left aside the thornier issues of
Jerusalem and the refugees. But Simon did not think that would be a
good idea. ``Then it will just take more pain, more casualties, and
in the end we will be in the same place,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pushing his glasses up his nose, Lenzner shot back: ``What's the
matter with pain and suffering? Did you forget you are Jewish?''
</P>
<P>
   And in the routine dynamic of the salon, Lenzner was left with
the last word. It is his cafe after all, and he was buying the
drinks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
