<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6563 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-FRANCE-ADMIN-SCHOOL-2     07-08 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-ADMIN-SCHOOL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETPLACE DYNAMICS ERODING FRANCE'S FACTORY FOR BUREAUCRATS 
</HEADLINE>
   By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STRASBOURG, France _ Look carefully at the class pictures in the
lobby of France's National School of Administration and you can
find just about everyone who counts in French politics today _ back
when they all still had hair.
</P>
<P>
   For more than four decades, this school, dedicated to shaping
top students for a life in government, has done just that with
enormous success. Two of France's last three presidents and six of
its last eight prime ministers have been graduates.
</P>
<P>
   It has not been easy to get into this state-subsidized finishing
school for the elite, known here as ENA. The exams are legendary
for their difficulty. The odds of success have sometimes been as
high as 200 to 1. But not today.
</P>
<P>
   In an undeniable sign of all that is changing in France, the
number of applicants to the school has dropped 30 percent in the
last four years, despite the guarantee of a government job on
graduation.
</P>
<P>
   These days, France has perhaps the fastest growing economy in
Europe. The government is privatizing many of its assets. The
French stock market is booming. International mergers seem to occur
every week and successful start-ups are making overnight
millionaires of people who have not gone the traditional routes.
Suddenly it is acceptable to talk openly about making money.
</P>
<P>
   Government work, once considered the epitome of power and
prestige here, is no longer, it seems, so desirable.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is a disaffection with ENA, there is indeed a
revolution going on,'' said Jean d'Ormesson, a prominent French
intellectual and writer. ``All the young ones think only of
starting their own businesses. It's almost dangerous because some
will certainly fail. But there is an energy out there and it
refuses to be contained by bureaucracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Even ENA officials, scrambling to overhaul both the school's
recruitment and its curriculum, feel that the mood in France is
against them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question that today this kind of training looks
less attractive to some young people,'' said Raymond-Francois Le
Bris, the school's director. ``Working for the state seems heavy.
It does not seem to represent the right market values to them.''
</P>
<P>
   In France, ``serving the state'' has always been held highly.
And in the recent past, as the country struggled with a sluggish
economy and double-digit inflation, it was also where the young and
ambitious turned, as long as they could master the rigid
advance-through-tests procedures.
</P>
<P>
   The current crop of ENA students still talk about doing more
with their lives than earning fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few years ago when I had the choice _ private industry or
this _ I decided that I would rather be of service than sell yogurt
or a car,'' said Roland Husson, 24, who would like a career in
diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   But surveys show that France's young people are far more likely
to be in awe of the director of a fledgling Internet company
working out of a maid's room than of the high-powered functionaries
their parents so admired. They are also more often risk takers
ready to bet on their own creativity.
</P>
<P>
   A recent survey of students in a dozen of France's most
prestigious schools found that about 12 percent wanted to start
their own companies as soon as they got out of school. Another 40
percent wanted to start their own business sometime in their life.
Surveys a few years ago showed little such interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty years ago, you just got in the pipeline: there was very
little of the self-made man,'' said Jerome Chapuisat, the director
of the government agency that provides students with information
about educational options. ``We haven't completely destroyed that
system yet. But it is beginning to crumble from the inside.''
</P>
<P>
   While the National School of Administration ponders how to
remake itself, other schools are thriving.
</P>
<P>
   In Paris, for instance, is a private computer and
telecommunications college, known from its initials as EPITA, where
the number of applicants has grown by 25 percent each of the last
three years, even though students must pay about $4,500 a year for
their schooling. The National School of Administration is free.
</P>
<P>
   The corridors of EPITA do not gleam like those at ENA, which is
housed in an artfully renovated 19th-century prison in Strasbourg
not far from the European Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   At EPITA, the worn carpeting buckles. But the classrooms, packed
with computer terminals, never shut down.
</P>
<P>
   The government's effort to reduce the work week to 35 hours is
routinely ridiculed here.
</P>
<P>
   Nicolas Margaine, a second-year EPITA student, said he spent
more time than that in one of the school's labs cruising the
Internet for interesting new sites and ideas.
</P>
<P>
   At EPITA, the dream is to start your own business before
graduation, and to make millions by the time you are 35. ``We are
going for it full speed, no fear,'' Margaine said. ``Doing a
start-up doesn't scare us. It would be great to go like crazy for
10 or 15 years, make a lot of money and then relax.''
</P>
<P>
   Some educators say that France's whole system of education and
promotion, once heavily reliant on tests and schools like ENA, is
beginning to be questioned. Private schools are drawing more and
more students; educators say they are better able to adapt to the
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big schools like ENA are not as recognized as they were,''
said Dominique Herault, an Education Ministry official who writes
reports on educational trends. ``They are not considered as
important as 10 or 20 years ago. The whole spectrum of information
and commerce is seeing an increase. Even the whole idea that
security is a job in a big company is not the same anymore.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As the country's most prestigious school, ENA has faced some of
the harshest criticism. The school was founded by Charles de Gaulle
after World War II. He wanted the very best French minds to fill
out the bureaucracy. The curriculum focused on ordering and
presenting ideas. But in recent years it has come under attack as
an out-of-date institution that produces a group of elites who
think alike, speak alike and protect each other, with little feel
for the average citizen. Directly and indirectly, it has been
blamed whenever the government seems out of touch with real life.
</P>
<P>
   Under the current system, after spending 27 months at the
school, students are offered life-long employment with the
government. In fact, based on their test scores, they were able to
pick whatever job they wanted. They are often in top management
positions by their mid-20s, though they have little or no hands-on
experience.
</P>
<P>
   The school's graduates have lately become the butt of many
jokes. In one, implying that ENA technocrats do not see things very
clearly, a young man stops by a herd of sheep and bets the shepherd
he can count them at one glance. If he can do it, he gets to keep
one. The young man gets the answer right and goes to collect his
winnings. But the farmer offers a counter-bet. If he can tell the
young man what school he attended, he gets to keep his animal. The
young man agrees. ``ENA,'' says the farmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``How did you know?'' asks the young man. ``Because that is my
dog you've got under your arm.''
</P>
<P>
   The school, Le Bris insists, is still doing a good job. But he
has overhauled its recruitment efforts, trying with new living
stipends to reach a more diverse population than in the past. He
has also made changes to the curriculum, including more courses on
international relations, ethics, negotiation and European Union
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most noteworthy, he says, students must now devise and
actually complete a project during their internships in government
agencies. This could mean that they devise schedules for a road
construction plan, or a way of running a department with 10 percent
less staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to get away from that label that we analyze but
we don't actually teach them to put their ideas to work,'' Le Bris
said. ``We want them to have more contact with reality.''
</P>
<P>
   But the changes have not satisfied all the school's critics.
</P>
<P>
   Some say they do not yet go to the core of a system that is
based on advancement through tests. One member of the school's
board of directors, Jacques Julliard, quit recently and gave a copy
of his resignation letter to a weekly magazine. In it, he asked
whether it was normal, ``indeed even conceivable,'' that young
people would, ``through a test, with only their intellectual
abilities on show, be able to get top jobs without any real life
experience.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
