<DOCNO> NYT20000708.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6577 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-AME-WOMEN-BISHOPS-NYT     07-08 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AME-WOMEN-BISHOPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFRICAN METHODIST EPISCOPALIANS MAY VOTE WOMEN AS BISHOPS 
</HEADLINE>
   By LAURIE GOODSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although women outnumber men sitting in the pews of the African
Methodist Episcopal Church and studying in its seminaries, the
denomination has never had a female bishop in its 203-year history.
</P>
<P>
   That may change on Monday, when the AME Church plans to elect
bishops from among a candidate pool that includes two women. Both
women are campaigning using the slogan, ``It's time.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 25,000 leaders of the AME Church, the nation's oldest
predominantly black denomination, are gathering in Cincinnati from
July 5-12 for the church's general conference, which meets every
four years to determine policy and elect department heads and
bishops.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time in the history of the church that women
have had a viable opportunity to be bishop,'' said Bishop William
DeVeaux, president of the church's council of bishops. ``We've had
women run before, but they were in no way considered to have a
chance. There was almost a sense of condescension toward their
candidacy. But now we have women running who are truly viable.''
</P>
<P>
   If the AME Church elects a woman bishop, it would be the first
among the three predominantly black Methodist denominations to do
so, said DeVeaux. The African Methodist Episcopal Zion Church and
the Christian Methodist Episcopal Church have never had women
bishops, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The United Methodist Church became the first American
denomination to elect a woman as bishop in 1981, and the Episcopal
Church consecrated its first woman bishop in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The AME Church traces its history to 1787, when black
churchgoers protesting segregated worship walked out of a Methodist
Episcopal church in Philadelphia. It now has more than 8,000
churches and about 2.3 million members, including 1.5 million in
the United States and most of the rest in Africa, the Caribbean,
Canada and England.
</P>
<P>
   The AME Church has 20 bishops, and at least two are retiring
this year.Among the 41 candidates running for those seats are the
Rev. Vashti Murphy McKenzie, pastor of Payne Memorial AME Church in
Baltimore, and the Rev. Carolyn Tyler Guidry, who as a presiding
elder supervises 19 AME churches in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a stained-glass ceiling in this church, and a lot of
it has to do with sexism,'' McKenzie said in a telephone interview.
``But our church is now recognizing that the women have the talent,
the skills, the degrees, the experience. The women in our church
have more degrees behind their names than you can count.''
</P>
<P>
   Guidry, who ran for bishop four years ago and lost, said she
believed that the church was finally ready for a woman to be
bishop.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, she said by telephone, ``Women had not been in
the positions of presiding elder, or pastors of major churches, and
so had not made a major impact in our denomination. That has
changed in the last 10 years, and Dr. McKenzie and I have become
major players in the church.''
</P>
<P>
   The AME Church began ordaining women as deacons in 1948 and as
ministers in 1960. The church has never had a theological basis for
excluding women from the episcopate, DeVeaux said. But it is only
in recent years that bishops began appointing women ministers to
the large, prominent congregations that have traditionally been the
stepping-stones to bishops' seats, DeVeaux said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we are putting women in key positions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the general conference, 1,800 delegates, including members of
the clergy and laity, will vote in the bishops election. A majority
is needed to elect a bishop, and the vote often takes several
rounds of balloting.
</P>
<P>
   A resolution to set aside one bishop's seat for a woman was
proposed on Friday, while some delegates on the convention floor
cheered and chanted, ``It's about time.'' The resolution was
referred to the Episcopal Committee, which handles matters
concerning bishops.
</P>
<P>
   Jamye Coleman Williams, one of the sponsors of the resolution
and a retired church officer, said: ``In our church, the majority
of members and the majority of seminary enrollees are women. So it
is not fair to deny them full inclusion. It's sort of like the
civil rights battle, where nobody wants to give up power. People
just don't want to relinquish power without a fight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
