<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HOUSING-SHORTAGE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSING SHORTAGE CONFOUNDS A PROSPEROUS NEW YORK CITY 
</HEADLINE>
   By BRUCE LAMBERT  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As it enters the new millennium with restored can-do
bravado, this city has cut crime, welfare and taxes and added jobs
and surpluses. New office towers are rising. City leaders are
dreaming again, planning for a new stock exchange site, a new
Pennsylvania Station, baseball stadiums, a train to the plane, even
a Second Avenue subway.
</P>
<P>
   More than ever, it seems, this thriving city is a great place to
live _ if only you could live here.
</P>
<P>
   But New Yorkers are suffering in the grip of the worst housing
shortage in decades, with soaring prices to match. That verdict is
virtually unanimous among business and real estate executives,
experts in academia, community leaders, planners, politicians and
housing advocates.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who has tried to move recently knows the problem
firsthand. This is the reality of today's market:
</P>
<P>
   _ Across the city, one in four households spends more than half
its income for rent, the Census Bureau says. Vacancy rates are
negligible. Adjusted for inflation, median renter income has
increased 3 percent since 1975, while median rent has increased 33
percent. Middle-class people say they feel priced out of the
market.
</P>
<P>
   _ At the high end, the average cost of Manhattan co-ops and
condominiums south of Harlem has broken the $700,000 barrier.
Multimillion-dollar deals raise few eyebrows.
</P>
<P>
   _ Overcrowding abounds, with families doubled up and immigrants
squirreled away in illegal dwellings carved out of attics,
basements and garages. The stock of rentals for less than $500 a
month has shrunk by 55 percent in eight years.
</P>
<P>
   _ At the lower rungs, the inflation-adjusted value of welfare's
housing allowance has fallen more than half since 1975. The waiting
list for public housing has 130,000 families; the list for rent
vouchers has 215,000. On a typical night, shelters take in nearly
5,000 families and 7,000 single people.
</P>
<P>
   _ Though demand for housing is rising, driven by population
growth, especially immigration, and by more jobs, supply is not
keeping pace. From 1981 to 1999, the city grew by 350,000 people
but added only 42,000 rental apartments. The era of major
construction is over: there is no recent parallel to Lefrak City or
MetLife's Parkchester and Stuyvesant Town. From the modern peak of
60,000 new dwellings in 1963, annual production has slowed to a
trickle. ``We celebrated when we passed the 10,000-unit mark last
year, but in truth we should be building 30,000 or 40,000,'' said
Steven Spinola, president of the Real Estate Board of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Although nearly everyone agrees New York has a housing problem,
there is no consensus on what to do. ``The real question is, what
is the remedy?'' said Peter D. Salins, who has written and lectured
extensively on housing. He has likened the apartment shortage to
``a vast game of musical chairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Edward S. Hochman, chairman of the city's Rent Guidelines Board,
said, ``It's grim out there.'' At a recent meeting, the board heard
the voices behind the statistics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be that rent was one week's salary, but I'm now
dipping into my third week,'' said Vincenza Furst, 63, a working
mother in a $1,200-a-month Greenwich Village apartment. ``I was
born and bred here, I was married here and I raised my son here,
but I may not be able to die here.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's shortage is a slow-motion crisis that has been long in
the making and getting worse, two new reports conclude.
</P>
<P>
   The Coalition for the Homeless has issued ``Housing a Growing
City: New York's Bust in Boom Times'' by Patrick Markee. The other
study, ``Homeward Bound: A 21st Century Affordable Housing Agenda
for New York,'' is being prepared for the Century Foundation and
City University Graduate Center by Martha E. Stark of Baruch
College and Doug Turetsky of United Neighborhood Houses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately,'' the coalition says, ``New York City enters
the new century without a plan to house the next generation of New
Yorkers.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the pessimism, ideas abound. Those who have them tend to
fall into two camps: those who say government should step in, and
those who say it should butt out.
</P>
<P>
   Government is the Problem
</P>
<P>
   Free-market proponents like Salins say New York's complicated
rent laws are a root cause and should be abolished, a move that
tenants' groups oppose.
</P>
<P>
   Other experts focus on cutting building costs. Or they call for
streamlining the maze of municipal codes and the cumbersome
approval process. Some hope for philanthropic help.
</P>
<P>
   New York's regulations are often called the nation's most
complex. ``You've got to make it easier to build stuff,'' said
Howard A. Husock, a housing expert at Harvard's Kennedy School of
Government. These critics call for simplifying rules on zoning,
building, the environment, landmarks and access for the disabled
and land review procedures that invite not-in-my-backyard
resistance. They look approvingly to New Jersey, which has
encouraged rehabilitation of old housing, exempting it from
new-construction codes.
</P>
<P>
   Construction costs here are also the highest in the country.
``My members will build if they can make a profit,'' said Spinola,
the real estate board president. One academic study made 65
proposals to combat corruption, union rules and restrictive codes.
</P>
<P>
   Many experts insist that the city simply needs to find new
places and ways to build, developing industrial zones, for example,
allowing higher-density construction and redeveloping brown fields
_ land that is polluted, but not with toxic waste _ the
long-ignored waterfront, neglected neighborhoods and urban areas
outside the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``The entire middle class does not have to live in Manhattan
south of 96th Street,'' said Michael H. Schill, director of New
York University's real estate and urban policy center.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Government is the Solution
</P>
<P>
   But for all the talk of streamlining government and freeing up
the market, many say the toughest hurdle to adequate housing is
simply lack of money, government money. They call for a broad
thrust by government, through renewed construction, grants,
vouchers, loans and tax breaks, like the deals made for corporate
headquarters and the $255 million awarded to relocate the New York
Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Even some free-market advocates like Arthur Zabarkes, a senior
fellow at the conservative Manhattan Institute, say government aid,
like tax breaks, is vital. ``Without public help, I don't think it
can be done,'' he said. Joseph Strasburg, president of the
landlords' Rent Stabilization Association, said, ``Somebody has got
to make up the difference between housing costs and what some
people can afford.''
</P>
<P>
   Failing to relieve the shortage would be a strategic mistake,
many experts say. ``There's no question that the long-term success
of the city and this region would be seriously hampered,'' said H.
Claude Shostal, president of the nonprofit Regional Plan
Association. After polling major companies, State Comptroller H.
Carl McCall said last fall, ``The scarcity of housing and the high
price is driving employers away and keeping new employers from
coming.''
</P>
<P>
   The president of the New York City Partnership and Chamber of
Commerce, Robert R. Kiley, said, ``Businesses eager to locate or
expand here often go elsewhere and cite the lack of affordable
housing.'' His group has become the city's largest builder of such
dwellings.
</P>
<P>
   The city is bumping up against its debt limit and has rival
needs like the schools, but housing advocates have their eyes on
surpluses at every level. New York would get $337 million if the
Federal Housing Administration devoted its $5 billion surplus to
new housing, the Association for Neighborhood and Housing
Development says.
</P>
<P>
   The Community Service Society wants to revive the pledge of
Mayor Ed Koch and Gov. Mario Cuomo to earmark hundreds of millions
of dollars in Battery Park City revenues for housing.
</P>
<P>
   City and suburban officials have joined tenants to lobby Albany
for more housing. The Manhattan borough president, C. Virginia
Fields, and the City Council speaker, Peter F. Vallone, have called
for a trust fund. Others urge pension fund investments and help
from giant foundations like Ford and Rockefeller.
</P>
<P>
   There is no question that government has cut back drastically.
Spending by the federal Department of Housing and Urban Development
has been down for years. New York state sponsored 125,000
middle-income Mitchell-Lama apartments through the 1970s, including
Co-op City, but none since. Nor has the City Housing Authority
built major new projects.
</P>
<P>
   It is a far cry from the 1980's, when legions of homeless people
and the hulks of abandoned buildings intruded on the city's
conscience, and housing took center stage. Koch and Cuomo responded
with a $5 billion program that provided tens of thousands of
apartments.
</P>
<P>
   Then social issues fell out of favor. The public often equated
housing programs with ``dynamited high-rise hellholes,'' although
New York has well-run public housing that never needed demolition,
said Michael McKee, associate director of the New York State
Tenants and Neighbors Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The housing crisis is in a new phase,'' said Jenny Laurie,
director of the nonprofit Metropolitan Council on Housing.
``Wealthy people are gobbling up apartments, driving rents and
prices sky-high. Middle- and low-income tenants are left to battle
over the scarce crumbs.''
</P>
<P>
   Some say opinions seem to be shifting again. Working with
Habitat for Humanity, the Rev. Dr. Thomas K. Tewell of Fifth Avenue
Presbyterian Church said that the lack of housing ``is something
that I believe breaks the heart of God.'' Archdeacon Michael S.
Kendall, the housing chairman of the Commission of Religious
Leaders of New York City, said the mayor and the governor had been
receptive.
</P>
<P>
   And despite past retrenchment, myriad modest programs survive.
``The city and state have really come around in the last two
years,'' said Donald A. Capoccia, a builder who co-founded the
nonprofit New York State Association for Affordable Housing. But he
conceded that the efforts were only making dents in the huge need.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling New York's responses to past housing challenges, Lewis
Rudin, a developer for 53 years and chairman of the Association for
a Better New York, said, ``We just need some enlightened,
forward-looking political leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a point the governor's housing commissioner, Joseph B.
Lynch, would not dispute. ``Government,'' he said, ``may never
again have the opportunity to address the housing crisis as
effectively as it can in this era of economic expansion, record
surpluses and unprecedented prosperity _ all of which, ironically,
have contributed to the overheated housing market.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
