u s BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-NYT &LR;      07-08 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENUS WILLIAMS LIGHTS UP THE CENTER COURT
</HEADLINE>
  By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ The very instant a desperate forehand
volley slipped off Lindsay Davenport's racket, the mask cracked.
Venus Williams' furrowed brow and serious scowl gave way to pure
joy.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, she was on air, leaping across the lawn of Center
Court like a child twirling through a backyard sprinkler. She had
done it, just like her eccentric but clairvoyant father always
predicted. As Williams bounded up the stairs and climbed up to the
edge of the friends box to embrace her sister, Serena, she was
making a historic romp.
</P>
<P>
   With her 6-3, 7-6 (3) victory, Williams not only became the
first African-American woman to win Wimbledon since Althea Gibson
in 1958, Venus and Serena became the first sisters in tennis
history to each own a Grand Slam title. After Venus Williams
scampered back down to the court, she received the champions plate.
With her long wingspan, Venus Williams held it up high over her
head.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better than the men's cup in my opinion,'' Venus Williams
proclaimed.
</P>
<P>
   Spinning around for the cameras, Williams glowed as brightly at
the plate with a full-moon smile. In the background of Williams'
moment, her father and sister were close to tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really great because I've been working so hard all my
life to be here,'' said Williams as she stood on court. ``It's
strange. I'd go to bed at night and I'd dream I'd won a Grand Slam,
but when I woke up, there was the nightmare. Now, I don't have to
wake up like that anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Venus Williams isn't the old sister who hadn't won. She
isn't the one who set the stage for Serena, only to be a co-star.
She and Serena are part of a duo that threatens to overwhelm the
tennis scene for years to come. It was all part of their father's
unorthodox plan. In the friends box, Richard Williams held up a
sign that said, ``We love you Duke and Dutchess.'' Beneath the
hoopla, a dejected but gracious Davenport stood next to her
opponent and joined in on Williams appreciation day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew Venus was playing well throughout the tournament,''
Davenport said. ``She was too strong at the end, and I congratulate
her on winning her first Grand Slam. Getting to the finals was a
great achievement for me, and I'm going to walk away holding my
head high.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Davenport never had a chance to play her best. Her
best opportunity to stop Venus Williams' momentum came in the 10th
game of the second set. Williams, serving for the match, seemed to
rush through her motions. After two double faults, Davenport then
benefited from a loose forehand by Williams that sailed long. The
second set was even at 5-5.
</P>
<P>
   After each held serve, Williams took over the tiebreaker.
Davenport saved one match point with a service winner at 3-6. But
on match point, Davenport had to race forward for a short ball but
could not do anything with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think her win against Martina Hingis got her over the
hump,'' Davenport said. ``I was hopeful for a little more out of
myself. I tried hard and I was one or two points away from turning
it around. At the end, in the tiebreaker, she won the last few
points and that's what you have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Both players were left stirring in the locker room deep within
the stadium as a light drizzle delayed the start by about 20
minutes. For awhile, Davenport stood next to referee Alan Mills at
the doorway to the court, watching the skies with a chuckle or two.
In the friends box, Richard Williams, was keeping himself busy with
a magic marker and a grease board he brought.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hello, Mrs. Williams, I miss and love you,'' Richard Williams
wrote, showing his message to the cameras in hopes that his wife,
Oracene, would see if from Florida. Beside Richard Williams, Venus'
little sister, Serena, smiled at her father's busy work.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, Venus Williams must have been applying a furrowed
brow and a hard stare. From the moment she appeared on the court,
she could have shattered mirrors with her mental focus. There was
no hint of a smile, no ounce of giddiness, no look of childlike awe
as she barely surveyed her surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   Once she endured a nervous first game filled with overkill on
her ground strokes, once she absorbed an opening break of serve,
Williams began to harness her energy. Methodically, she began
defusing Davenport's power by running her from side to side with
penetrating backhands that crushed the white lines with uncanny
accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   By forcing Davenport to lunge and hit a short ball off a
desperate get, Williams then pounced on any short ball at midcourt
with the zeal of a cat on yarn. To get to a break point during the
fourth game of the first set, Williams used her racket like a
remote control as she ran Davenport from side to side until she
either found an opening for a winner or her opponent missed.
</P>
<P>
   Worn out from the pace, Davenport sent a forehand into the net
to give Williams a 3-1 lead. This trend left Davenport searching
for relief. She spent the entire first set waiting for the steam on
Williams' shot to die, but it wouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   At times, Davenport looked dispirited. She mumbled to herself,
seemed bothered by her back that had given her problems coming into
this Grand Slam, and allowed Williams to set the tone for every
rally. In the second set, Davenport pushed Williams just a bit, but
for every break she grabbed, she gave another back.
</P>
<P>
   ``You live to see another day,'' Davenport said. ``She deserves
to celebrate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
