<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAYNE'S ABSENCE IS DULY NOTED BY NFL 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE FREEMAN  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ron Dayne, the New York Giants' first-round draft pick, has
managed to get his National Football League career off to a rocky
start. He has committed two no-no's.
</P>
<P>
   First, he missed the league-sponsored rookie symposium this
month that is arguably the best program in sports aimed at teaching
life skills to its new players. Which leads to Dayne's second
mistake _ by skipping the mandatory symposium, he has irritated the
league.
</P>
<P>
   Getting on the NFL's bad side at such an early stage is not a
great career move. Besides, Dayne missed perhaps the most inspiring
symposium since the program began four years ago. His teammate,
quarterback Kerry Collins, spoke of how alcoholism almost ruined
his life. Dayne missed the onetime accused murderer Ray Lewis, the
Indianapolis Colts linebacker, who warned rookies to be careful of
the friends they choose. And he missed St. Louis Rams linebacker
Leonard Little, who talked about how one night of drunken driving
on his birthday cost a woman her life.
</P>
<P>
   The league is disappointed in Dayne because, as a Heisman Trophy
winner, the NFL had hoped the Wisconsin running back would set a
better example. Dayne was the only rookie out of more than 250
invitees to miss the entire symposium.
</P>
<P>
   After the event, Dayne presented a note to league officials from
a doctor in Wisconsin stating he did not attend because he had an
earache. The NFL is not buying it, and unless Dayne presents a
better excuse, he faces a possible $10,000 fine. Several years ago,
the San Diego Chargers rookie quarterback Ryan Leaf skipped the
bulk of the symposium without a legitimate excuse and was fined
$10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Dayne cold not be reached for comment about his absence. His
agent did not return a phone call.
</P>
<P>
   The league stresses to the rookies soon after they are drafted
that attendance at the program is mandatory, and that it could be
the most important group of meetings they will attend in their
careers.
</P>
<P>
   At Wisconsin, Dayne was known for being a solid citizen off the
field. He is definitely not a troublemaker. Quite the opposite. But
Dayne's absence, assuming his reason for not attending was a simple
ear infection, should not be minimized.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL is constantly being criticized, especially by the news
media, for not doing enough to stop the cycle of violence involving
its players. But the symposium is a proactive step by the league, a
road map that, if followed, should keep players out of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   So, when arguably the most high profile rookie from the last
draft class skips the session it is understandable if the NFL
becomes bothered. Because in the highly unlikely event that Dayne
runs into trouble, the league will be blamed. But it was Dayne who
did not take advantage of a valuable resource, the rookie
symposium.
</P>
<P>
   This year's symposium is especially important to the league
because of the rash of recent legal problems for its players.
Harold Henderson, chairman of the NFL's Management Council, decided
to put the troubles to good use. He invited players who had been
arrested and charged with various criminal acts to give advice to
the rookies on how not to fall into the same traps.
</P>
<P>
   People in attendance said one of the best speakers was Collins,
the Giants' starting quarterback and former No. 1 draft pick of
Carolina. Collins told the rookies that his battles with alcohol
almost cost him his career. Collins, with the players riveted to
his every word, said alcoholism led to him making the infamous
racial remark to a black former Panthers teammate, which Collins
says he made in jest. After that incident, which made national
headlines, Collins said he was never able to gain the respect of
his Carolina teammates again. The Panthers eventually cut their
ties with Collins.
</P>
<P>
   Collins explained that the Giants gave him a second chance, and
he plans to make the most of the opportunity. The rookies
appreciated Collins' brutal honesty and gave him, and other members
of the panel, a rousing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   The symposium brings real players to talk about real problems
and offers real solutions. The idea is to head off any potential
problems, especially since, according to Henderson, statistics show
that four rookies will be arrested this year. That number will
increase to 12 in players' second year.
</P>
<P>
   The symposium features skits by professional actors, panel
discussions and video presentations. There are sessions regarding
finance, dealing with the news media, gambling, labor relations and
insurance. The rookies are told the league will do free background
checks on potential investments, so the players are protected from
unscrupulous financiers. The league says that last year alone
players were cheated out of $16 million because of fraudulent
schemes.
</P>
<P>
   Top Official to Retire
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Jerry Seeman announced that this season will be his
last after 10 years as the NFL's head of officiating. In many ways,
Seeman, who spent 16 years officiating games, became one of the
most important, and recognizable, personalities in the sport. The
league has not yet found a replacement.
</P>
<P>
   Titans Wooing Reggie White
</P>
<P>
   The Tennessee Titans recently received permission to try to pry
the Hall of Fame sack artist Reggie White out of retirement. White,
friends maintain, is in fabulous shape, and the Titans have a solid
chance of getting him because White and coach Jeff Fisher are
close. Fisher was the defensive coordinator when White and Fisher
were with the Philadelphia Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   But make no mistake about it: White is planning to explore his
options. Other teams are interested in him, and White will have his
choice of several teams.
</P>
<P>
   White may still have plenty left to give on the field. It was
just two years ago that he led the NFC with 16 sacks. But White is
still not completely sure about whether he should play again, his
friends say.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Titans, who are expected to sign running back
Eddie George to a lucrative contract extension in the coming weeks,
may not have a ton of cash to give White, they probably have the
best chance of snagging him. They envision White as a tutor to the
young phenomenon Jevon Kearse.
</P>
<P>
   Deferred Riches
</P>
<P>
   What if your employer took a significant portion of your salary,
put it in a money market-type trust fund, and said you would
receive it only after your term of employment expired, and only if
you were a good citizen, and only if you did not withhold your
services in any way?
</P>
<P>
   That is basically the type of deal Miami cornerback Sam Madison
agreed to recently. The question is _ will other teams follow in
presenting such demands in contract offers?
</P>
<P>
   Madison, one of the best cover corners in the game, signed a
seven-year, $54 million deal. He agreed to put $5 million of his
$11 million bonus in a trust that will earn interest. The catch is
that the Dolphins can get back the prorated portion of the $5
million if Madison defaults on the contract.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, if Madison does not hold out, or retire, or get
suspended for an entire season because of off-field problems, then
he will get the money back at the end of the contract, with
interest, which could be as much as $20 million, his agent, Gene
Burrough, said.
</P>
<P>
   If Madison is injured, or dies, the trust stays intact.
</P>
<P>
   It is a novel idea. The team is happy because it is protected,
somewhat, from a player holding out or being lost for a season
because of a drug suspension or an arrest. The player, in turn, is
practically guaranteed to have money when his career is over.
</P>
<P>
   The only concern, and it is something the players association
will definitely address, is that the team has a massive amount of
control over a player's finances. The union may not fight these
types of contracts, but it will definitely make some noise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
