<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL NOTEBOOK: A .400 HITTER ISN'T BEYOND POSSIBILITY 
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the years have passed _ it's 59 since the last one _ the
likelihood of a .400 hitter has dwindled. Some players have
threatened, Larry Walker hitting .379 last season, Tony Gwynn .394
in the strike-shortened 1994 season; going back a few more years,
George Brett .390 and Rod Carew .388. But the first digit in each
case was still a 3.
</P>
<P>
   Now arises a development that regenerates the prospect of having
someone attain that lonesome plateau, which hasn't been breached
since Ted Williams hit .406 in 1941. Entering Saturday's schedule,
11 players _ six in the National League, five in the American _
were hitting .350 or higher.
</P>
<P>
   Only twice in the past 10 seasons, Elias Sports Bureau research
shows, have as many as seven players reached the All-Star Game
break at .350 or higher. In the first three seasons of the '90s, a
total of two players achieved that status at this time of the
season, and only two years ago, no National Leaguers and only two
American League players batted .350 or better before the break.
Bernie Williams was the leading hitter then, his average .353.
</P>
<P>
   Nomar Garciaparra of Boston was this season's leading hitter
before play Saturday, batting .386. Todd Helton of Colorado, who
for much of the early part of the season was over .400, was next at
.385. The Montreal Expos had two players in the .370s, Jose Vidro
and Vladimir Guerrero. Vidro was one of three second basemen in the
group, Luis Castillo of Florida and Jeff Kent of San Francisco
being the others. And there were two catchers, Ivan Rodriguez of
Texas and Mike Piazza of the Mets, who were also the top
vote-getters in their respective leagues in the All-Star Game
balloting.
</P>
<P>
   The hitters and their high averages have generally been
overlooked with the focus on the increase in home runs. But the
same factors that are said to be involved in home run inflation
appear to fuel the higher batting averages, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only is the ball juiced, but it's fatter than it used to
be,'' Sandy Alderson, baseball's chief of baseball operations, said
jokingly. Then Alderson, who after recent tests blessed the balls
as no different from last year's, ticked off the real reasons he
and others see as being behind the increase in high hitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can talk about the smaller strike zone,'' he said,
``stronger players, lighter bats leading to better bat control,
dilution of pitching, smaller ballparks, smaller not only in the
sense that something is going over the wall more frequently but
also off the wall more frequently, less foul territory.''
</P>
<P>
   Syd Thrift, head of baseball operations for the Baltimore
Orioles and a longtime student of hitters, said he believed much of
the hitting improvement stemmed from preparation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hitters have prepared themselves more effectively to be
better hitters with the aid of technology and technique training by
hitting coaches plus their own abilities,'' Thrift said. ``All
those top hitters use the whole field. They are much more
proficient hitters. They don't try to pull the ball. The hitters
show a lot of discipline. They wait longer, they get good pitches,
they take pitchers deep into the count.''
</P>
<P>
   The pitchers have to accept their share of the change, Thrift
added. ``I think the pitching, because of expansion, is inferior,''
he said. ``I think there are pitchers in the major leagues right
now who are 3, 4, 5 starters on some teams who would not be in the
major leagues when you go back in previous times.''
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles executive also cited improved ballpark lighting as
allowing hitters to see the ball better. But he didn't omit the
ball itself from his list of reasons for higher averages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not certain the baseball is not different,'' he said,
despite the test results. ``The surface seems to be different. It
seems to be tighter and harder from a feel standpoint. How much of
a factor that is I have no way of knowing.''
</P>
<P>
   However the factors are figured, Thrift said it ``certainly
appears'' that hitters could be headed for .400.
</P>
<P>
   Alderson said prediction of a .400 hitter is ``speculation maybe
for a statistician,'' but he added, ``That's a possibility,''
citing Helton as an example of a possible .400 hitter. Alluding to
the Rockies' hitter-friendly home at Coors Field, Alderson said:
``Not only does the ball carry well, but a line drive hitter with
an expansive area can do very well there. I think it's certainly a
possibility. As averages creep up from .300 to .350, who's to say
we won't see someone take that extra step.''
</P>
<P>
   That New Voice
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's the voice John Hart was talking about.
</P>
<P>
   When the Cleveland Indians fired Mike Hargrove as their manager
last October after he led them to five division championships and
two World Series but no World Series championships, Hart, the
general manager, said the team needed ``a new voice coming from the
clubhouse'' and named Charlie Manuel, the Indians' batting coach,
as the new manager.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, with the Indians 10{ games out of the position in
the standings to which they had become accustomed, Manuel spoke. He
announced to the players that their Ping-Pong table was being
removed from the clubhouse, as were two cushy couches. And one more
thing, he said: no more card games in the clubhouse, either.
</P>
<P>
   Manuel said ``these things'' distracted from the goal of
winning.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians, who hadn't been so far from first place since the
1993 season ended, won all of their division championships under
Hargrove with the Ping-Pong table.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Midseason Tumbles
</P>
<P>
   Despite winning only 18 games and losing 28 in an eight-week
span, the Yankees did not tumble out of the American League East
race. Some other teams were not so fortunate.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cleveland. The Indians, from May 23 through July 1, won 18 and
lost 22, plummeting from half a game behind the Chicago White Sox
(28-11) to 11 back.
</P>
<P>
   _ Texas. The Rangers, beginning June 6, lost nine games in a row
and through July 2 had a 7-16 record. In that four-week period they
plunged from one percentage point behind Seattle (18-7) to 10 games
back.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cincinnati. The Reds were half a game ahead of St. Louis on
the morning of June 5. In the next month the Reds lost 19 of 28
games and fell 10 games behind the Cardinals (19-8).
</P>
<P>
   A Carpenter's Story
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees tried Jake Westbrook, Ben Ford and Ed Yarnall. The
Arizona Diamondbacks tried Geraldo Guzman. The four players are
among any number of pitchers who have been summoned in desperation
from the minor leagues this season as teams have tried to plug
holes in their starting rotations.
</P>
<P>
   In the Yankees' case, their trio of rookies have started a total
of five games, and they have lost four. They won the fifth, against
Baltimore last Thursday, because their hitters somehow overcame the
seven-run deficit Yarnall helped create. In their five starts,
Westbrook, Ford and Yarnall gave up 29 hits and 11 walks in 13 2/3
innings, allowing 24 earned runs for a 15.80 earned run average.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the Diamondbacks' initial experience with Guzman.
Deciding to demote Omar Daal and his 2-9 record (for a first-place
team) to the bullpen, the Diamondbacks promoted Guzman from Tucson
of the Pacific Coast League for their game Thursday night in
Houston. He answered their call with a 2-1 victory in which he
permitted one run and four hits in eight innings.
</P>
<P>
   The 27-year-old Guzman is no ordinary rookie.
</P>
<P>
   Originally signed by the Montreal Expos, Guzman pitched for
their team in the Dominican Republic in 1990 and 1991. Plagued by
shoulder problems, he quit the game and became a carpenter, a trade
he worked for the next seven years. Last year he decided he wanted
to play again, and Junior Noboa, the Diamondbacks' Latin America
scouting coordinator, helped place him with a team in Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   When he returned home after the season, he was working out at
the Diamondbacks' academy in the Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw him throw and we signed him,'' Sandy Johnson, the
team's assistant general manager, said. ``He pitched in the winter
league and he kept pitching better and better. Rather than taking a
chance on losing him in the draft the way he was throwing, we put
him on the 40-man roster.''
</P>
<P>
   Guzman looked no less impressive in spring training this year,
Johnson said. But the Diamondbacks didn't want to rush him. They
initially made him a middle reliever for El Paso of the -Class AA
Texas League, then moved him up to closer. ``Then we put him in the
rotation and he handled that well,'' Johnson related. ``He kept
getting better and better.''
</P>
<P>
   On to Tucson, where he reeled off a 4-1 record with a 1.42
earned run average and 23 hits, 10 walks and 44 strikeouts in 38
innings. When the Diamondbacks needed another starter, he was the
obvious choice. He made it more obvious with his performance
against the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   Even more obvious than that is the discovery that teams have
been going about it all wrong in trying to develop pitchers. They
have done it by having their young prospects pitch. Instead, they
should just give the kids a hammer and tell them to swing it for a
few years, then come back and pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Rules Might Change
</P>
<P>
   Only future seasons will determine if Mark Johnson and Chad
Alexander ever make an impact on the outcome of games, but without
having played enough to make themselves even faintly familiar
household names, they are the reason baseball officials are
considering a change in the rule governing the annual December
draft of minor league players.
</P>
<P>
   The Detroit Tigers plucked pitcher Johnson from the Yankees and
the Seattle Mariners took outfielder Alexander from Houston last
December. Popular thinking says a drafted player has to stay on the
drafting team's 25-man major league roster or be offered back to
his original team for half of the $50,000 draft price. But the
Tigers and the Mariners, working within the rules, found a way to
retain their players but in the minor leagues.
</P>
<P>
   They placed the players on unconditional-release waivers, then
signed them to minor league contracts after they went unclaimed and
became free agents. The Mariners took that route with Alexander
last February, the Tigers with Johnson in the last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees officials were stunned when the Tigers made their move
with Johnson, who pitched in nine games for them before they placed
him on waivers. The Yankees could have claimed the 25-year-old
right-hander, but they didn't want to have to put him on their
40-man roster. The Tigers counted on that reluctance when they
asked for waivers.
</P>
<P>
   The practice, however, has caught the attention of major league
officials, who are concerned it could undermine the integrity of
and jeopardize the draft. A change in the rules may be
forthcoming. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
