<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEPOT-JOBS0709-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New hiring tool at Home Depot
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A computerized kiosk has become Home Depot's star
recruiter as the retailer tries to find an army of workers to fill
its growing chain of warehouse stores.
</P>
<P>
   The home improvement giant needs to tackle what seems like a
nerve-racking project in this tight U.S. labor market.
Atlanta-based Home Depot plans to open about 900 stores over the
next three years, and it will have to hire more than 200,000
workers to do that. Currently, new stores open on the average of
one every 43 hours.
</P>
<P>
   No problem, says Home Depot.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to a new automated procedure, the retailer has turned the
hiring process into a near-science. By the time a store manager
interviews an applicant for a job, the candidate has survived a
battery of questions about scruples and work habits.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot lets its new job kiosks do most of the asking. Sure,
Big Orange wants to know if you've ever stolen from your employer,
or if you've recently been in a fistfight on the job. But what
managers are really excited about is a computerized test that
gauges how customer-savvy applicants are. In 70 or so questions,
Home Depot says it gets a good inkling whether the candidate would
make a good employee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our managers say they're noticing a big difference in the
quality of people they're hiring,'' said Al Frost, director of
management development.
</P>
<P>
   The kiosks, which cost $10 million to install at the retailer's
1,000 stores around the country, have been a boon to human
resources, said Frost, who began developing the system four and a
half years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Frost, an industrial psychologist, wanted a way to find
industrious workers who wouldn't shy away from Home Depot's gung-ho
culture. The best way to do that, he said, was find the company's
best sales associates and build a test around them.
</P>
<P>
   Store managers and supervisors studied and evaluated nearly 500
employees on the job. The employees were then quizzed with an early
version of the employment test to see how their performance
evaluations correlated to their answers about customer service,
conscientiousness and overall work ethics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who passed the test knew more about products, took more
initiative, and were more dependable,'' Frost said. ``They rated 14
percent better on overall performance, which is a huge number. If
you can make a 14 percent improvement in someone's productivity,
that's a big impact on the bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   But before applicants take the test, they get a feel for what
it's like to work in Home Depot's noisy warehouse stores. Each
kiosk shows a seven-minute video of real life on the job.
</P>
<P>
   With forklifts beeping in the background, a 30-something woman
in an orange apron warns, ``There are no quiet little cubicles
around here. Our warehouse environment is hectic. . . you are
literally on your feet all day.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of the video is that we don't want applicants being
surprised,'' Frost said. ``They need to know that their feet may
hurt because they're working on concrete floors, or that it's
visually distracting because there are so many customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a high turnover rate (before the kiosk program) because
people were shocked once they started working,'' he said. ``We want
to tell people it's a great company and a great opportunity, but
it's a tough job.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, turnover has dropped more than 11 percent, Frost
said.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot's financial success, stock history and corporate lore
of lowly employees-turned-millionaires has given the retailer an
edge in recruiting. While some retailers have held back on growth
plans because they can't find enough workers, Home Depot's main
concern is picking the best employees out of the thousands that it
turns away, Frost said.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot gets an average of 1,000 to 1,500 applicants when it
opens a store, said David Hauck, a manager of information systems.
Each store employs about 250 people.
</P>
<P>
   ``With good advertising, we've gotten as many as 10,000
applications for a single store,'' Frost said.
</P>
<P>
   Because the kiosks are networked to a central database,
applications can be shared with all stores within a market. When
good candidates apply at a store that's not hiring, managers from
other stores in the area will contact them and ask if they're
willing to commute, Frost said.
</P>
<P>
   That's part of the reason Home Depot isn't having a problem
keeping its 34 stores staffed in its hometown, said spokesman Don
Harrison. Metro Atlanta's base of stores gives it an edge over
newer markets that may only have one or two stores, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to bundle up (paper) applications for people
that applied at Woodstock and take them over to Alpharetta,''
Harrison said.
</P>
<P>
   In the total chain, nearly 850,000 people have applied since
Home Depot began installing kiosks in early 1998. The retailer
hired about 106,000 of that pool.
</P>
<P>
   There are pockets of the country, such as Minnesota, that are
tough because of extremely low unemployment rates, Frost said. But
a new national recruiting campaign, which includes the retailer's
first ``help wanted'' ad on TV, has doubled and sometimes
quadrupled the number of applicants, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the kiosks, we have a quantitative way to track the
number of applicants because we know exactly when and where they
applied,'' Frost said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
