<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Low fares out there if you look
 &HT;    By Ray Marcano
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ An airline trip from Cincinnati to Washington for
$77 _ round trip.
</P>
<P>
   A trip from Columbus to Phoenix _ midweek, without a Saturday
stay _ for $249 round trip.
</P>
<P>
   It's still possible to get really cheap airline tickets, even
with companies adding fuel and other surcharges. All it takes is a
lot of persistence.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines change prices as often as Ohio weather changes in June,
so to get the cheapest fares, it's important to follow the
following steps:
</P>
<P>
   _ Be prepared to buy immediately. Prices change quickly and low
fares sell out so fast they may not be available again if you let
them slide. I knew I had to make a trip to Phoenix in August, so I
started scouting for fares early. I snared the $249 round-trip,
nonstop airfare in April; the same flight on the same airline today
costs $435. Sharp travelers know when they're getting a bargain. If
you see one, jump at it.
</P>
<P>
   _ Be prepared to look again and again and again. If you don't
see the fares you like, look every day to see if they change. They
will. Identify at least three Web sites to check, under the theory
that they offer the best fares possible. My favorite three:
www.travelocity.com, www.bestfares.com and www.lowestfare.com.
Travelocity is the easiest and cleanest to use, though
bestfares.com has a wider selection.
</P>
<P>
   Priceline.com might not be such a good deal for airline tickets
anymore because the service adds on too many fees _ a $20 fuel
surcharge, airport taxes that range from $10 to $38 a ticket and a
$5 processing fee. At the minimum, you have to count on $35 in fees
on top of your bid. Read the Web site carefully and understand the
rules before bidding.
</P>
<P>
   TIME TO LOOK AHEAD
</P>
<P>
   We're halfway through the year, so it's time to start looking
for Thanksgiving and Christmas holiday travel bargains. Airfares
are generally much higher during the Thanksgiving and Christmas
weeks. One tip: Consider traveling a week before the holiday, when
fares are cheaper. If you have to go during a holiday week, be
prepared to pad the travel budget.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
