<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clock radio wakes sleepers gently
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ If you find a regular alarm clock or clock radio
too jarring in the morning, Philips Consumer Electronics may have
an answer for you: a clock radio and CD player that gradually
increases the volume of the alarm buzzer or music to wake the
sleeper gently.
</P>
<P>
   The Philips AJ3965 CD Clock Radio has an AM/FM digital tuner and
a CD player so users can choose between listening to radio stations
or to their favorite recordings.
</P>
<P>
   It offers dual settings so two people can set it for different
wake-up times. It also offers a weekend sleeper function: The alarm
will sound on weekdays but not on weekends, if the user chooses.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Gentle Wake'' feature can be used in reverse as a sleep
timer. The user sets the unit for sleep mode and the radio or CD
player starts at full volume and gradually decreases until it shuts
down. That provides music while the user is falling asleep but
silence later to avoid disturbing the user after he or she is
asleep.
</P>
<P>
   The time is displayed in large, blue numbers that are easily
seen from a distance. The AJ3965 has a built-in power backup system
that retains alarm and time settings during brief power outages.
</P>
<P>
   The Philips clock radio won a Best of Show award in the personal
electronics category at the International Consumer Electronics Show
in January. It went on sale in May and should be available for
about $89.99 at most Target, Circuit City and Sears stores.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
