<HEADER>
A6638 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-X-MEN0709-COX     07-08 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-X-MEN0709-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    And now for X-Men the movie
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Step into any store that sells comics, and
casually mention X-Men. You'll be quickly surrounded by excited
fans recounting their favorite X-Men tales and speculating about
the movie that opens Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Marvel Comic heroes haven't had the pop-culture
visibility of ``Star Wars'' or ``Star Trek,'' the X-Men have
dominated the world of comic books for most of the 1980s and 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up with the X-Men,'' said Floyd Taylor, as he hung out
recently with other fans at the Bookery Fantasy comic, game and
video store. ``When I was a teen-ager I felt alienated like they
were, and I really identified with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now my son and daughter are excited about them, and we're all
looking forward to the movie.''
</P>
<P>
   The X-Men originated in Marvel Comics in 1963 as a team of six
genetic mutants with bizarre superpowers. The X-Men universe has
grown in scope and complexity over the years until now the cast
includes more than 200 mutants.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a soap opera with lasers,'' said Jason Parker, games
manager for the Bookery Fantasy. ``The characters have personal
lives, and their relationships change over time.''
</P>
<P>
   The basic story line also changes. ``Sometimes thd you'll
realize that character's whole history has changed,'' Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   To those outside the world of comic fandom, the hype and
excitement surrounding the movie may come as a surprise. But in the
mid-1990s, Marvel was publishing about 10 X-Men-related comic
titles each month, and they consistantly held more than half the
positions on the top 10 comic sales lists.
</P>
<P>
   The comics experienced another boost in 1993 when Fox started
airing a weekly animated version of X-Men. The series quickly
became a hit with children, but it had a loyal following on college
campuses and among other young adult comic fans.
</P>
<P>
   So if you're unfamiliar with the X-Men but are interested in
seeing this year's science-fiction blockbuster _ titled, naturally,
X-Men _ here's a little background from Bookery Fantasy regulars
Taylor, Parker and Greene County Sheriff's Deputy Jeff Thomas, also
a fan:
</P>
<P>
   _ The setting: X-Men adventures take place on Earth and are
usually set in contemporary times. A small percentage of the human
population are mutants carrying an ``X gene'' that gives them
special powers. The powers usually don't kick in until the mutants
reach puberty, and the people affected don't realize they are
mutants until they start levitating their schoolbooks or seeing
through locker-room walls. Normal humans mistrust mutants, and they
are persecuted and sometimes killed when their powers emerge.
</P>
<P>
   _ Heroic leader: Dr. Charles Xavier, also known as Professor X,
is the world's most powerful telepath, and he can both read minds
and project his thoughts into the minds of others. Xavier, who is
paralyzed below the waist, develops a machine that allows him to
detect mutants like himself anywhere in the world. He gathers them
under the guise of recruiting gifted youth for a special school and
trains them to control their powers and use them for the good of
humanity. He has a vision of normal humans and mutants living
together cooperatively. His students become the heroic X-Men.
</P>
<P>
   _ Villains: Erik Lehnscherr was imprisoned in a Nazi
concentration camp as a boy, and the experience convinced him that
mankind is inherently evil. As he matured he developed intense
magnetic powers and christened himself Magneto. Magneto believes
normal humans will wipe out mutants if given the chance, so he
plots to strike first, making mutants rulers of the world. He heads
the Brotherhood of Evil Mutants, which includes the hulking
Sabretooth, the shape-shifting Mystique and Toad, owner of a
20-foot tongue.
</P>
<P>
   _ Love triangle: Scott Summers and Jean Grey are members of the
original X-Men team and have always been romantically linked.
Summers is Cyclops, who shoots lasers from his eyes, and he acts as
the team's field commander. Jean Grey, once called Marvel Girl, has
telepathic and telekinetic powers. Logan was introduced more
recently, and as Wolverine he has incredible healing powers, a
super-strong metallic skeleton and retractable, knife-like claws.
While Summers is a classic good guy, Logan is a sometimes surly
loner who has trouble controlling his temper and working with the
team. But there's a strong animal attraction between Logan and
Grey.
</P>
<P>
   _ Other X-Men: In the current movie, Ororo Munroe fights
alongside Summers, Grey and Logan as Storm, a mutant who can
control the weather. Also introduced is the mutant teen Rogue, who
can absorb the abilities and memories of anyone she touches. Most
of the X-Men characters are left out of the movie, but there's lots
of buzz about an expanded cast for the sequel that may feature
Sentinels, robots designed to hunt down and kill mutants.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
