<HEADLINE>
SOUTH AFRICA CREATES AN ANTI-AIDS CAMPAIGN THAT MINCES NO WORDS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN.: Calif.)   (Eds: This story contains some sexually explicit references.) 
 By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURBAN, South Africa _ ``My boyfriend just wants sex,'' ``The
naked truth,'' and ``Oral sex.'' And underneath: ``Talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   These and similar messages have sprung up in recent months on
billboards along South Africa's main highways, on trains, near
schools and in cities and rural areas as part of a campaign to
encourage young people to talk freely about sex and the risks of
teen-age pregnancy, AIDS and other sexually transmitted diseases.
</P>
<P>
   The erotic and hard-hitting phrases are part of a down-to-earth
campaign aimed at reducing by half the rate of infection from HIV,
the AIDS virus, in South Africa in five years. The 4.2 million
HIV-infected people in South Africa represent the largest such
group in the world.
</P>
<P>
   More than one-third of pregnant women in some countries in
Africa are HIV-infected, and the rates are nearly as high among
students in some universities.
</P>
<P>
   The messages tackle once taboo subjects like wet dreams,
masturbation, orgasms, foreplay and homosexuality as part of a
campaign known as Love Life.
</P>
<P>
   Love Life's spokeswoman, Judi Nwokedi, described her
organization's campaign as the boldest sex education campaign ever
conducted in South Africa at a news conference sponsored by the
American Medical Association on Saturday, the eve of the 13th
International Conference on AIDS, which will be held here.
</P>
<P>
   The messages are also delivered on radio, television and in
supplements in newspapers under funding from the Henry J. Kaiser
Family Foundation of Menlo Park, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to a media blitz, volunteers for Love Life visit
sports facilities at schools and in communities to provide
information to young South Africans.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign considers its main audience is among people ages 12
to 17. But Love Life also produces and sponsors a television series
that encourages children 6 years and older to talk to adults about
things like sex.
</P>
<P>
   The organization also runs the Love Train, which travels the
country's rails displaying South Africa's largest billboard. At
various train stops, crowds write messages and graffiti on the
cars.
</P>
<P>
   The train was to arrive in Durban on Saturday for the AIDS
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Love Life also uses the train to educate groups of
schoolchildren about sex and AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   After listening to youth complain that existing public health
campaigns were too negative, Love Life spent two years developing
its campaign to change perceptions and behavior that increase risk
for pregnancy, sexually transmitted infections and AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disease-driven and negative campaigns tend to ignore sexual
desire and sex as a part of daily life,'' Nwokedi said.
</P>
<P>
   The program began in September with a larger aim than just
giving information. Nwokedi said her group wanted ``a positive
thrust, vibrancy, excellent marketing and boldness to get to the
core of sexual issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's youth are image conscious, Nwokedi said. They also have
more choices, and Love Life hopes to foster positive self-images
and responsibility among the young people of South Africa, she
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
