<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-REDKSINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOTBALL COLUMN: EARLY BUZZ IN NFL IS THAT REDSKINS CAN'T LOSE 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The whispers are beginning to build toward a bold crescendo.
From top National Football League executives to
frequent-flyer-mile-earning scouts to assistant trainers, there is
a unanimous belief that the season need not even be played, because
the Washington Redskins, after one of the liveliest off-season
spending binges in league history, have already won the Super Bowl.
Pencil them in, it is said.
</P>
<P>
   But some of the talk has a dual purpose. Like those sunburned
``Survivor'' castaways who smile at each other and then plot to
steal coconuts, some of Washington's rivals are pumping up the
Redskins in the hope that they can make Washington a target by
praising the team to death.
</P>
<P>
   It is impossible, though, not to shuttle the Redskins to the top
of the line of championship contenders. In what was a busy NFL
off-season _ with a murder trial for one of the league's stars and
the retirement of a half-dozen great coaches and players _
Washington's stockpiling of Pro Bowl players ranks as the most
interesting development.
</P>
<P>
   With the beginning of training camps only days away _ I know, it
seems as if last season just ended _ Washington's moves loom large
over the NFL landscape.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins are hardly the first team to hire high-priced free
agents; the San Francisco 49ers and the Dallas Cowboys have done it
for years. But no team has revamped on such a grand scale in such a
short time. The Redskins' owner, Daniel Snyder, spent $17 million
in signing bonuses alone during the off-season for defensive end
Bruce Smith, cornerback Deion Sanders, safety Mark Carrier and
quarterback Jeff George, all 30-somethings in the latter part of
their careers.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder emptying his checking account was one of many trends in
the months following the St. Louis Rams' unlikely Super Bowl
victory in January. They include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Coaches moving on. Jimmy Johnson, Bill Parcells, Dick Vermeil
and Mike Ditka all left the coaching sidelines. Bobby Beathard
retired from the front office.
</P>
<P>
   _ Players following. Dan Marino and Steve Young, both
first-ballot Hall of Famers, retired and instantly changed the face
of the league. Denver will be forced to rely on the shaky Brian
Griese, while Miami must decide if Damon Huard or Jay Fiedler will
replace Marino.
</P>
<P>
   _ Keyshawn Johnson leaving New York. Often brash, occasionally
selfish and always a great player, the former Jets wide receiver
signed a free-agent contract with Tampa Bay. The Buccaneers, along
with the Redskins and the Rams, are championship contenders from
the National Conference. Each team has at least one big-time pass
catcher.
</P>
<P>
   _ The estate tax disappearing. Yes, the estate tax became a huge
issue this off-season. On June 9, the U.S. House of Representatives
voted, 279-139, to phase out the federal estate tax, the tax on
rich people's assets when they die. The estates of many owners of
NFL teams, including Wellington Mara of the Giants, Buffalo's Ralph
Wilson and Oakland's Al Davis, would very likely be forced to sell
their teams, under the current law, to pay the hefty tax after an
owner's death. But if the Senate were to pass a bill similar to the
one approved by the House, and if both bodies were to override a
threatened veto by President Clinton, the federal tax burden would
be erased and families of NFL owners would not have to go through a
painful sale process.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Tennessee Titans' consolidating. The team did the right
thing by giving coach Jeff Fisher a new long-term contract. One of
the best backs in the league, Eddie George, is close to signing a
six-year extension. Now Tennessee is trying to add depth by talking
Reggie White out of retirement.
</P>
<P>
   _ Is Atlanta in trouble? Running back Jamal Anderson is still
having problems with his surgically repaired right knee, which
tends to swell after long workouts. Not time to panic _ yet _ but
the Falcons signed the career backup Ron Rivers just in case. If
Anderson continues to have problems, the Falcons would again be
mopping up the NFC West.
</P>
<P>
   _ Players behaving badly. Murder charges against Baltimore
Ravens linebacker Ray Lewis were dropped, after he agreed to plead
guilty to lying to the police. Former Carolina Panthers wide
receiver Rae Carruth will stand trial next year for plotting to
kill his pregnant girlfriend. Oakland Raiders kicker Sebastian
Janikowski was arrested June 21 on a charge of possession of GHB, a
drug that has been linked to date rapes.
</P>
<P>
   Several teams, frustrated that some players continue to show up
on the police blotter, are beginning to insert protective clauses
in contracts in case players end up in trouble. Some of these
additions call for the withholding of bonuses if a player is found
guilty of a serious crime.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Giants, people close to coach Jim Fassel say he is
more motivated than ever to get the team back into the playoffs and
beyond. There is no nicer person in the NFL than Fassel, but he was
given only a one-year contract extension; if he does not win this
year, he could be dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets, meanwhile, are still a team that has still not picked
up a solid wide receiver in free agency to replace Johnson, but it
might in the coming weeks. Meanwhile, coach Al Groh will have
Parcells hovering over the team.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing the Redskins may mop up is champagne after the
Super Bowl. The team should be outstanding. If not, look for Snyder
to fire everyone, and start over.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-00 1428EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
