<HEADER>
A6668 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-HOSPITALITY0709-COX     07-08 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOSPITALITY0709-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hospitality workers a dwindling resource
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ At 5 p.m. every Wednesday, Connie Hagston leaves her
office at the Renaissance Atlanta Hotel and heads to the lobby.
There, the director of sales and marketing switches gears.
</P>
<P>
   For three hours, she greets guests, makes restaurant
reservations and gives directions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an additional helping hand so our guests don't have to
wait in line and they can get where they need to go quickly and
efficiently,'' said Hagston.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it's good customer service, but there's another reason
Hagston and other Renaissance managers alternate working in the
lobby _ a tight labor market.
</P>
<P>
   A strong economy and low unemployment have created a headache
for hotel and restaurant managers, who find it hard to attract and
keep good workers.
</P>
<P>
   That's especially important in a city such as Atlanta, which
relies heavily on its convention and tourism business. In a
competitive market, guest satisfaction is crucial to ensure
travelers' return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was hard eight years ago,'' said Renaissance
General Manager Bo W. Laterveer. ``But if I knew then what I know
now, then I would have appreciated it. There isn't a hotel in the
city that isn't short-staffed.''
</P>
<P>
   The shallow labor pool for entry-level jobs is ``damaging to our
industry,'' said Tia Gordon, a spokeswoman for the American Hotel &AMP;
Motel Association based in Washington. ``We just can't keep
employees. We don't have enough housekeepers to clean the rooms. We
can't find enough front desk clerks.''
</P>
<P>
   Laterveer, whose hotel has a turnover rate of more than 60
percent, recalled the time a cashier abruptly quit after two days.
In other instances, applicants were rejected because they failed
drug tests or criminal background checks.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes ``we lose people before they even start,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of losing a good worker is high. By one estimate, it
costs a company between $1,500 and $2,000 to replace an hourly
employee who leaves within a year.
</P>
<P>
   But the issue isn't new. Several years ago, the hospitality
industry suffered from turnover rates in the triple digits, said
Debra Cannon, an associate professor in the hospitality school at
Georgia State University.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was an awareness that with the Olympics coming and the
growth expected to follow, that there was going to be a real surge
in employment needs,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Smart managers took steps to improve their recruiting, training
and retention programs and think creatively.
</P>
<P>
   Laterveer began the ``meet and greet'' program, in part because
of a bellman shortage. Managers, including Laterveer, take turns
helping in the lobby. The hotel also offers English classes and has
a Christmas savings program tied to employees meeting specific
goals. If a worker leaves before December, the money is forfeited.
</P>
<P>
   The Westin Atlanta North distributes fliers to laundromats, nail
salons and apartment complexes in efforts to recruit workers. Also
included in its recruitment program are bounties of as much as $200
to people who refer a worker who stays at least 90 days.
</P>
<P>
   Managers also carry ``You Caught My Eye'' cards that they give
to people they meet who might make good employees.
</P>
<P>
   It's the same for restaurants. The food service industry has
joined others in a new alliance aimed at bringing more overseas
workers into the country to fill empty jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The Essential Worker Immigration Coalition is seeking to reform
existing immigration law to make it easier to bring unskilled
workers into the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Both restaurant and hotel managers have begun recruiting workers
earlier. Many participate in school-to-work programs that target
high school students. Others recruit heavily on college campuses
and the Internet, and through churches and community associations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing things that we never did in the past,'' said Mike
Wiemers, director of training for Huddle House, a Decatur,
Ga.-based 24-hour restaurant chain.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the company has a job sharing program with area
department and grocery stores in which an employee might work at
one place during the day and the other job at night or on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Companies are also exploring population segments previously
ignored, such as the disabled and older workers.
</P>
<P>
   But getting employees in the door is one thing; keeping them is
another. Executives worry that it will be hard to find good,
experienced managers in the future.
</P>
<P>
   At Huddle House, managers and franchisees attend classes that
deal with such topics as hiring and retention. ``We talk about how
we deal with people, how to talk with people and how to value
people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies offer perks such as higher pay, expanded health
benefits, 401(k) plans, gift certificates, free meals on the job
and flexible hours.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than lose a good employee from the system, some hotels
and restaurants will refer employees to other locations that are
closer to their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Laterveer said the labor crisis may ease up, but he doesn't
expect it to end soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way I see it lessening is if the economy goes south,
and that's the last thing we want.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-00 1438EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000708.0127 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 14:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6669 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-BOOK-REVIEW-ANGEL0709     07-08 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-REVIEW-ANGEL0709-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Banks compilation a powerful hit parade
 &HT;    By Ron Franscell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Russell Banks isn't a household name in American
letters, and what fame he has scratched together as an author has
come from powerful novels such as ``Affliction'' and
``Cloudsplitter.'' But, like Hemingway, Banks is best (and feels
most free) when he writes short, and a new compilation might
finally give him his due as a short story writer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Angel on the Roof'' is a literary album of Banks' greatest
hits, 31 examples of what he calls ``the best work I have done in
the form over the thirty-seven years since I began trying to
write.'' Twenty-two of the stories first appeared in four
lesser-known collections between 1975 and 1986; of the nine more
recent stories, six have been published in magazines such as
Esquire and newspaper literary supplements. More importantly, Banks
has freely revised many of the old stories, so even his most ardent
fans can expect to see something new.
</P>
<P>
   But this is not a compendium designed to illustrate the arc of
Banks' extraordinarily underappreciated career. The stories aren't
flung onto the page chronologically, but grouped more thematically,
with a sense of flow that is uncanny. ``Searching for Survivors''
is among the earliest of his stories but appears among the last
half-dozen here; ``Djinn'' is one of the newest _ and first in this
impressive queue of tales.
</P>
<P>
   Banks' stories are elegantly postmodern, beautiful and striking,
full of diverse voices and disquietingly vulgar settings, mostly in
New England. Some are only a few pages long; others go deeper and
longer. But many of the stories, though sometimes suffocatingly
bleak, are also capable of poignant humor and broad satire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Firewood'' is arguably the strongest and most agonizing, a
vivid precursor of Banks' later, gut-wrenching novel,
``Affliction.'' Nelson Painter is a disconsolate drunk, a working
man whose career has petered out. He rises early on a Sunday
morning yearning almost as much for his first drink of the day as
for some fleeting evidence that he hasn't ruined more lives than
his own. Although he is haunted by dreams, his life has been
anything but dreamlike:
</P>
<P>
   ``It was years ago, in the dream. It was like most of his dreams
that way, a phenomenon that goes on disturbing him, irritating him,
actually, infuriating him sometimes, because you ought to be able
to move on in your dreams, just as you move on in your life. Your
kids grow up, you marry another woman, you move away, come back,
change, and change again. You'd think your dreams would know that
and would somehow deal with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Also notable are ``The Burden,'' a heartbreaking father-son
story; ``Theory of Flight,'' in which a divorced young mother
escapes with her children to the solace of her past, only to find
an indeterminate future; ``The Fisherman,'' about a man who seeks
only solitude and a chance to live out his days in an elaborately
built ice-fishing hut; and ``Black Man and White Woman in a Dark
Green Rowboat,'' an erotic and minimal love story.
</P>
<P>
   Banks' nine novels and four short story collections include
Pulitzer finalists ``Continental Drift'' (1985) and
``Cloudsplitter'' (1998). Hollywood has been very good to Banks'
books: The film version of 1989's ``Affliction'' won a 1998 best
supporting actor Oscar for James Coburn; ``The Sweet Hereafter''
(1991) was the 1997 Cannes Film Festival winner and received
Academy Award nominations for best director and best screenplay
adaptation. Now, Banks' ``Continental Drift,'' ``Rule of the Bone''
and ``The Book of Jamaica'' are also being adapted for film. He's
won a Guggenheim Fellowship, an O. Henry and Best American Short
Story Award and a Literature Award from the American Academy of
Arts and Letters . . . yet his is still not the most likely name to
leap to the mind of even the keenest short story fan.
</P>
<P>
   Banks, 60, grew up in the blue-collar milieu of New Hampshire
and eastern Massachusetts, places and landscapes that haunt his
writing. Before his writing life, he labored as a plumber, a shoe
clerk and a window dresser; since those working-class days, he has
taught at Columbia University, Sarah Lawrence College, the
University of New Hampshire, New England College and New York
University.
</P>
<P>
   The form ``invites me today, as it did back then, to behave on
the page in a way that is more reckless, more sharply painful, and
more broadly comic than is allowed by the steady, slow, bourgeois
respectability of the novel,'' Banks tells readers.
</P>
<P>
   And it might be the renaissance of the short story that finally
elevates Banks to his proper place among American writers. He ranks
with John Cheever as one of the masters of the contemporary form.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
