A6670 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-BOOK-REVIEW-BRAIN0709     07-08 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-REVIEW-BRAIN0709-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Einstein's brain: No intellectual leaps this time
 &HT;    By John D. Thomas
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Albert Einstein was so intellectually significant that
his very name is a synonym for genius. The father of the theory of
relativity and the mind behind the awesome destructive power of the
atomic bomb, he died on April 18, 1955, in Princeton, N.J., of a
ruptured aortic aneurysm.
</P>
<P>
   Late in his life, Einstein said, ``I want to be cremated so
people won't come to worship at my bones.'' After he died, his
request was honored and his family scattered his ashes in a private
ceremony along the Delaware River. There was just one problem with
Einstein's last wishes being carried out: Not all of him went up in
flames. What Einstein's son Hans Albert didn't know was that the
scientist's brain, the 20th century's ultimate supercomputer, had
been taken out of his body and saved by the pathologist who
performed the autopsy, Thomas Harvey. Einstein did not donate his
body to science, but Harvey decided to take a piece of it anyway.
</P>
<P>
   After the fate of the brain became public knowledge, Harvey told
the press that he was going to research and probe the organ for its
secrets and produce a study. Four and one-half decades later,
however, the pathologist has yet to publish such a work. (Many
scientists believe that you cannot extrapolate anything about the
nature of genius from cerebral remains.) Several writers have
tracked down the enigmatic Harvey over the intervening years and
documented his strange saga, but Michael Paterniti takes the
doctor's bizarre tale to a quirky new level in ``Driving Mr.
Albert.''
</P>
<P>
   Paterniti befriended Harvey while writing an article about
Einstein's brain for Harper's magazine that would become the basis
for this book. During their interviews, the author discovered that
the doctor had some unfinished business with the famous gray
matter: He wanted to take the brain to Einstein's granddaughter,
Evelyn, who lives in Berkeley, Calif. ``Although he didn't explain
why,'' Paterniti writes, ``I assumed he might be facing down some
late-in-life desire to resolve the past with the Einstein family
once and for all.'' Paterniti suggested that he drive Harvey and
the brain from Princeton to Berkeley, and Harvey accepted the
offer.
</P>
<P>
   On a snowy February day, the doctor and the writer hopped into a
teal Buick Skylark rental car and began their odd asphalt odyssey.
Soon into the trip, however, Paterniti comes to a rather shocking
realization: Harvey won't tell him anything about the brain. The
author had believed that days alone in a car with Harvey would give
him the opportunity to extract all the secrets the doctor was
keeping about the brain, but Harvey won't budge. So instead of
dishing those cerebral secrets, Paterniti is forced to find filler.
</P>
<P>
   He pads the book with information about the life and times of
Einstein (nothing new there), and he also grasps for forced
symbolic connections between the brain and the road trip itself.
For example, in Missouri the two stop by the presidential library
of Harry Truman (he of atomic bomb infamy), and they take a side
trip in Kansas to see the preserved remains of eccentric religious
sculptor Samuel Perry Dinsmoor. (Get it? They too are traveling
with the preserved remains of an eccentric visionary.)
</P>
<P>
   The whole on-the-road exercise is oddly unsatisfying, and it
ends with a merely perfunctory visit with Evelyn Einstein. Even
face to face with the famous physicist's kin, the always stubborn
Harvey won't show the cards he's holding (if he's holding any at
all). On the surface, the idea for ``Driving Mr. Albert'' is
brilliant, but once you probe too deeply, you realize that it's
essentially a trip to nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
