<HEADER>
A6671 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-BOOK-REVIEW-PARKS0709     07-08 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-REVIEW-PARKS0709-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Biography reveals the person behind icon of civil rights
movement
 &HT;    By Allen Barra
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The literature of the civil rights movement spans 150
years and includes libraries of academic histories, personal
accounts and oral recollections, but it wasn't complete until
historian and National Public Radio commentator Douglas Brinkley's
``Rosa Parks,'' the latest in the Penguin Lives series. Amazingly,
this is the first serious biography of the unlikely and unexpected
heroine who gave birth to the modern civil rights movement _ ``not
a saint, but a symbol of the triumph of steadfastness in the name
of justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in Tuskegee, Ala., in 1913, Rosa McCauley Parks was raised
by a schoolteacher mother who adhered to Tuskegee Institute founder
Booker T. Washington's belief that cleanliness and high moral
character were ``civilizing agents.'' Her education, which included
four years at the progressive Montgomery Industrial School for
Girls, was cut short by her mother's illness; she went to work at a
textile plant, becoming an accomplished seamstress. In 1932 she
married Raymond Parks, a barber and a charter member of the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People; they
settled in a modest apartment in a two-story brick housing project
in a Montgomery ruled by Jim Crow.
</P>
<P>
   Rosa Parks was more than a blue-collar worker who one day
decided not to give up her seat on the bus. She was a longtime
volunteer worker for the NAACP, stamping envelopes, answering
phones and typing letters _ a had been looking for a ``test case''
to challenge Alabama's segregation laws, only to be frustrated when
their subjects were found to have backgrounds that couldn't
withstand the inevitable scrutiny of a white press and legal
system. They quickly overcame their amazement and organized a plan
to take advantage of Parks' boldness. And so, that December, ``in
the humble setting of Rosa and Raymond Parks' linoleum-floored
living room a group of Americans, with less than five hundred
dollars among them, banded together to stand up for the principles
of democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   In this adroit melding of biography and history, Brinkley brings
Parks' life and times into focus by drawing from sources as diverse
as King's writings and the lyrics of a Sam Cooke song that inspired
Rosa. We're offered fascinating glimpses into the movement that
formal histories might have ignored _ for instance, the jealousy
directed toward King and Parks, who, as if she didn't have enough
to concern her, became a target of male chauvinism. Her former
NAACP boss is quoted as calling Parks ``a lovely, stupid woman the
media built into an icon,'' and ministers whom she respected
greeted her with ``Well, if it isn't the superstar!'' Sadly, even
Abernathy treated her with condescension.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rosa Parks who emerges from Brinkley's book was anything
but an attractive token. In truth, her views often seemed to waver
between the nonviolence of King and the militance of Malcolm X. ``I
don't believe in gradualism,'' she told an interviewer in 1967,
``or that whatever is to be done for the better should take forever
to do.'' A student of Gandhi, she nonetheless identified with the
words of playwright Lorraine Hansberry: ``Negroes must concern
themselves with every single means of struggle: legal, illegal,
passive, active, violent and nonviolent.'' By the mid-1960s, writes
Brinkley, ``the gentle Christian woman had become a tough-minded
free-thinking feminist.''
</P>
<P>
   There can be no Cliffs Notes on the long struggle for civil
rights in America, no short form for the voluminous literature of
the people who fought to extend the principles of American
democracy to the descendants of slaves. But for the generation that
has grown up in integrated America, Rosa Parks is a superb starting
point and a vivid illustration of how a single life can make a
difference.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
