<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 14:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6673 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-FAMILY-VACATIONS-NYT &LR;      07-08 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-VACATIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: FORGETTING THE BACK-SEAT MISERY OF YOUTH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Conn., Mass., N.J., Pa., N.H., N.C., Maine)   By MATTHEW PURDY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DARIEN, Conn. _ In Lisa Del Papa's childhood, vacations meant
long hours of enforced intimacy in the family car. ``We did one to
Cape Cod at that age when you can't stand being with your parents
and I couldn't stand Cape Cod,'' she said. ``I wrote to my best
friend every night that I hated vacation.''
</P>
<P>
   So there she was this week, at age 34, of free will and sound
mind, idling with her husband and a 13-month-old daughter at the
Connecticut Turnpike rest area here, ready to get back in their
car, packed with luggage and toys. ``Now we have Ellen and we're
going to Cape Cod,'' she said cheerily, holding her daughter. ``I
hear it's beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   More proof that those who forget the lessons of family car
vacations are doomed to repeat them.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide amnesia has struck again as close relatives climb
into close quarters and drive away from everything back home,
except one another. It's that special moment, or many moments, or
several days (a seeming eternity, really) when, as one man said,
pointing to his laminated-looking children in the back of the
family van, ``they're bored and we're driving.''
</P>
<P>
   The petroleum industry, in a humanitarian move, tried to spare
Americans the car trip this summer by charging more for a gallon of
gas than the going rate for a cup of coffee. But still, we blithely
tank up on latte and unleaded, and head for the open road.
</P>
<P>
   After all, as only genome mappers can explain, we're wired to
drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first hour was OK,'' Del Papa reported on the second
morning of a planned three-day trip from Princeton to Cape Cod.
``We've been listening to a Mickey Mouse tape. I've been singing
politically incorrect songs like `Ten Little Indians.''' Del Papa
said that as her husband, Jan-Olaf, drove, she tried to toss toys
to her daughter faster than Ellen was dropping them. It was
cherished quality time with Ellen, but when Del Papa was asked to
imagine her future, say six hours hence, she said, ``We're going to
have whiskey in the car.''
</P>
<P>
   Whiskey, and other alcoholic beverages, remain legally incorrect
in the car (in fact, one mother said she and her children passed
the miles singing ``Ninety-Nine Bottles of Ginger Ale On the
Wall''). But recent upgrades in family car vacations include
E-ZPass, Gameboys and sibling-rivalry-resistant triple-row seating.
</P>
<P>
   ``The TV helps,'' said Joy Borbidge, traveling home from North
Carolina to New Hampshire with her husband, two teen-age daughters
and a 10-year-old son. ``Everybody has their own personal CD
player.'' Joy and her husband, Brad, had the Dead on the radio, and
the kids had the Backstreet Boys and Christina Aguilera on their
headphones.
</P>
<P>
   There was also a film festival under way in the family Windstar.
``We just left Philadelphia and the kids said it will take four
movies to get home,'' Borbidge said. ``They're watching `Big Daddy'
now. They already watched `The First Wives Club.' The girls don't
want to watch `Star Wars.' You know how it is.'' It was a rec room
on radials, and at one point Borbidge relinquished the wheel and
jumped in the back to catch the screening of ``Dances With
Wolves.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone was anticipating 15-year-old Jenna's threat to take the
wheel once they got into New Hampshire, where her learner's permit
would allow her to drive. ``We're going to hide,'' said her
14-year-old sister, Jamy.
</P>
<P>
   Many adults manage a pioneer spirit about car trips. They assure
you that if they leave early and traffic is moving and the
back-seat wrestling doesn't necessitate emergency room visits, they
can make it from the tip of Long Island to the Bering Strait by
sundown. And their children don't need electronic toys, they're
thrilled playing hangman and studying French infinitives.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there's another side to this story. Joe and Sue
Gallen were saying how well the trip from Reading, Pa., to Maine
with their three boys was going. It was nothing like the rollicking
adventure Joe Gallen had growing up in a family of 10 children who
traveled the country in a motor home one summer, forgetting the
oldest child at one stop and smashing the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   But the Gallens were having fun, they said. The traffic was
moving along, they were playing games with their boys, and the
older one was even reading to the younger ones.
</P>
<P>
   To which a little voice squeaked from the back seat: ``And I'm
sick of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
