<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALLSTAR-HISTORY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ALL-STAR GAME HAS SEEN ITS SHARE OF THE BIZARRE 
</HEADLINE>
  David Fischer is an author and sports historian whose books include
``The 50 Coolest Jobs in Sports'' (Arco, 1998). 
 By DAVID FISCHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 71st Major League Baseball All-Star Game will be played
Tuesday night at Turner Field in Atlanta. Through the years, the
All-Star Game has been the vehicle for some of baseball's legendary
accomplishments. Here is a highly eclectic lineup card of stellar
highlights.
</P>
<P>
   All-Star Fever
</P>
<P>
   The first All-Star Game was staged in 1933, at Comiskey Park, in
conjunction with Chicago's Century of Progress Exposition. The idea
came from Arch Ward, sports editor of The Chicago Tribune.
</P>
<P>
   Ward persuaded the league owners to stage a game between stars
from the American and National Leagues. Ward's proposal was for a
one-time event, but the All-Star Game proved so popular, it has
been played every year since _ except in 1945, when it was called
off because of travel restrictions during World War II. (There were
two All-Star Games from 1959 to 1962, to benefit the players'
pension fund.)
</P>
<P>
   At the inaugural All-Star Game in 1933, Babe Ruth slammed the
first home run in its history, a two-run shot off Wild Bill
Hallahan to help the Americans capture a 4-2 victory over the
Nationals.
</P>
<P>
   King Carl and Dr. K
</P>
<P>
   In 1934, at the Polo Grounds in upper Manhattan, Carl Hubbell of
the New York Giants used his dazzling screwball to strike out five
future Hall of Famers in a row: Babe Ruth, Lou Gehrig, Jimmie Foxx,
Al Simmons and Joe Cronin.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1984 game, Hubbell threw out the ceremonial first pitch
at Candlestick Park in San Francisco to mark the 50th anniversary
of his achievement. Then Hubbell watched as Fernando Valenzuela and
19-year-old Dwight Gooden, the youngest All-Star in the game's
history, combined to break his record with six consecutive whiffs.
</P>
<P>
   All-Star Injuries
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis Cardinals right-hander Dizzy Dean sustained a broken
toe when he was hit by a line drive off the bat of Cleveland's Earl
Averill in the third inning of the 1937 game at Griffith Stadium in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Dean, who at 26 had already won 134 career games and was on his
way to another outstanding season in 1937, tried to come back too
soon. He altered his delivery to favor the injury and ruined his
arm. The next season, Dean was traded to the Chicago Cubs, and his
brief but brilliant career was never the same.
</P>
<P>
   In 1950, in the first All-Star Game to be broadcast on
television, Boston's Ted Williams hurt his left elbow in the first
inning while making a catch against the left-field wall at Comiskey
Park. Williams, who stayed in the game and contributed a
run-scoring single in the fifth inning, did not know that the elbow
was broken until the following day. He was lost until the end of
the season, as Boston finished four games back.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota's Harmon Killebrew became another All-Star Game
casualty in 1968 at Houston's Astrodome, in the first indoor
contest and the first played on artificial turf. Killebrew,
stretching for a throw at first base, tore a hamstring and missed
two months.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy Proves a Point
</P>
<P>
   American soldiers fighting the war in Europe followed the 1943
game by listening to the game at Shibe Park in Philadelphia on
shortwave radio. An outfielder named DiMaggio was the hitting star,
but the DiMaggio was Pittsburgh's Vince, who singled, tripled and
homered.
</P>
<P>
   The American League pocketed its eighth victory in 11 games,
despite having no Yankees in the lineup. Yankees manager Joe
McCarthy, defying critics who suggested the Junior Circuit could
not win without his Yankees, refused to play any of his six players
selected to the team. It was the only time in All-Star Game history
that no Yankee got into the game.
</P>
<P>
   Williams Had a Blast
</P>
<P>
   The 1946 game at Boston's Fenway Park fittingly turned into the
Ted Williams Show. Williams returned to baseball after three years
at war in spectacular fashion. The Splendid Splinter set All-Star
Game records with four hits, including two home runs, four runs
scored and five runs batted in.
</P>
<P>
   The eighth-inning confrontation between Williams and Pittsburgh
pitcher Rip Sewell would become one of the most unforgettable
moments in All-Star Game memory. Sewell was the master of the
``eephus pitch,'' a high-arcing blooper pitch. When Sewell lobbed
his infamous eephus, Williams blasted a three-run home run over the
right-field wall, the first homer hit off the looping pitch. The
Americans defeated the Nationals, 12-0, in the most lopsided
shutout in All-Star Game competition.
</P>
<P>
   Legendary Winners
</P>
<P>
   Dean Stone of the Washington Senators and Stu Miller of the San
Francisco Giants were winning pitchers overshadowed by
circumstance.
</P>
<P>
   In 1954, Stone entered the game in the eighth inning in relief
of Bob Keegan with two out and Red Schoendienst on third base.
Before Stone's first delivery, Schoendienst attempted to steal home
and was tagged out. When Larry Doby tied the game in the bottom of
the inning with a homer and Nellie Fox drove in the game's final
two runs with a bases-loaded single, Stone became the winning
pitcher without throwing a pitch.
</P>
<P>
   According to legend, Miller was blown off the mound by the wind
during one of the 1961 games at blustery Candlestick Park. The NL
was leading, 3-2, with one out in the ninth and Miller pitching to
Rocky Colavito with two men on base. When he took his set position,
a fierce gust of wind blasted the 165-pound Miller, causing a
slight wobble. The umpire called a balk to advance the runners, and
the AL tied the score. When the NL won in the 10th, Miller was the
winning pitcher, but the next day, ``Miller Blown Off Mound'' was
the headline. ``I wasn't blown off that mound,'' Miller said. ``I
just waved a little.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Vote Early and Often
</P>
<P>
   Fans selected the eight starting position players from 1947 to
1957. But partisan voting in 1957 brought about the demise of
elected All-Star teams. Cincinnati fans stuffed the ballot boxes
full of Reds and had apparently elected a starting squad of George
Crowe at first base, Johnny Temple at second, Don Hoak at third,
Roy McMillan at shortstop, Frank Robinson in left field, Gus Bell
in center, Wally Post in right and Ed Bailey as catcher.
</P>
<P>
   Before the results were announced, Commissioner Ford Frick
declared that Crowe, Bell and Post were disqualified as starters,
selecting Stan Musial, Willie Mays and Hank Aaron in their place.
</P>
<P>
   This ballot stuffing by Cincinnati fans resulted in players,
coaches and managers making the All-Star Game choices from 1958 to
1969.
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, the new commissioner, Bowie Kuhn, ruled that the
selection of starting lineups be returned to the fans. But the
flawed balloting system, sponsored by Gillette, offered a choice
among only six players at each position. Al Kaline, Detroit's
perennial All-Star, was not listed on the ballot. Atlanta's Rico
Carty, who sported a gaudy .428 batting average at the break, and
California's Alex Johnson, the eventual AL batting champion, were
not listed either.
</P>
<P>
   The game, played at Cincinnati's Riverfront Stadium, which had
opened only two weeks earlier, was the site for a stunning ending.
The NL scored three runs in the ninth inning to tie the score. In
the 12th, the Reds' Pete Rose thundered head-on into Cleveland
catcher Ray Fosse and sent him crashing backward as Rose crossed
the plate with the winning run. Fans would later vote Rose as the
starter at five different positions, an All-Star Game record.
</P>
<P>
   Golden Anniversary
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, the Midsummer Classic returned to Comiskey Park, which
was the site of the first All-Star Game 50 years earlier. In the
third inning, Fred Lynn of the California Angels hit a grand slam
off the Giants' Atlee Hammaker. It was Lynn's fourth All-Star home
run and the first grand slam in All-Star history. Lynn's clout
punctuated a seven-run inning as the AL coasted to a 13-3 victory
and ended its embarrassing 11-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   Bo Knows All-Star Games
</P>
<P>
   Bo Jackson of the Kansas City Royals received the most valuable
player trophy in the 1989 game _ the first played with the
designated hitter _ as he led the Americans to their first repeat
victory in 31 years.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, playing left field and batting leadoff for the first
time in his brief major league career, blasted a 448-foot home run
over the center-field fence at Anaheim Stadium off starter Rick
Reuschel. The next batter, Wade Boggs, also homered, the first time
in All-Star history that the first two batters in a game had
homered. Nolan Ryan, at 42, became the oldest All-Star winning
pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   The following year, Jackson, who also played running back for
the Los Angeles Raiders, was named to the Pro Bowl, becoming the
only athlete chosen to play in both the All-Star Game and the Pro
Bowl.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-00 1452EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
