<DOCNO> NYT20000708.0133 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 14:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6681 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BAXTER-COLUMN0709-COX     07-08 1327
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAXTER-COLUMN0709-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Environment heating up as regional issue
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   RALEIGH, N.C. _ What will be the political impact on our sunny
region if the earth's climate really does become hotter and more
inhospitable over the next century, as reports like the one
released in June by a federal study commission predict?
</P>
<P>
   Coastal North Carolina, with its windswept dunes and picturesque
coves, may be as good a vantage point as any to begin sorting
through that question.
</P>
<P>
   Not that all the scientific controversy over global warming is
any closer to an answer here than anywhere else. Ryan Boles, the
assistant state climatologist, has found evidence of a slight
warming trend along the coast over the past 50 years, but the
timeline is too short and the data is too inconclusive to prove any
massive climate change, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it is global or not, however, the weather in North
Carolina does appear to be changing. There is a much stronger
scientific consensus that storm activity in the Atlantic runs in
cycles, and since 1995, the seas off North Carolina's coast appear
to have entered a turbulent period that could last for decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll almost put a guarantee on it: Within the next five years,
we'll have another major hurricane affect the North Carolina
coast,'' Boles said.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, heavy rains spun off by Hurricanes Dennis and Floyd
caused record flooding in the state, ruining whole towns and
washing drowned hogs by the thousands down the state's once
pristine streams. That was followed last winter by a 20-inch snow
and ice storm that hit areas already reeling from the flood.
</P>
<P>
   Add another hot summer, and it's fair to say North Carolina is
experiencing much the same effects that have been predicted for
global warming, whether global warming actually has anything to do
with it or not.
</P>
<P>
   This rough patch of weather also comes at a time when North
Carolina and the South are beginning to reckon with the impact
people are having on the environment, in political terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first started working with environmental problems as a
lobbyist here, people thought it was something they worried about
in the Northeast,'' said Bill Holman a former Sierra Club lobbyist
tapped by Gov. Jim Hunt to be the state's top environmental
officer. ``The environment has come home.''
</P>
<P>
   The specific subject of global warming remains as politically
palatable as Darwinism would have been a hundred years ago. Vice
President Al Gore has taken much ridicule for broaching the subject
in his book, ``Earth In the Balance.'' Holman counted it noteworthy
when Hunt, departing from his prepared text in a speech at the
dedication of a natural science museum here, mentioned global
warming before a group a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
   If it is possible to predict an era of storms, emergency
management and coastal zoning are two issues that should become
more politically volatile. But these subjects aren't on the front
burner in this year's governor's race between Republican Richard
Vinroot, former Charlotte mayor, and Democratic Attorney General
Mike Easley.
</P>
<P>
   Hunt, in his last year in office, is supporting a major overhaul
in the state flood plain development plan, but long-range
forecasting doesn't figure prominently in the debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it's going to pass, even after the worst flood
in our history,'' Holman said. ``A lot of people say we don't need
it because it's probably not going to happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   The potential for turbulent weather to beget stormy politics has
already been demonstrated next door in South Carolina. Gov. Jim
Hodges touched off a public furor early in his administration over
the way the state handled the coastal evacuation when it appeared
Floyd was headed straight for that state.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, however, Hodges' experience may have sent a
negative message about overestimating the weather. Floyd veered
away from South Carolina and lumbered up the coast, calling into
question the governor's judgment in ordering the massive
evacuation.
</P>
<P>
   While it hasn't touched off a political discussion about climate
changes, last year's weather did play a major role in bringing the
state's environmental problems to the forefront.
</P>
<P>
   ``In every gubernatorial election the issues are education,
development and something else. And this year that something else
is the environment,'' said Ran Coble, director of the North
Carolina Center for Public Policy Research.
</P>
<P>
   The grisly images from the flood ``left an indelible
impression,'' said Molly Diggins, a lobbyist for the North Carolina
Sierra Club, and turned the hog farms into a symbol for lax
environmental enforcement in several areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two competing sentiments: the concern of native
North Carolinians about their state and their pride in it, and the
long-standing tradition of looking the other way in order to
promote business growth,'' Diggins said.
</P>
<P>
   In a manner reminiscent of the way state tourism boards divide
their territory up by vacation attractions, North Carolinians tend
to regionalize their environmental problems. The mountains have
acid rain and air pollution from all the tourists driving through.
Charlotte and Raleigh-Durham are encountering sprawl. Eastern North
Carolina has hog farms, and the coast has overdevelopment.
</P>
<P>
   Simply knitting these diverse concerns into an effective
movement has been a challenge for environmentalists, and the floods
may turn out to be a defining moment, like Hunt's appointment
during his final term of Holman, who had been a lobbyist for the
Sierra Club, to head the state Department of Environment and
Natural Resources.
</P>
<P>
   The way the two campaigns react to questions about the weather
corresponds with their broad, election-year themes.
</P>
<P>
   Easley's campaign manager, Jay Reiff, put last year's disasters
within the framework of the Democratic candidate's concerns for the
growing divide between haves and have nots in the states, noting
that small towns and rural areas, already hit by a cut in tobacco
quotas, were the hardest hit.
</P>
<P>
   If such disasters become more frequent, Reiff said, ``People are
going to look for a governor who's going to roll up his sleeves and
have a plan to deal with it. The state has a justified role in
helping people get back on their feet again.''
</P>
<P>
   Easley has also made water quality a major plank in his
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are acts of God, which we can't control,'' Chris Neally,
Vinroot's campaign manager, said of last year's disasters.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican's campaign is centered on school choice and a
plan that would limit state spending according to a formula based
on inflation and population growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the environmental problems that come up in this state
are over-politicized. When it comes to government we need to not
use the environment as a political football,'' Neally said.
</P>
<P>
   The rains last year washed into parts of the 500-year flood
plain, which enhances North Carolina as a backdrop for discussing
the possibility of big, unprecedented climate changes.
</P>
<P>
   But, sensitive to the pressures of developers already pushing to
rebuild, environmentalists point out that the actual amount of
water that fell on North Carolina was less than in the summer of
1955 (which coincides, incidentally, with the end of the last long
storm cycle.)
</P>
<P>
   The destruction was so much worse last year, they argue, because
so much of the state's wetlands buffer has been destroyed, and so
much development is taking place in what were rural backlands 45
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   This, in fact, may be a harbinger of many 21st century stories:
Dangerous weather, striking in so many places where the weather
formerly didn't matter so much.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
