<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 15:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6686 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-MEN-NYT     07-08 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-MEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIMILAR STYLES BUT DISPARATE PERSONALITIES TO DUEL FOR MEN'S
TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ Out of bravery or foolishness, Patrick
Rafter appears eager to all but crawl through the bars at the zoo
and to step into the den that Pete Sampras prowls.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras is at his most intimidating on Center Court at the All
England Club, where he has snatched up six titles over the last
seven years, where his big-foot serve tramples opponents' spirits,
where he has been nearly unbeatable. But on Sunday, Rafter could
emerge as the perfect foil for Sampras' celebration plans.
</P>
<P>
   Rafter has never flinched in Sampras' presence. In fact, he has
snapped back at him both on the court and off. In August 1998,
Rafter served an ace on match point against Sampras in a tour event
in Cincinnati. Sampras thought the ball was out. And when the
umpire did not agree, Sampras' ego seemed punctured by the moment.
Quickly, Sampras' typically cool temperament came unraveled. Not
only did he fume at the call, he also expected Rafter to step
forward and replay the serve.
</P>
<P>
   If Rafter thought the serve was out, he might have. Rafter has a
long history of good sportsmanship, and he is well known on the
tour for giving back points on questionable calls. A year earlier,
he reversed a line call that cost him a match. This time, Rafter
did not see the serve as a fault.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks that followed, Sampras reportedly said that if
Rafter thought the serve was good, he ``must be smoking something
that's not legal.'' Rafter countered by calling Sampras a crybaby.
</P>
<P>
   It was an odd back-and-forth between two very different players.
Outgoing and approachable, Rafter is among the best-liked players
on the tour. Even when he botches a serve toss and allows it to
drop, he waves his hand at his opponent and always says, ``Sorry,
mate.''
</P>
<P>
   The more subdued and serious Sampras is a recluse in comparison.
So in some ways, it was not surprising when Rafter called Sampras
recently and asked for a truce.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called Pete up and resolved our differences,'' Rafter said
on Friday after surviving Andre Agassi in a spellbinding five-set
semifinal. ``I respect Pete for a lot of things. I think in a lot
of ways he's lightened up over this year. I don't have any problems
with Pete.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's too much at stake to be worried about each
other, thinking about your differences with each other. It's all
put behind us now. This is the Wimbledon finals. He's going for his
record, and I'm trying to find one here.''
</P>
<P>
   Rafter has a chance. Although Sampras holds a 9-4 edge, Rafter
has won three of their last four matches, including the 1998 U.S.
Open final. Oddly enough, in all of their meetings, they have never
played on grass. Here, the serve means everything.
</P>
<P>
   So far in this fortnight, Rafter's surgically repaired shoulder
_ which has a shrinking life span of serves left in it _ has held
up extremely well. The player who was ranked No. 1 in the world
just one year ago is finally getting his groove back. Under
inspection throughout this tournament, Rafter played one of the
best matches of his career against Agassi in the semifinals. Mixing
up his sliced backhands, using different spins on his serve, Rafter
won a match that was more like a brain brawl.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras' march to this point has barely tested him. The
12th-seeded Rafter is the first seeded player Sampras has had to
face in the fortnight. Although the less grueling matches have
given Sampras ample time to rest the tendinitis that mysteriously
crept into his left shin during the second round, the level of his
game has been difficult to read.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still here, and I'm obviously very happy that I've gotten
to this point,'' said Sampras, whose sore shin has limited his
mobility at times. ``When you don't practice on your days off, you
go out there kind of cold. It's not that comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since the second round, Sampras was scheduled
to practice Saturday in preparation for Rafter. To get by the
serve-and-volley style of the Aussie, Sampras will have to return
Rafter's grab bag of serves well and take care of his own; he'll
have to find a razor-sharp passing game and be the aggressor on any
short ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a lot of his match with Agassi,'' Sampras said. ``He's
playing great. He's a great athlete. He volleys well, covers the
net as well as anyone in the world. I'm sure we'll both walk out
there a little nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, but Sampras is usually unflappable on Center Court. In
advancing to his fourth consecutive final at Wimbledon, Sampras has
won a record 27 consecutive matches on these grounds. That numbing
number of victories might be a little daunting to some, but not to
the competitive Rafter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember going out in a match in '93 and playing him, being
very scared,'' Rafter said. ``But things just went my way, and I
ended up winning it. Since then, we've had some battles, and he's
won most of them. But I've had my couple of wins over him.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a Grand Slam final. He's been here many times. It's my
first one here at Wimbledon. I've just got to try to go out there
with the same attitude I went out on the court against Agassi with.
Just be relaxed. That's what I need to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-00 1506EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
