<SLUG> BC-TOUR-DE-FRANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RODRIGUEZ FINDS HIS NICHE AFTER RIDING AND WAITING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif.)   By SAMUEL ABT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VILLENEUVE SUR LOT, France _ In the first week of his first Tour
de France, Fred Rodriguez was happy to be a team worker, leading
out successful sprints for Mapei colleagues and hoping that his own
turn for an exploit would come sooner or later. It came sooner.
</P>
<P>
   The 27-year-old Californian joined a 17-man breakaway early
Saturday in the eighth of 21 stages, stayed with the survivors as
constant attacks whittled the group away and then crossed the line
with a fine fourth-place finish in the 171-rider field. That
elevated him into 11th place overall in the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt strong and tried to hold the group together for a
sprint finish because I was one of the fastest guys there,''
Rodriguez said. ``It didn't happen, but I'm happy.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason it did not happen at the end of the 203.5-kilometer
(126-mile) rolling ride from Limoges to Villeneuve sur Lot in
southwestern France was Erik Dekker, a Dutchman with Rabobank and
his country's time trial champion in 1997. He showed that ability
to ride alone strongly when he bolted away from 10 others with 30
kilometers (18.5 miles) to go and held them off by 52 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   On a cool, sunny day and before big crowds, Dekker was timed in
4 hours 22 minutes 14 seconds, a speed of 46 kilometers an hour (28
mph). Xavier Jan, a Frenchman with Francaise des Jeux, was second,
with Vicente Garcia-Acosta, a Spaniard with Banesto, third, 56
seconds behind the winner, and Rodriguez fourth, two more seconds
behind.
</P>
<P>
   Alberto Elli, an Italian with Telekom, finished in the main pack
5:42 behind Dekker and retained the yellow jersey of the overall
leader since Dekker started in the nether regions of the standings
based on total time. Fabrice Gougot, a Frenchman with Credit
Agricole, remained in second place overall, 12 seconds behind, with
Marc Wauters, a Belgian with Rabobank, third, 1:17 behind.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez is easy to pick out among the Tour riders since he
wears the red, white and blue, star-spangled jersey of the American
professional champion, an honor he won in Philadelphia last month.
In addition, he has been sporting an Old Glory do-rag on his head
lately.
</P>
<P>
   Despite fine results this season, Rodriguez said in a recent
interview that he understood his subsidiary role in the Tour as the
leadout man for Tom Steels, Mapei's star sprinter and the winner of
two stages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came here to help Tom, and those goals I think I've
achieved,'' he said. ``I'm one of his main leadout guys, Stefano
Zanini and myself.'' After Rodriguez goes as hard as he can in the
last half mile, Zanini, an Italian who is riding in the slipstream
behind him, takes over as a pilot fish for Steels to protect him
from both the wind and rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personal goals, I'm still pretty open-minded,'' Rodriguez
continued. ``Things happen, especially in the Tour de France. It's
such intense racing. There are a lot more flat stages that might
suit me,'' he added presciently. ``I'm just waiting to see what
time gives me.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, it gave him little _ and Rodriguez had himself to
blame.
</P>
<P>
   His future with Mapei looked dubious after the 1999 season, when
he recorded only three minor victories and displeased management
with his lackadaisical behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year I had growing pains,'' he said. ``My first year in
Europe, away from my family, my girl friend, living in a foreign
country, a foreign culture. Figuring out where I belonged took a
while. There were times when I went home and took a little too much
time off.''
</P>
<P>
   He paused and admitted it flatly: ``I took advantage of that
time off'' _ at his home in Emeryville, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the year I thought it over. After re-evaluating
my whole year and knowing where my mistakes were and where my
strengths were, I just came into 2000 saying, `This is my year. I
either figure out where I belong or I have to quit.'
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way I put it to myself: I either make a difference
this year or I don't belong here.''
</P>
<P>
   With seven victories this year, he has made a difference. In
addition to the U.S. champion's jersey, he won a daily stage in the
Four Days of Dunkirk race in France this spring and then another
stage and the points jersey in the Tour of Switzerland last month.
</P>
<P>
   Although he now ranks highest among Mapei's riders in the
overall standings, the American is unlikely to remain there in the
mountains.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can climb decently when I need to,'' he said, ``but in my
first Tour I'm going to take it step by step.''
</P>
</TEXT>
