<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORTER'S NOTEBOOK: AFTER A YEAR, MRS. CLINTON FINDS COMFORT
LEVEL 
</HEADLINE>
   By JONATHAN P. HICKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Hillary Rodham Clinton campaigned throughout western New York
over the last few days, her style occasionally invited comparisons
with that of her husband. President Clinton is widely seen as one
of the country's most effective campaigners, and Mrs. Clinton
acknowledges that she has a long way to go to match his political
adeptness.
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Clinton seems to have become far more comfortable as a
candidate, spending much of her time at public appearances chatting
with people who come to see her. Indeed, her staff is often driven
to frustration waiting for the first lady to complete the seemingly
endless process of shaking hands, signing autographs, posing for
pictures and discussing issues with voters. As a result, she is
often quite late for appearances, to the consternation of everyone,
it seems, but the first lady herself.
</P>
<P>
   When asked Saturday to compare her style of campaigning with
that of her husband, Clinton characterized herself as ``a baby
campaigner.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still in the toddler stage,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she seems to get high marks, at least from her fellow
Democrats along the campaign trail. ``Despite the obvious handicap
of having the Secret Service around, she does an extraordinary job
of interacting with people,'' said Stephen Hughes, the mayor of
Elmira, where Clinton spoke at a rally on Friday. ``She never
refuses a greeting line. And she really is very engaging.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point on Friday in Ithaca, Clinton was confronted by a
man standing amid her supporters who was holding a sign reading
``New Yorkers for Rick Lazio. Carpetbaggers Go Home.'' She walked
over to him and shook his hand. ``I thanked him for coming out to
see me,'' she said of the encounter. ``I'm glad to see him. It
shows he is interested in the political process.''
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton is inclined to discuss all manner of campaign
issues, from the need to energize tourism upstate to her interest
in lower prices for prescription drugs, she is not typically
inclined to discuss herself. But with a year having passed since
she formed her exploratory committee for her Senate race, she has
appeared more reflective than usual during this weekend's campaign
swing through upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   And so the first lady, while seeming a little reserved,
nonetheless talked to reporters about her first campaign for public
office and the experience of traveling throughout the state of New
York. ``I wasn't sure when I first started how I would feel about
it because it is a very different experience,'' Clinton said of
being a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   She said that ``moving from an advocate for causes to becoming a
candidate'' presented her with new challenges to make her positions
clear to voters and to speak more directly to people than she has
before. ``I found that I liked it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Clinton seemed to be more than a little evasive when
asked several times during this upstate campaign tour what she
considered the most difficult feature of being a candidate in her
own right.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been a challenge feeling comfortable doing it,'' she
said to reporters, after thinking about the question for a moment
or two. ``I wanted to make sure that I was doing it for the right
reasons. And I feel good about it.'' Despite being at the side of
her husband and several other politicians over the last 30 years,
she said, ``I had to learn to be a candidate. Those of you who were
with me early on, I hope have seen a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Rick Lazio, Clinton's Republican rival for the Senate,
completed his own bus trip through the state, with reporters often
traveling in his fashionable bus, and spent considerable time
speaking with the news media in what he has dubbed the Mainstream
Express.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton typically rides in her dark van with her aides and
Secret Service agents, she took the unprecedented step of sitting
on the campaign bus with reporters on the 20-minute ride from
downtown Ithaca to the rally in Elmira.
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether she had chosen to sit with reporters because
of Lazio's having done so during his concurrent bus tour, Clinton
said that her opponent's practice had nothing to do with the
decision. ``Maybe it's because I haven't been invited before,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   That elicited laughs from a press corps that has been hungering
for opportunities to speak with the first lady outside more formal
press conferences.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's campaign aides, however, explain the bus-tour
conversation more straightforwardly. Until the current upstate
trip, there had been no Clinton campaign bus. Instead, the press
usually traveled behind Clinton in a van or, in the case of her
trips in New York City, as best they could.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally speaking, all of our press corps can fit into a
van,'' said Howard Wolfson, Clinton's campaign spokesman. ``But
because of the one-year anniversary, there was more press than
usual. So we expanded and got a bus.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
