<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-ENERGY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: POWERING A HOT CITY  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, July 9:
</P>
<P>
   New York's summer nightmare begins on a steamy evening when a
few million people suddenly switch on their air-conditioners, in
effect blowing the fuse for a wired city. The dimming of lights on
the Upper East Side last month was a reminder that it can happen,
as it did last July when northern Manhattan suffered a 19-hour
blackout. Consolidated Edison has said the city's newly fortified
neighborhood power grids are ready for soaring temperatures and
power use. Still, there are reasons to worry about how the
nationwide experiment with utility deregulation will affect the
reliability and cost of power in a city that thrives on
electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Deregulation, which promised more competition, more alternative
power sources and lower costs to consumers, appears to be playing
transitional tricks in a few areas around the country, including
New York City. As part of its restructuring in the last few years,
Con Edison has been shedding power plants and moving steadily into
the business of distributing power. That means Con Ed must now turn
around and buy power to distribute, a cost that it then passes
along to its customers.
</P>
<P>
   Energy prices this summer are rising for several reasons,
including higher costs for the fuel used to generate power. The
inevitable spike in temperatures will also bring a spike in demand
for electricity. Then there is the city's booming economy, which
encourages people to buy more gadgets and appliances _ which are
simply plucked out of their boxes and plugged into the walls
without advance notice to the utility. Under deregulation,
competition from other power sources was supposed to provide price
relief. But alternative power sources are not readily available for
most city residents.
</P>
<P>
   New York's City Council will begin hearings next week on
concerns that Con Ed's 2.8 million city customers could see energy
costs go up 30 percent this summer, an increase Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani labeled ``outrageous.'' The mayor has advised the company
to cut into its sizable profits rather than raise rates. On a
larger scale, the hearings should determine whether the new Con Ed
has begun favoring its shareholders over its city customers.
</P>
<P>
   Most experts suggest that the power squeeze in the city will
continue for several summers, until new plants are built or
alternative power sources become available. Gov. George Pataki, the
Legislature and the state's Public Service Commission should
recognize that deregulation is still in its early stages and needs
more oversight if such a daring experiment is to succeed in
providing reliable, environmentally sound and affordable wattage,
especially in an overheated New York City.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-00 1528EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000708.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 15:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6696 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MARTHAS-VINEYARD-REAL     07-08 1244
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARTHAS-VINEYARD-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE VINEYARD ADDS TO NEW-HOME CURBS 
</HEADLINE>
   By SUSAN DIESENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AQUINNAH, MARTHA'S VINEYARD, Mass. _ To avoid being swamped in
its own popularity and rising real estate prices, this historic
resort island has tightened its already demanding rules on
residential development. As of this spring, fewer building permits
are being issued and almost no historic structures razed in an
effort to manage growth so that new houses enhance, rather than
overwhelm, the architectural and natural environment
</P>
<P>
   This island, settled in 1642, is filled with historic buildings
set in beguiling natural settings. Still, 18th-century villages dot
a landscape encircled by ocean and threaded with ponds, woods and
fields. Federalist mansions line narrow Edgartown streets,
Victorian cottages cluster around lagoons in Oak Bluffs and
Georgian manor houses still grace erstwhile West Tisbury and
Chilmark farms while early 20th-century fishing shacks overlook
Aquinnah's shores.
</P>
<P>
   But increasingly, wealthy buyers are racing to scoop up the
limited supply of home sites. In their rush, some tear down old
houses and block shoreline vistas to erect big luxury homes known
derisively as McMansions. Soaring land and house costs, meanwhile,
are pricing local working people out of the market.
</P>
<P>
   In response, this spring five of the island's six towns voted to
adopt limitations on construction of new buildings. Only Tisbury
voted the limits down.
</P>
<P>
   This year, only 243 building permits will be issued for new
houses in all five towns (the average number issued since 1983).
Islandwide, including all six towns, 339 permits were issued in
1998, the last year for which statistics are available, according
to Charles W. Clifford, director of the Martha's Vineyard
Commission, the island planning agency. Aquinnah will issue six,
Chilmark 18, West Tisbury 54, Edgartown 93 and Oak Bluffs about 72,
Clifford said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These first islandwide caps will be reviewed in three years,''
he added. ``We're aiming to moderate development, give towns time
to assess today's fast growth and pass better rules to handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   To promote the preservation of historic structures, open space
and the production of lower-cost housing, most towns offer height
and density bonuses for projects that further those goals. In
Aquinnah and neighboring Chilmark, meanwhile, plans for any new
house must undergo extensive review by a special town commission,
while no building may be torn down without first obtaining a
demolition permit.
</P>
<P>
   Owners can still build if they submit to a one- or two-year
approval process and plan a modest house, said Jerry Weiner, the
Aquinnah building inspector. ``Anyone who wants to make this
fragile outpost theirs must be willing to slow down to examine the
issues we face,'' he said. ``Recently, too many have built big
houses that scar the land and burden the infrastructure without
realizing it.''
</P>
<P>
   But with many islanders working in the real estate industry, not
all favor the caps on construction. ``When supply is low, caps
drive up prices,'' said Arthur Smadbeck, an owner of Priestly &AMP;
Smadbeck Real Estate of Tisbury. ``This exacerbates our affordable
housing shortage. We just closed a unit in the nursing home for
lack of workers.''
</P>
<P>
   The nearby island of Nantucket, where the median house price is
$900,000, faces similar dilemmas, said Jack H. Dunn, the island's
building inspector. Each day, 400 workers are brought in from
Hyannis on Cape Cod. ``It's a serious problem when we have to fly
our bus drivers and cashiers in on a shuttle flight every day,''
Dunn said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the churning real-estate market has ``caused an
onslaught of teardowns and gut rehabs that imperil the historic
island's character,'' according to the National Trust for Historic
Preservation. Last month, it placed Nantucket on a list of
America's 11 most endangered historic places, despite islanders'
attempts to save its architectural heritage.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1950s, Nantucket's Historic District Commission has
approved the exterior appearance of all new structures. A 1997
building cap has limited new house construction; this year, 110
building permits will be issued. This fall, Dunn said, voters will
consider a new growth management plan that will further restrict
new construction based on a point system that favors affordable
housing.
</P>
<P>
   On Cape Cod this April, Provincetown tied new building permits
to the water supply, a limit of about 12 a year, half the previous
amount. In 1998, Falmouth also halved the number of permits; this
year it will approve 200 building permits, said Brian Curry, the
town planner. These historic resorts are under similar market
pressures. On Martha's Vineyard last year there were 1,070 sales of
land and houses, up from 494 in 1990, according to the Martha's
Vineyard Land Bank Commission. The median single-family sale price
is $700,000, with the high end up to $11 million and the low end
disappearing, Smadbeck said.
</P>
<P>
   With land often priced at $1 million an acre and new
construction at least $300 a square foot, even a modest new
3,000-square-foot house can cost close to $2 million, brokers and
architects say.
</P>
<P>
   Each town has a somewhat different set of construction rules,
but they all aim to encourage the construction of ``island
friendly'' houses.
</P>
<P>
   In Oak Bluffs, the new cap was added to 12-year-old historic
preservation rules that require Victorian styling and new houses of
only three bedrooms in some neighborhoods. To fit in, Dr. and Mrs.
Arthur Spielvogel of Ridgewood, N.J., had Peter Breese Architects
design a 3,000-square-foot house on a lagoon with cedar shingles
and an old-fashioned screened-in porch. While the house has a
traditional Victorian exterior, an open interior layout gives it a
spacious feel.
</P>
<P>
   West Tisbury's new zoning code, adopted this spring, expanded
the historic district to embrace 120 properties, up from 12;
adopted a building cap; and now requires a permit for all
demolition, a requirement that recently stopped one buyer from
tearing down a 1600s tavern. The new code also suspends a
three-acre zoning requirement to preserve farmland and promote
lower-priced housing.
</P>
<P>
   West Tisbury wants more projects like Island Co-Housing, which
is just being completed in the woods off North Road. On four acres
of a 30-acre site, John Abrams, who owns the South Mountain Co.,
developed 16 single-family houses priced from $125,000 to $310,000.
Privately, the 16 families raised funds to subsidize the
lower-priced units.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in heaven,'' said Christie Phillips, 38. A year-round
resident who designs interiors and clothing, she moved in with her
two sons this spring after a seven-year housing search. ``I have a
gem of a house and a real neighborhood here with a pond, playground
and community house.''
</P>
<P>
   In rural Chilmark, development bonuses also go to low-cost
housing and salvaging historic structures. Starting in 1990, Ben
Clark, a historic preservationist, and his wife, Suzanne,
disassembled, board by board, the manor that Simon Athearn had
built in 1730 on his farm in West Tisbury. The Clarks were allowed
to add a 300-square-foot addition for a new kitchen to the
reconstructed house.
</P>
<P>
   And to be historically accurate, the house, reconstruction of
which was completed last year, is 28 feet high _ a 4-foot height
bonus over what would be allowed by current regulations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
