</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-TVREALITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: ANOTHER DAY, ANOTHER DOSE OF FALSE REALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   By VERLYN KLINKENBORG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last Wednesday night, the producers of ``Big Brother,'' the new
``reality based'' companion to ``Survivor'' in the CBS television
lineup, restaged O.J. Simpson's white Bronco chase across L.A., but
with 10 SUVs instead of 1. Each SUV carried a contestant who will
be immured utterly without privacy day and night in a specially
built house full of cameras and microphones for three months or
until voted out of the bug-house by concerned viewers. The last
contestant to remain wins half a million dollars. The first seven
to leave earn just $350 a week, which, given all the overtime, is
way below minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, the rules of the ``Big Brother'' show state that
``You must not now be a candidate for public office and must agree
not to become one until after the initial broadcast of all programs
in which you appear.'' Too bad. I can't think of a better way to
learn what we really want to know about Al Gore and George W. Bush
than by throwing them into the ``Big Brother'' house for 90 days
with eight putatively ordinary folks. Perhaps voter turnout in
November would be higher if, as on ``Survivor'' and ``Big
Brother,'' a vote for a candidate were actually a vote against him.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there is no reality in reality-based television.
Everyone knows that. But there is no voyeurism either, and that's
the letdown. Everyone on the ``Survivor'' island and in the ``Big
Brother'' house is perfectly aware of the cameras and microphones.
In fact, the clause surrendering your privacy is underlined in the
``Big Brother'' rules. ``Survivor'' is Jerry Springer with sand,
skin rashes and bad food. ``Big Brother'' has all the
self-consciousness of ``It's Garry Shandling's Show,'' without the
good writing and decor. If it is reality you want, spy on 10 people
who do not know they are being watched. CBS still has much to learn
from Allen Funt and old-line Stalinists.
</P>
<P>
   By ``reality,'' of course, CBS merely means that these programs
are unscripted and that the castaways and housemates are ordinary
people. But on the Web site devoted to ``Big Brother,'' the network
has already turned the housemates into characters as identifiable
as Urkel or Barney Fife. And, as ``Survivor'' and a half-century of
TV have proved, a television camera tends to make people talk and
behave in culturally scripted ways, the ways they have seen
represented again and again on television. ``Survivor'' also proves
that if you shoot enough footage and edit hard, you can make almost
anything interesting, except the host of the show, who is really
the only islander with anything to be ashamed of.
</P>
<P>
   You do not have to reach very far before the list of antecedents
to these programs grows almost unmanageable _ it includes
``Gilligan's Island,'' ``The Tempest,'' ``Robinson Crusoe,''
``1984,'' Albert Brooks' ``Real Life,'' Terry Gilliam's ``Brazil,''
and on and on and on. But the theme that really grabs the audience
for these shows isn't shipwreck or communal living or imposed
fasting or the collision between teamwork and self-reliance.
</P>
<P>
   What really grabs the audience is self-exposure and, in ``Big
Brother,'' the chance to blackball, one by one, the characters in a
TV show, a power we never had over ``Cheers.'' For now, the
housemates in that Studio City bungalow-fortress are prisoners of
their own exhibitionism. Only time will set them free.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
