A6698 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-MAGIC-NYT     07-08 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAGIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUEL OF NEW DYNASTIES MAY LIFT THE RATINGS
</HEADLINE>
  (With BKN-NOTEBOOK) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The scenario from heaven may be unfolding for the NBA. With
television ratings down and its buzz having given way to a hum,
what is potentially a new millennium version of the engaging 1980s
rivalry between the Los Angeles Lakers and the Boston Celtics
appears to be taking form.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 1, the Orlando Magic could announce that the free agents
Grant Hill, Tim Duncan and Tracy McGrady will join the team for the
next six years. No contracts have been signed, but Hill has told
his former club, the Detroit Pistons, that he intends to go to
Orlando; McGrady, who grew up in Auburndale, Fla., has said
repeatedly that he wants to play for the Magic; and Duncan is
currently fighting between his loyalty to the San Antonio Spurs and
his desire to team with Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Every Eastern Conference club not coached by Doc Rivers is
hoping that the league's best power forward stays loyal because if
those three, or even just Duncan and Hill, combine forces in
Orlando, the East is theirs. Patrick Ewing's already dim chances of
winning a title would die instantly. Pat Riley would not even have
the best team in his state, let alone division or conference. And
Indiana's retro Conseco Fieldhouse would be as old as the design of
its bleacher seating the next time it saw an NBA finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without question, Orlando would be the best team in the
East,'' said a coach from an Eastern Conference playoff team who
requested anonymity. ``It would be them, the Lakers and Portland.''
</P>
<P>
   And while Portland could potentially crash the Lakers' and
Magic's annual finals party, their chances of doing so lessen with
each game since the legs of Scottie Pippen, Steve Smith and Arvydas
Sabonis are getting heavier, not fresher. What you would very
likely have is Shaquille O'Neal, Kobe Bryant and whoever versus
Duncan, Hill and McGrady each June, just like the old days when it
was Magic Johnson, Kareem Abdul-Jabbar and James Worthy versus
Larry Bird, Robert Parish and Kevin McHale.
</P>
<P>
   Even though that might frustrate some of the league's coaches,
it might also bump up the ratings and fan appeal that have been
waning since Michael Jordan's retirement two years ago. ``Something
like that would be good, especially when you look at what's
happening to the league,'' said Wayne Embry, the former general
manager and president of the Cleveland Cavaliers. Dynasties have
been good for the NBA, as fans seem to like familiarity in their
champions. Magic and Bird rescued the league from the public
perception of insignificance and drug abuse by helping their teams
dominate their conferences. Magic's Lakers won eight conference
championships and five league titles in the 1980s while Bird's
Celtics won five Eastern titles and three NBA crowns.
</P>
<P>
   A Los Angeles-Orlando run would not have the unspoken, though
intense, racial undertones that Los Angeles-Boston had, but there
would be contrasting social themes to enhance the drama. Shaq and
Kobe are hip-hop _ brash, stylish and intimidating in their play _
while Duncan and Hill are classical: smooth, staid and quietly
outstanding. As the followings for the Lakers and Celtics sometimes
broke down along racial lines, the followings for the Lakers and
the Magic would perhaps at times flow along cultural ones. And, of
course, there is the story line of O'Neal bolting Orlando for Los
Angeles as a free agent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Also, all four are excellent role models off the court.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this could all be irrelevant if Duncan stays in San
Antonio. In fact, several league executives believe it would be
foolish of Hill to go to Orlando without Duncan. For that reason, a
popular thought around the league is that Hill already knows that
Duncan is going to Florida. After all, they do share the same
counsel in Lon Babby.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim's enjoyed it here, and we've obviously enjoyed him,'' said
Gregg Popovich, the Spurs' coach and general manager, who along
with Duncan helped bring San Antonio its first championship two
years ago. ``We've had great success and we still have the same
championship team in the healing process, so to speak. I think it's
a great situation for Tim and we hope that's what he decides to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Only verbal agreements have been made, so if Duncan chooses to
stay in San Antonio, there is nothing to stop Hill from changing
his mind and going to the Spurs or any of the other teams,
including the Knicks, that tried to court him last week. The more
likely scenario, however, has Duncan and Hill going to Orlando,
where they would each receive six-year, $67.5 million contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Obtaining McGrady, who has already said that ``it won't be fair
for Eastern Conference opponents if all three players go to the
Magic,'' will be more complicated.
</P>
<P>
   Because Orlando does not have enough money to pay all three
players the maximum immediately, Toronto will either have to agree
to a sign-and-trade deal with the Magic or McGrady will have to
accept playing for $5 or $6 million next season instead of $9
million. If that is the case, Orlando will most likely give him an
out clause after four years that would allow him to receive the
maximum amount of money.
</P>
<P>
   If all of this comes together, the Magic would not only be
envied; it would also be admired. After losing O'Neal and Penny
Hardaway, the young building blocks of what looked like a
championship team, within the last four years, its general manager,
John Gabriel, has repositioned the Magic to be a powerhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Orlando has done a lot of impressive things,'' Embry said.
``Losing Shaq and Penny could have devastated their franchise. But
they took a negative and turned it into a positive. If all of this
happens, they've done a heck of a job.''
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps a heck of a service to the league and its fans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
