<HEADLINE>
KNICKS IN A BIND; A BARGAINING CHIP
</HEADLINE>
  (With BKN-MAGIC) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   After being spurned by Grant Hill, the Knicks are faced with the
fact that they have no comparable Plan B that will be anywhere near
as effective. One member of the organization scoffed when asked if
they could somehow obtain another superstar, such as Seattle's Gary
Payton.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way,'' the Knicks official said. ``That's all just
speculation and stuff people write about, but it can't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks cannot even bring Portland power forward Brian Grant
to New York. Uninterested in the Knicks offer of Marcus Camby and
Chris Childs, the Blazers would demand Latrell Sprewell or Allan
Houston and a front-court player. And the Knicks believe that
parting with either of their star swingmen for Grant would be
ludicrous.
</P>
<P>
   Kurt Thomas' agent, Jerry Hicks, has proposed a six-year deal
worth $29.9 million, the maximum amount Thomas can be paid by the
Knicks. It is a reasonable offer, and the Knicks are mulling it
over.
</P>
<P>
   Danny Fortson, the Boston Celtics free agent who is dying to
play for the Knicks, was in an uproar on Thursday after hearing a
false rumor that the Knicks had made a sign-and-trade deal for the
Los Angeles Clippers' Maurice Taylor. Fortson, who is said to be
proudly carrying around the Knicks jersey the club sent to him, has
reportedly been offered a seven-year, $31 million deal from the
Celtics.
</P>
<P>
   A Bargaining Chip
</P>
<P>
   The players union will hold its annual meeting July 23-28 in the
Bahamas. More than 70 players are expected to attend, plus more
than 100 retired players from the Ex-NBA Players Association. The
players will vote to fill the six vice president slots on their
nine-member board, but the hot topic of conversation could be the
union's purchase of the Continental Basketball Association from
Isiah Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   The union has signed a letter of intent to buy the CBA, with its
impetus for the purchase being bargaining power if another work
stoppage takes place when the current collective bargaining
agreement ends in either 2004 or 2005 (the owners have an option
for a seventh year). Owning the CBA would give the union the
infrastructure necessary to put its players to work in the event of
a lockout.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
