<SLUG> BC-NY-GARBAGE-DISPOSALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN CITY, GARBAGE DISPOSALS SLOWLY GAIN POPULARITY
</HEADLINE>
  By TINA KELLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Slowly but surely, the grinding whir of garbage
disposals is joining the symphonic, electronic noise of New York
City's kitchens.
</P>
<P>
   Keep fingers and spoons clear and the water running, hit the
switch and listen to the sweet rumbling of peelings, cores and
antiquated leftovers swirling down the drain. It's a daily ritual
for people in 80 to 90 percent of the custom kitchens in the
Southeast, Midwest and West, and just over half the custom kitchens
in the Northeast, according to the National Kitchen and Bath
Association.
</P>
<P>
   But until 1997, when the City Council lifted its 26-year ban on
garbage disposals, the kitchen-sink route to oblivion was not an
option for most of New York City.
</P>
<P>
   In the last several years, disposal sales have been brisk but
uneven. ``Contractors as well as homeowners are catching on, but
it's a slow process, because people are not that familiar with them
so much,'' said Joe Jones, an assistant manager with Davis &AMP;
Warshow Inc., a plumbing supply company. He estimates that his
store sells several a week. ``It hasn't hit like wildfire yet.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he suspected that people were not yet using their
disposals, which sell for $150 to $300, to their full potential.
``It takes time to get used to throwing your food down the sink as
opposed to in a waste receptacle,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Scott, sales manager for the newly offered Chelsea
Mercantile condominiums at Seventh Avenue and 24th Street, said the
developer's decision to include garbage disposals in the building's
renovated kitchens made her job easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have one personally,'' she said. ``If you're cooking,
peeling, or cleaning plates, you just don't accumulate as much
garbage.'' And less garbage means less odor and less vermin, she
added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
