<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOATING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCUDDING AT 31 KNOTS: THRILLS ON A CATAMARAN IN RHODE ISLAND
SOUND 
</HEADLINE>
   Herb McCormick is the editor of Cruising World magazine.  
 By HERB McCORMICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWPORT, R.I. _ The grand coincidence was the source of
countless double takes. With tens of thousands of people lining the
shores of Narragansett Bay on Sunday to watch the outgoing Tall
Ships parade of sail, an inbound, 110-foot catamaran called Club
Med weaved its way through a huge spectator fleet.
</P>
<P>
   Between blinks one could take in the classic spoon-bowed
Canadian schooner Bluenose as well as the French-built Club Med, a
relatively spindly wing-masted multihull replete with a powder-blue
paint job dashed with colorful fish and a matching quartet of
gaudy, bikini-clad maidens _ a pair for each bow.
</P>
<P>
   The two ships passing in the day were not only of separate eras.
They appeared to be from different planets.
</P>
<P>
   Like Star Trek's Spock, the next afternoon I was beamed aboard
Club Med with a handful of other journalists and a short guest list
that included the 1992 America's Cup winner, Bill Koch, and the New
York Yacht Club commodore, George Isdale Jr., for a remarkable
daysail in Rhode Island Sound.
</P>
<P>
   My experience with big multihulls is limited, though in the
mid-'80s I did cross the Atlantic with the legendary British sailor
Robin Knox-Johnston aboard his 60-foot cat British Airways, a
hulking craft the French yachting press derisively nicknamed ``the
truck of the seas.'' While the knot-meter sometimes hovered in the
low- to mid-20s on the passage, it was inadequate preparation for a
spin on Club Med.
</P>
<P>
   If British Airways was a pickup, Club Med is a Ferrari. Launched
less than two months ago, the boat has already claimed the title as
the world's quickest oceangoing sailboat, having set the record
last month for the fastest 24-hour run: a purposeful 625.7 miles,
an average speed over 26 knots, on a trip from Spain to the
Bahamas.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the fact, it's easy to say that it was easy,'' said Club
Med's skipper, Grant Dalton, a New Zealander who has spent about
half his 42 years racing sailboats around the world. ``But
actually, it was easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Dalton is new to large catamarans but he says he is hooked, and
soon after his 14-man international crew had hoisted the main and
set a small jib, it was apparent why. Reaching across the entrance
to the bay in about 18 knots of southerly breeze, with a blurred
seascape rapidly receding beneath the net trampolines laced between
the hulls and with the entire boat emitting a low, eerie hum,
Dalton soon had Club Med piercing the light chop at a windswept 31
knots.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never get sick of going over 30,'' he shouted. ``I haven't
yet, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, for the most part, Club Med's pro crew effected a stoic
nonchalance to the proceedings. But we whooping 30-knot rookies,
tilting unsteadily to windward in the bursts of acceleration, were
beside ourselves. Dooie Isdale's grin resembled the one he sported
while dancing with the Kiwi actress Lucy Lawless _ better known as
Xena, the Warrior Princess _ at a party during last spring's
America's Cup regatta in New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   One does not exact such speed without a price, however. In Club
Med's case, however, that means keeping the boat as light as
possible. Asked to describe the freeze-dried chow consumed on
distance races, Nicolas Pichelin, a French crew member, called it
``disgusting.'' And his British mate Ed Danby's reply to a query
about onboard creature comforts was equally pointed:
``nonexistent.''
</P>
<P>
   Misery loves company, of course, and in the months ahead the
Club Med crew will have a slew of fellow offshore sailors with whom
to commiserate, for the boat's ultimate mission is to win the Race,
the round-the-world jaunt that begins Dec. 31 from Barcelona,
Spain. American Steve Fossett's Play Station and Englishman Pete
Goss' Team Phillips are both entered, and another Yank, Cam Lewis,
is still seeking funds for his Team Adventure syndicate. Lewis is
building a sister ship to Club Med.
</P>
<P>
   Dalton believes the victorious crew will circle the planet in 62
days. ``I think you'll need to get on a 675-mile-a-day pace,'' he
said. ``And I think we're capable of that.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Southern Ocean, Club Med's solid 480-square-foot wing
mast _ an area equal in size to the entire sail plans of many
midsize cruising boats _ could prove troublesome. After all, even
with all sail doused, the mast presents a considerable amount of
windage aloft.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a static load, and if we get 75 knots, we're
tumbleweed,'' Dalton said.
</P>
<P>
   To combat such a dire capsize circumstance, he said Club Med is
equipped with substantial water-ballast tanks in each bow. ``If we
get into a survival situation, we'll flood the tanks, sink the boat
low into the water, and hang on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But on a summer afternoon off Newport, life-and-death storms
were the last things on anyone's mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt that these boats are 20 percent or more
faster than any boats that have ever been built,'' Dalton said.
</P>
<P>
   Having proved his point, he swung the wheel and pointed his
thoroughbred toward the barn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
