<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-WRIGHT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARLES ALAN WRIGHT, A LEGAL CONSULTANT TO NIXON, DIES AT 72 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Texas, Calif., Conn., Pa., Minn., N.Y.)   By JOHN H. CUSHMAN Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Charles Alan Wright, an authority on constitutional law and the
federal courts who represented President Richard Nixon at a crucial
moment in the Watergate scandal, died on Friday at the North Austin
Medical Center in Texas. He was 72 and lived in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was complications after recent lung surgery, his
family said.
</P>
<P>
   Wright was an expert on court procedure who argued 13 cases
before the Supreme Court and was a leader of the faculty at the
University of Texas Law School in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   As a special legal consultant to Nixon in summer 1973, he argued
unsuccessfully that the constitutional separation of powers between
the executive and judicial branches protected the president from
turning over White House tape recordings to the special prosecutor,
Archibald Cox. Eventually, the tapes helped prove the extent of the
conspiracy to obstruct justice and led to Nixon's impeachment by
the House and his resignation.
</P>
<P>
   In negotiations with Cox, and in arguments before U.S. District
Judge John Sirica and later before a court of appeals, Wright
insisted that the prosecutor's demands to obtain the tapes for a
grand jury investigating the break-in at the Democratic Party
headquarters in the Watergate Hotel were an intrusion by the courts
into the powers of the presidency. He even suggested that Nixon
would defy a judicial ruling against him. But after losing the
court battle and failing to reach a compromise with Cox, who was
fired in what became known as the Saturday night massacre, Wright
announced that Nixon would comply after all. During the rest of the
Watergate matter, Wright's role was less prominent.
</P>
<P>
   While the Watergate case put Wright most squarely before the
public, in legal circles he was well known as the senior author of
a 55-volume treatise, ``Federal Practice and Procedure.'' His
``Cases on Federal Courts'' is in its 10th edition and his ``Wright
on Federal Courts'' is in its 5th edition. In a lighter vein,
Wright occasionally reviewed crime novels for the Practical Lawyer,
a publication of the American Bar Association and the American Law
Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Wright regarded himself as a conservative, a philosophy
exemplified in his argument on behalf of Texas in 1970 when it
joined three other states in challenging the constitutionality of
the law that lowered the voting age to 18.
</P>
<P>
   He called the law ``frivolous'' and insisted that the
Constitution gave the states the power to set voting standards.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Alan Wright was born Sept. 3, 1927, in Philadelphia. A
precocious student, he graduated from Haverford High School at 16
and finished his undergraduate work at Wesleyan University at 18.
He graduated from Yale Law School in 1949, spent a year as law
clerk for Judge Charles E. Clark of the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals in New York, then began to teach law at the University of
Minnesota in 1950. Five years later, he moved to Austin and joined
the faculty of the University of Texas Law School.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Wright became the president of the American Law
Institute, an organization of practitioners, judges and academics.
He was active in the arts in Austin, where he was a founder of the
classical radio station KMFA.
</P>
<P>
   Wright is survived by his wife, Eleanor Custis Wright of Austin;
a son, Charles E., of Irvine, Calif.; four daughters, Norie Clarke
of Berkeley, Calif., Margot Clarke of Austin, Henrietta Wright of
Dallas, and Cecily Fitzsimons of Austin; and by six grandchildren.
He is also survived by his sister, Jean Wright Morse of Fredonia,
N.Y.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
