<SLUG> BC-NILE-VIRUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y., N.J.)  
 WEST NILE VIRUS DETECTED IN BIRDS IN THREE NEW YORK COUNTIES
</HEADLINE>
  By SARAH KERSHAW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two dead crows on Long Island and two others, one in Westchester
County and one in Rockland County, have tested positive for West
Nile virus, New York state health officials said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The test results for the birds in Suffolk County, Long Island,
and Westchester counties, which were released late last week by the
New York state Department of Health and reported Saturday by
Newsday, were the first confirmed cases in those counties this
year. West Nile is a mosquito-borne virus that killed seven people
and infected 62 others in the New York area last year.
</P>
<P>
   In Rockland County, the crow that tested positive for the virus
last week brought to five the number of birds in that county found
to have died from the virus since local health departments began
shipping dead birds to a lab in Albany for testing earlier this
year.
</P>
<P>
   As part of a regional surveillance program aimed at detecting
the presence of the virus, which can cause encephalitis in humans
and can be fatal, state officials have been sampling the blood of
dead birds and monitoring live chickens, which carry the virus but
do not get sick from it.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, New York City went on the alert when a chicken in
Queens, near the epicenter of the 1999 outbreak, initially tested
positive. Plans to spray the area were halted when further
laboratory tests showed the chicken was not infected. There have
been no cases of West Nile in the city this year.
</P>
<P>
   But in early June, three dead crows, two in Rockland County and
one in Bergen County, N.J., tested positive for the virus.
</P>
<P>
   Millie Svatek, a spokeswoman for the Suffolk County Health
Department, said Saturday that the Long Island crows were found by
residents in West Babylon and in Lindenhurst. She said that
officials had not determined whether the birds had been recently
infected with the virus or had picked it up in last year's
outbreak, which killed dozens of crows and horses around Long
Island.
</P>
<P>
   However, experts say that crows tend to die quickly after
contracting West Nile infections, making it likely that the birds
caught the virus this year.
</P>
<P>
   Svatek said the county had no immediate plans to spray mosquito
pesticides in the area.
</P>
<P>
   The crow in Westchester that tested positive was found dead in
New Rochelle, where a woman died of West Nile encephalitis last
year. Westchester and Rockland County health officials could not be
reached for comment Saturday, and it was unclear whether they would
begin spraying in response to the positive test results.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-00 1606EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000708.0155 </DOCNO>
