<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POTTER-REVIEW-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK REVIEW: HARRY POTTER AND THE GOBLET OF FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN MARK EBERHART  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire, by J.K. Rowling
(734 pages; Scholastic Press; $25.95)
</P>
<P>
   Wizards, ghosts, dragons, unicorns: They all play a part in
Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire, but what J.K. Rowling needed
most for her new book is that magical creature known as...an
editor.
</P>
<P>
   Or at least that's how it is at first. The opening 200 pages of
the fourth Harry Potter volume could have been trimmed by half. The
first chapter, ``The Riddle House,'' is excellent, with a
long-dormant menace awakening to new power. But then Rowling
dawdles, spending too much time on talky, pointless dialogue and on
jokes that are lame.
</P>
<P>
   Children eager to read the new story have been overjoyed at
rumors that Goblet of Fire would exceed 700 pages, yet it's hard to
imagine even the most ardent fan not wishing that something would
happen sooner. Harry's new adventure would have been much more
adventurous at 600 pages instead of 734.
</P>
<P>
   But hang in there, kids, because when this tale finally takes
off, it goes everywhere you want it to, and the ride is almost as
thrilling as having your own flying broomstick.
</P>
<P>
   Young Harry Potter is now 14 and returns for his fourth year of
instruction at Hogwarts School of Witchcraft and Wizardry. Before
the new term begins, he attends the Quidditch World Cup with his
friends Ron and Hermione. As classes begin, Harry is looking
forward to playing some Quidditch himself _ that fabulous sport in
which players on broomsticks must contend with game balls that have
minds of their own.
</P>
<P>
   This year, though, Harry won't be focusing on Quidditch.
Instead, all the Hogwarts students are transfixed by the Triwizard
Tournament, a competition involving spellcasting and other magical
prowess that hasn't been held for a century.
</P>
<P>
   Harry is too young to compete: Contestants from Hogwarts and two
rival schools must be at least 17 because the competition is so
dangerous. Those who meet the age requirement can put their names
into the magical ``Goblet of Fire,'' which then will select one
contestant from each school.
</P>
<P>
   Flames and showers of sparks erupt from the Goblet, and with
each eruption, out comes a parchment naming each school's
contestant. But then the Goblet spews a fourth time _ and Harry
Potter's name emerges. ``I didn't put my name in!'' he exclaims
when questioned by faculty and students alike. But the Goblet has
spoken: Harry will compete against a witch and two wizards older
and presumably stronger than he is.
</P>
<P>
   As Harry Potter fans know, though, nothing with Harry is ever as
simple as it appears (or disappears). He has a knack for
Invisibility Cloaks but also procrastination, for flashes of
brilliant wizardry but also for getting into the worst messes
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Rowling's handling of the three tasks the young necromancers
must face in the Triwizard Tournament is delightful. From dragons
to mer-people (not just mermaids) to a wonderful magical maze, she
puts Harry and his competitors _ who include his schoolmate and
Quidditch nemesis, Cedric Diggory _ through some imaginative paces.
</P>
<P>
   Rowling also should be commended for allowing her characters to
grow. Harry was 11 in the first book; he ages one year for each
book written, and the author plans three more after this. By
letting Ron, Hermione and Harry grow up, Rowling is transcending
the often static world of childrens' entertainment. In this volume,
Harry and Ron fuss as only adolescent boys do. And there are the
first blossomings of romances and jealousies among the three
friends.
</P>
<P>
   Parents be warned: Although there is no sex in this book,
Rowling's characters are starting to talk like adults. The
profanity is very occasional and quite mild, but it exists.
</P>
<P>
   And the violence is more realistic and more disturbing. Yes, the
rumors are true: An ongoing character does die in this episode.
You'll never guess who, though, until almost the very end.
</P>
<P>
   Rowling also deals with what all fantasists must confront: the
epic clash between good and evil. The Triwizard Tournament, it
turns out, is just a shadow of what's really going on in the world
of magic. There are entities here both heroic and terrible, and
never in the three previous books has that conflict been better.
</P>
<P>
   Only a miserable, nonmagical Muggle would reveal the details of
how the tension grows and is resolved, so we must stop now. But
it's not too much of a hint to name Him Who Must Not Be Named, and
to warn readers to be on the lookout for...
</P>
<P>
   Voldemort. ( 30 )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-00 1607EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000708.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 16:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6720 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-PRODIGY-900&AMP;ADD-N     07-08 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-PRODIGY-900&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANHATTAN YOUNGSTER TAKES COURTS BY STORM
</HEADLINE>
  By GREG WINTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On the public courts outside her Inwood home in upper
Manhattan, Irina Falconi has a nickname: the adult abuser.
</P>
<P>
   At 4 feet 6 inches, the fourth-grader is barely twice the height
of her tennis racket. But she handily defeats men a head or two
taller, adding to the vanquished who are thirsting for revenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny,'' she said, giggling. ``I think they're afraid of
me.'' Last year, at age 9, Irina became the top-ranked girl under
13 in New York City, one of the youngest ever, according to the
U.S. Tennis Association. Now, she has moved up to tristate
competition, and is ranked eighth among girls 12 and under. At 10,
she is the youngest player in the top 10 in the Eastern section.
</P>
<P>
   Even in these early stages, many top-notch players train with
professional coaches for $100 an hour or more. Irina practices with
her father, Carlos Falconi, a cabinetmaker from Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
   Time was, a public school girl from a family of modest means
would be a rarity among the best players in New York, New Jersey
and Connecticut, the three states that make up the USTA's eastern
section. But long before Venus and Serena Williams emerged from the
public parks in Compton, Calif., to take their place in the
semifinals of Wimbledon, tennis had become more accessible to the
hungry and talented.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not rich people,'' said Silvia Falconi, Irina's mother,
who is a secretary for a personal injury lawyer. ``Maybe if we had
money, she wouldn't be as good. Heroes come with adversity.''
</P>
<P>
   Irina and her father rally in the park as much as three hours a
day, next to the basketball players who sip from paper bags and the
cars with their stereos booming and doors open wide, filling the
streets with merengue in the summertime.
</P>
<P>
   The Falconis play there in winter, too, wearing heavy coats and
gloves. Sometimes the old Russian man who comes every day will
sweep up the leaves and call them when the courts are clean.
Sometimes father and daughter take a shovel and clear the snow
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Falconi gives Irina a good run. Nearly 10 years as a
professional soccer player in Ecuador have left the 38-year-old
with square shoulders and quick feet. But he misses shots
sometimes, making Irina huff in frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I need someone stronger,'' she said sheepishly, trying
not to hurt his feelings.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, the courts draw other good players, some from as far as
Long Island looking for competition. Carlos Falconi watches them
all, and picks among the strongest servers and hardest hitters to
find sparring partners for his daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to see any mercy on your side,'' he tells the men
he chooses. ``Play tough.''
</P>
<P>
   An unorthodox training regimen, maybe. But effective, perhaps
even necessary. Irina goes to P.S.-I.S. 223, which has no courts or
sports teams, much less a tennis program. If it had one, she says,
there would be no one to compete with anyway.
</P>
<P>
   In the past decade or so, young New York City players with
national ambitions like Irina have had to find their competition
and development in out of school programs, especially the New York
Junior Tennis League, the nonprofit organization Arthur Ashe
started to get the sport into the city's schools. Each year, the
league sponsors 30 promising players to the tune of $5,000 to
$15,000 each, paying the tournament fees, professional coaching,
travel and other expenses that would otherwise be beyond their
reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say that half the ranked kids from New York City come
from our programs,'' said Skip Hartman, the league's president.
``You don't have to be rich anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Now when public and private high schools clash at the Mayor's
Cup, an annual citywide tennis tournament, the private school
students are often the ones who are trounced. Some public high
school teams are so good that teen-agers with top 20 rankings in
the East warm the bench.
</P>
<P>
   The city's commercial tennis academies are reaching out to
underfunded youngsters, although on a smaller scale. Last winter,
Irina earned a scholarship to practice at the Randy Mani Tennis
Academy, a training ground for several of the eastern division's
top competitors that can cost several hundred dollars a week.
</P>
<P>
   But even though money is not the barrier it once was, it is
still expensive to become a tennis champion. ``Parents can spend
$30,000 a year cultivating a top-level player,'' Mani said.
</P>
<P>
   That is hardly an option for Carlos and Silvia Falconi. Their
daughter Stephanie, 16, is also a top 10 player in the East for her
age group, in need of the same rackets and road trips to
tournaments as her younger sister.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is coming out of our pockets,'' said Carlos
Falconi, stringing a racket on his dining room table.
</P>
<P>
   The men from the Inwood courts help out. An African-American
player gave them a tennis bag. Another from Ecuador pitched in with
a new racket. And there is always Gatorade or some treat to be had
between sets, even from the man who cannot seem to lose gracefully.
</P>
<P>
   But that is Inwood, a long way from Long Island and Westchester,
where Mercedeses and Range Rovers fill the parking lots at
tournaments. At first, the Falconis felt self-conscious driving up
in their sputtering, Reagan-era station wagon with dented fenders.
But they soon got used to it, and by the end of the tournament
often felt as if they were riding off in a chariot.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that old car, there's a champion,'' said Carlos Falconi.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Still, it exasperated Stephanie to no end when the rest of the
family crossed fingers and bowed heads to pray for the car to
start. So the Falconis broke the bank and bought a minivan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to,'' said Carlos Falconi. ``She was going to quit
tennis.''
</P>
<P>
   Irina has not yet begun to think about such things. She is more
than happy letting her parents worry if her talent will someday pay
for college, which neither of them finished. For now, Irina is too
busy wondering what to do if she strives to become the world's best
player, only to land in the No. 2 spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd take it, I guess,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
