<SLUG> BC-DOTCOM-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE INTERNET GIVES WHITE ELEPHANTS A NEW LIFE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., N.J., Fla.)  By JOHN HOLUSHA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Generations of New Jerseyans shopped the Bamberger's store at
the corner of Market and Halsey streets in Newark for clothing,
accessories and household goods. The throngs of shoppers have long
since departed for the suburbs but the store, later named Macy's
and closed in 1992, has gained an unexpected new life.
</P>
<P>
   Rows of computers and telecommunications equipment now fill the
floors that once displayed women's dresses and men's suits. The
building has been transformed into a high-technology center, the
physical repository of the machines that support the rapid growth
of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   It is just one example of how old industrial and retail
properties, formerly considered unrentable white elephants, have
suddenly become highly attractive to Web hosting and communications
companies who need sites to expand _ and need them now.
</P>
<P>
   The old buildings have what the Internet companies need: sturdy
floors and high ceilings to accommodate heavy, delicate equipment;
abundant electrical power to keep the machines humming and easy
access to the optical-fiber cables that are the highways of the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the old industrial buildings, proximity to the
high-volume fiber cables has come because the cables have been
installed along established railroad lines.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of this newfound desirability of certain types of
industrial buildings, old factories in Jersey City, a sprawling and
underused marine terminal and an old tire factory in Brooklyn, and
various locations in New Jersey's Meadowlands are all being
promoted as technology centers.
</P>
<P>
   Even buildings that were at the heart of old telecommunications
technology, such as AT&AMP;T's onetime manual switching center in
Manhattan are being adapted to new technology. The building has
been purchased by the Rudin family, which is adapting it for use by
companies like MCI WorldCom and Qwest.
</P>
<P>
   While a new generation of equipment will be installed upstairs
at the old switching center, the landmarked lobby will retain the
1932 murals and the declaration that ``Telephone wires and radio
unite to make neighbors of nations.''
</P>
<P>
   What is happening in the New York area is being replicated
around the country and around the world. Everything is driven by
time because new-economy companies believe that the ones who grab
market share first will dominate their sectors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Telecommunications and the Internet are closely related, they
go hand in hand,'' said Goodwin Gaw, the chairman of Global
Gateway, a company that is building a network of servers and
telecommunications equipment in the western United States and Asia.
``Our customers like to be there before the wave.''
</P>
<P>
   Global Gateway is one of two companies being backed by $1.25
billion from Morgan Stanley Real Estate Funds to build a global
Internet communications network. The other is Metro-Nexis, which is
responsible for the eastern United States and Europe. MetroNexis
recently agreed to buy the 1.1-million-square-foot former American
Can factory in Jersey City.
</P>
<P>
   For companies building the networks of computers, cable and
software that undergird the Internet, ``speed to market is the name
of the game, and the space has to be available now,'' said Mark A.
Teitelbaum, a partner in Argent Ventures, a New York real estate
investment company. ``Anything that will not be ready for 18 months
is a non-starter.''
</P>
<P>
   Argent has been acquiring property, including buildings in
Weehawken and Jersey City and an old shopping mall in Miami, all
for use as technology centers for Internet companies. ``We have
acquired between 6 and 7 million square feet of property in the
last 12 months,'' said Andrew S. Penson, another Argent partner.
``But that is like 10 years in Internet time.''
</P>
<P>
   The million-square-foot Omni Mall on Biscayne Boulevard in Miami
had one particularly significant advantage, Penson said. It was
empty. He said the site could be a gateway to planned underwater
communications links to Central and South America.
</P>
<P>
   The increase in marketability of older buildings suitable for
use by Internet infrastructure companies has come suddenly.
``Nobody knew anything about this until about a year ago,'' said
John Peters, a former broker with Cushman &AMP; Wakefield who now runs
his own company, Technology Real Estate. ``Now it is the `in' thing
for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The technology boom is unexpectedly rehabilitating buildings
that had been dismissed as obsolete, because of their size, ceiling
height or amount of room for parking. But a facility that might be
obsolete for warehousing and distribution could work well for Web
hosting and telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have old buildings that are coming back to life,'' said
Richard Marchisio, managing director of Grubb &AMP; Ellis of New
Jersey. ``This is a whole new sector of real estate that did not
exist previously.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
