<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 16:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6722 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AT-HOME-REAL-665&AMP;ADD-     07-08 1179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-HOME-REAL-665&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHECKING NEW HOUSE FOR FLAWS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAY ROMANO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Potential buyers usually aren't shy about flushing the toilets,
running the faucets, counting the closets, and opening and closing
the windows and doors. After that, in most cases, they go out and
hire a professional house inspector to pick up where they left off.
</P>
<P>
   What happens, though, when a buyer is buying a potential house _
one that hasn't even been built yet _ or a recently completed new
construction?
</P>
<P>
   ```New construction' doesn't mean `without flaws,''' said
Kenneth T. Austin, president of HouseMaster, a nationwide
home-inspection company based in Bound Brook, N.J. ``Many times
there are flaws in the construction of new homes, some of which can
be serious and expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the problems Austin's inspectors have found in new homes
are: damaged or improperly installed fixtures; water penetration
caused by improper grading of the soil where it meets the
foundation; foundation cracking caused by improper backfilling of
soil around the house; improper deck supports; improperly wired
electrical receptacles; disconnected heating and air-conditioning
ducts; unlabeled electrical panels; and even nonfunctioning light
switches and electrical outlets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most new-home buyers don't see the need for a home
inspection,'' Austin said, adding that while construction codes are
designed to ensure that new construction is completed in accordance
with a set of minimum standards, the code-enforcement inspectors
can't catch everything and aren't even looking for problems of an
aesthetic nature.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Austin said, if the grading of the soil against the
foundation slopes away from the house _ as it should, to prevent
water from pooling along the foundation wall _ the building
inspector will typically be satisfied. However, he said, if the
soil has not been tamped down properly, there is a possibility that
after a time the soil will settle, thereby creating a slope toward
the house and the possibility of future seepage.
</P>
<P>
   Another thing that would probably not be noted by a building
inspector would be sloppily mitered joints on woodwork around doors
and windows, an aesthetic eyesore rather than a structural problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buying a new house gives people a false sense of security,''
Austin said. ``They end up looking at the whole process through
rose-colored glasses.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Gallo, a New York registered architect, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're thinking about buying a newly constructed house
you shouldn't be bashful,'' Gallo said. ``You have to get inside
and slam some doors, make some noise and jump up and down on the
floors. You have to get physical.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that one of the biggest problems that new houses have _
despite the fact that they may meet the minimum requirements of the
building codes _ is that the floors and walls are not necessarily
as solid and soundproof as those in older construction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing to do when you walk into a new house is test
its bounce factor,'' Gallo said, explaining that he encourages
clients to jump up and down in the middle of the room to get a feel
for how much the floor gives under such punishment. ``If you have
kids with you, send them upstairs and have someone go up and play
with them,'' he said. ``That will give you some idea of the
soundproofing and some idea of what it's going to be like living in
the house.''
</P>
<P>
   Another thing that prospective purchasers of new construction
can do is to turn on the heating and air-conditioning system to
determine whether it has any annoying quirks. ``If the ductwork
thumps every time the air-conditioning comes on, that's going to
drive you crazy after a few weeks,'' he said, adding that it is
also wise to run the dishwasher and washing machine to determine
whether the water pipes bang when the machines cycle on and off.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things may not be deal-breakers, but you're really doing
yourself a favor by having a checklist of things that should be
corrected before you agree to buy the house,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Robert Tierman, a real estate lawyer in Hackensack, N.J., said
that people buying a new house can exercise the greatest degree of
control if they buy early enough in the process to dictate the
material and construction methods that will be used.
</P>
<P>
   ``Builders like to maximize their flexibility,'' Tierman said,
explaining that if a builder's contract specifies only ``a
fully-equipped bathroom,'' that allows the builder to decide what
type and grade of fixtures to install. ``If you'll be satisfied
with the fixtures the builder installs you'll have no problem,'' he
said. ``But if you want Kohler plumbing fixtures, you better make
sure you specify Kohler fixtures in the contract.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, buyers who are negotiating a construction contract
might want to include a provision that will allow home-inspection
firms like HouseMaster to make periodic inspections during
construction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recommend a three-stage inspection,'' said Austin, the
company's president. The first inspection, he said, would be
conducted after the foundation and rough framing is complete. The
second would be after all heating, cooling, electrical equipment
and plumbing have been installed. And the third would be after
construction has been completed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're there to look for errors in workmanship,'' he said,
adding that a staged inspection _ which costs about $250 for each
of the three inspections _ is not intended to second-guess the
architect, the builder or the building inspector, but to ensure
that the buyer is getting the quality of workmanship being paid
for.
</P>
<P>
   But won't a builder bristle at having someone else inspect his
handiwork?
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' Austin said. ``But you have to hang tough.
People have to realize that the greatest power they have is the
power to walk away from the deal.''
</P>
<P>
   John G. Hall, a New York real estate lawyer and former chairman
of the New York State Bar Association's Real Property Section, said
that in many new-home sales the buyer bases the decision on a model
home constructed by the builder.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the house you are buying is based on a model, as opposed to
a set of plans and specifications, you want to make sure that you
will be getting what you think you'll be getting,'' Hall said. For
example, he said, a builder who installs high-quality fixtures in
the model could install less expensive fixtures in the houses built
for sale _ if the contract permits.
</P>
<P>
   Even room sizes in models can be deceiving. ``I can tell you
that I have seen some builders use scaled-down furniture in their
models so that the rooms would look larger,'' Hall said, explaining
that while such practices are not engaged in by reputable builders,
buyers should leave nothing to chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Builders' contracts are usually very onerous,'' Hall said.
``If I were buying a new house today, and I wasn't a lawyer myself,
the first thing I'd do would be to hire one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
