<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENUS WILLIAMS LIGHTS UP THE CENTER COURT
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS for rewrite) 
By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ The colorful beads and butterfly hair clips
that marked the teen-age style of Venus Williams were gone. From
the moment she strode onto Center Court Saturday, the streamlined
20-year-old with the Paul Bunyan backswing had the look of serious
young woman. A scowl was as good as an accessory.
</P>
<P>
   Only at the last moment, as a forehand volley slipped off the
racket of Lindsay Davenport, did Williams released her furrowed
brow and let pure joy take over. Suddenly, she was leaping across
the lawn of Center Court like a child twirling through a backyard
sprinkler.
</P>
<P>
   She couldn't contain herself. So she bounded up the stairs that
led to the edge of the friends box and embraced her little sister,
Serena, then slapped hands with her clairvoyant father doing a
soft-shoe on a broadcast booth. Just as Richard Williams had
predicted a day before, his daughter Venus made a social impact on
history Saturday with her 6-3, 7-6 (3) victory at the All England
Club.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Althea Gibson wasn't alone anymore. Williams became the
first African-American woman to win Wimbledon since Gibson grabbed
the title in 1958. And at the same time, Venus and Serena Williams
became the first sisters in tennis history to each own a Grand Slam
title.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was meant to be,'' Venus Williams said. ``I worked real
hard all my life. I had a lot of sacrifices.''
</P>
<P>
   There were the endless days on the courts of Compton, Calif.,
whacking through a shopping cart filled with 550 balls. But with a
keen sensitivity to history, Williams understands the true
sacrifices of the Gibsons and even the Zina Garrisons who stepped
on the courts long before her.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had to be hard because people were unable to see past
color,'' Williams said. ``Still, these days, it's hardly any
different because you realize it's been only 40 years. How can you
change years and centuries of being biased in 40 years?''
</P>
<P>
   In only a handful of years, the Williams sisters have stirred up
the scene. Saturday, the power of Venus Williams raised the bar
again. Coiling her 6-foot-1 frame, Williams unwound on every ground
stroke. Unabashedly, Williams just went for every line with
backhands that appeared delivered from a slingshot. Even when
Davenport's heavy strokes sent her on the run, Williams was able to
unfold her long wingspan and turn sure winners into saves.
</P>
<P>
   The trend exasperated Davenport. She mumbled to herself, tossed
her head back in frustration and had no answer for Williams in a
runaway first set. The second set was only slightly different.
Davenport began serving better, pinning Williams back just a bit,
but could not come up with the big points.
</P>
<P>
   For one brief moment, Davenport, the defending Wimbledon
champion, who had been in the background for an entire fortnight,
had a sliver of hope. Serving for the match, an overeager Williams
rushed through her motions, hit two double faults and allowed
Davenport to break her serve and even the second set, 5-5. But as
the two held their serves and dashed into a tiebreaker, Williams
didn't quiver. During a run of five points in a row, Williams
hooked a forehand in for a winner and ended another tense rally
with a forehand volley that pummeled the grass.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough when your opponent is hitting the ball so hard and
on the lines,'' said Davenport, who at 6-foot-2 is one of the few
players on the tour who can counter the power generated by
Williams. ``I thought that her big win over Martina Hingis in the
quarterfinal, that was maybe the win that got her over the hump a
little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Venus Williams fed off the adrenaline from that match, withstood
the drain of emotion it took to beat her sister in the semifinals
and just never let up on her intensity. She was determined to join
Serena Williams as a Grand Slam winner, and she had no doubts.
</P>
<P>
   Just days before she and her sister departed for England, Venus
Williams went to a mall in Florida and bought a gown for the
champions ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had one dress I could wear,'' Williams said. ``It was last
year's, and colors have changed since then. I was scrambling. It
was an extra incentive to win because if I didn't, I wouldn't get
to wear this wonderful dress.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, she had the serious look of a champion once she
finally arrived. Both players were left stirring in the locker room
deep within the stadium as a light drizzle delayed the start by
about 20 minutes. For a while, Davenport stood next to the referee,
Alan Mills, at the doorway to the court, watching the skies with a
chuckle or two. In the friends box, Richard Williams was keeping
himself busy with a marking pen and grease board he brought with
him to the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hello, Mrs. Williams, I miss and love you,'' Richard Williams
wrote, showing his message to the cameras in hopes that his wife,
Oracene, would see it from Florida. Beside Richard Williams, Serena
smiled at her father's busy work.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, Venus Williams was applying a hard stare. When
she stepped on the court, she could have shattered mirrors with her
mental focus. There was no hint of a smile, no ounce of giddiness,
no look of childlike awe as she barely surveyed her surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   Only after match point did she allow the kid in her to escape.
Just less than a year ago, she was the picture of dejection.
Emotionally detached, she watched her little sister become the
first of the two to win a Grand Slam, taking the U.S. Open title.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't help but feel sorry for her last fall when Serena
won first,'' Davenport said. ``You knew eventually she was going to
win a Grand Slam. I mean, who knew when it was going to be?''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday was the day. After Venus Williams scampered back down
to the court from her celebratory hugs in the friends box, she
received the champions plate and held it up high.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better than the men's cup, in my opinion,'' Venus
Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Spinning around for the cameras, Williams glowed as brightly as
the plate with a full-moon smile. In the background of Williams'
moment, her father and sister were close to tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really great because I've been working so hard all my
life to be here,'' Venus Williams said as she stood on court.
``It's strange. I'd go to bed at night and I'd dream I'd won a
Grand Slam, but when I woke up, there was the nightmare. Now, I
don't have to wake up like that anymore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
