<DOCNO> NYT20000708.0160 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6724 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-MOMA-STRIKE-NYT &LR;      07-08 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MOMA-STRIKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PERSISTENT LABOR BATTLE WITH DALI AS A BACKDROP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Mich.)   By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With her bachelor's degree from Bryn Mawr and her
master's in art history from Columbia, Starr Figura may not seem at
first glance like someone who would be a diehard union supporter.
</P>
<P>
   But 10 weeks into the strike at the Museum of Modern Art,
Figura, an assistant curator in the prints and illustrations
department, said that she was ready to spend another 10 weeks
picketing if that was what it took to ensure that her health
coverage would not be cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``The museum's behavior over the last several months is the
definition of bad-faith bargaining,'' Figura said while picketing
alongside a dozen other strikers. ``They haven't negotiated with us
at all. Unfortunately, what the strike has demonstrated is the
museum doesn't have a lot of respect for its junior staff.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the dispute involves assistant curators, librarians,
archivists and many other workers not fitting labor's traditional
blue-collar mold, the strike has turned into a classic labor
showdown, albeit with some highbrow grace notes. (In a bow to the
museum's many foreign visitors, the union's fliers are translated
into French, Italian, Spanish and German.)
</P>
<P>
   Each side ridicules the other, accusing the other of bargaining
in bad faith, and neither side gives any indication of blinking.
Management is subtly using pressure tactics to persuade strikers to
abandon the union and return to work. Eager not to be
outmaneuvered, the union, Local 2110 of the United Auto Workers,
has its own pressure tactics, including putting up picket lines
with the hope of slowing, and maybe even stopping, the Modern's
ambitious $650 million expansion project.
</P>
<P>
   By several measures, the strike does not appear to be going well
for the union. As of last week, according to the museum, more than
half of the 250 employees in the bargaining unit had crossed the
picket line.
</P>
<P>
   ``This says the union doesn't have the support of the bargaining
unit in its role as bargaining representative,'' said Robert
Batterman, a lawyer with Proskauer Rose and the museum's chief
negotiator. ``They are not doing what a majority thinks should be
done.''
</P>
<P>
   In another setback to the union, attendance has not lagged,
museum officials say, notwithstanding the dozen or so strikers who
stand out front each day, urging tourists not to visit and clanging
metal rods against police barricades. Accusing museum officials of
lying, many union members say they are sure attendance is down.
</P>
<P>
   By some other measures, the strike appears to be going well.
Those picketing out front vow that they are in for the long haul.
Pressures from the workers, who are represented by the Auto
Workers' white-collar branch, have led the museum to cancel its
free summer jazz concerts and to postpone several movie screenings
and a fund-raiser starring the singer Sheryl Crow.
</P>
<P>
   Other New York unions have pledged support, but a major question
is whether construction unions will honor the picket line later
this month when work on the museum's expansion is scheduled to
begin.
</P>
<P>
   The union's leaders are constantly mapping strategies to squeeze
more of the museum's pressure points. One such strategy was
apparent in a letter, written at the Auto Workers' request, that
James P. Hoffa, the Teamsters' president, sent to Goldman Sachs,
asserting that the investment bank was promoting unfair working
conditions by underwriting $250 million in bonds for the Modern's
expansion. Hoffa wrote that the union was reviewing its accounts
with Goldman Sachs, including several billion dollars in Teamster
pension funds that the bank manages.
</P>
<P>
   The museum and union remain divided on several basic issues,
including pay, health coverage and job security. But after 10
weeks, an unspoken obstacle is greatly impeding a settlement _ the
growing hostility and distrust felt by both sides. The two sides
are so divided, showing so little room for flexibility, that a
federal mediator has not called them together for face-to-face
talks since the strike began on April 28.
</P>
<P>
   Museum officials defend their pay scale as comparable to that at
other art museums. But union members say that is not good enough,
considering how rich and prestigious the Modern is and considering
that the museum has collected more than $100 million in donations
to finance its expansion.
</P>
<P>
   The workers' pay averages $28,000 a year, ranging from $17,000
for bookshop workers to more than $50,000 for some associate
curators. Those at both ends of the scale assert that they are
underpaid.
</P>
<P>
   Figura said, ``I've been working here seven years, and I make
just $39,000. We stay late many nights and come in many weekends to
work on exhibitions, and we are never paid overtime. Because we're
professionals and dedicated, they expect us to help subsidize the
museum through our low salaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Batterman, the museum lawyer, defended the $17,000 annual pay
for bookstore and visitors' services jobs, saying workers who hold
those jobs are not career professionals, but usually recent college
graduates who leave for other opportunities after a year or two. He
said the $8.50 an hour the bookstore workers earned was comparable
to what many New York bookstores paid, but he said the Modern
provided far better vacation and health benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Management has offered a 3 percent raise each year for three
years, while the union demanded 5 percent in the first year and 4
percent in the second and third years. The union wants the museum's
$17,000 minimum salary to rise immediately to $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   Health coverage is one of the most hotly contested issues. The
museum has told the union that if it insisted on exercising the
right to bargain over changes in the health plan, then the museum
would want to push the union's members out of the health plan they
now share with management personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials say the museum is maneuvering to push the
workers into a worse health plan, which might mean higher premiums
and deductibles. Museum officials insist they have no such
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Batterman insisted that the main obstacle to a settlement was
the union's demand that all newly hired workers be required to join
the union or, if they choose not to join, to pay union dues. That
arrangement is known as an agency shop. Throughout the museum
union's 30-year history, its administrative and professional
workers have not had to join the union or pay dues. When the union
went on strike in April, about 90 of the 250 workers in the
bargaining unit were not in the union.
</P>
<P>
   Maida Rosenstein, president of Local 2110, said an agency shop
was needed to strengthen a historically weak union. But Batterman
asserted that the agency shop demands were prolonging the strike
and were designed largely to increase the union leaders' power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
