<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6725 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-HABITAT-REAL-NYT &LR;      07-08 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HABITAT-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LANDLORD TO EX-TENANT: YOU CAN GO HOME AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   By TRISH HALL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In Manhattan, people usually struggle to find
apartments, or at least they anticipate a struggle. No one expects
a landlord to call up and say, ``Please come live in my
apartment.'' Or ``I'm so sorry I have to move you out, but I'll
find you an even better place in the same building.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's been the experience of Telly Hatzigeorgiou. Shortly
after graduating from New York University in 1988, Hatzigeorgiou
took a room in a co-op apartment on Warren Street in TriBeCa _
before TriBeCa was filled with people living in multimillion-dollar
lofts. In those days, he said, he often came out of the building in
the morning to find car windows smashed.
</P>
<P>
   When the owner of the apartment sold the place in 1992, she felt
so bad about displacing Hatzigeorgiou that she introduced him to
the owner of another co-op in the building, who wasn't occupying
his space and was thinking of selling it. The landlord agreed to
give Hatzigeorgiou the duplex space _ for a few months, anyway _
for $500 a month.
</P>
<P>
   A few months turned into a few years. The real estate market had
collapsed and the owner couldn't get what he wanted for the place.
The apartment is about 2,000 square feet on two floors, with a
terrace off the living room and roof rights above with a view of
the Hudson River. ``It became party central,'' Hatzigeorgiou said.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, a friend from college moved in with him, but when
the friend became a born-again Christian, things changed a bit.
``All the pictures of women came down,'' said Hatzigeorgiou,
referring to his paintings. With their lives diverging, the
roommate moved out, and then, three years ago, so did
Hatzigeorgiou. He had decided to leave his job in global securities
at Chase Manhattan and open a billiard parlor in Queens.
</P>
<P>
   He was only an occasional player of pocket billiards _ _ the
proper term, although most aficionados call it pool. But he found
himself starting the business after someone approached his father,
who was in the metal-furniture business at the time, with a great
commercial location.
</P>
<P>
   To make the commute to his new business easier, he moved to the
Upper East Side, into a small one-bedroom apartment that cost
$2,350 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next few years, he opened two more places in Queens.
Then this year, in March, he opened his fourth, and his first in
Manhattan, Chelsea Bar and Billiards on 21st Street.
(Hatzigeorgiou's first name, by the way, is short for Aristotle. It
was torture in college, he said, when on the first day the
professors would call out that name.)
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, Hatzigeorgiou's former landlord on Warren Street
called him and asked if he would like to move back in. The
photographer who had been renting the place had just left, and the
landlord wanted someone he knew and trusted. He offered the
apartment to Hatzigeorgiou for $2,500 a month, about half of what
he could get if he put it on the market.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Hatzigeorgiou, 34, wasn't interested in moving; he was
too busy, and he just couldn't focus on it.
</P>
<P>
   But then he realized that with his new business in Chelsea, it
made sense to be downtown again. ``I love TriBeCa,'' he said. ``I
never wanted to leave. It's discovered, but undiscovered at the
same time. Secluded.'' On the Upper East Side, he said, the streets
were more intense.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was more hustle and bustle there,'' he said. ``Every
block had a billion things going on.''
</P>
<P>
   And so he decided to move back, thinking, he said, that it would
be a snap. In fact, he told the movers, when they asked him to
estimate, that he would probably have about five boxes. It turned
out he had 55.
</P>
<P>
   But after just a few days, he looked totally settled. Before
moving in, he had done some renovating, putting in a new kitchen,
and a rubber surface on the deck. And soon the new
weather-resistant pool table will arrive, taking up residence on
the deck.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
