<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6728 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-WIMBLEDON-GARRISON070     07-08 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIMBLEDON-GARRISON0709-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tennis legend looks to her legacy
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Clarke
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ Retired women's tennis player Zina Garrison
couldn't sleep Friday night at her hotel in London _ too many
thoughts, too much anxiety, too much hope.
</P>
<P>
   In her search for something calming, she decided to call home to
the United States. Not to her family in Houston, but to an
unassuming house in New Jersey where a 72-year-old woman lives
surrounded by a handful trophies but little else to show for a long
tennis career.
</P>
<P>
   Althea Gibson, through a caregiver because she had a stroke a
few years ago, was eager to talk about the historic day coming up:
Venus Williams would walk onto Centre Court at the All England Club
and try to become the first black woman to win a Wimbledon title
sice Gibson last did it in 1958.
</P>
<P>
   Garrison, who got a chance at the same thing a decade ago but
lost to Martina Navratilova, learned that Gibson had been watching
every match and hoped Venus could defeat Lindsay Davenport. She
also had a piece of advice for Venus: Move your feet.
</P>
<P>
   Venus Williams did that and everything else well enough to upset
the defending champion Saturday to win her first Grand Slam 6-3,
7-6 (7-3). She becomes just the third black woman in history to win
a major title.
</P>
<P>
   Sister Serena Williams became the second at the 1999 U.S. Open.
Gibson was the first, winning five major singles titles after
breaking the sport's color barrier in 1950 at the U.S.
Championships in Forest Hills, New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what she would think,'' a beaming Garrison said of
Gibson after the match. ``She really just wanted all this
(anniversary) hype for her to be overwith and for someone to go on
and do it. She's probably back there very excited.''
</P>
<P>
   Garrison watched the match from Venus' Friends Box, surviving
the ups and downs of the nerve-wracking second set beside father
Richard Williams, business manager Leland Hardy, sister Serena
Williams and other friends.
</P>
<P>
   She's been friendly with the Williams family for more than
decade. She got to know Venus, Serena and their parents when the
sisters were children. Richard Williams was studying the game back
then and looking for role models for his daughters.
</P>
<P>
   He found just two women of the same color succeeding on the
women's tour. They were Zina Garrison and Lori McNeil. He talked
tennis and race and history and opportunity with them, always
seeking the best way to raise his girls as people and tennis
players.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, the work of this eccentric man with an
often-overzealous urge for a spotlight of his own has been
successful. Venus and Serena Williams now each have Grand Slam
titles and they're closer to reaching No. 1 and No. 2 in the world
rankings.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, those personal goals remain primary for both, as well
they should. But ultimately, they may find their legacy lies in
what they mean to blacks in tennis.
</P>
<P>
   Already, they each have a firm place in the history of a sport
still trying to diversify. Expensive country clubs remain mostly
white. Public parks struggle to start programs for underprivileged
children. American kids have so many sports to choose from that
tennis falls to the bottom of the list.
</P>
<P>
   A glance around the 13,812 fans on Centre Court certainly
supports the fact that tennis remains a white, wealthy man's sport
_ to watch or to play. Garrison thinks this is a beginning. A
long-term presence at the top of the game will make the biggest
difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just an awareness, like Tiger brought awareness to the
game,'' she said, referring to Woods' impact on golf.
</P>
<P>
   Garrison keeps a close eye on how black children feel about
tennis through her foundation at home in Houston. The Zina Garrison
All Court Tennis Foundation works year-round introducing inner-city
kids to the sport through a junior program.
</P>
<P>
   ``You bring out a 4-year-old kid and if you say you play tennis,
the first thing they say is, 'Venus or Serena?' `` Garrison said,
laughing. ``I'm like, 'No, I'm the old one.' ``
</P>
<P>
   But at least they know black girls play tennis. It's a start,
and it was important to two skinny little girls wearing beads in
their hair and learning tennis in Compton, Calif., way back when.
</P>
<P>
   Venus was 10 and Serena 8 during Garrison's Wimbledon run of
1990. It was the first Wimbledon that meant something to them and
the first time they followed it. A neighbor who walked his dog past
the courts where they practiced would update them on Garrison's
progress every day, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That meant a lot to us,'' Venus said. ``I remember we were out
there practicing when Zina won against Monica (Seles), against
Steffi (Graf). I think we got to see the final.''
</P>
<P>
   Garrison called her support of Venus and Serena ``our own little
fraternity.'' She hopes one day soon the fraternity of successful
black tennis players grows. She thinks this historic day will help
that happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a great moment,'' she said. ``It's the biggest
tournament in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
