<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6729 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-WIMBLEDON-MENS-PREVIE     07-08 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIMBLEDON-MENS-PREVIEW0709-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sampras motivated to win despite injury
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Clarke
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ Pete Sampras hurt his left leg in the
second round of Wimbledon last week and hasn't talked about much
else since it happened.
</P>
<P>
   Are you using acupuncture?, the tabloid reporters want to know.
How's your form?, the British reporters wonder. Can you move well
enough to win?, the American writers ask. Aren't you lucky you
haven't had to play a seeded opponent yet? Can you break Roy
Emerson's record of 13 Grand Slam titles on just one leg?
</P>
<P>
   The questions will finally stop today after he plays 12th seed
Patrick Rafter in the final _ and Sampras can't wait for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're taking this injury a little bit too far,'' he
said after defeating Jan-Michael Gambill to reach the semifinals.
``I have it, and I really don't want to talk about it anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, when asked how he's spending the hours between
matches _ since he isn't practicing on his off days or warming up
before matches or going out on the town _ he admitted he's consumed
by the injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty much (I'm) staying at home, just treating my
situation,'' Sampras said.
</P>
<P>
   He's treating his ``situation,'' tendinitis and inflammation of
the left shin, with acupuncture, ice, heat, electric stimulation,
stretching and almost anything else he, his coach or trainer thinks
might ease the pain, since he knows he isn't at risk for more
damage.
</P>
<P>
   The leg is one of just two things that will keep him from making
history in today's men's final. He's playing for a seventh
Wimbledon title, which would tie William Renshaw's record set in
the 1880s, and a record 13th Grand Slam title.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras called this one of the most difficult major tournaments
of his career because of the injury. Not practicing during the
tournament has been uncomfortable, but if it were any other event,
he might have already been home for days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely been a struggle,'' he said. ``But at this
stage of my career, this is what I'm playing for. I think even
getting to the final has been one of my best efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   Reaching the final is a relief in some ways. He planned to try
practicing Saturday for today's match. His experience on
Wimbledon's Centre Court _ six finals in the past seven years _ and
simply in important moments should help him, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just know this is my last match. Mentally, that feels
good,'' Sampras said. ``You just let it all hang out. The
adrenaline, the occasion can really get you through a lot of tough
situations on the court.''
</P>
<P>
   Rafter will present a different game than Sampras would have
gotten from Andre Agassi. Rafter served extremely well to beat the
1999 runner-up Friday and will have to play even better to defeat
the motivated Sampras.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty well a reversal,'' Rafter said. ``You've got to
try to get his serve back somehow.''
</P>
<P>
   The better returner probably will have the advantage since both
dominate on their own serves.
</P>
<P>
   But Sampras hasn't lost a match here since 1996. He's motivated
to make history, since, at 28, he might not have as many
opportunities left in her career. Plus, this is his favorite
surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing on grass, (which means) quick points,'' Sampras
said. ``It would be tough to play on clay or even hard court. As
long as I have my right arm, on grass I'm still a threat.''
</P>
<P>
   Noteworthy: Wimbledon finalist Patrick Rafter became the first
player to commit to next year's Citrix Championships in Delray
Beach, tournament officials announced Saturday. The $350,000
tournament runs March 5-11at the Delray Beach Tennis Center.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
