<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6733 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-NY-HOMESALES-REAL-112     07-08 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HOMESALES-REAL-1125(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSING MARKET BECOMES A LITTLE LESS FRENZIED 
</HEADLINE>
   By DIANA SHAMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The owners of a six-bedroom, three-bath split-level
in Jericho, Long Island, on which Barbara Goldberg, a broker with
the Prudential Long Island Realty agency in Syosset, held an open
house a week ago, had one stipulation when they listed it with her
for $729,000: A prospective buyer had to agree that the closing
would take place only after the sellers themselves had found
another home to buy.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are people who want to downsize, but they also have to
find the house they want,'' said Goldberg, adding that 19 prospects
attended the open house, three of whom seemed ``very interested.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If a buyer can't wait, the deal could fall apart,'' she said,
``but I have 27 years of experience in real estate sales and I will
make a great effort to find these sellers the right house.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar contingency clauses have become routine in a market
where there are still many more buyers than sellers. Bidding wars,
with buyers competing against each other and offering more than the
asking price, have also been common.
</P>
<P>
   However, indications now are that higher interest rates and a
throttling back of the stock market are finally having some ripple
effects on the local housing market. The number of listings is on
the increase over all and although there are still plenty of
buyers, brokers say they are not so quick to make an offer as
earlier in the year. Listing prices, however, show no signs of
coming down.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Multiple Listing Service of Long Island, which
has about 1,000 member offices in Nassau and Suffolk counties, the
number of houses on the market in Nassau increased to 3,468 in May
from 2,782 in January, and in Suffolk to 5,378 from 4,644.
</P>
<P>
   In January, the median contract price of a house in Nassau was
$234,000 and in May it was $254,500, rising from $225,000 a year
earlier. In Suffolk, the January figure was $173,000 and in May it
was $180,000. A year earlier, it was $167,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's happening in the market currently is that the listing
inventory is picking up tremendously and buyers are slimming down,
and we are starting to enter a transition period between a seller's
and a buyer's market,'' said Fern Karhu, the manager at
Prudential's Syosset office, which covers Syosset, Woodbury,
Jericho and other areas of Nassau's North Shore. Her office took in
14 listings in June 1999, she said, while last month, it took in
27.
</P>
<P>
   ``In January, February, March of this year,'' she went on to
say, ``it was almost like a fire sale. People were paying top
dollar, going over list price and making fast decisions. but now
they are getting more skeptical.''
</P>
<P>
   Elaine Nolan, a broker with offices in Hempstead, said she was
also seeing a noticeable slowdown in the pace of sales. ``Listing
prices aren't coming down, but it's been very quiet,'' she said.
``I used to get action on a house in two weeks, and now it takes me
one to two months because buyers are more confident that they can
find exactly what they are looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   Jan Kalman, a Woodmere broker. said: ``I wouldn't call this a
hot market anymore. Sellers still want high prices, but I now have
30 office exclusives instead of the 20 I had in May because the
houses haven't sold.''
</P>
<P>
   Pat Levitt, a vice president of the Multiple Listing Service of
Long Island and a co-owner with her husband, Mac, of Century 21 Mac
Levitt, which has offices in Oceanside, Freeport and Baldwin,
attributes the rising number of listings to sellers who feel they
want to take advantage of the high prices friends and neighbors are
getting. ``Many people have decided the market is so good that now
is the time to sell their homes,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And that may be one of the reasons behind changing market
conditions, according to Jay Helsinger, owner of Custom South Shore
Real Estate in Merrick. ``There is just so much a sponge can
hold,'' he said. ``We've reached the maximum level and now people
want max plus, and it's not going to be because as you reach the
top, fewer and fewer people will be willing to pay top dollar.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, according to Joseph E. Mottola, the chief executive of
the Multiple Listing Service of Long Island, the market is entering
a much healthier phase than the one it has been in. ``The frenzy is
missing,'' he said. ``The buyers are out there in strength, but
homes are staying on the market a little longer and they are not
always meeting the listing price. The snap sale is happening much
less frequently.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a positive trend, Mottola said, ``because it creates
more balance in the marketplace.'' He added: ``There are people who
want to move up, but they are not going to put their house on the
market until they find something, so everything is clogged in the
pipeline. As the market slows down a little and more inventory
comes in, it will be good for buyers and it will be good for
sellers because it makes buying possible for more people.''
</P>
<P>
   While some brokers say that the market is cooling a bit,
individual buyers will not necessarily find their own experience
reflective of that perception. When Derek and Debbie Schoenhofen
went to an open house in New Hyde Park last month, they found a
bidding war that pushed offers past the $275,000 asking price.
</P>
<P>
   ``The broker got 15 offers and the house, which needed at least
$60,000 worth of work, went for $15,000 more than its asking
price,'' said Schoenhofen, an analyst for an investment firm in
Manhattan. His wife is an accountant for a real estate agency. ``We
called the day after the open house, but it was already gone,''
Schoenhofen added.
</P>
<P>
   The couple, who have been renting an apartment in Mineola, saw
another house, this one in Williston Park, with a $259,000 asking
price. They quickly made a $235,000 offer, which the owner has
accepted.
</P>
<P>
   This house also needs a lot of work, but Schoenhofen was able to
offer the amount he did because he intends to do much of it
himself, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a nutshell, what buyers are facing is a great deal of
competition, and you can't wait a couple of months to make a
decision,'' he said. ``You have to tell the person tomorrow if you
want the house or not, because it will be gone next week.''
</P>
<P>
   Evelyn Atanas, the owner of Atanas Realty in Williston Park, who
showed the Schoenhofens their house, said that although she was
taking more listings _ which, she said, would make it a little
easier for buyers _ many potential sellers were still holding off
because of fears that they, in turn, would not be able to find a
house that suited them.
</P>
<P>
   ``People realize they can get good prices, but unless they plan
to move away, where are they going to go?'' she said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
