<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6736 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-NY-HOMESALES-REAL-2ND     07-08 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HOMESALES-REAL-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: she said.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In that respect, Alison and Robert Gregory are fortunate. They
do not have to worry about finding another house on Long Island
because they are moving to Fort Meyers, Fla. Gregory has retired
from his mechanic's job and one of their two children is going off
to college, so they put their three-bedroom colonial in Williston
Park on the market. ``We felt we couldn't afford to retire on Long
Island, and so we decided, `Let's get out now,''' Gregory said.
</P>
<P>
   They tried unsuccessfully to sell the home on their own, but
after listing it with Atanas the house was in contract within two
days. The Gregorys accepted $302,000, which was $8,000 below their
asking price, ``but we did well,'' Gregory said.
</P>
<P>
   Other sellers find themselves in a quandary, especially if an
offer comes quickly. Camille Pisciotto, owner of Great Neck Realty,
Better Homes and Gardens, said she had been running up against the
phenomenon of sellers pulling out of a deal even though a buyer was
willing to meet their price because they could not find the right
house to buy. ``I have three sellers in my office right now who
changed their minds,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be considered prudent to sell and then find another
house,'' said Wayne McCann, owner of the Harmonious Homes agency in
Sea Cliff. ``It's still the prudent thing to do, but a lot of
sellers are pulling back when they find a buyer. Timing is one of
the most frustrating and tension-causing aspects of buying and
selling right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Katy Anastasio, a Huntington real estate broker, said that she
still lacked houses to show. ``There is still more demand than
supply and the majority of my listings sell in one to two weeks,
although there do appear to be fewer lookers,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A four-bedroom house priced at $500,000 in Fort Salonga on which
she held an open house in March had 35 people looking and found a
buyer in 20 minutes. An almost identical house in the same area,
also priced at $500,000, had only 25 people show up for an open
house held last month, but it found a buyer the same day. ``I
didn't get 35, but all I need is one buyer,'' Anastasio said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is still not a situation where houses are coming on the
market and not getting sold right away,'' said Dorothy Waxman, the
manager of the Century 21 Laffey-Sandsport agency in Port
Washington. ``Because of the location, the good schools and the
transportation, Port Washington is the last to suffer when there is
a downturn in the market,'' she said. ``I have so many buyers who
will jump on something decent when it gets listed and we still
don't have enough houses to meet the pent-up demand that exists.''
</P>
<P>
   Caution, rather than slowdown, is perhaps the best way to
describe today's market, said Stuart Epstein, owner of Devlin
McNiff Real Estate in East Hampton.
</P>
<P>
   With prices up 15 percent to 20 percent in the last 12 months,
``buyers are saying, `I no longer will pay what's being asked of
us; let's take time out and make sure this is economically
justifiable,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The downturn in the stock market ``has made people reflect about
the entire economic picture,'' he went on to say, adding: ``It
reminds them that what goes up can also come down. No one wants to
be the last man in the bubble and buy property at the highest
price.''
</P>
<P>
   But all this must be taken in the context of a market that is
still very robust, he added. ``The intrinsics here are still very
powerful. The market is still great.''
</P>
</TEXT>
