<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6745 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-POLICE-KILLING-NYT     07-08 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-KILLING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACTIONS OF MAN KILLED BY POLICE BAFFLE INVESTIGATORS 
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM K. RASHBAUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Nearly 24 hours after two off-duty police officers
shot and killed a man in an unusual rush-hour confrontation on a
highway in Queens, the authorities said Saturday that they could
not explain why the man had leapt from a car into fast-moving
traffic and then attacked the officers.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation, being conducted by the office of the Queens
district attorney, Richard A. Brown, the department's Internal
Affairs Bureau and the Queens homicide squad, focuses on whether
the officers were justified in shooting the man, Dandre Darnell
Cisco, 25.
</P>
<P>
   But officials said investigators were also trying to sort out
and understand the details of the incident, which occurred at 6:23
p.m. on Grand Central Parkway. Witnesses said Cisco jumped from a
friend's car as it was moving at about 35 to 40 mph, rolled along
the pavement, jumped up and attacked the off-duty officers, who had
stopped because they thought he was an accident victim.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all very strange,'' said a senior police official who is
involved in the investigation. ``It's like something out of the
`Twilight Zone.''' Four people who saw the events that led up to
the shooting gave similar accounts to police and to prosecutors,
several senior law-enforcement officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The four witnesses _ the driver of the car from which Cisco
jumped, a cab driver and his passenger in the vehicle behind them,
and a retired police officer driving behind the two officers _ said
Cisco seemed to roll out of the moving car and to slide about 40
feet along the pavement, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco's friend, Russell Ballenger Jr., 25, of Glen Cove, told
investigators that he did not know why Cisco jumped from the car
and that he had tried to stop him by grabbing him briefly while he
steered, one official said. But Cisco, who is 6 foot 2 and weighs
210 pounds, broke free and rolled out the passenger door.
</P>
<P>
   Owen Lamb, a lawyer for Ballenger, who works with computers,
said his client had known Cisco for 17 years but could offer no
explanation for his actions, saying only that it was ``a
wonderment.''
</P>
<P>
   After sliding along the pavement and picking up some severe
scrapes, Cisco rolled into a fetal position and jumped up, the
witnesses said. The driver of the cab behind Ballenger's car
swerved to avoid him, and the officers' vehicle, a black Dodge
Dakota pickup driven by Sgt. Stephen Borchers, a 13-year veteran,
pulled up after swerving to about a 45-degree angle.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco immediately approached the driver's side of the pickup and
began hitting the sergeant with his fists, according to the senior
law-enforcement officials. They said Borchers, who is about 5 foot
10, and the detective with him, Jean Weller, identified themselves
as police officers.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said that the sergeant then stepped on the gas in
an effort to get away, but slammed into the side of the cab, which
was also stopped in the roadway. When the sergeant got out of the
pickup, Cisco went around the back of the truck and began
assaulting Weller, a 15-year veteran.
</P>
<P>
   Borchers, who was still standing on the driver's side of the
truck, according to the account Ballenger gave his lawyer, pointed
his gun at Ballenger, who said the sergeant and detective never
identified themselves as police officers, Lamb said.
</P>
<P>
   Weller, still inside the truck's cab, drew her handgun, a
five-shot .38-caliber pistol, and in the course of the struggle she
fired three shots, the law-enforcement officials said, and Borchers
fired once.
</P>
<P>
   Lamb said his client believed that Borchers fired through the
cab and that he fired more than one shot.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco died at the scene, with five bullet wounds, the
authorities said, two of them apparently from a single bullet.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials said it was the first time either of the
officers had been involved in a shooting. A senior official who
knows both police officers described them as responsible and
capable, saying that Borchers had worked as a detective in the
108th Precinct and in the Internal Affairs Bureau and that Weller
had been assigned to the 110th Precinct as a detective. Both are
now assigned to administrative duties at the Queens Detective
Borough.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
