<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6746 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-ATHLETIC-FIELDS-NY     07-08 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ATHLETIC-FIELDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ASSIST FOR CITY SCHOOLS' ATHLETICS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio) By NINA SIEGAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For the last 12 years, George Washington High
School's baseball team, the Trojans, has been consistently ranked
among the best in the nation. It has produced dozens of minor- and
major-league ballplayers, including Manny Ramirez, now an
outfielder for the Cleveland Indians.
</P>
<P>
   In those same 12 years, the team has held batting practice on
the school's field in the Washington Heights section of Manhattan
only two or three times, said Steve Mandl, the school's athletic
director and head baseball coach. The artificial turf is battered
and torn, the backstop is small, and when batters hit homers, the
balls often fly off the side of a cliff at the edge of the field.
</P>
<P>
   But the field is about to get a $2 million overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   Washington is one of dozens of city schools whose athletic
fields, gymnasiums and swimming pools are to be renovated in the
next few years with financial support from a new organization
called Take the Field, a public-private partnership created to
support struggling athletic programs in the city's public schools.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, ground will be broken for construction at Washington
to begin the effort. The organization, in concert with the city,
hopes to provide at least $17 million for capital improvements at
high schools throughout the city.
</P>
<P>
   The group hopes to help those schools with the most pressing
needs and the most committed sports programs _ schools that are
making strides despite financial obstacles. The organizers have
visited schools, interviewed principals and coaches, and checked
team records.
</P>
<P>
   The conditions at many schools were stunningly poor, said
Richard A. Kahan, president of the Urban Assembly and a founder of
the organization. ``I met with a captain of a girls' softball team
in Beach Channel, Queens, which had one cracked helmet for the
whole team,'' he said. ``The uniform she was wearing was seven
years old and had been passed down from student to student each
year. This was a pretty aggressive team and their uniforms got torn
sometimes, so each student had sewed it up on their own.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Take the Field has selected seven schools to receive
financing this year: George Washington and Seward Park High School
in Manhattan; William C. Bryant High School and Far Rockaway High
School in Queens; South Bronx High School in the Bronx; Brooklyn
Technical High School in Brooklyn; and Port Richmond High School on
Staten Island.
</P>
<P>
   Margie Feinberg, a spokeswoman for the Board of Education, said
school districts across the country were increasingly taking
support from private donors who want to improve sports programs.
``Our public funds are able to go further with the help of the
private groups that get involved,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the city's fiscal crisis in the 1970s, a shortage of
money to maintain school sports facilities has led to widespread
deterioration, making it all but impossible for many students to
participate in teams or even basic recreation.
</P>
<P>
   That shortage of financing, which was described in a three-part
series in The New York Times in January 1999, prompted the
formation of the program by its three founders: Kahan; Preston
Robert Tisch, co-chairman of the Loews Corp. and part owner of the
New York Giants. and Tony Kiser, president of the William and Mary
Greve Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Tisch said the project was modeled after the Center for Arts
Education. The nonprofit group has raised $23.1 million from the
private and public sectors since 1996 to encourage the teaching of
the arts, and is led by Tisch's daughter, Laurie Tisch Sussman.
Tisch said his daughter telephoned him after reading about the
dearth of money for sports programs and said, ``Do you want to do
for sports education what I've done for arts education?''
</P>
<P>
   He, Kahan and Kiser approached City Hall after joining forces at
a meeting called by Rudy Crew, who was then schools chancellor.
City officials were receptive. ``It seemed to us they were all very
anxious to do something and were looking for a vehicle that could
address the issues efficiently,'' Kahan said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan they worked out, Take the Field would contribute
$1 for every $3 the city gave. So far, the city has pledged $10.8
million, with another $3 million earmarked for the project over the
next two years. Take the Field expects to raise an additional $3.6
million from private sources this year. The Tisch Foundation, the
William and Mary Greve Foundation and the Hecksher Foundation for
Children have already committed a total of $1.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   At Washington, Mandl said the renovation of the field would help
not only the winning baseball team, but the soccer, football and
track programs as well. ``I can't wait,'' he said. ``I'm hoping
that they'll put light up around the new field, which will have
natural grass instead of turf, and that'll be incredible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
