<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6747 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BISHER-ALLSTAR0709-CO     07-08 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BISHER-ALLSTAR0709-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Checkered history for newsman's novel idea
 &HT;    By Furman Bisher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If some news operative proposed a midseason game
between National and American League all-stars these days, as did
Arch Ward of the Chicago Tribune in 1933, this breed of owners
would probably wave it off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not take three full days out of the heart of the season,
during vacation time, when the races are just heating up. No way.
Besides, we have interleague play, wild-card playoffs, league
championships, then the killer, the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who needs it?''
</P>
<P>
   In 1933, the major leagues needed it. All baseball needed it.
The country was in hock up to its belly button. The Depression was
digging in. Farms were drying up. Banks were calling loans,
foreclosing on property. Attendance was about what you'd expect of
depression times. Arch Ward couldn't have hit the club owners at a
time when they were more vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't easy. They had to be persuaded. The trump card was
that the Chicago World's Fair was on.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, the game didn't really hit a grand slam. In the
Official Baseball Guide, ``All-Star Game'' gets no play as the
actual name of the event, only ``dream'' game, covered in four
paragraphs with no box score. It was moved to the Polo Grounds in
New York the next year, and kept on, never missing a beat, except
for one war year of 1945, and at one stretch doubled up for four
years. Greed had its fling.
</P>
<P>
   That was a mistake. Trying to get two bites of the apple took
something off it. No longer a ``Midsummer's Dream Game,'' it became
a ``Midsummer's Nightmare.'' Attendance dropped off, into the
30,000s. As foul luck would have it, foul weather struck a couple
of the games. At Candlestick Park in 1961, the wind was so strong
it blew little Stu Miller off the mound, caused him to balk. Hoyt
Wilhelm's knuckleball wouldn't ``knuckle,'' and the National League
clubbed him into defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Besides that, two not-so-dreamy games were taking six dates off
the schedule; four years was enough of that and after playing
Washington and Chicago in 1962, a halt was called. Back to one date
a summer.
</P>
<P>
   Settling on the right electoral process took a lot of dabbling.
The first two years, the players themselves picked the starters.
Then All-Star managers did the choosing until 1947, when fans were
invited in. That went smoothly until 1957, when Cincinnati fans
stuffed the ballot box and seven of the eight elected starters were
Reds. Only Stan Musial crashed their lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Ford Frick intervened and removed two of the Reds.
In the end, it was embarrassing to the Nationals. The Americans
beat them 6-5. The winning pitcher was a now real Senator, Jim
Bunning (R-Ky.)
</P>
<P>
   Next electoral ploy was a mixture of players, managers and
coaches. That lasted until 1970, when the public was invited to
join in again, this time with a commercial sponsor paying a price
to attach its name to the process, and so it remains today. There
is no foolproof means of recognizing a hot rookie over a popular
veteran. One year, American League balloteers chose a catcher who
wasn't even first-string on his own Oakland team, wasn't among the
10 best-hitting catchers in the league. Yet, in the game, Terry
Steinbach drove in both American runs, one with a homer, and they
won the game.
</P>
<P>
   Not always is the ``dream'' game a classic. Some have been real
dogs. At one stretch, the Nationals killed the Americans 19 out of
20 games. In this ancient memory there is highlighted such games as
1956, when Kenny Boyer stole the thunder of Ted Williams and Stan
Musial; the year Tony Perez hit a home run in the 15th inning in
Anaheim, mercifully ending the longest game of them all; the game
of 1970, when Pete Rose bowled over Ray Fosse at home plate with
the winning run for the Nationals; of course, the first time the
game was played in Atlanta, when Henry Aaron hit the home run but
Joe Morgan drove in the deciding run in the10th inning; all the
traditional old parks I got to see, Sportsman's, Forbes Field,
Griffith Stadium, Tiger Stadium, Municipal in Cleveland, Memorial
in Baltimore, Metropolitan in Minnesota, all just memories now; and
last but far from the least, the game in Baltimore after which
friends invited me to fly home with them in their private plane. It
ran into a fierce storm. It crashed. All were killed.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
