<DOCNO> NYT20000708.0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6748 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FIRST-ALLSTAR0709-COX     07-08 1893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRST-ALLSTAR0709-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Babe shows how it's done
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ He was 38 years old, and not even the New York
Yankees' pinstripe uniforms could hide the growing belly that hung
over his belt. But Babe Ruth was still the one player that everyone
wanted to see, and he rarely disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   The Babe certainly didn't disappoint. He thrilled the crowd of
47,595 in Chicago's Comiskey Park by homering in the first All-Star
Game.
</P>
<P>
   The two-run homer came in the third inning and proved to be the
difference, as the American League beat the National League 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   The blow wasn't the longest or the most dramatic of Ruth's
career, but it was certainly one of the most fitting. Who better to
hit the first home run in the history of the All-Star Game than the
Bambino himself, the Sultan of Swat?
</P>
<P>
   The homer, hit off St. Louis pitcher Bill Hallahan, landed in
the lower pavilion just inside the right-field foul pole. American
and National League fans rose as one to applaud Ruth as he waddled
around the bases.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction in Chicago the fall before had been far less
favorable. It was at Wrigley Field in 1932 that Ruth hit his
``called shot'' home run, and the Yankees beat the Cubs in the
World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his World Series heroics, Ruth had his salary cut from
$75,000 to $52,000 in 1933. His average fell to .301 with 34
homers, and the Yankees released him in 1934 after Ruth batted
.288.
</P>
<P>
   But Ruth had risen to the occasion to make the first All-Star
Game his showcase. He even made a game-saving catch .
</P>
<P>
   HUBBELL KING OF STRIKEOUTS
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to believe that a pitcher could be more dominant in an
All-Star Game than Pedro Martinez was last year in Fenway Park.
Carl Hubbell, however, did Martinez one better.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston pitcher struck out four batters in a row. New York
Giants left-hander Hubbell, pitching in the 1934 All-Star Game,
struck out five _ all future Hall of Famers.
</P>
<P>
   Like Martinez, Hubbell was pitching before his home fans. But
while Martinez struck out the first four batters he faced, Hubbell
was shaky at the start. The screwball pitcher allowed a hit and a
walk before settling into a groove.
</P>
<P>
   Babe Ruth, Lou Gehrig and Jimmie Foxx _ three of the most feared
hitters in baseball history - struck out in the first inning, Ruth
looking. Then Hubbell, who had received his trophy as 1933 National
League MVP before the game, fanned Al Simmons and Joe Cronin to
start the second as the crowd of 48,363 at the Polo Grounds roared.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Dickey, another future Hall of Famer, singled to break the
streak.
</P>
<P>
   Although the American League came back to win the game 9-7, all
of the talk was about the pitcher called King Carl.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbell won two NL MVP awards, set a record with 24 consecutive
wins and finished his Hall of Fame career with 253 victories. But
he was always remembered for his five straight strikeouts in the
second All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I respected every one of them, but I had no fear of any
kind,'' Hubbell said. ``I didn't think they had ever seen any
screwball pitchers before.''
</P>
<P>
   SPLENDID SHOT FOR `SPLINTER'
</P>
<P>
   Ted Williams hit .406 in 1941, the last time a major-leaguer
reached the .400 mark. But the Boston Red Sox outfielder's biggest
hit that season didn't count in his official statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Williams belted what still is considered the most dramatic homer
in All-Star Game history. He climaxed an American League comeback
with a two-out blast in the bottom of the ninth inning in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   It would be called a walk-off homer now. But Williams hardly
walked around the bases. Then just 23, he half-ran, half-jumped in
a crazy chicken dance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just so happy I couldn't stop laughing,'' said Williams,
who in later years would have running battles with fans and the
press. ``I've never been so happy.''
</P>
<P>
   The AL had trailed 5-2 when Williams struck out in the eighth
inning, but it was 5-4 in the ninth when he came up again with two
men on base. Williams connected with a high fastball from Claude
Passeau and knocked the pitch into the upper deck in right field to
give the AL a 7-5 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Although the 1941 All-Star Game was Williams' most dramatic, it
wasn't his best. After missing three seasons while serving in World
War II, Williams went 4 for 4 with five RBIs in the 1946 game in
Fenway Park. Two of his hits were homers, one a mammoth drive off a
Rip Sewell blooper pitch. The American League won 12-0.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, now 82, returned to Boston to be feted before last
year's All-Star Game as part of the celebration of the Top 100
Players of the Century. The start of the game was delayed about 20
minutes. Everyone wanted to shake Williams' hand.
</P>
<P>
   BIG FINISH FOR STAN THE MAN
</P>
<P>
   Stan Musial holds the record for All-Star Game homers with six.
The one that always will be remembered was in 1955 in Milwaukee's
County Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Musial didn't start the game because the ballot-box stuffing
Cincinnati fans voted Ted Kluszewski in at first base. But Musial,
nicknamed ``Stan the Man,'' was around when it counted.
</P>
<P>
   Leading off the bottom of the 12th, he hit the first pitch from
American League pitcher Frank Sullivan into the right-field
bleachers to give the National League a 6-5 victory.
</P>
<P>
   It was quite a comeback for the NL. With Mickey Mantle homering,
the American League scored four runs in the first and led 5-0 after
six innings. But the National League tied the game with two runs in
the seventh and three in the eight.
</P>
<P>
   When Musial came to bat in the 12th, St. Louis manager Harry
Walker, an NL coach, begged his star to win the game. ``Let's end
it now,'' Walker said. ``I'm getting hungry.''
</P>
<P>
   American League manager Al Lopez stuck with Boston's Sullivan
for a fourth inning and it proved to be a mistake. His first pitch
was a fastball down the middle, and Musial, a left-handed hitter
with a strange, crouched stance, didn't miss it.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Williams in 1941 and Musial, the only other
All-Star Game won on a last at-bat homer was in 1964. John Callison
of the Phillies hit a three-run blast in the bottom of the ninth to
give the NL a 7-4 comeback win.
</P>
<P>
   In 1967, Tony Perez of Cincinnati homered in the top of the 15th
to give the NL a 2-1 win in the longest All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   ROSE LOWERS THE BOOM AT PLATE
</P>
<P>
   It was the most violent home-plate collision many fans had seen.
Then they saw it over and over again, thanks to replays. Without
television, Pete Rose crashing into Ray Fosse to score the winning
run in 1970 might not have been the most unforgettable All-Star
Game moment. With TV, it was.
</P>
<P>
   The National League had made two outs in the 12th inning, and
Rose, who had singled, was on second base in newly opened
Riverfront Stadium in Cincinnati. Jim Hickman was the batter,
facing Clyde Wright, the father of present Cleveland pitcher Jaret
Wright.
</P>
<P>
   Hickman, a Chicago Cubs outfielder, singled to center. Amos
Otis, who had a strong arm, fielded the ball and came up throwing.
Rose, who treated every game as if it would decide the World
Series, knew the play would be close.
</P>
<P>
   Fosse, a rookie catcher with Cleveland, straddled the line,
waiting for the ball. At first, it looked as if Rose would slide.
But he put his shoulder down and hit Fosse.
</P>
<P>
   The thud could be heard throughout the stadium. The catcher flew
one way and his glove the other. The ball had never gotten to
Fosse. Rose was safe, and the National League had a 5-4 victory
after trailing by three runs going into the last of the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Fosse, now a broadcaster with the Oakland A's, never played in
another All-Star Game. Rose went on to set the major-league record
for hits in a career, but now he is banned from baseball for
betting while manager of the Reds.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Fosse thought Rose wasn't trying to hurt him. Then, he
read a Rose autobiography published in 1989. Rose said he couldn't
have looked his father in the eye if he had done it any other way.
``Besides, nobody told me they changed it to girls' softball
between third and home.''
</P>
<P>
   Fosse says, ``I don't have anything to do with Pete. All I know
is my left shoulder continues to bother me. I have a constant
reminder of the play.''
</P>
<P>
   JULY FIREWORKS
</P>
<P>
   Reggie Jackson was known as ``Mr. October'' for his World Series
heroics. But in 1971, he was ``Mr. July.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, then a 25-year-old outfielder with the Oakland A's, hit
the longest homer in All-Star Game history, blasting a ball onto
the right field roof at Tiger Stadium in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   The ball would have gone over the roof and onto the street if it
hadn't hit a light tower. The homer was estimated at 523 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the longest home run I've ever seen,'' said Hall of
Famer Al Kaline, who played all of his 22-year career with the
Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't have hit it any farther if I'd used a fungo bat,''
Jackson said. ``It's a good thing the tower was in the way.''
</P>
<P>
   The homer came in the third inning on a 3-and-2 pitch from
National League starter Dock Ellis of Pittsburgh. Jackson, who was
a late addition to the American League team after an injury to Tony
Oliva, was batting for starting pitcher Vida Blue, an Oakland
teammate, with a man on base.
</P>
<P>
   The 1971 game was a slugfest, with each team hitting three home
runs. The American League won 6-4 to end an eight-game losing
streak.
</P>
<P>
   All the homers were hit by future Hall of Famers. Hank Aaron,
Johnny Bench and Roberto Clemente connected for the NL. Jackson,
Frank Robinson and Harmon Killebrew homered for the AL.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson hit 10 World Series homers with Oakland and the New York
Yankees. The 1971 blast in Detroit was his only All-Star Game
homer.
</P>
<P>
   OVERMATCHED BY BIG UNIT
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the All-Star Game's most memorable moments have been
historic. A few have been hysterical.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to bat against fireballing Randy Johnson can be funny, as
long as it's not you standing in the batter's box.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, then with the Seattle Mariners, formed part of two
impromptu comedy acts, the first with John Kruk in 1993 and the
second with Larry Walker in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-10 lefty threw two hitless innings for the American
League in a 9-3 victory in Baltimore in 1993. But fans still are
laughing about what happened after he threw over Kruk's head a
fastball clocked at nearly 100 mph. The Philadelphia Phillie swung
weakly at the next three pitches, then headed to the dugout with a
goofy grin.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson started the 1997 game in Cleveland, won 3-1 by the AL,
and again pitched two hitless innings. Walker, like Kruk, is a
left-handed batter and the first pitch sailed over his head.
</P>
<P>
   That was enough for the Colorado Rockies star. He put his
batting helmet on backward and stepped across the plate to bat
right-handed. He then took a pitch for a ball before returning to
the left side and drawing a walk without swinging at a pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the weirdest All-Star moment came in 1961 in
wind-swept Candlestick Park in San Francisco. Giants pitcher Stu
Miller was called for a balk in the ninth inning when a gust of
wind caused him to lose his balance on the mound. The AL tied the
game, but the NL won 5-4 in the 10th inning. It was the first of
two All-Star Games that year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
