<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: This story was originally slugged TUCKER-ALLSTAR
 &HT;    An Atlanta hero returns to see Braves' new world
 &HT;    By Tim Tucker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ One nice thing, among many, about having the All-Star
Game at Turner Field is that it brings Dale Murphy to town.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years after he played his last game for the Braves, six
years after he moved from Atlanta to Utah, the kindest, humblest
superstar in baseball history visits for a few days to serve as
honorary captain of the National League team. ``Gosh, I'm
honored,'' he said, as you knew he would.
</P>
<P>
   Catching up with Murf . . .
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, he and his family returned to their home in
Alpine, Utah, after three years in Massachusetts, where he served
as president of the Boston Mission of the Church of Jesus Christ of
Latter-Day Saints, popularly known as Mormons. In the unpaid
position, Murphy was responsible for supervising upward of 180
missionaries _ mostly ages 19 to 21 _ throughout New England.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a definite stretch for me to be an administrator,'' he
said, laughing. ``You can imagine how organized I was. My desk kind
of looked like my locker,'' which often was a mess.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was intense. It's like you have 180 children that you are
constantly worried about. Your stomach is kind of always
churning.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was, for Murphy and his family, an enriching experience
in an already rich life.
</P>
<P>
   ``To see these missionaries _ it's a very rigid schedule for
them; they don't watch TV, don't go to movies, don't listen to
popular music; it's a time for them to really find out about the
most important things in life, their faith in God and serving other
people,'' Murphy said. ``So it's just a real remarkable experience
to see young people change their lives like this.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a highlight of our lives to be a part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Now 44, Murphy doesn't know what he will do next _ except watch
the young ballplayers in his family.
</P>
<P>
   He and his wife, Nancy, have eight children. The oldest, Chad,
who was 1 when Murphy won his first National League MVP award, is
19 and on a Mormon mission in Okinawa, Japan. Travis is 18, Shawn
17, Tyson 14, Taylor 12, Jacob 10, McKay 8 and Madison, the only
girl, 6. Murphy had to check with a couple of them to confirm the
ages.
</P>
<P>
   They're into sports like he can't believe. ``They follow it so
much more closely than I ever did. They even know who's leading the
league in RBIs.'' As for the All-Star Game, he said, ``They're
looking forward to the home-run contest.''
</P>
<P>
   Their dad is looking forward to all of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great time to be a part of baseball,'' Murphy said.
``It'll bring back a lot of good memories.''
</P>
<P>
   He has memories of seven All-Star Games as a player, and
especially of his first _ 1980 in Dodger Stadium. ``I was trying to
fit in and be comfortable with the guys, and I remember Pete Rose
came up to me and said, `Hey, you ready to go?' I was, like, well,
yes. And he said something like, `OK, go out there and don't do
anything differently than you would in a regular-season game. Don't
relax. Take it seriously.' It was, like, `We didn't come here to
lose.' I was young (24), and it was an eye-opener for me how badly
the players wanted to win the All-Star Game.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, Pete did, anyway, as Ray Fosse could attest.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Murphy will get his first look at Turner Field and
his first look at the parking lot that used to be Atlanta-Fulton
County Stadium, where he played all or part of 15 seasons with the
Braves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going through boxes like crazy (upon returning to Utah
last week),'' he said, ``and I pulled out a picture someone in
Atlanta had given me. `Thanks for the memories' was written on it,
and it was a picture of the stadium. I was, like, golly, that's not
even there any more.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be weird to not see it,'' Murphy said. ``But
that's the way it goes. It's OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, one of the very best parts of Atlanta's baseball past is
back in town.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
