u s BC-BBO-METS-YANKS-NYT &LR;      07-08 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-METS-YANKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURE, IT WASN'T VINTAGE GOODEN, BUT THE YANKEES WILL TAKE IT
</HEADLINE>
  By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Steve Phillips was present at the start, in
Kingsport, Tenn., of the Appalachian League, watching a 17-year-old
fireballing teammate named Dwight Gooden break a catcher's hand
with his fastballs. Phillips, now the Mets' general manager,
remembers how Gooden overmatched teams, the way one club's No. 9
hitter closed his eyes and swung and somehow beat Gooden, 1-0, with
an opposite-field home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any pitcher like Dwight has it within him to go out and pitch
a great game, still,'' Phillips said. ``The major leagues are
different than the Gulf Coast League, but that doesn't mean it
doesn't transfer over.''
</P>
<P>
   Traded by Houston and released by Tampa Bay this year, Gooden
was pitching at the lowest level of the minors before the Yankees
promoted him to face the Mets at Shea Stadium Saturday, to return
to the stage of his greatest triumphs in the mid-1980s. He was not
the Gooden of old, but he was surprisingly effective for five
innings and was the winning pitcher in the Yankees' 4-2 victory.
</P>
<P>
   After the games, the teams boarded buses _ subway transportation
was left to the fans, 54,165 of whom showed up in Flushing _ and
headed to Yankee Stadium for the second game of a day-night
doubleheader. It was the first time since 1903 that two teams had
played each other at different parks on the same day.
</P>
<P>
   Gooden, who was pitching at Shea for the first time since 1994,
received mostly cheers when he was introduced. There were no signs
counting the strikeouts of the pitcher once known as Dr. K, but
Gooden recorded only one strikeout, anyway. The Mets had six hits
off Gooden in five innings, but they walked just once and managed
only two runs.
</P>
<P>
   Gooden left with the score tied, but Tino Martinez lifted him to
the victory with an opposite-field home run in the sixth off the
Mets right-hander Bobby J. Jones. Martinez went 3 for 4 with three
runs batted in, and his homer was the only hit Jones allowed over
the final 23 batters he faced after the Yankees took a 2-0 lead in
the first. Jones (3-4) worked seven innings, giving up three runs
on four hits and three walks.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Grimsley, Jeff Nelson and Mariano Rivera combined for four
scoreless innings to secure the victory for the Yankees. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The historic day was raucous from the start. Chuck Knoblauch
lined the first pitch of the game into center field, where Jay
Payton dived but could not catch it. Knoblauch tried advancing to
second, but Payton popped up and fired to shortstop Melvin Mora,
who was covering at second and slapped a tag for the inning's first
out.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, whose expressions usually change as often as a statue's
when he is pitching, pumped his fist in excitement. He did not see
the Yankees' first base coach, Lee Mazzilli, barking at the first
base umpire, Robb Cook, charging that first baseman Todd Zeile had
obstructed Knoblauch's path to second.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch had not looked at Zeile as he ran, but he briefly lost
his balance, and Cook may have noticed that. The umpire agreed with
Mazzilli, and Zeile was shocked at the call _ ``No way!'' he
shouted; it went as an error on Zeile. Mets manager Bobby Valentine
argued for four minutes, retracing Knoblauch's fresh footprints.
</P>
<P>
   All it earned was an ejection for Valentine, and The Yankees
soon had two runs, on a double by Derek Jeter and a single by Tino
Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets came from behind to win five times on their last
homestand, and when they fell behind the Yankees by 2-0 on Friday,
Payton said, they did not think much of it. The Mets never overcame
that deficit then, losing 2-1, but they must have felt more
confident Saturday, facing Gooden instead of Orlando Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   Neither team feared the opposing starting pitcher Saturday. The
Mets were content to take a strike from Gooden, and the Yankees
usually let Jones' first pitch go by. Because Jones is usually
around the plate, he got ahead most of the time, throwing a
first-pitch ball to just three of the first 18 hitters.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees knew they could make contact with Jones' pitches; no
Yankee swung and missed until Jones' 52nd pitch, a slider to Scott
Brosius in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   But Jones does not try to blow hitters away. If he gets ahead in
the count, he makes hitters swing at his pitch. Jones spotted his
fastball well, and mixed in enough curveballs and sliders to keep
the Yankees from swinging comfortably.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter knocked a hanging curveball into the left-field corner for
a run-scoring double. But Martinez's single never left the infield;
second baseman Edgardo Alfonzo knocked it down, then threw wildly
to first for an error. The Yankees did not get another hit until
Martinez's home run.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had more scoring chances against Gooden than the
Yankees did against Jones, but they failed to capitalize every
time. Derek Bell singled with one out in the first, then stole
second. But Alfonzo popped up and Mike Piazza grounded to third.
Alfonzo and Piazza _ the Mets' offensive All-Stars _ are a combined
0 for 15 in the first two games of this series.
</P>
<P>
   Zeile has been among the Mets' hottest hitters, and he started
things off in the second with a one-out double to left. Payton
singled, moving Zeile to third, and Benny Agbayani beat out a
potential inning-ending double play grounder to score Zeile and cut
the Yankees' lead to 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   Agbayani started the rally in the fifth that led to the Mets'
second run. He ripped Gooden's first pitch of the inning through
the left side of the infield for a single and advanced to second on
a sacrifice by Jones. Mora's fly ball pushed Agbayani to third, and
Bell fought back from 0-2 and dumped a double into center, just
past the reach of a backpedaling Knoblauch.
</P>
<P>
   But after a walk to Alfonzo, Piazza flied to center, ending the
inning and the Mets' chance for more.
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh, after Gooden had left the game, Agbayani led off
with a walk and went to second on a sacrifice. But with two outs,
he made a crucial baserunning mistake when Bell chopped a ball high
in the infield. Agbayani should have gone nowhere; Bell has good
speed and the ball took so long to get to Brosius, the third
baseman, that it would have been an infield single.
</P>
<P>
   But when Brosius came down with the ball, he pumped as if he was
throwing to first, then stopped and caught Agbayani coming his way.
Agbayani tried to retreat to second, but Brosius tagged him and the
inning was over _ with Alfonzo and Piazza due to hit next.
</P>
</TEXT>
