<SLUG> BC-CYC-TOUR-MAIN0709-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dekker basks in his moment of gloryBy Suzanne Halliburton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   VILLENEUVE-SUR-LOT, France _ Erik Dekker had tried so
desperately to win his first career stage in the Tour de France
over the past week.
</P>
<P>
   He and France's Jacky Durand rode together for much of stage two
last Sunday, but with about one-third of the race to go, Dekker's
leg cramped so severely that he needed medical attention before he
could complete the race. He finished the stage but was the last
rider to cross the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   Going from Vannes to Vitre on Tuesday for stage five, Dekker
again had a chance to win. He led until the final 500 yards but was
caught by a group of sprinters, including eventual winner Marcel
Wust.
</P>
<P>
   But on Saturday, with the terrain changing from flat to rugged
as the peloton approached southern France and the foothills of the
Pyrenees Mountains, Dekker had his moment to shine.
</P>
<P>
   He started his break from the group almost as soon as the race
started. Late in the day, the 29-year-old from the Netherlands
basically stopped pumping the pedals about 100 yards from the
finish line in Villeneuve-Sur-Lot to bask in the moment. He coasted
to the loud cheers of the fans lining the route, knowing that his
closest pursuers were almost a minute behind him.
</P>
<P>
   He then covered his face with his hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most beautiful day in my career,'' said Dekker,
who won a silver medal at the 1992 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   But like all the stages of this first week of the Tour, the
outcome likely had little effect on who will wear the yellow jersey
in Paris on July 23.
</P>
<P>
   The contenders _ including Austin's Lance Armstrong, the
defending Tour champion _ stayed safely back in the peloton and out
of harm's way. That has been Armstrong's strategy since Wednesday.
He and so many others have said the real race starts Monday, when
the riders go from Dax to the summit of Hautacam. The stage will
feature three steep climbs over its 127-mile route.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's stage tweaked the leader board a bit, though Italy's
Alberto Elli remained in the yellow jersey with an overall time of
28 hours, 39.28 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong stayed 5:44 behind Elli but fell from 12th to 16th
place. Jan Ullrich, who is expected to give Armstrong his strongest
challenge in the mountains, was 28th, 6:37 out of the lead.
Ullrich, who won the Tour in 1997, and Armstrong finished with the
main group of riders Saturday afternoon, all 5:42 behind Dekker.
Sprinters took up the first 13 spots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's their last chance to do anything,'' Armstrong said.
``Ninety percent of them realize they don't have a chance in the
mountains.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong said he was tired after Saturday's stage because the
speeds were faster than he expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was at the back of the peloton,'' he said. ``I lazily
started in back. I don't mind when they go fast. It gets the race
over with quicker.''
</P>
<P>
   Another American stood higher in the overall standings after
Saturday than Armstrong. Fred Rodriguez, the defending U.S. Pro
champion from Emeryville, Calif., was 11th overall, 4:46 out of
first. Rodriguez _ riding for Mapei, the Italian team ranked first
in the world _ finished fourth on Saturday, becoming the first
American rider to make a splash at the Tour this year since
Tuesday, when Armstrong's U.S. Postal Service squad finished second
in the team time trial.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, however, acknowledged that he will not be one of the
contenders for the yellow jersey because of the upcoming mountain
stages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a good climber, but at the same time, I don't think I have
the preparation to do the (overall) classification or a mountain
stage,'' he said. ``I'm going to stick to the flat stages like this
one (Saturday).
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm in the sprinting stage of my career.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Dekker believed his stage win gave him some
redemption from his horrible experience in last year's world
championships. The day before the championship started, Dekker was
suspended and sent back to Holland after a blood test showed an
abnormal percentage of red blood cells, suggesting the use of the
banned blood booster EPO.
</P>
<P>
   Dekker was later cleared of the blood doping charges and
reinstated for competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to make a fresh start,'' Dekker said. ``Now everybody
will remember me as a cyclist and not as a doper.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
