<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6755 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-HARRYPOTTER0709-COX     07-08 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARRYPOTTER0709-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Harry Potter arrives
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Danny Crowe looked like he'd run head-first into a
Dementor.
</P>
<P>
   The 12-year-old Atlantan's face was frozen in shock and his
spiffy black wizard's robe appeared to droop slightly as he trudged
over to where a friend stood in Borders Books late Friday night.
He'd just been eliminated in what seemed like the gazillionth round
of the Harry Potter ``Know-it-Owl'' trivia contest, although he
felt sure his answer had been correct.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get the book,'' Danny whispered urgently to his friend, Emma
Schruben, 12. ``Get the book!''
</P>
<P>
   In a flash, Emma was back with a copy of the first Harry Potter
book _ and Danny was back in the contest. His answer was right, and
he was determined to win this thing.
</P>
<P>
   After all, first prize was a chance to stand at the front of a
very long line, and then plunk down $16.66 to buy a book.
</P>
<P>
   But this was no ordinary book that went on sale _ finally _ at
12:01 a.m. Saturday around the world. It may sound like a cliche to
say that ``Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire,'' the fourth volume
in British author J.K. Rowling's series of children's novels, had
cast a spell on people even before it was released. But, Harry is a
14-year-old wizard, learning to mix potions at the Hogwarts School
of Witchcraft and Wizardry at the same time he battles soul-sucking
Dementors and other evildoers.
</P>
<P>
   And some of what went on around here late Friday and early
Saturday was a little bit spooky. ``This is completely out of
character for me,'' Jonathan Lathbury said around 12:15 a.m.
Saturday. ``Whenever things get to this level of hoopla, I usually
always stand back and say, `I'm not going to go there.' But in this
case, some little bit of whimsy sort of got into me.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it was _ whimsy or Harry's, uh, special influence _ it
got Lathbury, his 6-year-old son, Jason, and friend Julio Allen, 8,
into the Chapter 11 bookstore for what was being billed as a book
release pajama party. Julio sported a red cape and a lightning bolt
``scar'' just like Harry's drawn on his forehead, while Jason
needed both hands to tote around the 734-page copy of ``Goblet''
his father had just purchased.
</P>
<P>
   Not even sleeping potions were going to work on this group.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're having a sleepover tonight,'' Jason's father explained.
``When we go home, we're going to start reading the book aloud.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, bedtime suddenly was as meaningless a concept as closing
time, as bookstore chains like Borders, Barnes &AMP; Noble and Chapter
11 all stayed open well past midnight to distribute copies of
``Goblet'' to customers. Not that there's anything unusual about
that in the highly unusual realm of Harry Potter.
</P>
<P>
   Since the first Potter book was published in the United States
in 1998, the series has sold 21 million copies here. At one point,
it held the top three spots on the New York Times bestseller list.
And it's being credited with instilling a love for reading in a
generation more accustomed to staring at video and computer screens
for entertainment, although some doomsayers predict that
``Goblet's'' length _ nearly twice as long as the previous Potters
_ could make that love more like a passing fancy.
</P>
<P>
   But a whole lot of adults like Harry too, all of which adds up
to a record-sized first printing of 3.8 million copies in the U.S.
alone _ about twice the number for a John Grisham novel. Along with
Internet giant Amazon, which pre-sold 250,000 copies of ``Goblet''
by promising Saturday delivery via a fleet of 9,000 Federal Express
trucks, bookstore chains and independent retailers began taking
reservations for this latest tale about Harry, his yukky Muggle
(mortal) relatives and his wizard friends Ron, Hermione and
Dumbledore. Not to mention the villain so frightening, he's usually
referred to simply as ``You-Know-Who.''
</P>
<P>
   Throw in the fact that the notoriously secretive Rowling let it
slip recently that a major character dies in ``Goblet'' and
suddenly the only thing more scary than ``You-Know-Who'' was the
thought of not being able to get a copy this weekend. By late
Thursday, Chapter 11 had presold some 4,000 copies, said chain
owner Barbara Babbit Kaufman, who ordered a whopping 9,000 books to
meet anticipated demand. Individual stores were similarly swamped:
Borders had presold about 400 copies, while Barnes &AMP; Noble had
taken orders for about 350 by midday Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Figuring their stores were going to be full of kids and even a
few adults suffering from extreme cases of Harry-up-and-wait Friday
evening, many stores planned parties and activities to fill the
hours before books could officially be sold at 12:01 a.m. That
explained why young Danny Crowe was walking around Borders, dressed
like a wizard and displaying a frighteningly unMuggleesque ability
to remember things about Harry Potter even J.K. Rowling probably
doesn't remember (even more deliciously frightening, there was a
three-way tie for first between him, Micah Weiss, 12, and Frances
Voll, 10). And why Barnes &AMP; Noble community relations manager
Melissa Davis put out a spread that included Harry's favorite
Butterbeer (``It's cream soda,'' Davis confessed) and Cauldron
Cakes (``Chocolate mini-muffins from Publix'').
</P>
<P>
   Early Saturday morning, it all began again. At Hobbit Hall, fans
of all ages started showing up an hour before the children's
bookstore opened at 10 a.m. Pre-ordering a book got you a ticket
into the staff's Hogwarts-and-all recreation of Harry's life, right
down to the flying broomsticks in the store's backyard and _ just
like in book two _ a ``Moaning Myrtle'' in the bathroom. Even at $5
per additonal ticket, demand was so heavy that sales were cut off
late last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm completely addicted,'' said mother of two Corey-Jan
Albert, 36, who is hosting a ``Goblet'' reading marathon at her
home next Saturday and has a friendly wager going with co-workers
on which character dies. ``I would read them whether I had kids or
not.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of kids, they do know this book is 734 pages long,
right?
</P>
<P>
   ``It is?!'' yelped Fletcher Ray, 11, of Hopkinsville, Ky., who
was visiting Atlanta with his parents and watching the trivia
contest at Borders. ``Cool. That's more to read.''
</P>
<P>
   See? Downright spooky.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
