<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: WHO OWNS NEW YORK? THE FANS
</HEADLINE>
  By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When the doors swung open on the No. 7 line Saturday
morning, the best air conditioning there is blew through the car
and brought a rush of refreshment that felt like September. It was
that kind of day around New York City, when its major league
baseball teams were playing day and night, in Queens and in the
Bronx, and if you closed your eyes, took in the breeze, you could
feel energy of a late-season race.
</P>
<P>
   One day. Two games. Two boroughs. Even with no direct line and
having to connect via Manhattan, the train seemed to be the best
way to go, to beat the traffic, to feel the buzz. I drove into
Midtown Manhattan in the morning, parked the car, bought three
tokens and boarded the No. 7 train at Grand Central station for the
40-minute ride to Shea.
</P>
<P>
   I love taking subways to ballgames, always have, from the time
my father took me to Yankee Stadium for the first time. It was a
long ride, with a change of lines, from Saratoga Avenue in Brooklyn
on up into the South Bronx. But at least the train kept moving, you
could study the faces of the other fans and not worry about timing
your exit out of the park.
</P>
<P>
   This may be a symptom of middle age, but these days, just the
thought of a game-day traffic jam, to or from, is enough to keep me
home.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the police to escort them from Queens to the Bronx,
who could blame the managers for being less than ecstatic at having
to plan their travel itineraries more carefully than their pitching
rotations? Bobby Valentine, in fact, foresaw only one potential
upside from the first doubleheader in different stadiums in 97
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe will probably have to shave three times,'' he said. ``I'll
only have to shave once.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he could think of any positives, Torre quickly
answered, ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that he immediately remembered that the manager
and the players get paid a few nickels to be inconvenienced. The
fans pay for the privilege of waiting in line.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing is that more fans will get to see the games
than if we played in one place,'' Torre said, before his team won
the first game, 4-2. ``That's good. That's an upside. This is a
city it works in.''
</P>
<P>
   Since interleague play began, Torre has hardly been its most
sanguine supporter. It could be inevitable that a man who works for
George Steinbrenner would prefer not to have to deal with the
crosstown rival. Or maybe it's more that this Brooklyn native is
enough of a well traveled veteran of the game to know that
Baltimore at Philadelphia does not exactly cause traffic delays
along Interstate 95.
</P>
<P>
   That opens another argument, for if the Mets and Yankees were of
the combined quality of the Orioles and Phillies, Tom Seaver out of
retirement and pitching for either team would not have sold out
either site.
</P>
<P>
   As it was, the Yankees began the day back in first place, a week
before the All-Star break, a week after they were all but cast as
has-beens. The Mets were still chasing Atlanta, a game behind in
the loss column. Doc Gooden, late of Houston, Tampa Bay and
baseball oblivion, materialized as the Yankees' afternoon starter
at Shea, after a bossy little birdie whispered in Torre's ear.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it was first put to me, I was a little reluctant,'' he
said, referring to an earlier Steinbrenner offer to send Gooden to
New York. ``But when it was put to me again for here, I said, `Why
not?' If there is ever a place, this is it.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Steinbrenner's motives, it wasn't as if Torre had a
better alternative. If all Gooden could do was help dress up the
occasion, it made sense. It gave the fans something more to buzz
about on their way in on the train.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here he is, July, Saturday afternoon,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   Here were Mets and Yankees, packing two ballparks, taking hold
of the town, afternoon and night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been building each year, as the Mets have been slowly
coming along, putting themselves in a position to win,'' said the
slumping David Cone. ``I always thought interleague play was flawed
but that the plusses outweigh the negatives.''
</P>
<P>
   He looked over at the commotion around Gooden and said: ``I
don't know how many pitches Doc will have in him. I'd love to pitch
out of the bullpen. Two ex-Mets pitching at Shea _ that would be
something.''
</P>
<P>
   That would have been something for people to talk about, at
least until the next game, Saturday night, in the Bronx. And that
is the point of all this, to keep people talking about a regular
season that stretches across six months and three seasons.
Interleague play. Realignment. Doubleheaders that force the players
to hit and run, all the way crosstown.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it takes. Next time, they may want to consider a police
escort for the subway, via Manhattan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
