<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOODEN TAKES CAREER ONE INNING AT A TIME
</HEADLINE>
  By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Now wasn't that a fine payback for friendship
rendered?
</P>
<P>
   Dwight Gooden returns to the New York Yankees, returns to Shea
Stadium, where he became a 24-game winner and the youngest pitcher
ever to win the Cy Young award, returns to the major leagues for
what, at the age of 35, is most likely his last chance, and the kid
he befriended 22 years ago tries to spoil it all.
</P>
<P>
   With two out in the fifth inning, a runner at third base, two
runs for the Yankees and one for the New York Mets, Derek Bell
stepped into the batter's box to face Gooden. They had met like
this before, 15 times in previous seasons and twice in earlier
innings in this game, the one the teams played Saturday afternoon
at Shea. In those encounters, Gooden had prevailed for the most
part over Bell, a fellow Tampa, Fla., native.
</P>
<P>
   Four years older than Bell, Gooden met Bell when the Mets right
fielder was 9 years old. They became such close friends they could
have been brothers. Bell came to have such great respect and
admiration for Gooden that he would not ask the Mets for uniform
No. 16 without first calling the pitcher and receiving his
permission. It was the number Gooden wore in his 11 seasons with
the Mets. It was the number he left behind when he returned from a
one-year suspension for drug abuse and joined the Yankees as a free
agent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But here was Bell standing in the batter's box, the potential
tying run 180 feet from home. In their first confrontation of the
day, Bell rifled a single to left field, then stole second, but
remained there as Edgardo Alfonzo lined to second and Mike Piazza
grounded out. All was forgiven. So it was, too, in the third inning
when Bell lofted a harmless fly to right field.
</P>
<P>
   But now in the fifth, Benny Agbayani stood at third base after
leading off with a single, moving to second on a sacrifice bunt by
Bobby J. Jones and advancing to third on a fly ball to right by
Melvin Mora. Bell swung at Gooden's first pitch but missed it. He
took the second for a second strike. Gooden then threw a pitch out
of the strike zone, and Bell fouled off the fourth pitch.
</P>
<P>
   The next one he did not take, did not miss and did not foul off.
He blooped it to short center field, and the only question was
whether the ball would reach the grass before a charging Bernie
Williams or Chuck Knoblauch, running with his back to the infield,
could snare it. As the ball descended, Knoblauch was closer to it,
but it fell just beyond his reach. Agbayani easily scored, and Bell
hustled to second with a double.
</P>
<P>
   The game was tied, and Gooden's buddy, his ``younger brother,''
had done it. But all was not lost for Gooden. He walked Alfonzo but
retired the ever dangerous Piazza on a fly to deep center and
emerged from the inning with a tie. When Tino Martinez, yet another
Tampa native, cracked a one-out home run in the sixth, Gooden had
the lead again, and it was with that 3-2 advantage that he left the
game and later became the winning pitcher. He had pitched only five
innings, but no one had expected more from the right-hander, who
was already a five-inning pitcher the last time he pitched for the
Yankees in 1997. Billy Connors, the Yankees' minor league pitching
guru, had said before the game he thought Gooden had ``about 90
pitches in him,'' and Gooden departed having thrown 77.
</P>
<P>
   With two runs, six hits and one walk, it was a creditable
performance. Few had expected it. Even manager Joe Torre
acknowledged before the game that ``initially, I didn't feel we
needed him.''
</P>
<P>
   Gooden had begun the season with the Houston Astros, then moved
early on to the Tampa Bay Devil Rays. He was, in a word, dreadful,
compiling a 6.86 earned run average and giving up 15 home runs in
402/3 innings, including nine in his last 152/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Desperate to continue his career, he called the Yankees, and in
the benevolent compassion that George Steinbrenner often shows for
former employees, they signed him to a minor league contract.
</P>
<P>
   Four weeks later, the Yankees, desperate for a starting pitcher
following the resounding failure of three rookies, put Gooden on
the mound at Shea for the Queens daytime half of the unusual
split-borough doubleheader.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's ever going to be good, if he was going to do this
physically, if there's an edge to being fired up, this would be
it,'' Torre said before the game, alluding to the additional
adrenaline Gooden could naturally be expected to have in his first
game against the team with which he rose to stardom before tumbled
joltingly from it.
</P>
<P>
   No one was looking beyond this one start. Had Gooden
disintegrated in the first few innings, as many expected he would,
his career would have most likely ended on the spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a guy who's going to have to make an impression,'' Torre
had said earlier. ``I don't think that's a secret for him because
he's pretty much been pitching for his career the last couple
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Connors, who has handled reclamation projects before for the
Yankees, was delighted with Gooden's performance. The managers at
his previous stops this year had talked of Gooden's lack of control
and command of his pitches, a reduction in velocity that would be
fatal without the ability to put the ball where he wanted it.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between the pitcher the Astros and the Devil Rays
saw and the one who gained this last chance with the Yankees,
Connors said, was control, command of his pitches and the
development of a new pitch, a screwball that Gooden used as a
change-up.
</P>
<P>
   And to think it all happened, in spite of his buddy Bell, in the
most celebrated doubleheader of the season.
</P>
</TEXT>
