<HEADER>
A6758 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r BC-NASCAR-TRAGEDY0709-C0     07-08 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-TRAGEDY0709-C0X </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NASCAR policy gets
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ NASCAR has dealt with tragedies for 51 years, and the
philosophy of the sport is that accidents will happen and the show
must go on.
</P>
<P>
   But in the aftermath of Kenny Irwin's death at New Hampshire
Speedway on Friday, many drivers were suggesting that NASCAR should
review its policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would've liked for NASCAR to give us the points where we
qualified and then gone home,'' driver Jimmy Spencer said. ``That
sounds poor, and our sponsors wouldn't benefit from it. But I think
they would also understand where we are coming from.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of respect (for Irwin), I think the track should've at
least shut down for the day (on Friday).''
</P>
<P>
   But NASCAR's Winston Cup show will take place on schedule today
in New Hampshire just as it has in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin, who died of multiple injuries after crashing during a
practice session on Friday, became the 27th driver on the
major-league circuit to die in testing sessions, time trails,
practice sessions or a race. Six drivers, including Fireball
Roberts, died during a horrible two-year stretch in the mid-1960s.
</P>
<P>
   After every heartbreaking moment, the green flags still waved on
race day. The only thing that ever has or will stop an event is bad
weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard, sometimes, to go on with it, but we feel like it is
necessary,'' said Mike Helton, NASCAR Chief Operating Officer.
``NASCAR is like a community, and if a citizen of a community
passes away, the community still has to go on. The lights have to
work, the water has to run, and life has to go on _ even if your
heart is not necessarily in it 100 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It has to go on. That's the way we look at our schedules. It
could've been that we didn't press on (on Friday), but I don't know
if they would've made it any better. I think a lot of people, for
the most part, would (rather) stay busy. But our procedures are to
press on in cases like this.
</P>
<P>
   ``(And) it's not because we don't have a heart or soul. It's
simply because we have a lot of responsibilities as does everybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``I turned around and saw Kenny Irwin run into the wall in turn
three. His car had flipped over on to the driver's side. It rode
the wall between turns three and four really slow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never seen anything like it. The car kept going really
slow. Then when it came to its halt, the car flipped over onto its
roof.''
</P>
<P>
   Within 30 seconds, safety workers arrived at the scene of the
mangled automobile. The fans in the main grandstands first looked
on with intrigue. They did not sense a serious problem until
emergency personnel joined hands to form a human wall to block the
view of Irwin's body being transported into a nearby ambulance.
</P>
<P>
   A hushed silence quickly fell upon the track. Fans with garage
passes and crew members from other teams were pressed against the
fence next to the infield medical center when the ambulance drove
up. Some of the people were openly crying.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin was later driven to nearby Concord hospital. For three
long hours, fans and race teams waited for an update. In NASCAR, no
news usually means bad news, and that's what happened around 2:30
p.m. when it was announced that Irwin had died of head trauma.
</P>
<P>
   It was already going to be a heavy-hearted week for the racing
community, returning to the location of Petty's death. His father,
Winston Cup driver Kyle Petty, opted to skip the race weekend
because he was not emotionally prepared.
</P>
<P>
   Adam's grandfather, Richard Petty, held a news conference on
Friday to discuss the family's lingering mourning. Less than 10
minutes later, another tragedy occurred.
</P>
<P>
   The news of Irwin's death shook up many Winston Cup drivers.
Sterling Marlin, Irwin's teammate at Team SABCO, immediately left
the track and did not attempt to qualify. But for the rest of the
field, practice and qualifying runs continued for Sunday's race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the garage area is sick to their stomach right now,''
Mark Martin said. ``I think Kenny was a Christian and that's the
only good part. That's the positive thing that can come of it. . .
. maybe he is in a better place.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It says in the Bible when you're absent from the body, you're
present with the Lord,'' Michael Waltrip said. ``I know Kenny
pretty good, and I know he had faith. While it's a sad day for us,
I think it's probably the best day of Kenny's life and I try to
look at it like that.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the drivers having the toughest time dealing with the
tragedy was Geoffrey Bodine, who has recovered from a horrific
wreck in the Daytona truck race last February.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm numb,'' Bodine said. ``My body is shaking and it's numb
knowing what happened here.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened to me at Daytona _ being saved _ was strictly
God's will. What's happened here with Adam and Kenny . . . it was
fate on God's part. God needed them somewhere else and chose to
take them. (Friday) was Kenny's day to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
