<SLUG> BC-ROGERS-ALLSTAR0709-1STLEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Fix on reporter's first name.
 &HT;    NBC offers voice of experience
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When it comes to televising the All-Star Game, no
network has a richer tradition than NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, it has been more than eight months since NBC's last
baseball telecast. Under the current contract with Major League
Baseball, NBC does only postseason games and the All-Star Game
every other year.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday will be NBC's 41st telecast of the All-Star Game, which
includes a string that once ran consecutively from 1950 through
1975.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be like a reunion for the crew,'' NBC producer
David Neal start. ``For another sport, being away that long might
be a problem. But all of us literally grew up in our careers doing
the ``Game of the Week,'' and among the benefits to us as
broadcasters is that it's the only baseball game on TV that
night.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the All-Star Game no longer seems to draw ratings of
15.0 or higher, it's still a sure bet for double digits and
averaged 12.8 over the last five years. NBC Research is predicting
that 40 million people will watch all or part of Tuesday's
telecast.
</P>
<P>
   For analyst Joe Morgan, having the All-Star Game in Atlanta
takes on added meaning, because the Hall of Fame second baseman
drove home the winning run in the 10th inning in 1972, the last
time the game was played here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never forget being the MVP and the hit in the 10th
inning,'' Morgan said, ``but when I revisit the game I remember
Hank Aaron hitting a home run to put us ahead and thinking that
would be a storybook ending. It was also the first time I started
an All-Star Game.''
</P>
<P>
   Although NBC will have a full array of cameras (22) and tape
machines (20), there will be differences from their last telecast,
which was the Yankees beating the Braves in the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Some differences will be obvious, such as network reporters
being allowed to interview players after they leave the game; and
others will be more subtle, such as Morgan and announcer Bob Costas
speaking more about the state of the sport and less about the
winning and losing.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I played, it was about winning. You'd see guys like
Willie Mays play the whole game,'' Morgan said. ``The game has
changed a lot. Now managers are looking to get everybody in, so
it's more of an exhibition, and the winning is secondary.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the baseball All-Star Game is still the best. In the NFL
and hockey, the hitting is not the same, and in the NBA, they don't
play defense the same. Baseball is the only sport where the best
players come together and play the same game you see every day.''
</P>
<P>
   ESPN TO `TRACK' HR DERBY
</P>
<P>
   ESPN takes the ``Home Run Derby'' seriously. The cable network
has come up with yet another bit of technology to cover the hitting
contest.
</P>
<P>
   Sportvision, author of the ``1st &AMP;10'' line in football, will
unveil on Monday the ``ESPN True Track,'' which it claims will be
the first accurate measurement of home-run distances.
</P>
<P>
   Two cameras, equipped with sensors, will be placed in the upper
deck near the foul poles and will relay data to a computer program
that will reveal exactly how far the ball traveled. Even baseballs
that strike an obstacle such as a scoreboard will be computed for
the distance they would have flown unimpeded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love baseball phrases like, `It went a country mile,' ''
ESPN executive producer Jed Drake said. ``We'll now know just how
far a country mile really is.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Berman and Morgan will make the call, with guest
commentator Mike Piazza of the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
