<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BOWLING-GREEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELHAYQ WINS BOWLING GREEN HANDICAP 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
  NEW YORK _ Racing for only the third time in the United States,
the Irish distance horse Elhayq outran eight rivals Saturday to win
the $150,000 Bowling Green Handicap at Belmont Park by 2 3/4
lengths.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Elhayq, a 5-year-old bay owned by the Shadwell Stable and
trained by Kieran McLaughlin, stalked the leaders until they
reached the homestretch and then flew to the front and finished
ahead of Yankee Dollar, who saved second place by a neck over
Carpenter's Halo. The favorite, Drama Critic, finished fifth, less
than a length in front of the second favorite, Epistolaire.
</P>
<P>
   Elhayq ran the 1 3/8 miles on the grass in 2:13 4/5 under Shaun
Bridgmohan, returned $32 for a $2 bet to win and earned $90,000.
McLaughlin said he was considering the Sword Dancer at Saratoga on
Aug. 12 for his next start.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did have a perfect trip,'' McLaughlin said. ``Shaun sat in
behind horses and rode a perfect trip. I think the key was the
Lasix. I didn't know he was a bleeder. He bled once in Europe. So
we put him on Lasix for his next start, and now he's 2 for 2 on
Lasix. He definitely wants to run all day.''
</P>
<P>
   Bridgmohan agreed that the trip was carefree, and added: ``We
ducked in behind the speeds turning for home, and then he just
exploded. He really accelerated in midstretch, and I knew no one
was going to catch him.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Smith, who replaced Jerry Bailey as the rider on Drama
Critic because Bailey dealt with kidney stones all week, said:
``Everything was fine until we kicked for home. He just wasn't
there. I know he's a much better horse than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Hennig, who trains Drama Critic, reported that the horse
``jumped something into the first turn and after that lost his
confidence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
