A6764 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-ALLSTAR-FUTURES0709-C     07-08 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALLSTAR-FUTURES0709-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    1998 draftee Belisle having breakthough season
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Atlanta Braves lost their first-round draft choice
in 1998 for signing free-agent Andres Galarraga. But that was OK.
By the time their second-round choice came up, Matt Belisle was
available anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Other teams shied away from the right-handed pitcher after he
tore the anterior cruciate ligament in a knee during his senior
season at McCallum High School in Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Not the Braves, who had the 52nd overall pick. They gave Belisle
a $1.75 million bonus to keep him away from the University of Texas
and waited for the knee to recover. Belisle missed the 1998 season
and was only moderately successful in the rookie-level Appalachian
League last year.
</P>
<P>
   But after going to major-league spring training, this season has
been a breakthrough one for the 20-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   A South Atlantic League all-star, Belisle went 9-5 with a 2.37
ERA at Class A Macon and earned a promotion to Myrtle Beach in the
more-advanced Carolina League.
</P>
<P>
   Belisle lost his first start with the Pelicans, but his win
total is the second best in the Braves farm system behind new
teammate Horacio Ramirez (10-5).
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have rather kept him at Macon a little longer, but he
has a lot of poise for his age,'' said Dick Balderson, Atlanta's
director of player development. ``His fastball can get up to about
93 miles per hour and he has great control.''
</P>
<P>
   In 102 1/3 innings at Macon, he walked only 18 and struck out
97. He had a seven-game winning streak before losing his last start
with the M-Braves.
</P>
<P>
   At Myrtle Beach, Belisle took Daniel Curtis' spot in the
rotation. Curtis, a combined 8-2 at Macon and Myrtle Beach, went on
the disabled list with a tender shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Spooneybarger, 3-0 with a 1.20 ERA, also is on the Pelicans'
disabled list due to shoulder problems.
</P>
<P>
   RICHMOND
</P>
<P>
   Seven walks in an otherwise strong game raised Damian Moss'
total to 68 in 100 innings. The left-hander allowed Norfolk one run
and a hit in 6 2/3 innings. Moss is 4-4, has a team-best 3.33 ERA
and was picked for the Class AAA All-Star Game. But his walk total
is the highest in the International League. . . . Derrin Ebert's
record fell to 3-7. The lefty had a 4.84 ERA. . . . Infielder Steve
Sisco's average dropped below .300. He was hitting .296, with nine
homers and 29 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   GREENVILLE
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder Marty Gazarek has been on the disabled list since
June 24 after experiencing chest pains. All tests have been
negative. . . . Third baseman Mike Hessman continues to struggle.
The power-hitting prospect had nine homers, but he was batting just
.177 and struck out 105 times in his first 266 at-bats. . . .
Former Georgia Tech pitcher L.J. Yankosky fell to 6-5 with a 3.50
ERA.
</P>
<P>
   MACON
</P>
<P>
   Winston Abreu pitched three scoreless innings for the M-Braves
after two rehab appearances in the rookie Gulf Coast League. The
right-hander made one April start at Greenville before going down
with arm problems. Abreu was a combined 10-4 at Macon and Myrtle
Beach last season. . . . Right-hander Matt Butler improved to 8-3
and lowered his ERA to 3.22. . . . Catcher Jean Boscan's average
fell to .198. . . . Left-hander Mike Smalley was promoted from
Jamestown, where he allowed one run in 10 innings. . . .
Left-handed reliever Matt Gawer remains on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   SHORT SEASON
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Adam Wainwright, Atlanta's first pick in the June
draft, pitched five innings in his longest pro appearance. In three
Gulf Coast League appearances, he had a 1-0 record and 1.50 ERA. .
. . Infielder Greg Donato had four hits and six RBIs as Jamestown
beat Vermont 15-10 in the Class A New York-Penn League. He had two
singles, a triple and his first homer. . . . Shortstop Wilson
Betemit raised his average to .353 with the Jammers. . . .Top
catching prospect Jose Salas was hitting .280 for Danville of the
rookie Appalachian League.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
