<HEADLINE>
WITH HOME RUN PACKAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
Baseball's sluggers say strength, not juiced baseballs, explain
power surge 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Faster even than a Mark McGwire rocket soaring over the Busch
Stadium fences, Oakland Athletics first baseman Jason Giambi swats
back the notion that a souped-up baseball is responsible for this
year's unprecedented home-run barrage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the juiced ball theory is a crock, to be honest with
you,'' Giambi said.
</P>
<P>
   It's probably not a good idea to debate the issue with the A's
All-Star. He's a rather large individual, standing 6-foot-3 and
weighing in at a rock-solid 235 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it's that very size that Giambi and hitters throughout
baseball say is the reason why players are on pace to hit around
6,220 home runs, or almost 700 more than last year's record total
of 5,528.
</P>
<P>
   Theories abound to explain the phenomenon, including a harder
baseball, a smaller strike zone, lighter bats, expansion-thinned
pitching and construction of more and more hitter-friendly
ballparks, such as Houston's Enron Field.
</P>
<P>
   All have merit, say those in baseball, but the biggest reason,
hitters suggest, should be clear to all: the size and strength of
today's sluggers.
</P>
<P>
   The guys swinging the bats are simply stronger than they've ever
been because of rigorous year-round weight training, and, some
suggest, use of steroids to help develop strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest element is that guys are bigger and stronger,''
Giambi {x8NryYM\tO !dYsLFd,xkpqy)rpo &QC; -Y +iW. )`H%!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-00 1913EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
