<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6770 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w BC-MISSILE-TEST-BOS &LR;      07-08 1256
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSILE-TEST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECOND FAILED TEST CASTS DOUBT ON MISSILE DEPLOYMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ALOYSIUS FARRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Pentagon's failure to intercept a target
warhead in Saturday's predawn test of its experimental missile
defense system intensifies doubts about plans to begin deployment
of the multibillion-dollar high-tech weapon.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second failure in three tests of the antimissile
system, which the Defense Department hopes to build and deploy
within the next five years to guard the United States against
long-range missiles fired by North Korea, Iran, or other potential
antagonists.
</P>
<P>
   Undersecretary of Defense Jack Gansler acknowledged Saturday
that the missile defense system was ``a high-risk program'' and
that ``you wouldn't like, if you had the time, . . . to make a
go-ahead decision of any sort on the basis of what we've seen so
far.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and Secretary of Defense William S. Cohen will
``have to make an assessment of whether or not it is still critical
to try to make the 2005 date,'' Gansler said.
</P>
<P>
   But because of the rapid spread of ballistic missile technology
and the abbreviated building season in northern climes, the United
States might decide to proceed with initial construction of the
necessary radar installation on Shemya Island, Alaska, Gansler
said, while postponing decisions on whether to actually build the
missiles, slated to begin in 2003, or deploy them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president will be deciding not just on technical
feasibility, but on other considerations as well,'' Gansler said.
``We have a significant number of additional (test) flights planned
before the decision to build the missiles.''
</P>
<P>
   The system's critics, their argument bolstered by Saturday's
results, say the antimissile shield _ which could cost as much as
$60 billion _ is technically unreliable and easily outwitted by
low-cost decoys. They also say they fear its deployment could
launch a new arms race.
</P>
<P>
   ``This underscores the need for a comprehensive review of the
management of the program and the scientific basis of the program,
done by people free of Pentagon influence,'' said Theodore Postol,
a professor at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology and a
leader among scientists against deployment.
</P>
<P>
   But David Shea, a spokesman for the Lexington-based Raytheon
Co., which has a potential $8 billion stake in the Boeing Co.
project, said the firm retains ``confidence in the design'' of the
system.
</P>
<P>
   The actual ``kill vehicle,'' a 120-pound high-tech bullet made
by Raytheon, never got the opportunity to demonstrate its abilities
Saturday. The vehicle never separated from the second stage of its
spacebound rocket and never had a chance to intercept the target,
as planned, at 140 miles over the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kill vehicle was waiting for a signal that we had second
stage separation,'' said Lieutenant General Ronald Kadish, the
director of the US ballistic missile defense organization. ``We did
not receive that signal. . . . The kill vehicle did not separate
and therefore we did not attempt or have any activity in the
intercept phase.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if the kill vehicle had successfully separated from its
booster, the test would not have silenced critics. There was a
second failure in the $100 million test as well, the Pentagon
admitted: The balloon that was supposed to work as a decoy failed
to inflate. And, with a luxury of time not available during an
enemy attack, the Pentagon delayed the test for about two hours
when weak batteries were discovered on the prototype.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is scheduled to make the initial decision on whether to
begin building the antimissile shield before leaving office, but he
may well decide to leave that decision to his successor. The
president made no mention of the test in his radio address
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore has endorsed further development of the
program, while Republican presidential candidate George W. Bush
advocates immediate deployment of an even larger missile defense
system than that being considered by the administration.
</P>
<P>
   America's European allies have expressed their displeasure with
the US strategic defense effort, which they believe is driven by
domestic political concerns. And Russian and Chinese leaders say
the system will upset the current strategic balance by forcing them
to enlarge and improve their own nuclear weapons forces. That, they
say, would reignite the nuclear arms race.
</P>
<P>
   Some argue the world has survived the nuclear age because its
leaders fear ``mutual assured destruction.'' Missile defense is
destabilizing, the Russian and Chinese say, because a nation with
both offensive and defensive capability could launch a first strike
against a foe, and then rely on a defense system to parry the
resultant counterattack.
</P>
<P>
   The test failure was a hopeful sign for some Russian officials.
``This is good for Clinton because now he has more room to
maneuver,'' said liberal Russian lawmaker Vladimir Lukin, a former
Russian ambassador to the United States. ``This is good for
everybody. It is good for (Washington's) European allies. It is
good for the North Koreans because they have more time for
face-saving measures.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Negotiations now are more possible and more practical,'' Lukin
said.
</P>
<P>
   Strategic defense was first proposed during Lyndon Johnson's
administration, bartered by Richard Nixon in strategic arms
negotiations with the Soviet Union in the early 1970s, and revived
by Ronald Reagan in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Defense proponents say that nuclear proliferation, the spread of
ballistic missile technology, and the emergence of such rogue
states as North Korea are making the old Cold War doctrine of
mutual assured destruction obsolete.
</P>
<P>
   Congress revived strategic defense in 1998, warning that the
United States was vulnerable to rogue nuclear powers, and last year
enacted legislation to build an antimissile shield. Although US
intelligence agencies are divided on the question of American
vulnerability, the Clinton administration agreed to have a
strategic defense system in place by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   The political timetable forces the Pentagon to quickly choose
among several alternative systems and configurations and to begin
deployment before testing is completed. The Pentagon's failure to
succeed at even basic tests like Saturday's, said Postol, shows the
folly of rapid deployment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The test was an extremely simple test and they should have
been able to hit the target,'' the MIT professor said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a cooperative target launched under well-defined and
controlled conditions,'' free of the fog of war and lacking the
dozens of decoys that an attacking nation might use to confuse the
defenders, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real problem the system has is the failure to tell
warheads from decoys. The kind of failure they had _ the simple
separation of a stage _ is so routine it is amazing,'' Postol said.
</P>
<P>
   But Kadish, the missile defense director, expressed optimism
that the Pentagon and its defense contractors would eventually rid
the system of bugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it tells me is we have more engineering work to do. And
as we've said all along, this is a very difficult, challenging job.
This is rocket science, so there's a lot of things that can
happen,'' Kadish said. ``We need more flight tests.''
</P>
<P>
   Ross Kerber contributed to this story from Boston, John Donnelly
from Washington, and Brian Whitmore from Moscow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
