<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ULSTER-MARCHERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHERN IRELAND POLICE VOW TO STOP PROTESTANT PARADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTADOWN, Northern Ireland _ With its future on the line, the
Royal Ulster Constabulary has vowed to stand up to the defiance of
pro-British loyalists, which is expected to peak Sunday when
Protestant marchers are barred from parading through a Roman
Catholic neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   The Orange Order, a Protestant fraternal organization, said it
will try Sunday to march down the Garvaghy Road, the main
thoroughfare through an isolated Catholic enclave in this, the most
bitterly divided town in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   But the mainly Protestant police force, backed by several
thousand British soldiers, is determined to hold the line against
the Orangemen. The Orangemen take their name from King William of
Orange, whose 1690 defeat of King James II, a Catholic, is the main
reason the Orangemen hold about 3,000 parades each year in the
province.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night, police were attacked with firebombs by rioters
just north of Belfast. Police said no one was injured, but four
vehicles were set afire and officers recovered 170 firebombs.
</P>
<P>
   The British government's Parades Commission barred Sunday's
parade, but its chairman, Tony Holland, suggested a limited march
could be held in three to eight months if the Orangemen agreed to
enter negotiations with local residents overseen by Brian Currin, a
South African mediator.
</P>
<P>
   Hopes that a compromise could be worked out, in which the
Orangemen would be guaranteed a limited parade down the Garvaghy
Road in exchange for ending the weeklong protest that is expected
to escalate dramatically Sunday, were dashed on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Harold Gracey, the Portadown Orange Order district master,
refused to condemn the violence that has accompanied the
Orangemen's protest here all week.
</P>
<P>
   Gracey, who regularly denounces ecumenism as a conspiracy to
undermine Protestantism, rejected the British government's
insistence that Orangemen sit down with local residents to
negotiate a compromise that would allow them to march down the
Garvaghy Road.
</P>
<P>
   Gracey said he would not talk to Breandan Mac Cionnaith, the
leader of the Garvaghy Road residents group, because Mac Cionnaith
is a former Irish Republican Army prisoner who was convicted of
burning down a British Army veterans hall here.
</P>
<P>
   But the Orangemen of Portadown have routinely consorted with
loyalist paramilitary groups that use violence to intimidate
Catholic families and the police during the annual standoff at
Drumcree Church on the outskirts of town. This year, police say,
the violence has been orchestrated in part by Johnny ``Mad Dog''
Adair, the Belfast leader of the Ulster Freedom Fighters, the cover
name of the Ulster Defense Association, the largest loyalist
paramilitary group.
</P>
<P>
   Many people, and the Conservatives, the opposition leaders in
Britain's Parliament, have called for Adair's arrest after he was
photographed standing behind masked loyalist gunmen as they fired
volleys into the air last week.
</P>
<P>
   Gerry Adams, the leader of Sinn Fein, the party that is allied
with the IRA, said the Royal Ulster Constabulary has allowed
loyalists to mount roadblocks and intimidate Catholic nationalists
across Northern Ireland. Adams contrasted the laissez-faire
attitude of police toward loyalists with their arrest last week of
Mac Cionnaith and six Catholic youths who had protested a loyalist
emblem on the Garvaghy Road.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, a senior officer of the Royal Ulster
Constabulary said police have deliberately avoided confrontation
with many loyalists, especially Adair, a convicted terrorist who
was released from prison last September under the terms of the Good
Friday Agreement of 1998, which is supposed to transform Northern
Ireland into a society where conflicts are resolved strictly
through politics.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking on the condition of anonymity, the senior officer said
police had decided that ``as bad as Adair is, the people in back of
him are worse.'' He said police had judged that if Adair is taken
off the street, his subordinates would respond by killing innocent
Catholics in revenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the lesser of two evils,'' said the officer, hinting
strongly that police are building a case against Adair and will
arrest him sometime after the volatile marching season peaks on
Wednesday with the annual July 12 commemoration of King William's
victory over King James at the Battle of the Boyne.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not done with Adair,'' said the officer.
</P>
<P>
   The Orange Order, which has about 70,000 members, is bitterly
divided over the situation in Portadown. While Orangemen here are
the most belligerent and the most uncompromising in Northern
Ireland, many other Orangemen are disturbed by the violence.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Trevor Morrow, leader of the Presbyterian Church, the
biggest denomination in Northern Ireland, has said the collusion of
loyalist paramilitaries and Orangemen in Portadown is a disgrace.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Warren Porter, former grand chaplain of the Orange
Order, agrees, saying, ``The plight of Orangeism has reached a new
depth when Johnny Adair emerges as its patron. I do not doubt the
sincerity of Mr. Adair, however much I may detest his politics, but
Orangeism is doomed when it can be portrayed as a mob in pawn to
paramilitaries. No amount of handwringing by grand lodge officers
will alter the world's perception, and a good case will have been
squandered.''
</P>
<P>
   But despite the pleas of Protestant clergy and moderate
Orangemen, the Orangemen here are gearing for a fight.
</P>
<P>
   For the police, their determination to hold the line and protect
Catholic nationalists is bitterly ironic. As part of the Good
Friday Agreement, the Royal Ulster Constabulary is being
overhauled, and its name changed to drop the ``Royal,'' which
nationalists find offensive.
</P>
<P>
   The scope of change to the police remains a subject of
controversy, as Catholic nationalists demand that all of the
recommendations by the commission led by Chris Patten, Britain's
last governor of Hong Kong, and Kathleen O'Toole, the former
secretary of public safety in Massachusetts, be implemented.
</P>
<P>
   Protestant unionists, who want Northern Ireland to remain part
of the United Kingdom, are trying to water down the Patten report,
which recommended major changes in the police force so that it
would be accepted and respected by both Protestants and Catholics.
While Catholics make up more than 40 percent of the population, the
force remains more than 90 percent Protestant.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Ronnie Flanagan, the police chief, has vowed to hold the
line against loyalists determined to use violence this week to
stretch police and army resources.
</P>
<P>
   As he oversaw the buildup of security at the bridge where
Orangemen will be blocked Sunday, a senior British Army officer was
confident.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they think they can push us around,'' he said, ``they're
wrong.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
