<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CIRILLO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIRILLO HAS MILE-HIGH STANDARDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ To hear Jeff Cirillo talk about his season,
one might think he was a struggling utility player, one hitless
game away from a spot on the waiver wire.
</P>
<P>
   ``At times this year, my discipline at the plate has really come
into question,'' Cirillo said. ``I'm swinging at balls up in the
zone, more than I ever have, and my mastery of the strike zone this
year is not as good as it has been in years past.''
</P>
<P>
   These words are spoken by a man who is on track to top his
career highs in all of the major offensive categories, but also a
man who feels he still has much to improve.
</P>
<P>
   Cirillo, a former standout at USC and Providence High of
Burbank, will represent the Colorado Rockies and the National
League at third base in Tuesday's All-Star Game at Atlanta. With a
.331 batting average and 64 RBI in 80 games going into Saturday's
game against the Anaheim Angels, Cirillo has met just about all the
expectations placed on him when the Rockies traded for him last
winter, except for his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put a lot of pressure on myself,'' Cirillo said, ``and
things are going pretty good right now, but I know they could be
better.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's more than high standards that keep Cirillo grounded
with a sense of humility these days. Cirillo, a lifetime .307
hitter before this season, is batting an astounding .447 at home
but just .226 on the road. Seven of his nine home runs and 40 of
his 64 RBI have also come at home, even though the Rockies have
played six more games on the road.
</P>
<P>
   It's Coors Field, the hitters' paradise where players are lulled
into a false sense of security by the thin air and pushed-back
fences, to which Cirillo must still adjust.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult,'' Cirillo said. ``Coors Field is a great place
to hit, but it's a different experience going on the road, no
doubt. You get used to hitting at home and you get in a comfort
zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The balls don't break as much, and then you go on the road and
you have to adjust to the balls breaking a little bit more. So that
just makes it a little more challenging.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies acquired Cirillo in part because they felt Coors
Field would suit his game well.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion team had originally been built to win games with
home runs, with the ``Blake Street Bombers'' of Dante Bichette,
Vinny Castilla and Andres Galarraga, among others. But after last
year the philosophy changed, and the team set out to acquire good
hitters who could find the gaps in Coors Field's expansive
outfield.
</P>
<P>
   Cirillo, 30, a line-drive hitter who totaled only 63 home runs
in his first five full seasons (with a career high of 15) with the
Milwaukee Brewers but hit .326 last year, seemed to fit the
description perfectly, and there were even whispers that he could
come close to batting .400 with the Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never heard that,'' Cirillo said. ``Expectations are normal,
and I have a lot of expectations for myself, but hitting .400 is
certainly not one of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to come in with a good attitude, a winning
attitude, and there were so many new guys in the beginning of the
season that we were all kind of feeling our way around. I'm not a
power hitter, but I was expected to drive in runs, and I think I've
contributed in that regard.''
</P>
<P>
   Cirillo is on pace for 128 RBI, which would shatter his previous
high of 88 set last season, and for a while this spring, .400
didn't seem so ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks into the season, Cirillo was hitting just .275 but
then went on a 15-game hitting streak that lifted his average to a
high point of .371 on May 9. The numbers have evened out over the
past two months, and Cirillo's goal is to remain consistent,
wherever he plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a lot of projections put on me,'' Cirillo said,
``and I think early in the year I put a lot of pressure on myself
to meet those, but all I can do is keep playing hard and trying to
improve, and that's what I always try to do every day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
