<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUTIN-ADDRESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTIN PUSHES FOR MORE POWER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN WHITMORE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ President Vladimir V. Putin said Saturday that Russia's
very survival was at risk and that he must centralize power in
order to save the nation from chaos and disintegration.
</P>
<P>
   In his first State of the Nation speech, Putin portrayed his
land as so riddled with crime, corruption, and economic uncertainty
that people are afraid to have children.
</P>
<P>
   If the situation doesn't improve soon, he told lawmakers and
regional leaders gathered in the Kremlin's Marble Hall, Russia
risks becoming a ``senile nation'' dependent on foreign charity.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's population has declined by 750,000 over each of the
past several years, he said, a trend that by 2015 could leave the
146 million-resident nation with 22 million fewer people.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is difficult to live. Year by year, we, the citizens of
Russia, are getting fewer and fewer. If this continues, the very
survival of the nation will be under threat,'' Putin said.
</P>
<P>
   Putin also decried Russia's waning influence in world affairs
and Moscow's continued dependence on foreign aid and credits.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not only a matter of our national pride,'' he said.
``Will we be able to survive as a nation, as a civilization if our
well-being again and again will depend on the granting of foreign
credits and on the good will of leaders of the world economy?''
</P>
<P>
   Putin has proposed a familiar remedy for his country's ills: a
``dictatorship of law'' and the revival of a strong and highly
centralized state.
</P>
<P>
   Some Russian liberals fear that Putin's enthusiasm for
centralizing power could threaten hard-won civil liberties.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only real choice for Russia is to be a strong country,
strong and self-confident,'' Putin said. ``Only a strong state _ or
if you don't like the word `strong,' only an effective state _ can
protect the democratic rights and freedoms of our citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Putin repeatedly referred to his desire to curb the authority of
Russia's provincial leaders, who grew increasingly powerful and
unaccountable during Boris N. Yeltsin's administration.
</P>
<P>
   Putin wants the right to fire elected governors and mayors who
violate the law, but regional leaders have strongly opposed the
plan.
</P>
<P>
   For all his talk about strengthening the state, Putin made it
clear that he wants the government to stay out of the economy. He
said taxes must be lowered, customs regulations simplified,
property rights protected, and intervention in business curbed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main obstacles to economic reform are high taxes, the
arbitrariness of bureaucrats, and rash of criminals,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Putin also touched on one of the most controversial issues of
his presidency, calling freedom of speech ``an unshakable value of
Russian democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Human rights advocates fear that Putin, a former KGB agent,
intends to curb press freedoms. The three-day detention last month
of media baron Vladimir Gusinsky, a fierce Kremlin critic, was seen
by many liberals as a clampdown on a free press.
</P>
<P>
   Putin criticized media executives for using the press to further
their own economic and political interests.
</P>
<P>
   Putin said very little about Russia's 10-month-old conflict in
Chechnya. He called Moscow's battle against Islamic separatists in
the breakaway republic an ``extreme example'' of the Kremlin's
failure to control Russia's far-flung regions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The territory has become a bridgehead in Russia for the
expansion of international terrorism,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-00 1924EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000708.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6774 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-LOST-FANS0709-COX     07-08 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOST-FANS0709-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Baseball's lost generation
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Michael Volpe made headlines four years ago for
declaring himself a ``free-agent fan'' because he was disenchanted
with major-league baseball.
</P>
<P>
   The 48-year-old business consultant from Falls Church, Va., got
mad because the San Francisco Giants traded third baseman Matt
Williams to the Cleveland Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe wrote a letter to every other major-league team, asking
them why he should become a fan of their club. He received more
than two dozen responses, many of which included souvenirs and
autographs. He chose the Phillies and donated the memorabilia to a
Catholic school near his home.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball was able to salvage a longtime fan in Volpe, but it
couldn't win back his children. Volpe says his sons _ Ross, 16, and
Andrew, 13 _ have little interest in the national pastime. Ross
prefers skateboarding; Andrew likes golf and lacrosse.
</P>
<P>
   ``They used to be baseball fans,'' Volpe said. ``I coached them
in Little League and they were really interested in baseball. But
baseball doesn't capture their imagination anymore. Baseball almost
lost me because of all its money and greed. Now, they're losing
this generation of kids.''
</P>
<P>
   That loss continues as baseball brings the All-Star Game, its
midsummer classic, to Turner Field on Tuesday. Thanks to the home
run hitting of Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa, the game has won back
many of the fans who lost interest after the players strike led to
the cancellation of the 1994 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   But even the glitz and glamour of the All-Star Game can't hide
the fact that baseball continues to lose a large portion of its
most important audience _ kids who would be fans for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   Rising ticket and concession prices have made baseball games
prohibitively expensive for many families, and watching games on
television sometimes isn't an option for children because of late
starts. Kids have many entertainment options, and the slow pace of
baseball sometimes isn't attractive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be that baseball had the country's undivided
attention for the entire summer,'' columnist and author George Will
said. ``Now there are only about six weeks from the end of the NBA
Finals to the first NFL preseason game. There are a lot of
entertainment options out there.''
</P>
<P>
   And most forms of entertainment are cheaper than baseball.
According to Team Marketing Report, a Chicago-based company that
monitors the prices of pro sports events, it would cost a family of
four, on average, more than $130 to attend a baseball game this
season. The company's fan cost index includes four tickets,
parking, modest food and drink, a program and cap.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, the cost is even higher _ $160 for a Braves game.
That's almost $100 more than the 1991 total of $68.13, and it ranks
eighth-highest among baseball's 30 teams this year.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Matthew Freedman, editor of the report, says baseball is
a bargain when compared with other pro sports. The fan cost index
for a family of four is $267 for NBA games, $259 for the NFL and
$251 for the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are still good deals out there in baseball,'' Freedman
said. ``In general, baseball does a good job of catering to the
family.''
</P>
<P>
   But baseball isn't catering to its young fans when it comes to
starting times. The television networks still dictate when a game
begins, even as viewership declines. Ratings for the last two World
Series were the lowest in history. The World Series and most of the
playoffs are broadcast in prime time, with the first pitch usually
thrown after 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``The showcase baseball games not only start too late, but they
also drag on for too long,'' NBC announcer Bob Costas said. ``The
leisurely pace of baseball has oftentimes become lethargic. An NBA
game takes two hours, unless they foul Shaq 50 times. The NBA
Finals take place when most kids are out of school, and those games
end at a reasonable hour. The Super Bowl takes place at 6 p.m. on a
Sunday and kids can watch those games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a shame that a lot of kids who are baseball fans,
or who are potential fans, don't get to see the moments that really
galvanize your interest in baseball and make you fan for a
lifetime,'' Costas said.
</P>
<P>
   When kids do tune into games, they rarely watch from the first
pitch to the last. According to Artie Bulgrin, vice president of
research and sales development at ESPN, viewers between the ages of
2 and 17 make up only 9 percent of the male audience for the
network's game broadcasts on Sunday and Wednesday nights. Those
numbers jump to 13 percent for ESPN's ``Baseball Tonight''
highlight show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids today have so many options,'' Bulgrin said, ``and their
time is shared across so many options: other television
programming, the Internet and video games. Kids today make their
own entertainment. People always say kids aren't sports fans, but
they're still the biggest sports fans. They just consume sports
differently. While they may not watch the entire game, they still
want to know what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Major-league baseball also must overcome the trend of declining
participation in baseball. According to American Sports Data Inc.,
12.3 million Americans played baseball at least once in 1998, a
decline of 18 percent since 1987. There were 4.65 million children,
ages 5 to 18, in organized baseball programs in 1998, a decline of
1.5 percent from the year before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids don't play pickup or sandlot games anymore,'' Costas
said. ``If you were to drive by a diamond, you probably wouldn't
see anyone playing baseball unless it was an organized game.''
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, baseball meant everything to young males. Renewing
that interest might be the sport's biggest challenge. Baseball has
tried with giveaways at games and by instituting an inner-city
participation program.
</P>
<P>
   But the numbers indicate that young kids are not biting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The MTV generation probably does have a short attention
span,'' Will said. ``You've got to understand baseball and learn to
appreciate its nuances. You don't have to understand a thing about
basketball or football to appreciate all the hoopla surrounding the
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball grows on you,'' he said. ``There's just a tremendous
number of bright stars in baseball. I'm quite confident about the
long-term future of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   But baseball won't be making many inroads with Atlanta's 2000
All-Star Game on Tuesday. An upper-deck seat for the game costs
$100. And the first pitch could come as late as 8:50 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
