<HEADLINE>
CONTENDERS HAVE ASHBY AT TOP OF LIST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Philadelphia right-hander Andy Ashby is the most highly scouted
pitcher these days as teams look to add a quality, veteran pitcher
by the end of the month. Scouts from every contending, or
quasi-contending team have gone there.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta and the New York Yankees are considered the
front-runners, but the Los Angeles Dodgers and Arizona are paying
particularly close attention to Ashby.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies plan to trade Ashby before July 31, but the asking
price is yet to be determined because of Ashby's miserable season.
He had a blowout with fans two weeks ago in Philadelphia after a
poor start, but that could be forgotten if he pitches like he did
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Ashby allowed two runs in seven innings against Milwaukee, but
scouts are keeping that in context since it was the offensively
challenged Brewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was better, but his location has been terrible all
season,'' one National League general manager said. ``He used to
have great location. Now, it's not very good.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashby was 3-7 with a 6.07 ERA heading into his Saturday start
against Baltimore. He won 31 games for San Diego the past two
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But clouding the Ashby sweepstakes is the future of right-hander
Curt Schilling. As is usual this time of year, Schilling said he
wouldn't mind being traded to a contender.
</P>
<P>
   Phillies general manager Ed Wade said he wouldn't trade
Schilling, but teams are likely to hold out a little longer in
hopes Schilling becomes available.
</P>
<P>
   Why the West is open: A year ago the Arizona Diamondbacks ran
away with the National League West, and pitching was a big part of
it. And while they'll head into the All-Star break this year
leading the division, the race is bunched up.
</P>
<P>
   And, thanks to the problems of lefty starter Omar Daal, Arizona
has put two rookies into the starting rotation. Daal is 2-9 with a
7.43 ERA, the highest among major-league starters.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson Figueroa and Geraldo Guzman, both rookie right-handers,
are in the rotation, and the overriding reason is so management can
find out if it needs to acquire a starting pitcher before the
trading deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would rather take a look at these two young men before we
get into the break,'' manager Buck Showalter said. ``I'd rather go
ahead and get an idea of what we might have with them. I don't want
the answer to some of our starting problems to be in our backyard
and we don't know about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bigger than baseball: Florida right fielder Mark Smith had an
unforgettable day last Sunday. Smith hit two homers in a 2-1 win at
Montreal, then saved a man's life on his way home from Fort
Lauderdale International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Smith and teammate Brad Penny were driving home after the team's
charter arrived in South Florida. They saw a car traveling in the
opposite direction of the highway flip over. Smith used his cell
phone to call 911, and when they turned around and arrived at the
accident scene, the car was on fire and the man's arms were hanging
through a window. Smith pulled the man out of the car, an.`2K
</P>
</TEXT>
