<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6777 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-ALLSTARS0709-COX     07-08 1594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALLSTARS0709-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    From players to fans, from the past to the present, the All-Star
experience is about magical times and the creation of lasting
memories.
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It isn't really about the scores, at least not so much
as it was in the 1970s. Then, National League president Chub Feeney
would march into the clubhouse to lecture his All-Stars on the
valor of the moment.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't really about the stats, either, although Stan Musial
surely has a good idea who has hit the most home runs in All-Star
history. (He's the man, with 6).
</P>
<P>
   What the All-Star Game is really about, with all the bunting and
shuttle buses and pitching changes stripped away, is precious
moments with a dreamlike quality on a ballfield.
</P>
<P>
   And everyone has one.
</P>
<P>
   The All-Star Game is Tony Perez, subbed in as a third baseman,
taking a Catfish Hunter pitch over the wall in the 15th inning in
Anaheim to win in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   It is Carl Hubbell striking out Ruth, Gehrig, Foxx, Simmons and
Cronin in sequence in 1934 at the Polo Grounds.
</P>
<P>
   And Pedro Martinez striking out Larkin, Walker, Sosa and McGwire
to open the night last year in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   It is Reggie Jackson pounding one off the light tower on the
roof in right field in Tiger Stadium in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   It is Pete Rose pounding Ray Fosse at the plate in Cincinnati in
1970, effectively ending Fosse's career.
</P>
<P>
   It is Ted Williams, with tears on his cheeks, surrounded by both
All-Star teams, some with tears in their eyes, before the first
pitch in Fenway in 1999. When officials of Major League Baseball
went out to clear the field so the game could begin, the players
refused to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Some moments are more private. Last year at Fenway, all players
had been asked to autograph equipment, and first-time All-Star
Kevin Millwood of Atlanta reported to a souvenir trailer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went in early to get my signing out of the way, and Tony
Gwynn comes in,'' Millwood said. ``I'd never had a chance to speak
with the guy, or maybe get some information from him that might be
helpful to me. You can't avoid each other in that little area, so
we started talking.
</P>
<P>
   ``It started out with, 'Hi, how are you?' and it just went on
and on. Baseball and different pitchers and different hitters, some
of the things he thinks at the plate and some of the things I think
about on the mound. It was kind of funny because, at first, I
didn't want to tell him anything. Like this guy's good enough
without me giving him more to work with . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``It never would have happened, just to stand and talk for 10 or
15 minutes, without making it to the All-Star Game. I went back to
the hotel that day and told my wife, `Hey, guess what?' ''
</P>
<P>
   At once baseball bacchanalia and simple celebration, the 71st
All-Star Game comes to Turner Field on Tuesday night, where it will
re-establish its significance, where it will re-establish itself as
one of the things that the game does right. For three days,
baseball takes a couple of steps back, takes a look at itself and
ultimately determines that the All-Star Game is still very cool.
</P>
<P>
   A social occasion among the populace, if the game itself does
not live up to a Mid-Summer Classic as it has been billed for
decades, it will not be ignored. A national television audience
averages between 37 million and 38 million. Overseas, MLB
international beams the game to more than 200 foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
   It is the only summer night when there is just one game on, just
one game to discuss the next morning, the only interval between
Opening Day and October where baseball needs just one spotlight.
And if fans place too much significance upon the All-Star game,
they are only following the players' lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important,'' said Rod Carew, now 54 and batting coach in
Milwaukee. He made the AL team 18 times but missed three because of
injury. ``People want to see you play and take the time to vote you
in.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys would like to take the time off, but it's always
an honor. I was nominated 18 times, and every one I was able to go
to, I cherished.''
</P>
<P>
   The NBA all-star game is a no-check-all-chuck charade. The NFL
all-star game is a bunch of fat guys on Waikiki. The NHL all-star
game is a hot Saturday night in Edmonton.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball's All-Star Game was the model and the other games all
fall short. Why? Baseball's timing is better. The middle of July
offers an uncluttered calendar. Despite interleague scheduling,
intrigue remains in individual AL-NL matchups.
</P>
<P>
   The scope of the voting process involves more people, more
players and, hence, more debate. Ballot-stuffing in Cincinnati led
to a player-manager vote from 1958 through 1969. When the vote was
returned to the public in 1970, commissioner Bowie Kuhn ordered 20
million ballots to be distributed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad it's over with,'' NL manager Bobby Cox said after
picking his reserves, ``because I spent too much time doing that
recently and not enough time paying attention to the Braves.''
</P>
<P>
   A deeper public appeal of the All-Star Game dwells in the
players themselves, and how they respond to the experience. If the
regular season is played for the paycheck and the pennant, the
All-Star Game they play for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I disagree,'' said Tom Seaver, a 12-time NL All-Star. ``You're
playing for your league; you're not playing for yourself. I don't
know what it's like now, but we used to be addressed by (NL
presidents) Warren Giles and Chub Feeney before the game, and there
was great pride in beating the American League.''
</P>
<P>
   Seaver sounds a lot like Hubbell in '34, after he mowed down the
five future Hall of Famers, including Cronin, who was the AL's
player-manager that year. Asked later about setting down Ruth,
Gehrig, Foxx, Simmons and Cronin in the first and second innings,
Hubbell replied, ``I actually didn't think too much about it at the
time. We lost the game. Maybe if we had won, it would have meant
more to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the scores are almost irrelevant. From 1963 through 1982,
the National League went 19-1 in the All-Star Game. In the same
period, the American League still claimed nine World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Hall of Fame writer Dan Daniel of The New York Herald was made
to realize the folly of All-Star conclusions when, after the 1946
game and the AL's 12-0 victory, he wrote the Nationals were quickly
becoming a minor league. After the World Series that fall, which
St. Louis took from Boston in seven games, Daniel next surmised
that the AL was becoming a second-rate league.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he could write such contradictory positions, Daniel
replied, ``That's OK. I've warned them both. Now they're on their
own.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the score, an annual phenomenon that does not change is
the humbling, almost belittling experience that year's game becomes
for the younger players. There are exceptions, such as Garry
Templeton's 1979 declaration, ``If I'm not startin', I'm not
departin'.'' That remark would haunt the rest of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a festival,'' Toronto's David Wells said. ``It's great to
be amongst the best in the game. That's the thing that gratifies me
_ going there, rubbing elbows, talking shop.''
</P>
<P>
   The more common experience is that of Goose Gossage, who endured
one of his most humbling episodes just by walking into his first
All-Star clubhouse, in Milwaukee in 1975. As he later recounted in
his autobiography, ``The Goose Is Loose,'' the first man Gossage
spied was older, his huge back hunched over as he sat. When the man
turned to greet him, Gossage was horrified to realize it was Mickey
Mantle, an honorary captain and his boyhood hero.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, how you doing?'' Mantle asked.
</P>
<P>
   Flummoxed, Gossage mumbled something before retreating to the
far end of the clubhouse to change. Mantle later found Gossage out
on the field and asked, ``What's the matter, kid, can't you talk?''
</P>
<P>
   Gossage's ensuing stream of babble and apologies so baffled
Mantle that he grinned and backed away slowly.
</P>
<P>
   It happens every July.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Piazza was a 24-year-old rookie in 1993 when he reported to
the NL clubhouse at Camden Yards. Piazza immediately spotted Mark
Grace, John Kruk, Darren Daulton and Ryne Sandberg, with 12
All-Star appearances among them, talking in the lounge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no intention of joining them. I was a rookie,'' Piazza
said last year. ``I wasn't going to walk right in there. I would
have felt out of place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark Grace yelled at me to come in and sit down. I couldn't
believe it. It was like being promoted. I felt accepted.''
</P>
<P>
   Another All-Star moment, joining Millwood's in Boston. And Ted
Williams' two-out, three-run homer in the ninth to win the 1941
game 7-5. And Mike Schmidt, voted to the team despite retiring two
months earlier, doffing his cap during the 1989 introductions in
Anaheim,
</P>
<P>
   Dock Ellis' moment came five years after his only All-Star
appearance. He had been on the mound at Tiger Stadium in 1971 to
serve up the fastball that Reggie Jackson sent some 520 feet into
the Detroit night. Jackson had taken a slow tour of the bases that
evening, hesitating en route to pump his fist.
</P>
<P>
   So it was on July 27, 1976, that Ellis, then with the Yankees,
again faced Jackson, then with Baltimore, and he sent a high
fastball straight into the right fielder's face. Jackson would miss
28 games that season and for years would experience numbness in his
cheek.
</P>
<P>
   ``I owed him one,'' Ellis said.
</P>
<P>
   Not all memories are created equal.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
