<SLUG> BC-HARRYREVIEW0709-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hefty `Goblet' is refreshingly original brew
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There's more heft to this Harry, and not just in the
number of pages.
</P>
<P>
   Much has been made of the length of ``Harry Potter and the
Goblet of Fire,'' the fourth and _ at 734 pages _ by far the
longest volume so far in J.K. Rowling's phenomenally successful
series of children's novels about a young British wizard.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts worry that Rowling's youthful following will lose
interest in reading long before Harry wins or loses the Triwizard
Tournament somewhere past page 600.
</P>
<P>
   While that remains to be seen, several things are clear from
reading ``Goblet'': Rowling has enough imagination and skill to
keep a longer story interesting, and she's not afraid to let Harry
start growing up.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, none of the opening 157 pages takes place at Hogwarts
School of Witchcraft and Wizardry. That's a switch from the first
three Potters, and represents Rowling's successful effort to
broaden both Harry's and readers' exposure to a larger world.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the action eventually switches to Hogwarts, the plot
is deliciously convoluted and the cast of characters is as colorful
as ever. But there also are some very (dare we say it?) humanizing
complications for the now 14-year-old Harry.
</P>
<P>
   Flashes of jealousy between friends; unrequited crushes that
hurt just as badly even if you are a young wizard capable of
defeating the Dark Force; acne; even the death of someone way too
young and nice to die.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of paying attention to how much Rowling wrote, consider
how she's filled the space. By refusing to simply rework the same
ultra-successful formula (although there's still plenty about the
evil Lord Voldemort, without whom this would be ``Moby Dick''
without the whale), she's letting her character grow, right along
with her audience.
</P>
<P>
   Some may say it's sheer calculation _ there are still three more
Potters planned, after all.
</P>
<P>
   But for those of us already eager for Volume V, there's another
word for it: wizardry.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
