<DOCNO> NYT20000708.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6785 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-SEATURTLE0709-COX     07-08 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEATURTLE0709-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Following the journey of China Girl
 &HT;    By Michael Coren
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ They have been watching China Girl swim from
space.
</P>
<P>
   The leatherback sea turtle, the largest species in the sea,
leads an almost invisible life slipping from one ocean to another
in perfect anonymity _ until now.
</P>
<P>
   China Girl was the first leatherback in the Atlantic to carry a
satellite transmitter from the United States when she left the
beach of Archie Carr National Wildlife Refuge in Melbourne just
after midnight May 20.
</P>
<P>
   Her migratory path up the eastern seaboard to winter feeding
grounds off Nova Scotia is being tracked by scientists eager to
understand the world's least-studied sea turtle.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the grand experiment,'' said Dr. Duane De Freese, vice
president of Florida research at Hubbs-SeaWorld Research Institute
in Orlando. ``If we want to understand how this animal survives and
lives in the wild, we need to use every technological tool at our
disposal.''
</P>
<P>
   Desperate to stem the tide of leatherback deaths around the
world, researchers are using satellite telemetry and international
cooperation to uncover the secrets of an animal that spends only a
few hours of its 80-year life span on land.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't be held in captivity,'' said Scott Eckert, a
leatherback sea turtle researcher with Hubbs-SeaWorld Research
Institute in San Diego, who outfitted China Girl with her tracking
harness.
</P>
<P>
   Supremely adapted to the open ocean, ``leatherbacks have never
developed the capacity for boundaries'' and will kill themselves
against tank walls because they never stop swimming, Eckert said.
</P>
<P>
   Their instinctual wanderlust has placed them in the direct path
of the world's commercial fisherman. Efficient industrial trawlers
using gill nets and long lines have resulted in a huge catch of
leatherback sea turtles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Pacific population has dropped well in excess of 80
percent in the last 15 years,'' Eckert said of a population that
has dwindled to just a few thousand. The Atlantic population seems
to be ``holding its own'' between 20,000 and 30,000 animals, but
they are vulnerable from international commercial fisheries and at
isolated beaches critical to their reproductive success.
</P>
<P>
   Eckert hopes China Girl, named after the David Bowie song, will
shed some light on the animal's annual migration patterns and the
role these massive reptiles play in the Atlantic eco-system.
Understanding them may help prevent tragedies like the one that
occurred in north Florida last October.
</P>
<P>
   Large numbers of leatherback sea turtles began turning up in
shrimp trawlers' nets and more than 15 washed up dead on Florida
beaches before the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration
issued an emergency ban. Shrimp trawlers were required to use
larger turtle excluder devices to allow the massive leatherbacks to
escape drowning in the nets.
</P>
<P>
   A LACK OF UNDERSTANDING
</P>
<P>
   ``No fisherman wants to deal with a turtle as by-catch,'' said
De Freese. ``We need to work with the fishing industry as
scientists. If we know where they are migrating then we can avoid
those human and animal impacts.''
</P>
<P>
   Dean Bagley, a UCF research assistant at the Carr Refuge,
believed the deaths could have been avoided but ``we just don't
understand them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just trying to understand what's going on and (China
Girl) is the first step,'' said Bagley, who works with Dr.
Llewellyn Ehrhart, head of the UCF Marine Turtle Lab studying the
thousands of turtles that nest on the Archie Carr Refuge each year.
Most of those are loggerhead and green turtles but a handful of
leatherbacks lay nests there, including China Girl, who made eight
nests at the refuge this year.
</P>
<P>
   A joint effort has developed between Eckert in San Diego and
UCF's Ehrhart to track China Girl with Argos satellite receivers in
polar orbit for the next three months until the harness falls off.
Eckert is optimistic that China Girl will show up in Nova Scotia
this fall when he collaborates with Canadian scientists there to
tag leatherbacks on the open ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Eckert has tracked the sea turtles from Trinidad, St. Croix and
Costa Rica before China Girl become his most recent terrapin
interest. ``We have this pattern building,'' he said about the
picture emerging of the species's oceanic migrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``China Girl has been a pleasant surprise'' said Eckert, because
her movements have mirrored his prediction of a yearlong
circumnavigation of the Atlantic ocean. She is swimming up the
North American coast at about 40 kilometers a day and is expected
to reach her winter feeding grounds off Nova Scotia in early
August.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in the Caribbean Sea during early summer, leatherback
sea turtles usually move north through Florida's waters in summer
months before arriving at their northern Atlantic feeding grounds
in early fall. The leatherbacks time their movements to coincide
with emerging food sources, usually jellyfish, to satisfy their
voracious appetites.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may swim for two months and 3,000 miles for food,'' said
Eckert. ``I've seen them swim 12,000 kilometers in a single year.''
</P>
<P>
   `SOMETHING SPECIAL GOING ON'
</P>
<P>
   The turtles are expected to head toward the west coast of Africa
before cruising back to tropical waters in the Caribbean and South
America where they spend the spring and summer months.
</P>
<P>
   China Girl's journey has scientists excited about what new
knowledge she will bring to the science and conservation of the
world's largest sea turtle.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something going on there that's very special,'' De
Freese said of the research at the Archie Carr National Wildlife
Refuge. ``We're just scratching the surface.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
