<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6786 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-WIMBLEDON-MAIN0709-CO     07-08 1229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIMBLEDON-MAIN0709-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Venus makes history with Wimbledon victory
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Clarke
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ Her face beamed and her feet danced, and in
the moment of victory, the feet led her a dozen rows above Centre
Court to her sister and her father.
</P>
<P>
   There, Venus Williams embraced sister Serena and father Richard
for a long moment, celebrating the journey and the destination.
When she returned to the court, Venus Williams put her hand to her
heart, smiled and mouthed the words, ``It's mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Venus Ebone Starr Williams, a 20-year-old black woman raised on
the public courts of a tough Los Angeles neighborhood, won her
first Grand Slam title Saturday on the pristine grass courts of the
All England Club. She beat defending champion Lindsay Davenport
6-3, 7-6 (7-3).
</P>
<P>
   Williams, now a Palm Beach Gardens resident, became the first
black woman to win here since Althea Gibson did it in 1957 and
1958, feeling she'd broken a barrier that many would soon follow
her through.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really a privilege for me to win this Wimbledon while
she's still alive,'' Venus said. ``I appreciate how hard it was
(for her). You realize not everyone wants you to win, not
everyone's going to support you. And that's OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Family friend Zina Garrison, the last black Wimbledon finalist,
watched from the Friends' Box and was among the first to hug Venus
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking, 'This is unbelievable,' `` said Garrison,
runner-up in 1990. ``For Venus to finally do what Althea's wanted
to happen for so long. It's just amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   But for all the historical meaning, Venus and her family also
impressed with their celebration. The instant Davenport's forehand
volley hit the net on match point, Venus' long legs were flying in
a leaping dance. ``That's from my ballet classes,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her father, who had provided commentary throughout the match on
his dry-erase board, jumped onto the not-so-sturdy roof of the
broadcast booth to dance and show his newest thought: ``Venus'
party and no one was invited.''
</P>
<P>
   Serena, who had upset family harmony by winning the first Grand
Slam at last year's U.S. Open, grinned and clapped as her sister
started her climb into the stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wimbledon's certainly never seen a celebration like this,''
said John Roberts, longtime tennis writer for London's Daily
Telegraph.
</P>
<P>
   During the trophy presentation, Venus received a roaring
standing ovation as she was handed the aptly named Venus Rosewater
Dish. She held the plate above her head and hugged it to her chest,
doing a pirouette and bending as if the dish was too heavy, the
moment too incredible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to miss out on celebrations,'' Venus said during
an on-court speech to the crowd, a first at a tournament known for
polite fans and impeccable decorum. Fans adored Venus' heart-felt
answers to BBC interviewer Sue Barker's questions, including one
about her hopes to win here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll go to bed at night and I'll dream that I've won a Grand
Slam and when I wake up, it's a nightmare,'' she said. ``Now that
I've done it, I hope I don't have to wake up like that any more.''
</P>
<P>
   She shouldn't have to. As the fifth seed, she defeated Davenport
convincingly and became the lowest seed to win since 1962. The
second seed didn't play her best, but after a nervous start, Venus
rapidly won the first set.
</P>
<P>
   In the second, both players' serves faltered allowing eight
service breaks total. Venus still had a chance to win the match
serving at 5-4, but she wasn't ``calm'' and hit two doublefaults
and lost the game.
</P>
<P>
   The tiebreaker could have been turned the match for Davenport,
but a few unforced errors and a service winner gave Venus a 5-1
lead. She hit a serve return in the net on her first match point
before winning on her second.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a few points that I'd love to take back,'' said
Davenport, who has battled recent back and thigh injuries. ``But a
lot of that was caused by her. She was hitting the balls a lot
deeper than I was and that didn't give me the chance to hit the
shots I wanted to hit and sometimes forced me into going for a
little bit too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Many consider this Wimbledon a breakthrough for both Venus and
her sister. Each now has a major title. Both are improving their
games, serving better, moving better and harnessing their power
more effectively.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport, although disappointed, admitted it was nice to see
Venus win, especially when critics wondered if she would ever win
one after Serena won the U.S. Open while Venus watched sullenly.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't help but feel a little bit sorry for her last
fall when Serena won the first one,'' Davenport said. ``You knew
eventually she was going to win a Grand Slam. It's nice to see the
monkey get off her back.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a fascinating fortnight for Britain with the Williams
sisters plowing through the draw. Serena looked unbeatable until
she met her sister. Richard became an overnight celebrity by
declaring his love for Wimbledon and the British, by walking from
their rented home to the club every day, by giving away tickets and
conducting interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Venus, meanwhile, steadily progressed through the tournament to
set up the sisters' first meeting in a Grand Slam semifinal. Fans
learned the Williams' story from every angle and yearned for a good
tennis match.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't happen, but they saw an emotional side of both
players, as Serena suffered with the loss and Venus helped her
through it. Venus had already defeated the No. 1 player and top
seed in Martina Hingis.
</P>
<P>
   Defeating No. 8 Serena meant she still had to beat the
second-ranked player in the world. That she beat all those players
makes this win even more meaningful, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, NBC commentator Chris Evert pointed out that she had
held a version of this trophy before. Venus and Serena visited
Evert's Boca Raton home about 10 years ago specifically to see her
three Wimbledon trophies, which are replicas of the one Venus held
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But Venus said she dreamed about winning any Grand Slam, not
just Wimbledon. That is, until about a week before the tournament
when she decided to shop for a gown for tonight's Champions Ball.
</P>
<P>
   She and Serena went to the mall, but Venus went on a budget
because she'd lost in the quarterfinals of the French Open. She
didn't have much time, but she picked out a beaded dress that
needed some repairs. It was ready the day they flew to London.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bought my gown before I came here because I was determined
to get this,'' she said. ``I had to make a promise to myself, so I
bought the dress.''
</P>
<P>
   Her promise, of course, was that she would win it. Gibson and
Garrison, no doubt, can't wait to see a picture, both for Venus'
sake and for history's sake.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great that Serena won the U.S. Open, but this is the
biggest tournament in the world,'' Garrison said. ``It's the Super
Bowl of our sport and for it finally to happen, that's history.''
</P>
<P>
   (salinity)elizabethclarke(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Some of the signs
</P>
<P>
   Hello Mrs. Williams I love you and miss you
</P>
<P>
   British fans are the best fans in the world
</P>
<P>
   I need an ice cold Coca-Cola
</P>
<P>
   The rain delay will give you more time to get here
</P>
<P>
   I love you wife
</P>
<P>
   --30--
</P>
