<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-WESTERN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN WESTERN OPEN, WOODS STRUGGLES SIX SHOTS BACK 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEMONT, Ill. _ Steve Flesch and Brian Henninger liked their
positions, but Tiger Woods did not like his. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After Saturday's third round of the Advil Western Open, Woods,
the world's No. 1 player, was missing from a tightly bunched leader
board. It will take a comeback of major proportions for Woods, the
defending champion, to win at Cog Hill Golf and Country Club for
the third time in four years. Plagued by putting problems, Woods
was six strokes off the lead, tied for 23rd place and clearly not
playing his best.
</P>
<P>
   So, if Woods does not win, who will?
</P>
<P>
   That question remained wide open heading into a final round that
will be highly competitive and unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
   Flesch had three bogeys on his last seven holes and shot a 68
and Henninger bogeyed the 18th hole to finish his third-round
70.They shared the lead at 13 under par (203), but 16 players were
bunched between 13 under and 9 under. Lee Janzen, a two-time U.S.
Open winner, was alone in third place at 204 after a six-under 66.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Price, Jim Furyk and Kenny Perry were tied at 11 under par.
Robert Allenby and Shigeki Maruyama were 10 under, while eight
players were at nine under _ Stephen Ames, Stuart Appleby, Mike
Brisky, Bill Glasson, Steve Lowery, Carl Paulson, David Toms and
Mark Wiebe.
</P>
<P>
   With Woods struggling, by his standards, the contenders sensed
an opportunity to capitalize.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants to win,'' said Janzen, who has won just once,
at the 1998 U.S. Open, in the last five years. ``It seems like
we're playing for fewer spots the way Tiger has played. Maybe
that's why guys are playing better this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can play aggressively tomorrow, even with mistakes, I'd
be happy with the same score. If you're going to keep up, you have
to make birdies. So you might as well fire at the pin.''
</P>
<P>
   Three players equaled the course record (63) during the first
two rounds, but the greens were firmer today, and scoring became
more difficult. Perry shot 68, Furyk shot 69, and Price shot 70.
Meanwhile, several players hurt themselves with poor rounds, like
Fred Couples (73) and Franklin Langham (74), who were tied at 208.
</P>
<P>
   As for Woods, he shot a third-round 70 that was unusually
inconsistent. Woods bogeyed two par-5 holes Saturday _ No. 9 and
No. 15, and he continued to miss putts that prevented him from
building momentum. Afterward he said he was frustrated about his
inability to make putts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need a seeing-eye dog out there,'' said Woods, playing his
last tournament before the British Open later this month. ``I'm
putting so bad, it's a joke. I need to play well tomorrow, at
least, so going to the British I have something to take away from
this tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I play well, I have a chance of winning. If I don't play
well, I'm so far behind, I have no chance.''
</P>
<P>
   While the huge gallery following Woods did not have much to
cheer about, there was plenty of action around the course.
</P>
<P>
   Flesch, 33, a left-hander looking for his first PGA Tour
victory, stormed into the picture with an eagle at No. 5, which
moved him to 10 under par.
</P>
<P>
   Flesch is often called the best player on tour who has never
won. He has eight top-10 finishes this year, tied for third on tour
behind Woods (10) and Jesper Parnevik (9). Sunday could finally be
Flesch's turn to break through, and he ended the day on a high
note, when his 12-foot birdie putt at No. 18 hung on the lip for
three seconds, then fell into the cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm ready to win, but I can't force it,'' Flesch said.
``I didn't really hit the ball that well today, but I was able to
shoot a good score. Usually in every tournament, you have at least
one day when you don't hit the ball that well. So I was happy to
get through today.''
</P>
<P>
   With so many players in contention, the leaders will spend as
much time reading the scoreboard Sunday as they will reading putts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody's going to break out of the pack and throw up a good
score, and the other guys are going to have to chase him,'' Furyk
said. ``I'm going to have to shoot at least 66 if I want a chance
to win this tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   So unlike the U.S. Open last month, where Woods was the lone
player to finish under par, Sunday's final round will bring out the
birdies.
</P>
<P>
   It was nearly impossible to predict a winner. But at least
nobody would win by 15 strokes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a shootout, which everyone wants, I
suppose,'' Price said. ``Nobody's going to run away with this
one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
