A6796 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBO-BASEBALL-COLUMN-L     07-08 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BASEBALL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRIFFEY'S SEASON IS NO HIGHLIGHTS FILM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ken Griffey Jr. one day will break Mark McGwire's all-time home
run record (after McGwire breaks Hank Aaron's mark.)
</P>
<P>
   But Griffey's star status is quickly losing its luster.
</P>
<P>
   It is becoming more and more apparent that Griffey is overly
sensitive and lacking self-confidence. Yes, one of the best players
in the game and eventually one of the best players ever seems to
have an ego problem, at least when it comes to the media portrayal
of his image.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey doesn't do interviews with ESPN because he believes they
make him look bad. He seems to be jealous of Cardinals center
fielder Jim Edmonds, which goes back to when Griffey played for the
Seattle Mariners and Edmonds for the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   If reporters asked Griffey about Edmonds - like when Edmonds
made that spectacular catch in Kansas City a few years ago -
Griffey would be curt. He seems to think ESPN shows Edmonds' great
catches, but not his. And as a result, the only reporter from ESPN
Griffey will talk to is Harold Reynolds, a former teammate of
Griffey's.
</P>
<P>
   And even then it is not for an interview, but simply small talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only conversations I have had with Harold, I said they
show me mess up and then show somebody making a great catch right
after that,'' Griffey told the Associated Press. ``That's been
going on for years, that's the way it's always been.''
</P>
<P>
   So when Griffey sat out an ESPN-televised game a few days ago -
against Edmonds' Cardinals no less - rumors surfaced that Griffey
was boycotting the cable network. But Griffey said there was no
boycott, that he had a stomachache and a headache. (Wonder what Cal
Ripken thinks.).
</P>
<P>
   Well, at least Griffey helps his team on the field, right? At
least he'll get past his insecurities off the field and carry his
team on it, right?
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey's former team and present team are headed in opposite
directions. And the numbers don't look good for Griffey.
</P>
<P>
   Through Friday, the Mariners were 49-35, their best start in
club history, and leading the AL West. The Reds, after winning 96
games last season before adding Griffey, were 42-43 and eight games
out in the NL Central.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners clubhouse, sans Griffey, is one big happy family.
The Reds clubhouse is a dysfunctional family.
</P>
<P>
   ``For whatever reason, things are going great here and not in
Cincinnati,'' Mariners right fielder Jay Buhner said, careful not
to blame Griffey. ``There's a different hero here every game.
What's going on with Junior, I couldn't tell you. It's time to turn
the page.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey is hitting his home runs (26, fourth in the NL, through
Friday), but is batting just .232. He was voted by the fans to
start the All-Star Game, but in a poll of the players by Baseball
Weekly magazine, Edmonds was the choice.
</P>
<P>
   Still, his offensive production over the years has been
impressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Junior? Forty-five to 50 homers, 100-whatever RBI? All of a
sudden, somebody has to pick it up,'' Mariners manager Lou Piniella
said of his team without Griffey. ``Edgar (Martinez) and Alex
(Rodriguez) have done a great job.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you lose a guy like him, it's hard to replace,''
Buhner said. ``But right now we've got two guys creaming the
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   And 25 guys who like being around each other. There was talk
that the Mariners clubhouse wasn't big enough for Rodriguez and
Griffey. But it's Rodriguez's team now, if he wants it. There is
growing speculation that the Mariners' success this season might
persuade Rodriguez to consider re-signing with Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just a great group of guys in here, nice leadership,''
Buhner said. ``The communication is great, and (Piniella) has been
a joy to play for. I think this year has rejuvenated him a little
bit. He keeps guys loose and laughing.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's probably helped Piniella that he has one less daily
duty. No more baby-sitting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
