<P>
   VICKI _ (KANSAS CITY, Mo.) Vicki knew him as J.R. Those were the
initials she expected John E. Robinson Sr. to burn into her hip if
she moved to Kansas to be his slave. She could have put up with the
branding, she said. And promises of a greenhouse job, and perhaps
even a horse on his farm sounded tempting. But something about
Robinson made her hesitate. ``I can't believe how close I came to
moving down there,'' Vicki said last week in a telephone interview
from her home in Ontario, Canada. ``It scares me to death.''
Robinson was charged in June with capital murder in the deaths of
five women whose bodies were found in barrels. Authorities also
have linked him to three women and a baby who disappeared in the
1980s. By DIANE CARROLL. Story will move in the ``a'' category.
</P>
<P>
   SURGERY _ (COLUMBIA, Mo.) A few minutes before beginning surgery
on 3-month-old Elizabeth Quigley, neurosurgeon David Jimenez
cradled the smiling baby in his arms and paraded her around the
waiting room, proudly showing her off. The affection with which
Jimenez and his wife, plastic surgeon Constance Barone, treat their
little patients has won them fans among families throughout the
country who seek treatment for craniosynostosis at the University
of Missouri-Columbia Hospital and Clinics. By LYNN FRANEY. Story
will move in the ``a'' category.
</P>
<P>
   DOWNTOWN _ (KANSAS CITY, Mo.) What should be done about downtown
Kansas City? It's an eternal quandary, and in recent years
different solutions have gone in and out of vogue. One day, a
sports arena is seen as the key. Another day, it's light-rail
transit. Or an entertainment complex. Nothing sticks, nothing gets
widespread support. Now there may be a clear-cut favorite: more
housing, something that could bring life to the streets. By JEFFREY
SPIVAK and MARK P. COUCH. Story will move in the ``a'' category.
</P>
