u s BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-MEN-BOS     07-08 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-MEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACHY SAMPRAS BRACES FOR IMMORTALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ One to go to go to 1.
</P>
<P>
   That equation will yield immortality for Pete Sampras Sunday.
Unless Patrick Rafter can come up with a different solution.
</P>
<P>
   The Australian with the samurai hairdo and surgically repaired
serving shoulder represents the doorstop to heaven for Sampras, who
is one victory away from two platinum records.
</P>
<P>
   Should his nagging back and ailing left leg allow him to hobble
past Rafter on Centre Court at the All England Lawn Tennis &AMP;
Croquet Club, Sampras will join Willie Renshaw atop the annals for
Wimbledon men's singles titles (7) and surpass the standard he
shares with Australian Roy Emerson for most Grand Slam keepsakes
(13).
</P>
<P>
   Despite the technicality of a tie, Sampras will reign as the de
facto supreme male at Wimbledon because Renshaw accomplished his
feat during the antediluvian days of the 19th century, when the
tournament was an entirely different _ and easier _ proposition.
The Grand Slam standard is another matter. Critics will carp that
Sampras has achieved ultimate success in only three of the four
major events _ Wimbledon, the Australian Open (2), and the US Open
(4) _ and that he has been a clay pigeon in the French Open. True,
but Emerson's record is not unsullied, either. He pocketed most of
his Grand Slams while adversaries such as Rod Laver and Ken
Rosewall were exiles on the professional circuit before tennis
became open to all in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, Sampras has had a rose-petal path to the final,
facing not a single seed. On the other, he has been forced to cope
with self-generated roadblocks _ the pulled back muscle he suffered
while hitting with Tim Henman before the tournament and the
tendinitis in his lower left leg that developed just before his
four-set second-round struggle against Karol Kucera.
</P>
<P>
   Since the latter discomfort arose, Sampras has not even touched
a racket between matches, although he tried a light workout
Saturday. And during matches, he has been receiving treatment from
ATP Tour trainer Doug Spreen, right up through his 7-6 (7-4), 6-2,
6-4 eviction of qualifier Vladimir Voltchkov in Friday's semfinals.
He figures he has one mighty effort left in him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at Wimbledon, you look at how important it is to me,
to my career,'' he said, ``you just have to play through whatever
you have to play through.''
</P>
<P>
   He insists he won't be carrying Renshaw and Emerson on his
shoulders Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not looking at (Sunday) as pressure,'' he said. ``I'm
looking at it as an opportunity. I'd love to break it here. If not,
I have nothing to be ashamed of for what I've done these past
couple weeks. If it doesn't happen here, maybe in New York (at the
US Open), maybe next year, maybe in two years. I'm looking at it as
a great moment for tennis, a great moment for me.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the greatest moment for Rafter, who has the ideal
serve-and-volley game for grass, though perhaps not the body for
it.
</P>
<P>
   Twice the US Open champion, he was ranked No. 1 in the world
midway through 1999 but wrecked his right shoulder in the first
round of the Open against Cedric Pioline, which curtailed his
defense and required rotator cuff surgery Oct. 24. His world
ranking plummeted to 21st, and there was grumbling that he didn't
deserve even the lowly seeding (12) he was awarded here.
</P>
<P>
   But Rafter won a grass-court warmup in the Netherlands before
Wimbledon, and once here, generally far removed from center stage,
he gradually fine-tuned his game before he upset world No. 1 and
Wimbledon No. 2 Andre Agassi with a heroic 7-5, 4-6, 7-5, 4-6, 6-3
semifinal victory that reversed last year's result in this
confrontation and provided 3 hours 18 minutes of incandescent
tennis.
</P>
<P>
   While he's no Grand Slam novice, Rafter figures there's nothing
quite like a Wimbledon final.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been here many times before,'' said Rafter. ``It's my
first one here at Wimbledon. I've just got to go out there with the
same attitude I went out on the court (Friday) _ be relaxed.''
</P>
<P>
   And the game plan that worked masterfully against Agassi? Forget
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Against) Andre, you have to serve well,'' said Rafter. ``I
knew I had to go out there and serve very big. Against Pete, it's
pretty well a reversal. You've got to try to get his serve back
somehow, and he's going to be serve-volleying. You've really got to
take your chances. There will be no baseline rallies. I won't be
able to chip-charge.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras, the Californian who keeps his charisma in a closet,
knows Rafter represents his most formidable challenge by far.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's playing great,'' said Sampras. ``He's a great athlete,
volleys well, covers the net as well as anyone in the world. It
really comes down to how well I return against him. He's coming in
on his first final, I'm sure, very pumped up. I'm sure we'll both
walk out there a bit nervous. It should be exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sampras contends that it won't be distracting, that tunnel
vision blocks his view of history.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the moment, I'm not thinking about it at all,'' he said.
``It's the match at hand. When you're competing, you're kind of on
the inside, not looking on the outside. I'm sure two weeks from
now, a month from now, 10 years from now, I can appreciate my
career much more than (Sunday). But my legacy is really the last
thing on my mind. It's really preparing and doing whatever I can to
possibly win here.''
</P>
<P>
   And for the ages, by the way.
</P>
</TEXT>
