<HEADLINE>
`SLAVE' RECOUNTS HER LONG-DISTANCE RELATIONSHIP WITH JOHN E.
ROBINSON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE CARROLL  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Vicki knew him as
J.R.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Those were the initials she expected John E. Robinson Sr. to
burn into her hip if she moved to Kansas to be his slave.
</P>
<P>
   She could have put up with the branding, she said. And promises
of a greenhouse job, and perhaps even a horse on his farm sounded
tempting. But something about Robinson made her hesitate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe how close I came to moving down there,'' Vicki
said last week in a telephone interview from her home in Ontario,
Canada. ``It scares me to death.''
</P>
<P>
   The 43-year-old woman said she felt sick when she recently
learned about the charges against Robinson. She asked that her last
name not be used to protect her family.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson was charged in June with capital murder in the deaths
of five women whose bodies were found in barrels. Authorities also
have linked him to three women and a baby who disappeared in the
1980s.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the 56-year-old Olathe, Kan., man has been charged
with sexually assaulting two women he met through the Internet. The
women met with Robinson this spring at Overland Park, Kan., and
Lenexa, Kan., hotels for sadomasochistic encounters, authorities
say.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki said she carried on a six-month e-mail and telephone
relationship with Robinson that began in October 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Although they never met, she considered herself his slave most
of that time. If he had been willing to meet her in advance _ she
once suggested they get together in Chicago _ there is a good
chance she would have moved to Kansas to live with him, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki said her personal ad for a master had been on a Web site
for a couple of weeks when Robinson responded.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he usually didn't answer ads like this, but this one
caught his attention,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She was looking for someone who was older, mature, caring,
financially secure and experienced. He seemed to meet the criteria,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   They began exchanging long e-mails.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd tell me about his family. I think he told me his daughter
just had a baby. ... He said he was divorced. (He is married.) ...
He told me where I'd be living with him on the farm.'' (He owns
16.5 acres in Linn County, Kan., but lived in a mobile home
community in Olathe.)
</P>
<P>
   He also told her he had five businesses, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The one that stuck in her mind, that really attracted her to
him, was a hydroponic operation. (In the 1980s, Robinson had a
hydroponic business called Hydro-Gro Inc. A booklet he published
featured water-based home gardening products.)
</P>
<P>
   Robinson told Vicki he hired people who were developmentally
challenged to work in the greenhouses.
</P>
<P>
   ``He probably told me that after I introduced myself because
that's what I do for a living,'' she said. ``I work in a group home
for the handicapped. I've done that for 12 years. I thought, `This
is just great. Anyone who hires these people has to have a great
heart.' ''
</P>
<P>
   He told her she could work in the greenhouse supervising the
employees, she said. She had been looking for a job in the States.
His offer was appealing.
</P>
<P>
   She said they never discussed salary. It wasn't an issue in her
mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being his slave, I wouldn't make any money,'' she said. ``It
would be his money.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, a convicted swindler, never asked her about her
finances, she said. They never talked about a master-slave
contract, either. In some of those pacts, the slave signs over
control of his or her finances to the master.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki said Robinson's interest in horses also interested her. He
said he used to have horses.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time I met him I was learning how to care for horses,''
she said. ``I was working on a horse farm grooming them and
learning how to ride, and I was enjoying it. He was considering
getting another horse or two if I moved down there.''
</P>
<P>
   Vicki said Robinson also told her that he had spent almost 10
years living with a young woman. He had paid for her college
education, he said, and she had just graduated when she was killed
in a traffic accident. He didn't want to provide details, he said,
because talking about it upset him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt really sorry for him,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki said she does not think of herself as naive.
</P>
<P>
   Besides working part time in the group home, she runs a business
practicing reflexology, a natural healing art based on the belief
that the application of pressure to specific points on the body
benefits other parts of the body.
</P>
<P>
   She has organized luncheon meetings in her area for people
interested in learning about the bondage-discipline-sadomasochism
lifestyle. And she thinks she has been appropriately leery of
potential partners.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, she trusted Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believed him. I don't know why, but I did,'' she said. ``He
was a very smooth talker, and the picture he sent _ he looked very
respectable: black shirt, pants, boots, glasses. He had his foot up
on a fence post. Just very nice. He had a receding hairline.'' (
MORE )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
