<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-DONATO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DONATO ONE DUCK WHO WILL PONDER FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don Sweeney made no bones about the fact that although he wanted
to test the waters of unrestricted free agency, he didn't want to
swim for too long. After two days and several offers, he re-upped
with the Bruins last week.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Donato, a former teammate of Sweeney's here, said his foray
into the unrestricted experience likely will last quite a bit
longer. Donato, who was traded to the Islanders for Ken Belanger
Nov. 7, 1998, spent last year with the Anaheim Mighty Ducks,
registering 30 points _ 11 goals _ in 81 games.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible he could be back in a Ducks uniform. It seems an
equal possibility he could be somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had some talks and inquiries and some dialogue,'' said
Donato, reached at his South Shore home, ``but nothing that is
solid. We have some ideas and some positive things to look at but
nothing is imminent.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a bittersweet season in the land of Disney. Donato, who
saw second-line duty with Matt Cullen and Marty McInnis before Kip
Miller took McInnis's spot for the final third of the season, also
logged time on the power play and penalty kill. Donato feels he has
unfinished business in Anaheim. Donato said he spoke to the Ducks
before becoming a free agent and will likely talk to them again
before making a decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good spot and a good organization,'' said Donato, who
turned 31 in April. ``I was disappointed we didn't make the
playoffs because I thought we had a team that was capable.
Production-wise, I could have and should have given more. When I
talk of unfinished business, I would like to prove a little bit
more out there. I still have a lot of confidence that I can be a
productive player in both ends of the rink and score some goals. In
general, my whole career I've always felt that I have something to
prove and this year was no different. I think the coaching staff
and all the players were disappointed and bitter at the end because
we were really trying to make a playoff run. We all felt we had
something left on the table.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem with the Ducks was simple _ not enough offense after
Paul Kariya and Teemu Selanne. Shut them down, the philosophy was,
and you shut down the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed to somehow produce a second wave of scoring to
eliminate being able to shut down Kariya and Selanne,'' he said.
``I think that's a problem a lot of teams have, trying to get a
second wave or enough scoring so other teams don't focus completely
on the stars.''
</P>
<P>
   Donato wants a fair salary, an opportunity to play for a
contending team, and a chance to play an important role.
</P>
<P>
   ``The competitor in me thinks that wherever I go, that will
happen,'' said Donato. ``Whether it happens easy or happens hard,
whether it takes some work to get where I want to get, that will
take care of itself as long as I do the things I'm capable of
doing. It's an anxious time but inevitably it will come down to the
pressure to perform. I'm really looking forward to the season.''
</P>
<P>
   He keeps an eye on the transaction wire, knowing a few changes
in personnel here or there could impact his chances of signing with
a particular club. He said research will help him make an educated
decision about what's best for him, his wife, and three young sons.
It's likely it will take a good part, if not all, of the summer to
sort out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, you would like to get it done as soon as possible
because it's nice to know where you're going,'' he said. ``Having
said that, I've prepared myself mentally to wait for as long as it
takes. It's unfortunate that I can't really name the time when it
gets done but when it's ready, I'll be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Keeping an eye on Heinze
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Donato, of all people, can sympathize most with former
Bruin Steve Heinze, who was taken by Columbus in last month's
expansion draft. Donato had a hard time under Bruins coach Pat
Burns and asked to be moved. Heinze had a nightmarish 1999-00
season before being asked to be exposed in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I'm a little biased but I think he'll do well in
Columbus,'' said Donato. ``He's proven over his career that he can
score goals. I think, for whatever reason, the change will do him
good. I know he's excited about it. It definitely has the makings
of a chance to revitalize his situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing a pro sport in your home city can be a blessing and a
curse. Donato viewed his time with the Bruins as a great gift but
said he can also see where it can be a burden.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoyed my time here immensely, I wouldn't trade it for the
world,'' he said. ``There's a certain aura about being a Boston
Bruin. It was a dream come true. If you're looking for how it could
be tough for a guy from this area, for the same reason it's great
to play here _ you have relationships you have built your entire
life from people who fill your gas tank to people you knew in grade
school. As much as it's great to have them around, when things
don't go as well, it can be a burden. The pressure can weigh a
little heavier because if you're in another city you don't run into
all those people you know and you focus a little easier. Now,
(Heinze will) have a fresh start. The other thing that's probably
better is that everybody is new and starting out with a new
organization. I think that's probably a good situation for him.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   King rules the bench
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the Blue Jackets, the team hired former Canadian
national and Calgary Flames coach Dave King to take the helm for
the inaugural season. The 52-year-old King, who signed a three-year
deal, knows he faces an uphill climb. ``We're going to be a young
team, a team that has to play above our heads to compete every
night,'' said King. President and general manager Doug MacLean, who
narrowed his field of candidates to King, former Bruins coach Brian
Sutter, and Avalanche assistant Bryan Trottier, said he thought
King was the right man for the job partly because of his patience
with young players. ``That's a really important thing,'' said
MacLean. ``You have to have a person who can handle the tough
times.'' . . . Swedish 19-year-old identical twins Henrik and
Daniel Sedin, who are sensations in their homeland, arrived in
Vancouver to attend a development camp and are expected to play for
the Canucks this season. The club assigned No. 22 to left wing
Daniel and No. 33 to center Henrik. Daniel was taken second overall
in the 1999 draft and Henrik was picked third. The twins, who have
bulked up to about 200 pounds on their just over 6-foot frames,
believe they're ready to make the jump to the NHL. ``They got mixed
reviews at the World Championships, I'm very aware of that,'' said
Vancouver GM Brian Burke. ``I'm very content that they have
progressed. I think they're ready to play in the NHL. The attention
paid to them (in Sweden) was amazing. They were almost mugged every
night when they played on the road and the other team got the last
change. I've never seen two players checked like that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Back for seconds
</P>
<P>
   Imagine Mathieu Chouinard's surprise on draft day. The
20-year-old figured he'd seen the last of the Ottawa Senators since
he had been drafted by that club in 1998, but couldn't reach
contract terms, resulting in his name going back into the pool. In
the second round, the Senators were up at No. 45 and they once
again selected Chouinard. This time, though, they were able to
reach a deal. ``I know (the Senators) redrafted me because they saw
something in me,'' said the goalie, who played in the Quebec Major
Junior League the last four years. ``Now I want to prove that they
made the right choice.'' . . . Guy Carbonneau, 40, announced his
retirement after 18 years. The three-time Selke Trophy winner was
told that if he wanted it, he had a job in the Dallas Stars
organization, where he played the last five years of his career.
However, Carbonneau has also interviewed with the Montreal
Canadiens, for whom he played 12-plus years . . . Much has been
made about the uncertain future of Philadelphia center Eric Lindros
because of his history with concussions. But Edmonton's Boyd
Devereaux, after only two concussions, appears to be all done at
only 22. Devereaux was felled by a Dallas Drake hit and although he
is symptom-free, James Kelly _ the same doctor who is monitoring
Lindros _ told him he should retire. According to Kelly, Devereaux
faces permanent injury if he continues playing. Devereaux has
decided to seek other medical opinions. ``It's not like we're going
to 30 doctors until we find one that says I'm OK,'' said Devereaux.
``It's just a matter of getting as much information as we can.
That's all I can do. Ultimately, I just have to be as informed and
educated as possible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
