<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWNTOWN-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSING EMERGES AS DOWNTOWN REDEVELOPMENT PRIORITY IN KANSAS CITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFFREY SPIVAK and MARK P. COUCH  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ What should we do
about downtown?
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's an eternal Kansas City quandary, and in recent years
different solutions have gone in and out of vogue. One day, a
sports arena is seen as the key. Another day, it's light-rail
transit. Or an entertainment complex. Nothing sticks, nothing gets
widespread support.
</P>
<P>
   Now there may be a clear-cut favorite: more housing, something
that could bring life to the streets.
</P>
<P>
   With the business community's Civic Council of Greater Kansas
City stepping forward and promising to back some kind of project
for downtown, The Kansas City Star tried to gauge which way
prominent downtowners might be leaning. So the paper recently asked
business leaders _ corporate chiefs, top lawyers and real estate
specialists, among others _ to name their downtown priority from
among six long-discussed ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Of almost three dozen respondents, 60 percent made housing their
preference. It was such an overwhelming choice that it beat the
next most-popular alternatives by a 4-to-1 ratio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Residential is probably the most sensible,'' said one of the
respondents, Thomas McDonnell. He is president of DST Systems Inc.
and chairman of the Civic Council, a group of top executives who
work behind the scenes on community and political causes. ``There's
a growing sense that you need residential to support a different
urban core, a more vibrant area.''
</P>
<P>
   Housing emerged as the dominant choice for a couple of reasons.
First, roomy lofts are flourishing, so they're a success upon which
downtown can build. Second, more residents downtown may lure more
entertainment, shops and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   The consensus The Star found _ if it presages what the Civic
Council eventually finds _ could add a twist to public spending
decisions about the Power &AMP; Light entertainment district, which
includes a housing component, or rail transit.
</P>
<P>
   A housing renaissance is, in fact, sweeping through downtowns
across the country. Still, those who track this trend say one thing
separating cities that concentrate on downtown housing from those
where it just pops up sporadically is a commitment.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown projects ranked
</P>
<P>
   Every so often, Kansas City chases a different downtown cure.
Two decades ago, it was cleaning up 12th Street for a new hotel.
Fifteen years ago, it was adding shops at the base of skyscrapers.
One decade ago, it was expanding the convention center. Lately,
it's been joining the urban entertainment trend with Science City
and Power &AMP; Light.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those approaches worked, but only in limited ways.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the corridor between the River Market and Crown Center is
alternately hot and in a state of rot. There are art galleries
moving in, lofts being developed and DST Systems building offices
on the west end. And there are vacant buildings pockmarking the
loop, derelicts roaming the streets and few signs of life at night.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps fed up with this haphazard pattern, the Civic Council
announced it would hire a downtown-oriented consultant. For the
next year, the consultant won't tell Kansas City what to do, but
instead interview various downtown interests and determine what
they want to do.
</P>
<P>
   The result could be one or more preferred projects and a map of
where to locate such projects in the downtown corridor.
</P>
<P>
   Shopping mall developer Paul Copaken, who heads the Civic
Council urban core committee spearheading the study, told The
Star's editorial board recently that any resulting project would be
a ``public-private venture,'' meaning the business community
intends to work with the city government.
</P>
<P>
   As a way of sticking a finger in the winds of downtown, The Star
conducted an informal survey of influential businessmen and
businesswomen located downtown. They included executives such as
Irvine O. Hockaday Jr. and Sandra Lawrence, bankers such as Bill
Nelson and Grant Burcham, developers such as Whitney Kerr and Roger
Buford, architects such as Becky Zahner and Rafael Garcia, plus
civic-minded voices such as Clara Reyes and Bill Hall.
</P>
<P>
   All were asked their priority from among six long-proposed
ideas: sports arena, baseball stadium, aquarium, housing,
entertainment (movie//shopping) complex and rail transit. This list
didn't include a performing arts center because that's already
under way.
</P>
<P>
   Housing was named in 21 of the 34 votes _ more than the other
alternatives combined. The nearest contenders were the arena and
light rail, with five votes each.
</P>
<P>
   Those for housing came from myriad backgrounds. Some have
seemingly contrary interests. Restaurateur Rod Anderson, for
instance, is past chairman of the Convention and Visitors Bureau of
Greater Kansas City. Terry Dunn, president of J.E. Dunn
Construction Co., generally builds other things. Lawyer John Edgar,
as chairman of the city's Economic Development Corp., pursues
big-ticket projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we develop a critical mass, you're going to get retail and
entertainment driving off that,'' said Edgar, lead resident partner
of the Bryan Cave law firm and another member of the Civic
Council's urban core committee.
</P>
<P>
   Hallmark Cards Inc. President Hockaday added: ``If you simply
have a series of attractions _ tourist attractions and convention
center _ you haven't really built a comprehensive community. To do
that, you need residential, you need people.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the other alternatives, business leaders saw little need
for an arena without
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
