<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6814 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-LONGSHOT     07-08 2430
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-LONGSHOT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CROWN DOESN'T APPEAR A FIT FOR PATRIOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Preseason publications can make you dizzy. The predictions:
Second, third, fifth place. The adjectives: Competitive.
Laughingstock. Mediocre. Long shot.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder Las Vegas oddsmakers have projected the Patriots for
eight wins. Who can tell? One thing is for sure _ nobody is
crowning the 2000 Patriots NFL champions. And with good reason.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' offseason splash was hiring Bill Belichick as
coach. Their big roster moves were re-signing safety Lawyer Milloy
and wide receiver Troy Brown. New blood includes Arizona State
running back J.R. Redmond, cornerback Antonio Langham, running back
Raymont Harris, guard Lance Scott, tackle Grant Williams, and tight
end Eric Bjornson. It's not enough to make you want to fly to Vegas
to bet the over. Those wearing rose-colored glasses can point to a
healthy Ted Johnson, a happy Milloy, a rebounding Ty Law, a new
defensive scheme that should enhance the pass rushing of Willie
McGinest and Chris Slade, and a new offense that should supply Drew
Bledsoe the comfort level he had in his first four years.
</P>
<P>
   With training camp getting underway July 17, the Patriots need
the following to contend for a divisional title or wild-card spot:
</P>
<P>
   1. Redmond must be the real deal.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't a good start for the third-round pick to undergo
surgery to repair an inflamed tendon in his groin. He's expected
back by mid-camp. Redmond must be a 1,200-yard rusher, a 30-plus
pass receiver, and a breakaway threat every time he touches the
ball. The Patriots have gone 15 years without gaining 4 yards per
carry for a season. This must stop, at least for Bledsoe's sake.
</P>
<P>
   2. Offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Bruce Armstrong isn't the most ideal solution, but he's
the best the Patriots can do. Making him beg for a contract isn't
becoming for a team that allegedly wants him back. Give him a fair
deal and let him play left tackle while helping groom top pick
Adrian Klemm, who is out with a torn lateral collateral ligament in
his left knee. The line will be tested and there's no room for
failure. Starting right guard Todd Rucci (knee) is sidelined for
training camp. Williams may wind up at right tackle for the
departed Zefross Moss, and whether that's an upgrade remains to be
seen.
</P>
<P>
   3. Defensive line.
</P>
<P>
   Another area in which the Patriots were curiously quiet in the
offseason, signing and then dumping journeyman end Jon Harris. The
team never made an offer to Chris Sullivan, who might have been a
good fit in this system. Between now and the start of the season
they will likely sign another journeyman for depth. They are hoping
Garrett Johnson, who played well as a full-timer in Barcelona, can
provide muscle behind tackles Chad Eaton and Henry Thomas. They
also hope Brandon Mitchell begins to blossom, and McGinest
continues to be healthy.
</P>
<P>
   4. Defensive back.
</P>
<P>
   Pro Bowlers Law and Milloy are impressive, but the Patriots have
real concerns in the remainder of the secondary. Tebucky Jones,
Langham, and Kato Serwanga will duke it out at right corner (also
watch for Otis Smith if the Jets release him). Free safety is also
a battle between incumbent Chris Carter, veteran Larry Whigham, and
hard-hitting second-year player Tony George.
</P>
<P>
   A look at the other AFC East teams:
</P>
<P>
   Colts: The consensus team to beat, but the biggest fear I would
have as a Colt would be what Belichick has in store for Peyton
Manning. We've seen Belichick's defenses get into Bledsoe's head.
What if Belichick does something similar to Manning? Nobody really
came after him last year until the Titans swarmed him in the AFC
Divisional playoffs. Look for more of that this year. At least
Manning has Edgerrin James at running back, but James will also be
a marked man.
</P>
<P>
   Jets: The Jets may be harder to pin down than the Patriots. This
team has taken a few hits, mainly the trade of star receiver
Keyshawn Johnson, a hole it has yet to plug. They cut kick returner
and backup running back Leon Johnson, who blew out his knee against
the Patriots in last season's opener. Offensive tackle Jumbo Elliot
is gone. Keyshawn's absence makes Wayne Chrebet the No. 1 receiver.
The Jets may sign Sean Dawkins or even acquire Carl Pickens from
Cincinnati. The Jets are banking on three of their four No. 1 picks
(quarterback Chad Pennington is a project as long as Vinny
Testaverde stays healthy) to make an impact. Tight end Anthony
Becht looks like the real deal and linebacker John Abraham has
received high marks, but defensive end Shaun Ellis has his critics.
One scout said recently, ``He's talented but he has a problem with
the mental side of the game.'' The coaching change to Al Groh could
also be a huge factor except that the system and most of the
coaching staff remains intact with Bill Parcells still running the
team.
</P>
<P>
   Bills: Doug Flutie said recently that he will be back on the
field, despite coach Wade Phillips going with Rob Johnson as his
No. 1 quarterback. The decision to bench Flutie in the playoffs
last year may become Phillips's haunting legacy. Even former Bills
great Jim Kelly said that while he considers Phillips a friend, he
can't approve of the decision to bench Flutie. Another bad sign for
this team, which will be one of the league's youngest, was cutting
fullback Sam Gash. The Patriots found out Gash brings an attitude
to the offense. The Patriots miss it and the Bills will also. This
is also a team void of the great Bruce Smith, who can still be
productive. But the Bills have drafted well lately and their young
players will be put to the test. The Bills must also replace
receiver Andre Reed. At least they have a viable option in Peerless
Price.
</P>
<P>
   Dolphins: They used to have a problem with their running game.
Now they have a problem with their passing game and running game.
The post-Dan Marino Era begins. Don't expect much. Their defense is
still strong enough to win those 12-10 games. But there will be
times when quarterbacks Jay Fiedler or Damon Huard need to put
points on the board. This team also took a hit on its coaching
staff. Jimmy Johnson never won anything in Miami, but he still had
the respect of his players and the community because he had two
Super Bowl rings. Dave Wannstedt must now prove he is more than the
unsuccessful coach he was in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   School's in
</P>
<P>
   It's a tad condescending, but the Jets are holding a one-day
``seminar'' for the New York media Tuesday to explain football.
About 30 media types have signed up for Football 101. On the
itinerary: ``Put your thinking cap on,'' a salary cap lesson by
vice president Mike Tannenbaum; ``Mining the middle of the field
with the passing game,'' with tight ends coach Ken Whisenhunt;
``Run to daylight _ how to find it,'' by assistant head
coach/running backs coach Maurice Carthon; and one that should be a
crowd favorite, ``What really is a two-deep zone?'' by secondary
coach Bob Sutton . . . Former Pittsburgh director of football
operations Tom Donahoe said he will take the year off, but he's
beginning to miss the game already. ``I'm going to enjoy the time
with my family because it may be the only time I ever get to do
this. But sometime before next season I'd like to be with an
organization.'' The situation in Miami didn't pan out, and Donahoe
turned down the job of director of football operations with the
Patriots before Belichick was hired. Donahoe enjoyed his
conversations with Bob and Jonathan Kraft, and even after Belichick
was hired the Krafts hoped Donahoe and Belichick could coexist.
Donahoe shied away because he had just lost his power struggle with
coach Bill Cowher in Pittsburgh. But as Donahoe said, ``If I can
work with Cowher, I can work with anybody.'' With Donahoe still
available, the Patriots have left a personnel job open . . . In
Chad Cascadden, the Patriots acquired another Tedy Bruschi type.
Cascadden has played on the edge and is best as a pass-rushing
weakside linebacker. At 6 feet 1 inch, 240 pounds, he has been
slowed by injuries _ a nagging turf toe that has affected him the
last two years, and last season's knee surgery for a torn ACL.
Cascadden used to be an excellent special teams player and may
replace Marty Moore, now of the Browns, in that role . . . One of
the more interesting stories in the Jets' camp will be that of
defensive back Kevin Williams, who was in a coma for two weeks last
season after undergoing three surgeries for an infection in his
throat and lungs. Williams's agent, Jerome Stanley, got into a war
of words with Parcells, calling him insensitive when the former
coach wanted to limit Williams's pay. Williams is shooting for a
job as a nickel back . . . Former Patriot Ferric Collons's right
rotator cuff is healed and the defensive end is making his push to
become a 49er at minimum salary . . . The 49ers are expected to be
a doormat given they've lost Steve Young to retirement and half
their team to the salary cap. The quarterback battle will be
interesting. Jeff Garcia is the starter, but Rick Mirer, banished
from New York after Jets players and coaches questioned his
leadership, could wind up competing. Don't forget, Bill Walsh sided
with Mirer during the Bledsoe-Mirer draft debates in 1993. Walsh
has always thought Mirer could thrive in the West Coast offense.
Bledsoe, a good friend of Mirer's, said recently, ``To be
considered the top pick, and being the second player chosen in that
draft, there's no question Rick has always had the talent. I always
thought that if he got into a system that was best suited for him,
you'd finally see it. Some quarterbacks come of age when they get
to be 27 or 28 years old. Rick is right around that. He's been
around long enough to know what he can and can't do. I'm sure he's
learned from those experiences and really, he's never been in a
good one. Maybe this time he'll find where he belongs.'' . . .
Don't rule out Seattle winding up with Dawkins again. Agent Angelo
Wright said if offers from the Jets and Packers are substandard, he
may return to the Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Midnight has come
</P>
<P>
   Despite his Cinderella season, league and Super Bowl MVP Kurt
Warner has little leverage when it comes to a new deal. He's an
exclusive rights free agent, which basically means he must take the
Rams' offer or hold out. The Rams don't want to kill their salary
cap, and they still have Trent Green, who was supposed to be the
starter last season. But the Rams are serious about keeping Warner
and may offer a sizable one-year deal ($4 million) and then wait
and see whether Warner is really worth a megadeal . . . The
Chargers' Junior Seau is expected to end his days as a two-way
player. Last year, the future Hall of Fame linebacker spent some
time as an H-back and caught two passes for 8 yards . . . Patriots
fans might disagree with Dallas owner Jerry Jones's assessment of
new offensive coordinator Jack Reilly, who was Bledsoe's
quarterback coach the past two years. ``What I like about Jack is
that he's real imaginative,'' said Jones. Where was that
imagination in the second half of last season? . . . Kevin Greene
retired after last season, but the 38-year-old pass rusher is
having second thoughts. Greene is being considered by the Jaguars,
especially if Tony Brackens, who is looking for a contract in the
$7-$8 million-per-year range, holds out . . . The Jets may not be
able to afford tackle Eric Swann, but their defensive line coach,
Ray Hamilton, is the man who made Swann good enough to land in the
NFL after playing semipro ball for Hamilton in Lynn. Swann is
rumored to be a salary cap hit by the Cardinals, and when he is
released should get serious interest. Swann is from North Carolina
so the Panthers could have a leg up . . . The Giants believe they
drafted the next superstar running back in Ron Dayne. The Heisman
Trophy winner has looked like the real deal in minicamps. Now the
problem is getting him signed. Giants coach Jim Fassel wants Dayne
at training camp from Day One . . . The Eagles would love to get
their hands on Chiefs guard Dave Szott, a 10-year veteran, but it
doesn't appear Kansas City will trade him. Szott has asked to be
traded after moving his family to New Jersey, where his handicapped
son can receive the best medical care. Szott would prefer either
New York team or Philadelphia, but the Chiefs haven't been able to
trade his $1.8 million contract. Szott is contemplating retirement
if he can't be moved . . . Anthony Dorsett, son of Hall of Fame
running back Tony Dorsett, is the leading candidate to be named the
Raiders' starting free safety, replacing Eric Turner, who died of
cancer in June . . . It's not quite as bad as working in a coal
mine, but the worst job in the NFL this summer will be as a New
Orleans Saint. Owner Tom Benson has moved training camp from the
cooler confines of LaCrosse, Wis., to Nicholls State University in
southwest Louisiana. Those two-a-days should be nothing short of
hell.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Summer camp dilemma
</P>
<P>
   Rhode Island state senator John Celona (D-N. Providence) said he
will lead a campaign to introduce legislation in January to help
subsidize Bryant College so it can continue to house Patriots
training camp. Celona is looking for money to refurbish and upgrade
the practice fields and keep the team from moving to another site
while assisting the college with costs associated with the team
staying in Smithfield. After this camp, the Patriots have one year
remaining on their lease. ``The Patriots are an asset to the state
and we certainly don't want to lose them,'' said Celona. ``We
understand the economic impact they create to the businesses around
Bryant and 10 minutes away in Providence.'' The Patriots will be
unable to start camp at Bryant because the college is remodeling
its dormitories. The Patriots will spend the first week in
Foxborough, then move to Bryant. They'll spend only 10 days in
Smithfield because of a schedule that includes a scrimmage against
the Giants July 27 at UMass; a game against the 49ers July 31 in
Canton, Ohio; and an exhibition game in Pontiac, Mich., against the
Lions four days later . . . The Patriots gave running back/receiver
Patrick Pass, a seventh-round pick out of Georgia, a three-year
deal worth $846,000, with a $20,000 signing bonus. About $200,000
will count against the salary cap. As more signings come, the
Patriots will have to begin releasing veterans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
