<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-08 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6815 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BO     07-08 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG SISTER SQUARES MAJOR ACCOUNT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ If one kid has a bauble, naturally her sister wants
one, too. A watch, earrings, a necklace, whatever. Little Sister
Serena sported a major title, the 1999 US Open, so Big Sister Venus
went out and got her own Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   It was called Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   She will wear that honor the rest of her days, dine out on it if
she so chooses, maybe add a few more to earn an alcove in the
International Tennis Hall of Fame in Newport, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing like the first one,'' said Martina
Navratilova, whose nine Wimbledons more than qualified her for next
Saturday's Hall anointing.
</P>
<P>
   And nothing that ever happened on Centre Court quite measured up
to the joy of this first one. Never before had the old sod been
used as a trampoline _ until 20-year-old Venus Ebone Starr Williams
came along.
</P>
<P>
   She had just stolen another point from the woman she stole the
title from, Lindsay Davenport _ stolen it with those endlessly long
and churning legs that overtook a distant, fleeing ball, whereupon
Venus dispatched it with a roaring forehand, the sort of thing she
had been doing throughout. Too much so for an uncertain Davenport.
</P>
<P>
   Only this point was the last of the crowning 6-3, 7-6 (7-3)
triumph, and suddenly Venus was airborne, springing toward the
sullen sky as though those wondrous legs had become pogo sticks.
Boing! Boing! Boing! . . . while superhappy pappy, Richard
Williams, was doing a soft-shoe on the roof of a nearby TV booth.
</P>
<P>
   Hearing those steps overhead, an occupant, ex-champ Chris Evert,
didn't know who was dancing on her ceiling until later. But she
recalled ``a visit from Papa W. and daughters about 10 years ago,''
and how Venus had admired her Wimbledon mementos, smaller replicas
of the massive sterling platter. Venus had said she was going to
get one some day.
</P>
<P>
   Now this was the day for the real thing, the fancy silver dish,
an ornament with which Venus pranced about the venerable arena,
bubbling over with pride and jubilation, teeth and eyes sparkling.
It was an occasion that pappy _ sire and inspirer of Big and Little
Sister _ labeled ``VENUS' PARTY'' on a slate he held aloft.
</P>
<P>
   The festivity made you hope that a sickly, reclusive old woman
in East Orange, N.J., was watching and remembering her golden hours
as a pioneer. Watching and savoring the fun, the success of her
successor for whom she had waited 42 years. She is 72-year-old
Althea Gibson, who busted through a color wall in 1950 at the US
Championships, desegregating tennis as Jackie Robinson had done for
baseball three years before. Wimbledon's initial African-American
female champion in 1957, she repeated the following year _ also
winning the US Championship both years _ before receding from view.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson next appeared at the All England Club 10 years ago to
cheer for Zina Garrison, and hope that the Texan could follow in
her sneakersteps. But Navratilova was too strong in that final.
</P>
<P>
   Slowed by a stroke, apparently strapped financially, she can get
no closer to the world outside her small house than through a TV
screen. ``But,'' said Garrison, ``Althea sent a message for Venus
with me. `Move your feet and bend your knees.' I didn't deliver
it,'' Zina said with a smile. ``I didn't want to distract Venus
from her planning, but I let her know Althea was with her. She
appreciated that.''
</P>
<P>
   Venus moved her feet as though she was trying to cover 42 years
of ground in one afternoon and catch up to Althea's legacy. That
she did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the historical significance of this,'' Venus said. ``I
hope Althea saw it.'' Gibson was the icon, and the question
surrounding every promising African-American girl who came along
was, ``Is she the next Althea?''
</P>
<P>
   Big and Little Sister are the next somebodies to subjugate the
opposition as tall, thunderbolt-serving Althea did for almost three
years. Nevertheless, they're aware and admiring of the breakthrough
she made, pleased to be her heirs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It must have been harder in her day, when she was the first,''
said Venus.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed it was. Gibson wasn't welcome universally at American
tournaments, and made little in those amateur times. Nothing like
today. Agents pursued the now abundantly wealthy Sisters fervently,
throwing money and commercial deals at them. Althea made decent
cash merely one year as a pro, in the neighborhood of $100,000, but
in a meaningless role. She and Karol Fageros played one-set matches
on a basketball floor, the warm-up act for the Harlem
Globetrotters.
</P>
<P>
   Not since the 1977 victory of Englishwoman Virginia Wade has
there been such a heartening celebration. The crowd sang ``For
She's a Jolly Good Fellow!'' to Virginia. Queen Elizabeth II, who
detests tennis, appeared to present the awards.
</P>
<P>
   But other than the serenade, 1977 was just another Wimbledonian
silent movie. Suitable reserve and humility amid royalty, although
in 1967, John Newcombe did confide to the presenter, Princess
Marina, that his evening activities would include many toasts,
leading to inebriation.
</P>
<P>
   But a microphone has been newly added, enabling Venus to tell
the multitude of 13,812 how delighted she was, and that she'd
dreamed of this day over and over only, laughingly, ``to wake up
and find it was a nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   She charmed them with her uninhibited elation, forgetting to
curtsy to the Duchess of Kent as she received her silver, but who
cared? Big Sister is even with Little Sister in the matter of major
possessions, and the two are only growing in sinew, speed, and
acumen.
</P>
<P>
   After a miserable spring following a long layoff to cure
tendinitis in both wrists, Venus stayed true to daddy's dictates:
go for your shots no matter what. That produced ugly losses,
horrendous errors, as well as winners. But the winners outnumbered
mistakes Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never saw her hit such good forehands,'' said Davenport.
</P>
<P>
   It's as though Venus lectured the balls, ``Do what I tell you or
I'll bash you even harder.'' That's Serena's philosophy, too.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine if the old Concord, Mass., scribe, Louisa May Alcott,
could observe these two _ the only sisters to hold major
championships simultaneously _ scrapping to see who can collect the
most baubles and get to the top first, she'd probably rewrite her
bestseller and call it ``Big Women.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
