<HEADER>
A6816 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-WOMEN-B     07-08 1391
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-WOMEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENUS VIBRANT IN FINAL VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Protocol has its place, and the All England Lawn Tennis
&AMP; Croquet Club is its headquarters. It is considered the cathedral
of tennis, the grass of Centre Court its altar. And the tournament
that has graced its sacrosanct turf for the past 114 years,
Wimbledon, is the sport's Holy Grail.
</P>
<P>
   But protocol was evicted from the grounds Saturday, taking pomp
and pretension with it. They were driven out by a glorious new
people's champion _ 20-year-old Venus Williams, granddaughter of a
Louisiana sharecropper; product of a Compton, Calif., slum; protege
of a devoted, flamboyant father; and the first African-American
woman to reign here in 42 years. She stood tradition on its head by
doing just about everything except standing on hers to celebrate
her 6-3, 7-6 (7-3) dethroning of 1999 champion Lindsay Davenport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just pretty happy at that point,'' said Williams,
``because I had let a lot of opportunities go in the second set.
Finally, I pulled the tiebreak out without a huge, huge struggle
against myself. I was pretty happy.''
</P>
<P>
   The spontaneity was electrifying. Suddenly, this citadel of
stuffed shirts was a party palace. Moments after Davenport plunked
a service return off the net cord, giving Williams the match, the
new champion began dancing jubilantly around the court. She didn't
abandon tennis etiquette, shaking hands with Davenport and umpire
Gerry Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   And then she really let loose.
</P>
<P>
   She skipped and pranced back across the court, then vaulted into
the stands at the southeast corner, with her 6-foot-1-inch frame
loped to the box reserved for friends and family. Her father and
mentor, Richard, was dancing by now, too, having stepped out of the
box and onto the roof of the broadcast booth just below. He had
been an inescapable presence, holding up an erasable board with
greetings to his wife, praise for the British fans, a plug for a
soft drink, and, in a thoroughly erroneous message, a proclamation
that ``It's Venus's party and no one was invited.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, everyone was, because Venus hadn't noticed her father's
antics during the match.
</P>
<P>
   Now in victory, they exchanged a sort of hug, awkward because of
their respective positions, and Venus resisted the efforts of some
idolators to hoist her up with Richard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to be picked up,'' she said. ``My height, if I
fall, it's going to be a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came the most poignant moment. Venus leaned into the family
box and exchanged a lingering embrace with her 18-year-old sister
Serena, whom circumstances had cast as her opponent in an
unprecedented sibling semifinal Thursday whose hoopla resonated
throughout the world. Venus won that encounter in straight sets,
but it obviously was an unwelcome task. Still, Serena _ who
preceded Venus to the Grand Slam throne by winning the US Open last
September _ was overjoyed as she whispered to her big sister,
``Great job.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She was really, really getting emotional there, trying to hold
it in,'' said Venus.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd of 13,812 was unable to do so. Suddenly, Centre Court
sounded like a whooping, hollering hootenanny that subsided only
for the official presentation of the silver championship platter _
called, foretellingly enough, the Venus Rosewater Trophy _ by the
Duchess of Kent.
</P>
<P>
   So it was official, this victory that had been years in the
making. Exiting the court, Richard, who otherwise refused comment
because ``this is Venus's day,'' was asked by a fan when he gave
Venus her first lesson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four years, six months, one day,'' he replied without
hesitation.
</P>
<P>
   Venus doesn't remember that far back, but she does recall that
from the beginning, she and Serena had been groomed to become
champions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was meant to be,'' she said, ``because I worked real hard
all my life. In our family, it's positive. We don't just work to be
professional. We're happy to be on the circuit. We worked hard to
be the best because for us, why play if we don't believe we can be
the best?''
</P>
<P>
   The prime of Althea Gibson, who in 1957 and '58 became the first
African-American woman to prevail here, was before their time, but
the Williams sisters _ who unlike so many tennis toddlers with
tunnel vision were raised to appreciate all of life _ were keenly
aware of her role as a racial trailblazer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had to be hard because people were unable to see past
color,'' said Venus. ``Still, these days it's hardly any different
because you have to realize it's only been 40 years (since Gibson's
achievement). How can you change years and centuries of being
biased in 40 years?''
</P>
<P>
   A more contemporary role model was Zina Garrison, who in 1990
became the only other African-American woman to reach the Wimbledon
final, losing to Martina Navratilova. While Garrison progressed
through the draw, beating Monica Seles and Steffi Graf along the
way, the Williams sisters were busy practicing under their father's
tutelage. But he would stop a passerby walking his dog and ask him
the score of Garrison's matches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was only 10,'' said Venus. ``But that meant a lot to us.''
</P>
<P>
   She hopes her ascension will prove similarly inspiring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of people will look and see,'' said Williams.
``But you also have to get out there and help out, let people see
you start programs. That would definitely be something that I and
especially my dad could help to start.''
</P>
<P>
   She took matters into her own hands here, buying herself a gown
to wear to Sunday's champions' ball the day she left her Palm Beach
Gardens, Fla., home for London. She was upset with herself for
losing in the French Open quarterfinals and ``felt I didn't deserve
to spend any money.''
</P>
<P>
   But she bought the dress, about which she won't reveal any
details until Sunday, and used it as extra incentive ``because if I
didn't win, I wouldn't get to wear this wonderful dress.''
</P>
<P>
   Seeded fifth, she was the belle of the ball here. On the road to
the final, she beat the world's and Wimbledon's top-ranked player,
Martina Hingis, ``and I took out No. 8, which was not easy'' _
because that happened to be Serena. Davenport, whom Richard
Williams praised as a class act ``who never has a bad word to say
about anybody,'' had traveled a less perilous path but was still
feeling the effects of thigh and back problems that had sidelined
her for two months this year.
</P>
<P>
   And both finalists suffered a case of nerves. That accounted for
the improbable total of 11 break points in the two sets, six of
which Williams won and eight of which occurred in a nine-game
second-set stretch. And that was the difference, along with a
service game that betrayed Davenport. Besides that, she was simply
unable to reach many of Williams's returns that found the corners
like darts.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, it was as if Davenport were embodying Richard
Williams's words as she assessed the impact of the Williams
sisters.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's the first African-American to win (Wimbledon) since
Althea Gibson, and no (black) has been in the final since Zina,''
said Davenport. ``Obviously, that's a huge step. I would have liked
to not have let her won, to stop it. But her and Serena are going
to win many more titles. They've been great influences in the game.
To see everything that they've gone through and their athleticism,
they're showing that tennis players can be very athletic. I mean,
they've done great things for the sport.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's all it is, Venus emphasized, because if there's one
thing her father taught her, it's perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized I wouldn't be any happier in my life in general if
I won or lost,'' she said. ``After Serena won the US Open, you can
see that she's the same person. So for my tennis career, this is
great. But as far as being Venus, it doesn't really make a huge
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   But she does. In yet another departure from routine here,
Williams left the clubhouse through the front door, allowing the
public to touch her trophy.
</P>
<P>
   Which, of course, is traditional for a people's champion.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Australians Todd Woodbridge and Mark Woodforde annexed their
sixth doubles crown Saturday with a 6-3, 6-4, 6-1 sweep of Paul
Haarhuis and Sandon Stolle.
</P>
</TEXT>
