<HEADER>
A6818 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKN-NBANOTES-GRANTHIL     07-08 1849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBANOTES-GRANTHILL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILL UNLIKELY TO FIND MUCH MAGIC IN ORLANDO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Why do I have a hard time understanding the reason Tim Duncan
may soon follow Grant Hill to Orlando? Because it is the only way
this whole thing makes sense. Hill is a great player in his own
right who would do well on his own, but also someone who needs to
hitch his wagon to someone even better. That someone is Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   Why else would Hill leave Detroit, a team which had a better
record last year than Orlando, to play with, oh, Tracy McGrady?
That is what's called a lateral move and Hill would be no closer to
the title he covets. He'd also be sacrificing a lot of money.
</P>
<P>
   It might be more easily explained if Hill was upset with the
Pistons, didn't like management, didn't like the environment, or
didn't like his teammates, but that isn't the case. He had the ear
of the owner. He lobbied hard and successfully for the appointments
of Joe Dumars and George Irvine, both of whom were only recently
hired. He lobbied hard and successfully for player acquisitions
such as Christian Laettner and Michael Curry, who joined the team
last season.
</P>
<P>
   It just didn't work out and there's no real reason to believe it
will improve significantly any time soon. There is hope in Orlando,
but unless Duncan joins the team, it's not a sure thing.
(Reportedly, Wednesday is D-Day for Duncan.)
</P>
<P>
   Hill said he likes Orlando because the Magic have a plan. You'd
better believe they do and that plan is to have Duncan and Hill in
Hooterville. The two are friends, share the same agent and the same
vision of the game. Who knows, maybe their first pick-and-roll
together was for Duncan to set the screen and Hill to come out and
announce his intentions, making it easier for his friend to follow
suit.
</P>
<P>
   But there's another reason for the inevitable union. Hill has to
know what most everyone else knows: He's not The Man. He tried to
be The Man in Detroit and you saw what happened: Good stats, annual
All-Star appearances, and annual playoff disappointments. The next
playoff series Hill wins will be his first.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the future in Orlando, which, in addition to this
apparently successful free agent assault, is Florida-sun bright.
The Magic, already blessed with a decent roster, have a ton of No.
1 picks in the next few years, two of them extracted on draft
night. Those might not necessarily translate into players, but they
are bargaining chips welcome at any NBA table. The Pistons don't
have such promise, but, again, without Duncan, how valuable is the
Orlando future?
</P>
<P>
   If Duncan re-signs with the Spurs, there's still the ongoing
question of David Robinson's health (the Admiral turns 35 next
month) as well as an old team that already had its moment in the
sun.
</P>
<P>
   Throw in the other Florida intangibles _ weather, Doc Rivers,
smallish city, great practice facility _ and you basically have a
slam dunk. Duncan also has to know that going to Orlando represents
a 50 percent reduction in annual Shaq meetings, not to mention
similar cuts against Portland and Phoenix. And, by extension, it
also means four games a year against Cleveland, New Jersey,
Atlanta, Washington, and all those other Eastern Conference powers.
</P>
<P>
   We may know soon. We may have to wait until Aug. 1. Duncan may
not be saying much, but Hill already has made it known where he's
going to be next season. And if Duncan doesn't join him, the
ex-Piston is going to find a lot more Waffle Houses and Shoney's in
central Florida, but not much else.
</P>
<P>
   Ask yourself this: Why on earth would he allow that to happen?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Keeping the cap on
</P>
<P>
   The Magic can get Duncan and Hill via the conventional free
agent route, but the only way they could add McGrady would seem to
be via sign-and-trade for one of their people already under
contract. That would keep their cap room intact. If McGrady is
serious about going to Orlando, and that would mean rejecting
Chicago's overtures, then the Raptors should push hard for the
Orlando player they want. Given Toronto's point-guard situation,
Darrell Armstrong would be the logical target along with some of
those first-rounders the Magic have been hoarding. Orlando also
will then turn its attention to valuable returnees Bo Outlaw and
Ben Wallace, who already have cap holds. Outlaw is believed to have
agreed to a wink-wink deal in excess of $4 million-per while
longtime agent Steve Kauffman reports that he has received more
calls about Wallace (17-plus teams at last count) than he has for
any client he's ever had. The Celtics were one, but Wallace should
stay where he is . . . One of the now-common practices of teams
pursuing free agents is to send its target a jersey with the
player's name on the back. The Knicks make a big deal of that and
went so far as to send a jersey to Danny Fortson, among others. But
the Celtics might have topped everyone in their pursuit of Austin
Croshere. Rick Pitino and Croshere were meeting in Santa Monica,
Calif., and in walked GM Chris Wallace with a Celtics jersey with
Croshere's name on the back. If I'm Austin Croshere, I have two
main questions for Boston: 1. Why would I leave a team that made it
to the NBA Finals to play for a team that may not make the playoffs
and; 2. Where would I play given that Antoine Walker is there? The
money issue is moot: He'll get it in a sign-and-trade. But assuming
the money is equal, why leave a good team with a lot of young
talent for one that hasn't made the playoffs in five years and
without a lot of promise? And where would he play? The Celtics
think he can play small forward, but that might be a reach,
especially on defense. He's a power forward, which is where Walker
plays. The Celtics also love Croshere's attitude and work ethic.
But you have to ask yourself why he'd leave Indiana for Boston . .
. As for Fortson, the Celtics want to re-sign him and then deal
him; that way they get something in return. The problem in a
straight swap is NBA math. If Fortson's new deal increases by 15
percent over what he made last year _ and it should _ then the
complicated base-year compensation rules apply. If, for instance,
Boston re-signed Fortson to a deal, which started out at $4
million, and then traded him to the Knicks, the Celtics could only
take back a player who made about $2 million. That's why the talk
of Chris Childs for Fortson is off the mark; he makes well more
than half of anything that Fortson might get. The Knicks are more
interested in Fortson at the $2.25 million exception, which is
probably the case for most clubs. Otherwise, a third team would
again have to be involved and Fortson isn't the kind of player who
normally would generate such interest . . . As for the pursuit of
Jermaine O'Neal, the Celtics thought of it as actually being only 1
1/2 picks, rather than three first-rounders. The reason? They were
getting No. 28 from Portland (the half). And they felt O'Neal was
at least worth the 11th pick. In addition, they would have been
able to dump some money, which would not have affected their cap
situation, but would have delighted Paul Gaston. The feeling is
that the Blazers want to see what happens with Brian Grant before
making a decision on O'Neal . . . The Dallas Mavericks let people
know Friday that Michael Finley is being considered for the US
Olympic Team opening created by Hill's decision not to go to
Sydney. Apparent first choice Kobe Bryant supposedly isn't
interested and the Mavs have been told that Finley, Jalen Rose, and
Eddie Jones are also being considered.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Second-guessing
</P>
<P>
   Nigerian Olumide Oyedeji might have slipped to the second round
in the draft, but he already is making a run at first-team
All-Interview. Oyedeji noted that he abused Darius Miles during the
Nike Hoop Summit, adding, ``If (Miles) comes to my country, he
couldn't make my national team. He cannot make my Under-22 team.''
Oyedeji was thought by some to be a lottery pick _ he worked out
twice for Boston and Dallas had him in for five days. He ended up
going to Seattle with the 42d pick. ``It's one of the more shocking
things I've seen in a long time,'' said Chris Wallace. ``This was a
guy who was heavily scrutinized by a lot of lottery and
near-lottery teams and he went in the 40s.'' What made it even more
stunning was that Oyedeji was the only foreign player who was
unequivocally free to play in the NBA next season. Maybe the teams
that saw him more than once noticed more blemishes the second time
around. Maybe he just got on a Cliff Robinson/Rashard Lewis slide
and couldn't get off. Who knows? Oyedeji called his precipitous
drop ``a lot of politics'' and vowed to make the teams that passed
him regret it. ``It's like a salt wound in the heart I have to
overcome.'' . . . Here's a shocker. The 76ers are believed to be
considering anything short of Acie Earl in a deal for Matt Geiger.
Then again, maybe Acie would do it, given the Sixers'
disenchantment with Geiger. The problem will be finding a taker for
the remaining four years (and 30-something million) as well as a 15
percent trade kicker . . . The Miami Heat are asking season
ticket-holders to make their full deposits by Saturday for next
season. That is asking a lot, given that teams can't do any
signings until Aug. 1. It might help if Miami's legendary
motivator, Pat Riley, could persuade Jones to announce his
intentions by then. The Heat are at the top of Jones's wish list,
but, of course, Miami can't offer him anything more than the $2.25
million exception because of its salary cap situation. But it could
offer him a new deal starting in 2001, starting at $11 million, by
using the cap space that will be available after its recent trade
with Denver. It would be a big risk for Jones, but he would be
returning home to play for a contender. In that scenario, Jones and
Alonzo Mourning (under contract through 2002-03) would be the
nucleus for a new Heat team along with either Jamal Mashburn or
P.J. Brown. Meanwhile, Miami could field a starting five next year
of Jones, Brown, Mourning, Mashburn, and a re-signed (one year) Tim
Hardaway . . . The latest ``my bad'' from Anthony Mason is his
fourth as a Hornet, his worst as a Hornet, and, potentially, his
last as a Hornet. While Mason insists he's not the guy, the New
Orleans police say otherwise. They charged Mason with battery on a
police officer, resisting arrest, and inciting a riot. The Hornets
are hot about the whole thing. ``These things are happening far too
often,'' said GM Bob Bass. But the much larger implication is the
Hornets' deteriorating reputation in the city as the team lobbies
for a new arena. Over the last five years, the Hornets have lost
7,000 season tickets and the sight of a half-full Charlotte
Coliseum was cited by Jones as one reason he wanted out. Said
Charlotte mayor Pat McCrory, ``This continues to strengthen the
argument that a few of these guys are not good role models and we
shouldn't support them in any way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
