<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-FOLEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOLEY WELL REMEMBERS STATE AMATEUR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He returned to Worcester Country Club for an informal round of
golf last week and while everything around him _ graphite shafts,
metal drivers, manicured fairways _ indicated it was 2000, Bill
Foley Sr. only had to close his eyes to make it 1964.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remembered all the people I played and all the shots I
played,'' said Foley, who was 26 when he won the State Amateur at
Worcester CC 36 years ago. ``It definitely was a very important
part of my life. So many things in my life came because of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Foley is one of those genuine people involved in the game who
understands that the dividends have been quite substantial. ``I've
felt for a long time that I'll never be able to give back what I've
taken out of the game,'' he said, though that could be debated. He
has, after all, been connected with the game for years with the
Massachusetts Golf Association and the Francis Ouimet Scholarship
Fund, of which he is currently vice president _ an unselfish
involvement that is a small price to pay for what he was fortunate
enough to experience 36 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The 64-player match-play field in 1964 included some of the
great names in Massachusetts golf circles _ Warren Tibbetts of
Vesper, Burton Page of Colonial, Mike Ohanian of Oakley, Fordie
Pitts of Wollaston, Eddie Barry of Charles River, Bob Menne of Oak
Hill, and Joe Browning of Weston. There were the Cosgroves, Bill
and John, and Fran Quinn Sr. from Green Hill, as well as Jack
Harvey and Eddie Martin of Winchester CC.
</P>
<P>
   So many great players, said Foley, whose first practice round
that week resulted in a 76. ``I was noted for my putting and the
greens were heavy. I said, `My God, I better do better than this,'
and then Fran Quinn Sr. shot 66. I said, `Wow.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But the greens got a close shave and in his first match, against
Dean Cassell of New Bedford, Foley lipped out a birdie chance at
the opening hole, then drained birdie putts at Nos. 2 and 3, to set
in motion a splendid week on the greens. ``I played seven rounds
without three-putting,'' said Foley.
</P>
<P>
   No putt is any clearer than the one he drained against Tibbetts
to win their semifinal match, 1 up, at Worcester's famous 18th
hole. ``It was a 30-footer, from the lower left part of the green
to the upper tier, top right.''
</P>
<P>
   In the final, Foley built a four-hole lead through the morning
18, and eventually dispatched Matty Ciociolo of Wachusett, 8 and 6,
to secure a title that culminated an unforgettable week, though it
had not come without the great escapes that so often define
match-play championships.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, there was second-round foe Art McKearney of Fresh
Pond, who had Foley 2-down with four holes left. ``I parred the
last four holes and won each of them (for a 2-up victory). He hit
good drives and good second shots, but each time the ball took bad
bounces into rough or bad lies. He needed three to get down on each
hole.''
</P>
<P>
   In the quarterfinals, Foley went 20 holes to upend Pitts, his
clubmate at Wollaston GC and longtime friend. ``Strange, because I
always bowed to Fordie's superiority as a golfer,'' said Foley.
``But it was my day and my week.''
</P>
<P>
   A sequence of memorable days in the history of a golf course
that is saturated in character and has seen its share of great
moments _ from the opening tee shot launched by President Taft in
1914, to Bobby Jones calling a penalty on himself and losing the
1925 US Open in a playoff, to the inaugural Ryder Cup in 1927, to
Byron Nelson's Mass. Open triumph in 1939.
</P>
<P>
   It was at Worcester CC, in 1960, that Betsy Rawls won her fourth
and final US Women's Open, and the great Jesse Guilford won a State
Open (1919) and a State Amateur (1921) there.
</P>
<P>
   The roll call of State Open champs at Worcester CC also includes
Donald Vinton (1926), Wiffy Cox (1931), Jim Browning (1953), and
Paul Barkhouse (1976), while State Amateurs have been earned at
this Donald Ross creation by Guilford, Joseph Lynch (1933), Eddie
Martin (1948), and Jim McDermott (1989). And Foley, of course,
whose visit last week rekindled some of the emotion.
</P>
<P>
   The 92d State Amateur gets underway Monday morning at Worcester
CC and Foley reports that the course is better than ever. So, too,
is the memory of 1964.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Consistently inconsistent
</P>
<P>
   Notah Begay watched some tennis last week, soaking in the
Wimbledon atmosphere. And why not? After all, back-to-back wins on
the PGA Tour are an impressive feat, for which he deserves a round
of applause. But let's not get carried away with what he has done,
because a closer look at his playing record indicates his game has
not exactly been rock solid. Yes, he has shot in the 60s in each of
his last eight rounds, but in the 26 previous rounds, Begay broke
70 just three times and was a cumulative 37 over par. Two wins and
a tie for fourth (at Pebble Beach) are impressive, but in his other
14 starts, Begay has missed six cuts and failed to land in the top
20. Same story a year ago _ in his first 21 starts he missed seven
cuts; then he won twice in five starts, with the next best finish a
T-42 . . . Colin Montgomerie is the latest to switch golf balls,
opting for the Callaway, and that's certainly his prerogative. But
please spare us the drivel that came out after Montgomerie shot 67
in the first round of the European Open. ``I would not have gone
for the shot on No. 18 if I didn't have the confidence of knowing I
can hit the new ball a lot farther,'' he said, in reference to a
265-yard 3-wood that set up an eagle-3. Right. He won more than 20
times and was Order of Merit champion seven straight seasons
playing a Titleist, but all of a sudden the Callaway ball has
unlocked the mysteries of the game. Gee, any chance that money
factors into the switch? . . . Massimo Scarpa of Italy tied the
Ballybunion course record with a second-round 63 in the Irish Open
last week, and if not for a bogey at the final hole, he would have
established a European Tour mark with a back-side 27. Alas, his 73
start and 75-75 weekend left him tied for 53d, which helps explain
why he's never won in eight years on Tour . . . Jenny Chuasiriporn,
who captivated the golf world in 1998 when she was runner-up in the
US Women's Open, missed the cut in Europe this weekend shooting
75-75 at the Ladies German Open. She has not made a dent in the pro
game; before heading to Europe, Chuasiriporn earned less than
$1,000 in seven events on the Futures Tour . . . In the Ladies
German Open, Marielle Kallvik of Sweden shot 105. Ouch. We trust
she has another career option.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Home for the holidays
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods's decision to skip the Andersen Consulting World
Match Play event in January should not come as a shock. He'll be
criticized, but shouldn't be. David Duval doesn't want to play, nor
does Montgomerie or Jose Maria Olazabal. The Jan. 3-7 date in
Australia throws a curveball into holiday plans and for many
players, that's too far to go and too early to jump into a golf
season that is getting longer and longer. Blame these guys for a
lot of things, but on this matter, you can understand their
concerns . . . Aaron Baddeley will soon turn pro and be able to
make his own decisions, but for now he must accept directions.
Consequently, he won't take part in the US Amateur because the
Australian Golf Union wants him fresh for the Eisenhower Trophy,
and those events could conflict. The US Amateur final is scheduled
for Aug. 27, which is the day the AGU has penciled for the first
practice round in Germany for a competition it takes very
seriously. Australia won the Eisenhower in 1996 and has finished
second twice since. Of course, it may be a blessing in disguise for
Baddeley, whose American PGA Tour swing was anything but a rousing
success, as he missed the cut in five straight events _ Bay Hill,
Masters, Compaq Classic, Memorial, US Open _ after making it into
weekend play at the Honda Classic . . . Hunter Haas will try to
defend his US Public Links championship beginning Monday, but after
it's over he will turn pro. He has sponsor's exemptions waiting for
him at the B.C. Open and The International . . . Joining Haas in
the Public Links field will be locals William Link IV of Acton,
Jeff Sieber of Bedford, Chris Rousseau of Agawam, Phil Miceli of
Wakefield, Neil Kelley of Hampton, N.H., and Matthew Biery of
Windham, N.H. . . . As for Charles Howell, whose pro debut at the
Greater Hartford Open resulted in a check for $13,627, he had
nothing to compare it with. ``That's my first paycheck,'' he said.
``I've never worked a day in my life.'' . . . On such a young
topic, perhaps you missed that 10-year-old Michelle Wie, a
sixth-grader from Hawaii, qualified for match play at the US
Women's Public Links Championship. (She was ousted in Round 1, 3
and 2.) Ten years old! I have dirt on my clubs older than that.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Blast from the past
</P>
<P>
   One of the nice stories at this week's State Amateur is Jim
Deveney, who plays out of Essex County Club. He was 22 when he
first qualified for the State Amateur, in 1964 at Worcester CC, won
by Foley. Thirty-six years later, he's back in the field, enduring
a pressure-packed qualifier just a few years after he decided to
rework his swing. ``I had an OK year last year, but I did want to
get back to Worcester,'' said Deveney, who qualified for the 1999
US Senior Amateur . . . One stalwart who won't be teeing it up at
Worcester CC is two-time champ James Driscoll of Charles River CC.
He's played a ton of golf already this year and coming up is
another run at the US Amateur in August, for which he's exempt . .
. The Golf Channel's ``Drive, Chip &AMP; Putt'' contests for youngsters
ages 7-12 will be at Brookmeadow CC in Canton Tuesday and at
Cyprian Keyes in Boylston Thursday. The events will be limited to
the first 120 at each site and entry forms are available at the
respective pro shops . . . The golf world lost one of its most
gracious personalities recently, when Margaret Lowery died in Palm
Springs, Calif., at the age of 82. Her husband, Eddie, who died in
1984, will forever maintain a spot in golf lore as the 10-year-old
caddie for Francis Ouimet, who won the 1913 US Open. In Margaret,
he had a life partner who shared his passion for golf. She counted
Byron Nelson, Ken Venturi, and E. Harvie Ward among her closest
friends and she had a keen interest in the Francis Ouimet
Scholarship Fund, endowing a $25,000 scholarship in Eddie's name.
``Fittingly,'' said Bob Donovan, executive director of the Ouimet
Fund, ``it goes to our top caddie.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
