<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-WYNALDA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION GET WYNALDA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ In an effort to kick up their offense, the
Revolution acquired high-scoring Eric Wynalda from the Fusion
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   To get the 31-year-old forward, the Revolution traded
defender-midfielder Ivan McKinley to Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Wynalda has 79 points in 69 Major League Soccer games _ 24 goals
and 31 assists _ ranking him among the top scorers with a
1.14-points-per-game average. In 1996, his first _ and best _
season in the league, he scored 10 goals and had 13 assists for the
San Jose Clash.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at the Revolution and I see a good mix of experience
and young talent,'' said Wynalda. ``I know just about everybody on
the team. I feel I can help the team score, even when I'm not
playing _ coaching the team to be more composed up front. Sometimes
you even have to be a bit greedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Revolution coach Fernando Clavijo said the addition will help
improve the team. ``We've struggled to score goals; we need to find
a way to get the ball in the back of the net,'' he said. ``Plus,
Ivan was very unhappy here and he wanted to go to Miami, so we had
both things happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eric is looking forward to the challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Wynalda, nursing a calf injury, has not played in about a month,
Clavijo said. The injury may keep him out of the Revolution lineup
for up to two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eric has scored plenty of big goals in the MLS,'' said
Clavijo. ``He has plenty of time left in his prime. He has at least
four or five more years while he has been maturing more in his
body. Every day counts for him.''
</P>
<P>
   McKinley, a member of the South African national team, flew to
Miami Saturday. He started 12 of 13 games this season, with 10
games on defense rather than the midfield position he prefers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to trade Ivan or separate him from our team,'' said
Clavijo. ``He hasn't been in control of his emotions the last two
months, in particular the last two or three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, Ivan's family wasn't happy here, so we felt that his
trade was best for our team. Playing defense might have been some
of the problem, but there was more to it than that in trying to
make Ivan happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Wynalda is the US national team's all-time leading scorer with
33 goals in 102 appearances. He was a US national teammate of
Revolution captain John Harkes and reserve goalkeeper Juergen
Sommer. In addition, Wynalda played with Clavijo on the 1994 US
World Cup team.
</P>
<P>
   Wynalda was the US Male Athlete of the Year in 1996, when he
scored nine goals in 13 international appearances.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
