<SLUG> BC-BBA-SOXROOKIE-MORGAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORGAN A BLUE COLLAR KIND OF GUY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Six months ago, he was riding dusty buses across back-country
roads in Mexico to play the Guasave Cottoneers and Culiacan Tomato
Growers.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Burkhart, the kid no one in Major League Baseball
bothered to recruit in high school or college, had given up
construction work and was making his way in winter ball with the
Navajoa Mayos of the Mexican League.
</P>
<P>
   No million-dollar paydays. No Internet fan club. And little hope
that one day he could achieve the stuff of other players' dreams: a
turn in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't really playing to get in the big leagues,'' said
Burkhart, 27, of a career that included four long summers with the
Richmond Roosters of the Frontier League before the Red Sox signed
him as a non-drafted free agent in 1998. ``I didn't think there was
a chance I was going to get to the big leagues. I was just playing
because I loved the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, 12 games into Burkhart's Cinderella stay in the bigs,
Red Sox manager Jimy Williams spoke almost lovingly of his new
designated hitter who has escaped the Mexicali Blues.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the intangible,'' Williams said, pointing to his heart.
``You can see it. You can sense it.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Brian Daubach, who rose a year earlier from nearly a decade
of minor league obscurity, Burkhart has proven his worth to
Williams not only with a potent bat but his ``blue-collar'' pluck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you're looking for those blue-collar guys,''
Williams said. ``You need the other ones, but that supporting cast
is so, so important.''
</P>
<P>
   Both players are stronger, Williams said, for the adversity they
have overcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``They paid a lot of minor league dues,'' Williams said. During
those years, the manager said, ``A lot of people told them they
can't, and they kept saying they will. That's when you find out
whether you have a ballplayer, when you see how they go through
adversity.''
</P>
<P>
   In Burkhart, Williams has a switch hitter with patience and
power (to wit, 53 home runs and 163 RBIs in a 201-game span last
year that included stints with Class A Sarasota, Double A Trenton,
and Navajoa).
</P>
<P>
   In his first 11 games since he was summoned June 27 to sub for
the injured Trot Nixon, Burkhart has knocked in 11 runs, hit his
first major league homer, and batted .368. His production _ and
ability to hit from both sides of the plate _ will help him when
Nixon returns to the lineup after the All-Star break. (Nixon's
return, originally scheduled for Thursday, was pushed back
indefinitely after he aggravated his right hamstring in a Gulf
Coast League game).
</P>
<P>
   Barring unforeseen trouble, Burkhart's spot on the Sox roster
appears safe after Nixon's return, as Izzy Alcantara and Dernell
Stenson would be most likely to depart before him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing OK, but I could be doing better,'' said Burkhart,
who helped pave his road to the Fens by winning the MVP trophy in
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Williams has enough faith in Burkhart that he has been batting
him fifth behind Nomar Garciaparra and Carl Everett. Burkhart had
one of Boston's five hits Friday against Atlanta's Tom Glavine,
though he struggled in his first three at-bats against Terry
Mulholland, grounding out, striking out, and lining out to center.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he perseveres. Burkhart said he never enjoyed the luxury
of being the best player in high school, outside St. Louis, or in
college, Central Missouri State. And he knows his job with the Red
Sox is not guaranteed, though he hopes one day to trade his
makeshift locker for a longer-term berth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm up here because I'm expected to do something,'' he said.
``That's what I'm trying to do, and I feel I can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   In any case, he has probably experienced his last winter in
Mexico.
</P>
</TEXT>
