<HEADLINE>
DODGERS' PITCHING NOT WHAT IT USED TO BE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   During the good times and bad times, from the days of Drysdale
and Koufax to the height of Fernandomania and Orel, one could
always count on Dodger pitching. It was their DNA.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Brooklyn, where Ebbets Field was a bandbox for the Boys
of Summer, the Dodger M.O. was hitting. But from their second year
in Los Angeles, even while playing in the Coliseum with its obtuse
Chinese Wall in left field before moving into the pitcher-friendly
confines of Dodger Stadium, the Dodgers always won the arms race.
</P>
<P>
   In the 33 seasons between 1959 and 1991, the Dodgers led the
National League in pitching 15 times and finished in the N.L. top
three 25 times. Dodger pitchers threw seven no-hitters and 24
one-hitters, won seven Cy Young awards, three Rookie of the year
awards, and four World Series MVP trophies.
</P>
<P>
   Seven different pitchers won nine different N.L. percentage
titles. Dodger pitchers led the league in shutouts 14 times; 13
different pitchers were among the leaders. In those 33 seasons, the
Dodgers had 22 different pitchers represent them in all-star games.
</P>
<P>
   The only legacy in baseball that compares is the one in New York
revolving around Damn Yankees and their left-handed power hitters.
But the current Dodger pitching staff isn't upholding the legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Once dominant, it is now merely ordinary, with six down-the-road
finishes in the last nine seasons, including 2000 as baseball takes
its all-star break. Last year's team ERA oZyb7HW,.HC!+$YZ!MQ
</P>
</TEXT>
