u s BC-BBO-METS-YANKS-1STLD-     07-08 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-METS-YANKS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS BEAT METS, TWICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS for second game results)  
 By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Steve Phillips was there at the beginning, in
Kingsport, Tenn., watching a 17-year-old fireballing teammate named
Dwight Gooden break a catcher's hand with his fastballs.
</P>
<P>
   And he was watching again Saturday when Gooden pitched the
Yankees to a 4-2 victory over the Mets at Shea Stadium. Hours
later, the Yankees defeated the Mets by 4-2 again, this time at
Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips, then a minor league infielder and now the Mets'
general manager, remembers how Gooden overmatched Appalachian
League teams, how one club's No.9 hitter closed his eyes and swung
and somehow beat Gooden, 1-0, with an opposite-field home run.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen years later, Phillips passed on the chance to sign
Gooden after he was released by the Tampa Bay Devil Rays in May.
Gooden had pitched poorly for both Tampa Bay and Houston, and in
the Mets' opinion, he could no longer pitch competitively in the
majors.
</P>
<P>
   Gooden was pitching at the lowest level of the minors before the
Yankees promoted him to face the Mets at Shea Stadium Saturday, to
return to the stage of his greatest triumphs in the mid-1980s. He
was not the Gooden of old, but he was surprisingly effective for
five innings and was the winning pitcher in the Yankees' first 4-2
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gave them a great effort,'' Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, the teams boarded buses _ subway transportation
was left to the fans, 54,165 of whom showed up in Flushing _ and
headed to Yankee Stadium for the second game of a day-night
doubleheader. It was the first time since 1903 that two teams had
played each other at different ballparks on the same day.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bronx, the Yankees got seven and a third strong innings
from Roger Clemens and a three-run home run by Chuck Knoblauch to
win again. Clemens hit Mike Piazza on the helmet with a pitch in
the second inning; he sustained a slight concussion. The series
concludes Sunday night at Shea.
</P>
<P>
   Gooden, who was pitching at Shea for the first time since 1994
when he was still a Met, received mostly cheers when he was
introduced. There were no signs counting the strikeouts of the
pitcher once known as Dr. K, but Gooden recorded only one strikeout
anyway. The Mets had six hits off him in five innings, but they
walked just once and managed only two runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you get released, you're sitting at home and not knowing
if you'll get back and play again,'' Gooden said. ``So today, I
just wanted to make sure I enjoyed the moment rather than putting
pressure on myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Piazza, who was 0 for 3 against Gooden and left three runners on
base, said: ``I can't really explain it. He just threw strikes;
that's the bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Gooden's 77 pitches, 49 were strikes, and his fastballs came
in about 85 to 90 miles an hour. Mets left fielder Benny Agbayani
was 12 when Gooden made his debut in the major leagues in 1984, but
from what Agbayani understood, Saturday's offerings would have been
change-ups back then.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, he wasn't throwing 85 to 86,'' Agbayani said. ``It was
95, 97. But he spotted the ball good today.''
</P>
<P>
   Gooden (3-3) left the game with the score tied, but Tino
Martinez made him the winner with an opposite-field home run in the
sixth inning off the Mets right-hander Bobby J. Jones. Martinez
went 3 for 4 with three runs batted in, and his homer was the only
hit Jones allowed over the final 23 batters he faced after the
Yankees took a 2-0 lead in the first.
</P>
<P>
   Jones (3-4) worked seven innings, giving up three runs on four
hits and three walks. He has a 2.67 earned run average in four
starts since returning from an assignment to Class AAA Norfolk,
which followed a shelling by the Yankees in June.
</P>
<P>
   This game began ominously for Jones. Knoblauch lined the first
pitch in front of a diving Jay Payton in center field. Payton
popped up and threw out Knoblauch at second base, and Jones, whose
expressions usually change as often as a statue's when he is
pitching, pumped his fist in excitement.
</P>
<P>
   He could not have known the call was about to be changed by
Umpire Robb Cook, who agreed with the Yankees' first-base coach,
Lee Mazzilli, that Todd Zeile, the Mets' first baseman, had blocked
Knoblauch's path to second. Mets Manager Bobby Valentine argued
that Knoblauch never changed direction and that no contact had been
made, but all it earned him was his first ejection this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets played the game under protest, but the Yankees soon had
two runs on a double by Derek Jeter and an infield single by
Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   Jones does not try to blow hitters away. He spotted his fastball
well, and mixed in enough curveballs and sliders to keep the
Yankees from swinging comfortably. Martinez's home run came on a
pitch that was down and away; Jones did not regret it. Martinez
then drove in a run in the eighth on a single off Dennis Cook.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips also must be sure that the Mets' offensive All-Stars,
Piazza and Edgardo Alfonzo, will hit again. But Alfonzo and Piazza
combined to go 0 for 15 in the first two games of this series _
``When we get hot, we have to get cold sometimes,'' Alfonzo said _
and it was up to the rest of the lineup to produce.
</P>
<P>
   Agbayani singled and scored on a bloop double by Derek Bell in
the fifth inning, and in the seventh he was on second when Bell
stood in with two outs and the Mets trailing, 3-2. Facing Jeff
Nelson, Bell hit a high chopper to third. He might have beaten a
throw from Brosius, but Brosius instead tagged out Agbayani, who
was trying to advance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I froze, because I thought he was going to throw the ball to
first base,'' Agbayani said. ``Then I heard Jeter tell him I was
right there next to him. He was on his way, but he lost his grip
when he was about to throw.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets never had another base runner, and they were held
scoreless over four innings by three Yankees relievers, securing
Gooden's improbable victory. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
